<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS' HOMERS PUTS YANKS WITHIN ONE VICTORY OF TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Previously budgeted as BBO-YANKS-PADRES; the story is an
added starter on The New York Times front page.) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The day before the playoffs began, David Cone was
asked to pick one Yankee who might shine in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, Cone replied. ``He's got that glint in his eye,''
</P>
<P>
   And how. Brosius slugged two home runs Tuesday night in Game 3
of the World Series, including a three-run shot in the eighth
inning that gave the Yankees a 5-4 victory over San Diego and a
commanding three games-to-none lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   No team has ever come back from a 3-0 deficit to win the final
four games of a World Series. The Yankees' Andy Pettitte will try
to finish off the Padres Wednesday night and give the Yankees their
24th World Series title and second in the last three seasons.
Pettitte will be pitching against San Diego's ace, Kevin Brown.
Another victory for the Yankees would be their 125th over the
regular season and postseason, and could qualify the Yankees as the
greatest team ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trailed, 3-2, in the eighth inning, with San Diego
intent on delivering a lead into the hands of its dominating
closer, Trevor Hoffman. But with the left-handed hitting Paul
O'Neill leading off the eighth for the Yankees, Padres Manager
Bruce Bochy elected to start the inning with left-hander Randy
Myers on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Myers walked O'Neill, putting the tying run on base, and Bochy
then called for Hoffman, who converted 53 of 54 save opportunities
during the regular season. But it was apparent immediately that
Hoffman, who hadn't thrown in a game in six days, was pitching at
less than his best. Typically, Hoffman throws a fastball at 92-94
mph. His first fastball to Bernie Williams Tuesday night was
clocked at 88 mph, and Williams drove a pitch to the base of the
wall in right field, a 355-foot out.
</P>
<P>
   With Tino Martinez batting, Hoffman began pitching passively,
throwing his slider and his changeup, and Martinez also drew a
walk. Dave Stewart, San Diego's pitching coach, went to the mound,
perhaps to ask why Hoffman wasn't going with his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius was next, having hit a single and a home run in three
at-bats. He tried checking his swing unsuccessfully on the first
pitch, a ball in the dirt, then took two more off-speed pitches for
balls, before fouling off an 89 mph fastball. Hoffman came back at
him with another fastball, 91 mph. Brosius swung, the ball soared.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego center fielder Steve Finley ran back to the wall,
Hoffman staring at the numbers on the back of his jersey. When the
ball carried over the fence, Brosius, halfway between first and
second, thrust both arms into the air.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego scored a run in the bottom of the eighth, shaving the
lead to 5-4. But the Yankees held on to salvage a gallant effort
from Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Hitchcock baffled the Yankees at the start, allowing
only a hit and a walk in the first four innings. Contrary to the
advance notices, Hitchcock was more aggressive with his fastball
than the Yankees probably expected. They were unable to force him
deep into ball-strike counts, as they had done to Kevin Brown and
Andy Ashby, San Diego's starters in Game 1 and Game 2,
respectively. Hitchcock threw just 50 pitches in the first four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been to Cone's benefit: With the Yankees' at-bats
progressing rapidly, Cone didn't have to sit and wait at length on
the bench. He got stiff resting between innings in winning Game 6
of the American League Championship Series and nearly blew a 6-0
lead. He had reached the fifth inning with a relatively low pitch
count and had simply run out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is 35, two years removed from an aneurysm, a year beyond
shoulder surgery. He's been throwing a baseball for 10 months,
beginning his rehabilitation last December, and there have been
signs for weeks that his body has worn down. Cone stopped throwing
between starts in August, preferring instead to ``save as many
bullets as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone's stuff seemed quite ordinary Tuesday night, his first
fastballs clocked at 87-88 mph, and Cone seemed unable to command
his fastballs consistently; he would throw only 53 percent of his
pitches for strikes. After Tony Gwynn's first at-bat, in which he
lined out to left field, he returned to the dugout and told hitting
coach Merv Rettenmund that Cone didn't have a good fastball, and
Rettenmund agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone did manage to keep his pitches out of the middle of the
strike zone, out of the danger area, and when he reached two
strikes on any right-handed batter, Cone did not procrastinate,
immediately throwing his best pitch, his sidearm slider. Somehow,
he got through, keeping the Padres hitless and scoreless through
five innings. The Yankees had two hits and no runs against
Hitchcock.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cone led off the sixth inning and plunked a single into left
field, his third hit in eight career at-bats in the World Series.
In an odd way, reaching base might've been the worst thing to
happen for Cone; instead of being on the bench and resting, he
would have to run the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch bunted down the third base line and Cone hustled
to second on the single. Joey Hamilton began warming up in the San
Diego bullpen, as the Yankees began the third turn through their
lineup; all during the postseason, Padres Manager Bruce Bochy has
tried to avoid giving opponents a third look at Hitchcock in the
same game.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock struck out Derek Jeter on an inside fastball, before
Paul O'Neill grounded a single through the middle. Cone chugged
toward third, the coach Willie Randolph waving and waving _ and
then throwing up his hands, the stop sign. Knoblauch, perhaps 30
feet beyond second base, had to stop and retreat. Bases loaded and
one out. Cone stood at third, waiting for a chance to come home.
</P>
<P>
   But Bernie Williams whiffed and Tino Martinez popped out and
Cone went back out to pitch the bottom of the sixth, when his
evening would disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock looped a single over second base. Cone walked Quilvio
Veras on six pitches, and Gwynn pulled a grounder through the first
base hole for a single. Hitchcock ambled around third base, taking
home the first run of the game. The Yankees' right fielder O'Neill
threw back to the infield, between first and second, and the ball
rolled through the infield and into visitors' dugout. Veras was
allowed to walk home and Gwynn went to third, from where he would
score on Ken Caminiti's fly ball to the base of the wall in center
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees drove Hitchcock from the mound in the top of the
seventh, Brosius bashing a home run and Shane Spencer lacing a
double. Joey Hamilton replaced Hitchcock, and Spencer moved to
third on a passed ball and scored one out later when Chili Davis'
ground ball rolled under Caminiti's glove for an error.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch walked, pushing pinch-runner Homer Bush to second base
with only one out. Jeter smacked a hard liner through the middle,
the ball popping off the heel of the shortstop Chris Gomez _ and
into the air again. Gomez, in full stride, caught his own rebound
and flipped to second to double-off Bush and end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
