<HEADLINE>
JC FOOTBALL ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Saturday will see a showdown between Long Beach City College
and El Camino College, the nation's top two ranked junior college
football teams.))
</P>
<P>
   Delvon Flowers is not Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The El Camino running back is not demanding the darn ball when
his Warriors face Long Beach City on Saturday. Flowers also refuses
to make predictions on the game (italics), which pitsthe nation's
top two junior college teams.
</P>
<P>
   After every leading question, Flowers defers. He doesn't say
anything resembling locker-roomtrash talk. Assumedly, he does not
want to provide extra motivation to LBCC.
</P>
<P>
   But in a game of this magnitude, a rivalry with implications of
whom has the best JC squadin the nation, Flowers need not worry
about stirring a controversy with LBCC. Both teams knowthe
importance of the game and will be ready for it, regardless of what
is said beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Flowers --- a graduate of Inglewood High --- appears
to be a difference in thegame. While LBCC calls on four capable
running backs, Flowers is obviously the Warriors'offensive leader.
Leading the Mission Conference in a variety of categories, Flowers
hasrushed for 14 touchdowns in five games. He averages 131 yards
per game and 10.4 yards percarry.
</P>
<P>
   That the Warriors average a first down when Flowers touches the
ball is a staggeringstatistic that even he finds hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, it was sort of always like that,'' he said.
``You get the ball, and thereyouhave it. Here, this is college
football, and I didn't expect it to be like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the running back remains cautious about the LBCC game out
of respect for the Vikings'defense. Flowers, whose test scores
didn't qualify him for Division I football out of highschool,
should be on his way a football powerhouse because Nebraska, USC,
Arizona State andothers all have expressed interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his level of play is high, however, so is LBCC's
defense, which has allowed justfour touchdowns this season and 199
yards per game. In addition, the Vikings' opponentsaverage just 64
rushing yards per game against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told him all week this is a great test for him,'' El
Camino coach John Featherstonesaid. ``Delvon knows this is a
Division I school, a Division I defense, that he's goingagainst.''
</P>
<P>
   El Camino's defense isn't too shabby, either. It is second in
the conference to LBCC, butadmittedly, is not as stocked as LBCC.
About the game in general, Flowers said, ``It'llprobably be won by
one of the defenses. I'm looking forward to the defense deciding
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   LBCC's secondary and linebacking corps is unmatched in the
conference, but El Camino mayhave an edge on the defensive line
because of DeLawrence Grant and Ladarias (cq) Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is no mistakes and no stupid penalties,'' Grant said.
``We've been practicing hardand this is the biggest game I've ever
played in. It's looks pretty even, so we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing Featherstone expects to see is the unexpected.
While Flowers and the defensiveline look like El Camino's
strengths, the coach said in big games things always happen
thatcannot be predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The coach's experience may add validity to his theory. Two weeks
ago, he set an El Caminorecord for most wins. He is 101-39-1 in his
14 seasons and just edged Ken Swearingen, who had99 wins and
coached Featherstone in 1967 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we've talked about the marquee players, the Delvon
Flowers and Sean Stein's,''Featherstone said. ``In games like this,
you watch, it's always the unsung heroes that decidethe game.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, LBCC's Sean Stein and Markus Steele.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
