<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PADRES FACE THE SWEEP OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Pa.)  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It is no fun facing the prospect of becoming the
latter-day equivalent of the 1927 Pittsburgh Pirates, who were
drubbed by the Murderer's Row of Yankees in what legend insists was
something less than the minimum four games.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the Padres are at the moment, after the 5-4
defeat to the inheritors of that 1927 uniform and all the mythical
powers within.
</P>
<P>
   This version of the Yankees was so potent that the normal No. 9
hitter, Scott Brosius, drove in 98 runs during the season. Tuesday
night Brosius was elevated to the sixth position in the lineup and
cranked up two homers that gave the Yankees their third straight
victory of this World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday night, the Padres were walking the fine line
between respect and awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a great team,'' said Tony Gwynn, the gracious San
Diego hitter. ``When we beat them, it will be a pleasure to say we
beat a great team like the New York Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was talking like that because there was still space to
come back. Nobody wanted to be depicted by the slapdash historians
known as sportswriters as a team that was beaten before it even
started.
</P>
<P>
   The 1927 Pirates are conveniently remembered as the most
mismatched team in World Series history because they ran into what
may have been the best team in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that who the Yankees beat?'' Gwynn professed on Monday.
``See, I never knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those guys _ do the names George Herman Ruth and Louis Henry
Gehrig strike a familiar cord? _ had clubbed the league into
submission with 110 victories and only 44 losses. Then came the
World Series, then an attractive best-of-seven treat, played in
daylight in early October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The myth-making machinery now didn't even have to wait for a
game to take place,'' writes Leonard Koppett, in his new and
stimulating Koppett's Concise History of Major League Baseball,
published by Temple University Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``America was told that the Yankees' batting practice at Forbes
Field the day before the Series so intimidated the Pirates that
they were beaten then and there,'' Koppett adds.
</P>
<P>
   It is a wonderful misty legend, of the Pirates standing around
the batting cage with their jaws hanging down to the letters on
their shirts, watching Tony Lazzeri and Bob Meusel whack balls into
the foliage behind the outfield walls.
</P>
<P>
   Koppett then debunks the legend somewhat by noting that the real
imbalance lay in the Pirates' starting pitchers being all
right-handed while the Yankee sluggers were left-handed except for
Earl Combs. He also notes that the Yankees hit exactly two homers
in the Series, both by Ruth, and that the fourth game ended with a
wild pitch: ``So much for intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe the Pirates were intimidated before it began. It
makes for a good story. The Padres were determined not to be
intimidated, and Gwynn surely did not want to waste time thinking
about 1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you compare one team with another?'' Gwynn asked on
Monday. ``I've only been in baseball for 20 years and followed it
as a kid, but I can't compare today with those days.''
</P>
<P>
   He would, however, praise these current Yankees, who won 114 and
lost 48 during the regular season and have now won 10 of 12
postseason games. Nobody compares them to the 1927 Yankees, because
they do not always murder their opponents, sometimes merely
tenderizing them with their wooden mallets.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Gwynn performed obeisance to the Yankee history by
trekking out to the monuments in Yankee Stadium, where he had never
been.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, shuffling in place in right field, Gwynn
observed every ball, every strike, every foul, of the 11-pitch
leadoff walk Chuck Knoblauch finagled. Gwynn understood that
Knoblauch had not only worn down Andy Ashby by some slight
increment but had also provided a guidebook for all the other
perceptive Yankee hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great piece of hitting,'' Gwynn was still raving on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had bedeviled the Padres in so many ways, overt and
subtle, that southern California dailies knee-jerked into the
convenient ritual of using verbs like ``Mugged'' and ``Battered''
in every headline, equating what happened to the Padres in Yankee
Stadium to what obviously happens to every innocent who wanders
onto the sidewalks of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gwynn's pilgrimage to the shrine of Yankee history will
one day be incorporated into legend, like the 1927 Pirates gaping
at the real-live Ruth and Gehrig. More to the point were the two
clutch hits by the gallant Gwynn Tuesday night, and how they were
overcome by these modern destroyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
