<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAY-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NO WAY TO HANDLE A PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Oct. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Outrage and fear brought thousands of marchers into midtown
Manhattan Monday night to protest the brutal murder of a gay
college student in Wyoming last week. The death of 21-year-old
Matthew Shepard, who had been beaten and lashed to a fence near
Laramie, was worthy of what was billed as a ``political funeral''
in a major center of gay life.
</P>
<P>
   But both the marchers and the police mishandled the
demonstration, which ended with about 120 arrests. March leaders
should have planned more carefully and obtained a permit, and the
police should have acted with greater restraint.
</P>
<P>
   First Deputy Police Commissioner Patrick Kelleher has said that
the organizers failed to get a proper permit. The march drew more
than 4,000 people, far more than expected. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
said that for this ``worthy cause,'' the city could have worked
with marchers to craft a plan protecting free speech and minimizing
disruption for the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But once the protesters strayed into traffic, the police shifted
into excess. With mounted police and seemingly random arrests, they
refused to talk to march leaders, rounding up those seen as
troublemakers. Many were kept overnight, some apparently deprived
of crucial HIV and other medications.
</P>
<P>
   For New York City's Police Department, this is the third time in
recent months that a protest or rally has ended in trouble. First,
thousands of construction workers swarmed into midtown to protest
nonunion MTA contracts, landing a few dozen in jail. More recently,
a rally in Harlem ended with arrests when organizers went over
their allotted time limit and police tried to shut down the event.
</P>
<P>
   Although the police have won high marks over the past few
decades for dealing with large protests, the mayor and police
commissioner should review these three troubling cases to determine
if there are better ways to accommodate the needs of the city while
protecting the constitutional right to protest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
