</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-HOFFMAN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BROSIUS POUNDS HOFFMAN AS YANKEES STUN PADRES  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ They wouldn't voice the concern, but the San Diego
Padres privately wondered, ``What if we play an entire World Series
and we never get Trevor into a game?''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres would need a lead against the Yankees late in the
game to use Trevor Hoffman, perhaps the major leagues' premier
closer, and the latest they held a lead in the first two games was
with one out in the seventh inning of the opening game. That, in
the thinking of Manager Bruce Bochy, was a tad early to bring
Hoffman in.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night the Padres had a 3-2 lead in the eighth
inning, and when Randy Myers walked Paul O'Neill, the leadoff
batter, Bochy waited no longer. He summoned Hoffman, and the crowd
of 64,667 raised the roof with their thunderous roar of greeting.
Qualcomm Stadium doesn't have a roof, but the fans raised it
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later Scott Brosius turned the deafening noise to
silence. With two teammates on base, he whacked a Hoffman fastball
over the center field fence for a three-run home run and,
eventually, a 5-4 victory that catapulted the Yankees one victory
away from the World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   That's how good the Yankees have been this year. Not even the
game's best reliever, the pitcher who secured 53 saves in 54 save
situations during the regular season, could stop their relentless
march toward their coveted goal. Hoffman had the lead, and the
Yankees rudely but determinedly snatched it out of the right hand
that has been so golden this year.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, as the prospect of a World Series without Hoffman
pitching loomed, the question was raised about Bochy's decision in
the first game. He made clear that he did not trust the other
members of his relief corps in the fifth game of the National
League Championship Series when he brought in Kevin Brown, his No.
1 starter, to protect a 4-2 seventh-inning lead in what could have
been the pennant-clinching game for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bochy said the next night, sometimes managers get carried
away with slotting their closers for the ninth inning only, but he
had brought in Hoffman in the eighth inning at times this season.
But the seventh? No. He had confidence in other relievers, Bochy
said, even though Donne Wall gave up a game-tying three-run home
run to Chuck Knoblauch in that seventh inning and Mark Langston
gave a grand slam to Tino Martinez later in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees never saw Hoffman in that game, and they didn't
have the privilege the next night either because they scored seven
runs in the first three innings, and the Padres never got close
enough to use him.
</P>
<P>
   When they scored three runs in the sixth inning last night,
Hoffman became a distinct possibility. When the Yankees rallied for
two runs in the seventh, he became a certainty. It was just a
matter of when the Yankees would see him. But again, it wasn't the
seventh inning. It wasn't at the start of the eighth either.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Myers, who until the Padres claimed him on waivers from
Toronto in August was a closer himself, began that inning. But as
soon as he walked O'Neill, it was Hoffman time. Bochy slowly
emerged from the dugout and signaled for his last best hope. Bernie
Williams, the first batter to face the unbeatable one, put a
serious scare into the Padres and their fans by lofting a fly ball
to deep right field. But Tony Gwynn backed up all the way to the
fence and caught the ball as it fell in front of the fence and not
behind it. But then Hoffman walked Tino Martinez, and the Yankees
had two runners on base with Brosius coming to bat.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, who had hit a home run in the previous inning against
Sterling Hitchcock, was batting sixth in the order, high for him,
because the pitcher and not the designated hitter was hitting in
this game. The DH isn't used in World Series games played in
National League parks. Brosius, a remarkably productive hitter for
the Yankees this season, worked the count to 2-2, then drove a
fastball out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, he had stripped Hoffman of his invincibility.
Just like that, the Yankees had the lead, and Mariano Rivera, the
Yankees' closer, would not give it back. Hoffman, the Padres
desperately hope, could get another chance Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
