<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-HITCHCOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK SHOWS HE CAN USE A BAT, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It is rare these days to find a major league pitcher
who can also hit. Rarer still, however, is the prep school pitcher
who is not allowed to hit.
</P>
<P>
   A high school team's best pitcher is usually its best athlete,
which often means he serves as the cleanup hitter as well. But even
when Sterling Hitchcock was the star left-hander at Armwood High
School in Florida, the designated hitter batted for him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in starting against a Cy Young award winner in each of his
four 1998 playoff starts, Hitchcock _ who has arguably been as
valuable to the San Diego Padres as Kevin Brown this post-season _
has helped himself with the bat his last three times out.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Hitchcock _ who had defeated Houston's Randy
Johnson and Atlanta's Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine in his previous
three starts _ turned in six-plus strong innings in Game 3 of the
World Series against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But it was what Hitchcock did with his bat in his first career
World Series start that helped knock David Cone out of the game.
The only difference from Hitchcock's previous outings this
post-season was that the Padres lost.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the bottom of the sixth inning in a scoreless game after
he had just pitched his way out of a bases-loaded, one-out jam,
Hitchcock slapped a single to left to break up a no-hit bid by
Cone, his former Yankee teammate and mentor. Hitchcock's hit opened
the way for a three-run rally, one that the Padre bullpen could not
protect as San Diego lost, 5-4. The Padres are one game from
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering that I couldn't hit Little League pitching, and
then now I've got major league fastballs and sliders coming after
me, I'm still learning,'' Hitchcock had said Monday. ``It's a
battle. It's certainly not easy to do. And taking 11 years off
between swinging bats didn't help any. I think if you ask around,
I'm night and day from last year. But I still stink.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Maddux or Glavine. And please don't tell that
to Cone, who has three World Series hits in his career after
singling off Hitchcock to open the sixth. The difference was that
Cone was stranded at third, while Hitchcock eventually came around
to score.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3 of the National League Championship Series,
Hitchcock's fifth-inning single off Maddux led to a two-run rally
as the Padres took a 3-0 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's liner to left off Glavine was muffed by Danny
Bautista for a two-run error that gave the Padres a 4-0 lead en
route to their series-clinching victory over the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the sixth inning Tuesday night, Hitchcock and Cone had
faced the same number of batters _ 17, two over the minimum. Steve
Finley had made three exceptional plays in center field to help
Hitchcock out. But the Yankees had only two hits heading into the
sixth. And though the Yankees picked up three more singles in the
sixth, Hitchcock struck out Bernie Williams and got Tino Martinez
to pop to second with the bases loaded to preserve the scoreless
tie.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was not so lucky in the bottom of the inning as the Padres
took a 3-0 lead. And even after Hitchcock surrendered a leadoff
homer to Scott Brosius and a double to Shane Spencer, Hitchcock
still had a 3-1 lead when he left the game. But Trevor Hoffman, in
his first appearance of the Series, could not hang on to a 3-2 lead
in the top of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   And once Brosius drilled his second homer of the evening, a
backbreaking three-run shot over the center-field fence, the Padres
_ who could not do to Mariano Rivera what the Yankees did to
Hoffman _ had wasted both Hitchcock's efforts on the mound and at
the plate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
