<HEADER>
A8199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-SPENCER-NY     10-21 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-SPENCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENCER'S FAIRY TALE CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Shane Spencer keeps wondering what the next chapter
of his fairy tale of a season could possibly be. Getting recalled
to the Yankees for September was nice. Hitting a rash of homers as
the Yankees sealed their position as one of the best teams ever in
the regular season was nicer. Belting two homers against the
Rangers in the division series was still nicer.
</P>
<P>
   But, after becoming the forgotten Yankee for the last 10 days,
Spencer was back home for Game 3 of the World Series, and the
rookie was starting in left field Tuesday night. Spencer's story,
which was stagnant while manager Joe Torre started Ricky Ledee or
Chad Curtis, was pulsating again and Spencer wanted to add more to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just special to be up on the Yankees. And
then we made it to the World Series, so that was special,'' said
Spencer. ``Then the Padres made it. I don't know how much you could
ask for in one year. What do I do after this?''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer did a little more for the Yankees in their 5-4 victory
over the Padres. He was instrumental on a night when the Yankees'
offense struggled against a stubborn Sterling Hitchcock. Hitchcock,
who was in the Yankees' minor league system for parts of three
seasons with Spencer, made most of the Yankees look like minor
leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   But after Scott Brosius opened the seventh with the first of his
two homers, Spencer, who had struck out in his first two at-bats,
doubled to left to keep the Yankees churning. Spencer's hit also
caused the Padres to remove Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were relieved to see Hitchcock leave. Spencer, who
later scored New York's second run on Ken Caminiti's error, had
succeeded in giving the offense a late boost. That trend continued
when Brosius smoked a three-run homer off Trevor Hoffman in the
eighth that put the Yankees ahead and silenced a boisterous crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it strictly on, hopefully, the ability of putting the
right guy in left field,'' said Torre, remarking on why he started
Spencer. ``It's tough not to pick Chad Curtis because of what he's
meant to us. The thing that made my decision more than anything is
the power threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 26-year-old Spencer wondered how difficult it would
be to play such a pivotal game in his back yard, he responded. In
addition to the double, Spencer nabbed Chris Gomez with a
one-bounce throw as the Padres tried to stretch a single to a
double in the seventh. That play loomed large after the Yankees
took a 5-3 lead in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought about what my first hit would be like, my
first homer if I ever would have one,'' said Spencer. ``All that's
happened. Now I'm in the World Series in my first year. Now I'm in
San Diego, which is special to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was talking fast, faster than a teen-age boy who was
trying to borrow his parents' car for a date that was supposed to
start an hour earlier. Spencer was relieved, not about starting in
the World Series and not about securing 14 tickets for friends and
family. He was relieved that the weather he has raved about was
gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's spoiled out here,'' said Spencer. ``That's why I
live here. Everybody's got smiles on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially Spencer. The Padres were his team as a kid. The last
time the Padres snared a World Series game was a 5-3 victory over
the Tigers on Oct. 10, 1984, and Spencer, who moved to San Diego
from Key West, Fla., when he was 5, was shouting from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still pull for Tony and the Padres, but this week only I
don't want them to win a game,'' said Spencer. ``I really can't
describe it. Maybe after the game I'll be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was as much a fixture in the lineup as anyone in the
last two games of the division series and the first three games of
the American League Championship Series. But he stumbled into a
1-for-10 drought against the Indians and Torre benched him until
Tuesday night. When Torre was asked why Spencer sputtered, the
manager said: ``If he didn't, he would have caught McGwire. You
can't do it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees worked out on Monday, Spencer rushed to his
friend Todd Holverson's apartment and watched the Jets-Patriots
game. Spencer slept on Holverson's couch free in the winters
following minor league seasons, so Spencer repaid him with airline
tickets for the division series in Arlington, Texas, and the ALCS
in Cleveland. But Spencer did not have to pay any air fare Tuesday
night so his benevolent landlord could see him in a World Series
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that has happened has been unbelievable,'' said
Spencer. ``But I don't expect anything less. I really can't say
this is a dream. That's what I always thought would be happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
