<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGINGS KINGS HOPE THERE'S NO PLACE LIKE ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ It's no secret Kings coach Larry Robinson has
not been overjoyed with the inconsistent play of his team in the
first four games of the season. On the surface, things appear fine,
given the Kings' 2-1-1 record. But they have struggled offensively
and Robinson has questioned some of his players' intensity.
</P>
<P>
   With this as a backdrop, the Kings begin a five-game trip
tonight against the Florida Panthers (2-0-1), and Robinson is
hoping his team can gel while away from home. After tonight, the
Kings visit Tampa Bay, Carolina, the New York Islanders and New
Jersey before returning to the Forum against the Lightning on Oct.
30.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson can look back a year ago to a similar trip that came
only slightly later in the season. The Kings were 3-5-3 when they
began a five-game trip with a sluggish 3-1 victory in Tampa Bay
last Oct. 26. Two nights later, they tied Florida 2-2 in a game in
which they didn't manage a single shot in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up having to have a no-pucks practice in Florida to
get us going,'' Robinson recalled. ``That's not the way it should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings finished the trip with one-sided victories over
Detroit and New Jersey sandwiching a loss to the Islanders. They
returned home with a .500 record, went 4-2 on a subsequent six-game
home stand, and were above .500 the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is hoping for a similar jump start for his team on this
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of in this situation last year when we went on a
road trip like that,'' Robinson said. ``We weren't playing good,
grinding, working-hard hockey. If we're not prepared and we're not
playing well, we could be in deep (trouble) when we come back from
this road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   At least for the beginning of the trip, the Kings will be
relying on a rookie goalie, as Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr
recover from groin strains. Manny Legace, 25, is scheduled to make
his first NHL appearance tonight, with 18-year-old Alexey Volkov as
the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a great way to do it,'' Robinson said of starting an
important trip with a rookie in goal, ``but what are you going to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Legace, however, said he wants to make the most of his
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody who plays hockey wants to get to the highest
league they possibly can,'' said Legace, who had been playing in
the IHL for the Long Beach Ice Dogs. ``Hopefully I can play well
and stick around for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Time needed: Look for Robinson to find playing time on the
trip for defenseman Garry Galley and forward Roman Vopat, neither
of whom has played in the first four games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 35-year-old Galley, whose absence from the lineup has
been something of a surprise, Robinson said, ``I'd certainly like
to get him in. Practice shape and game shape are two different
things. He hasn't played in a while. We're going to be playing a
lot of games on the road. I want to get everybody in, get them in
game shape.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Green's day: When their son's first NHL goal came Friday
against Boston, rookie Josh Green's father, Svend, was on a
business trip in Winnipeg, and his mother, Carol, was watching the
game in the family's hometown of Camrose, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom watched it at the neighbors' house,'' said Green, 20.
``The neighbors weren't home. She was watching it by herself in
their basement. She said she felt pretty weird jumping up and down
by herself.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal seemed to get Green going, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really energized,'' he said. ``As soon as I got the
first goal, I felt better out there. I don't know what it was. I
was just really pumped up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8205 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      10-21 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
After losing one of the biggest bargaining chips in their labor
battle with the NBA owners, the members of the National Basketball
Players Association will convene Thursday in Las Vegas for what can
be called the bargaining equivalent of a 20-second timeout.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, arbitrator John Feerick refused the players' grievance,
saying the owners were not obligated to pay 226 players their
guaranteed contracts during the lockout. With Nov. 15, the day
first paychecks are due, approaching, the players must figure out
their next tactic in an effort to get back on the court.
</P>
<P>
   And lately, the tactic being mentioned most often is
decertifying the players' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to think of what's best for the players now,
considering where we're at,'' said the Rockets' Brent Price. ``We
went for the gold, and we didn't get it. Now, we have to minimize
the losses. Realistically, I don't know how we're going to avoid
signing a hard (salary) cap at this point unless we decertify.''
</P>
<P>
   The union has been fighting the owners' demands for a hard
salary cap, which would fix the amount of money devoted to player
salaries. Unable to reach anything near an agreement, a vote to
decertify would remove the union as the official bargaining agent
for the players and open the door for the players to return to the
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Labor laws allow the owners to lock out a body of players
represented by a union, but not individuals. Without the union, the
players would come back under rules set by the owners.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the next round of problems begins, said agent Steve
Woods, a professor of sports administration at the University of
South Carolina and Clark Atlanta University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once those new rules were established, the next mechanism
would be the players would sue based on antitrust provisions saying
the league was setting a system that limits individual income,''
Woods said. ``The only way you're able to suppress salaries, or
come up with an economic-income system, is within a mutually
agreed-upon collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like price-fixing. The tactic would be to take away the
union so the owners would have to do some sort of price-fixing,
which would open them up to the antitrust lawsuit. Then they would
be right back where they started.''
</P>
<P>
   But some advise the players to exercise caution when considering
a vote to decertify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel, as a whole, that if that's something you throw out
there, then you'd better be prepared to do it,'' said player agent
Tony Dutt, a member of the agents' advisory council, which is
advising the players during negotiations. ``You can't just say,
`Oh, yeah, we might just decertify.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you're going to do it or you're not. I think that's
what we want to come out of this (the Las Vegas meeting) with _
some definites on what the next plan is. You can't afford to make
the wrong move at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   But the players are prepared to decertify the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've actually already signed decertification papers as
individual players,'' Price said. ``Each individual player had to
sign a paper saying whether they would decertify if it came to that
so the union could vote on it. We did that way back when as kind of
a last resort, just in case we ever had to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that would be the best answer. If you
decertified, there would be chaos _ you'd break up the union, and I
think you'd further delay the start of the season because there
would be a lot to be established and determined. I don't know all
the facts, so we have to see what all our options are. I don't
think that would be the best option for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the options being mulled by the players:
</P>
<P>
   Going back to the bargaining table and working out an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing to the owners' latest offer, which calls for a luxury
tax on all Larry Bird-exception contracts above the average salary,
which was $2.6 million last season.
</P>
<P>
   Decertification, but only as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, NFL players opted for decertification after their
failed strike and fought a five-year battle in the courts before a
settlement was reached with owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to talk about the various options,'' said union
executive director Billy Hunter.``We'll make some determinations
about what we'll do from there.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern, who has canceled the first two
weeks of the season and said there might be more cancellations
announced next week, hopes the players vote to return to the
bargaining table rather than decertifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfair-labor-practice charges, arbitration, decertifications,
antitrust lawsuits don't get it done,'' Stern said. ``All they do
is cost the players more money, owners more money and the fans the
game. If the record to date doesn't demonstrate that the way to get
out of this is to negotiate, then I don't know what else to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
