<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESS PAID TOO MUCH HEED TO SPECULATION ABOUT SCANDAL, STUDY
FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major news organizations, long under fire for their coverage of
the investigation into President Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, showed reasonable care with facts but sometimes placed
unreasonable credence in investigators' speculation, according to a
new study by a watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the Committee of Concerned Journalists, found
that ``the press also ferried speculation, some of which could have
been construed as threats, from investigators into news accounts,
raising questions about whether the press was sufficiently wary of
being used by sources, especially law enforcement sources.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the report said, accounts _ later discredited _
that the prosecutors might have found a witness to a clandestine
sexual encounter, may indicate that ``investigative sources used
the press to float rumors, to put pressure on potential witnesses,
including Lewinsky, and to try out a prosecution theory that
included a possible conspiracy to cover up the affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the general criticism that some news
organizations, including Newsweek magazine, gave too much credence
to investigators' version of evidence, Newsweek's Washington bureau
chief, Ann McDaniel, said, ``All along this was a difficult story
to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, for the first seven or eight months we only had
information that was coming from the accusers, whether witnesses or
sources close to Starr's office,'' Ms. McDaniel said, referring to
the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   She added that reporting was complicated ``by the fact that many
of the people involved on the president's side refused to talk and
the president himself lied.''
</P>
<P>
   The report on the press' coverage took special note of Starr's
contention, in a legal argument, that his office's contacts with
the press could be shielded from scrutiny by the ``informants'
privilege,'' which implied that Starr saw some reporters as
extensions of his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he himself chose to defend his contacts that way
should raise a question in journalists' minds,'' said Bill Kovach,
the chairman of the committee and curator of the Nieman Foundation
for Journalism at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises a question about whether the prosecutors were
passing stories to a less-than-skeptical press,'' sometimes to
intimidate witnesses, Kovach said.
</P>
<P>
   Supervised by James Doyle, who was special assistant to the
independent counsels investigating the Watergate scandal, the
report analyzed particular aspects of coverage that have been
heavily criticized, including the reports, which were never
substantiated, of a witness to a sexual encounter between Clinton
and Ms. Lewinsky. The committee noted that ABC News' report about a
potential witness prompted a rash of press speculation about
corroborating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the president of ABC News, David Westin, said on
Tuesday that Westin could not comment on the report until he had
had a chance to review it.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the news organizations was tempered with the
observation that ``the press was largely on the mark'' in reporting
that Ms. Lewinsky had saved a dress reportedly bearing DNA evidence
of an encounter with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the contention that ABC News was lucky when
it reported the dress ``may be too harsh.'' Reliance on a single
source can be justified, if the network ``had good reason to
believe its lone source,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The echo-chamber effect of such reports remains a troubling
aspect of the coverage of this investigation, said Michael Oreskes,
the Washington bureau chief of The New York Times. ``It has
sometimes, in the minds of editors, replaced the need for a second
source or the need to double-check,'' Oreskes said.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at reporting from CNN, PBS, the three network
news broadcasts, The New York Times, The Washington Post, The Los
Angeles Times, USA Today, Time and Newsweek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
