<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VETERAN-QBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S BEST QUARTERBACKS ARE AGING TO PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro football teams in recent years have been enamored of youth.
Youth usually means speed, quickness and an open mind that can be
easily molded. Youth has often meant a cheaper player, one who fits
more easily under the salary cap. Youth has meant freshness, a
bushel of players less prone to injury who often heal more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Through seven weeks of the National Football League season,
however, youth at quarterback is not being served.
</P>
<P>
   The six top-rated quarterbacks in the league are at least age 32
and have played at least nine pro seasons. Randall Cunningham of
Minnesota is first with a 121.3 passer rating. He is followed by
Vinny Testaverde of the Jets (108.8), Steve Young of San Francisco
(105.8), Neil O'Donnell of Cincinnati (102.2), John Elway of Denver
(100.7) and Doug Flutie of Buffalo (93.8).
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 35, is in his 13th pro season. Testaverde (35 next
month) is in his 12th, Young (37) in his 16th, O'Donnell (32) in
his ninth, and Flutie (36 on Friday) in his 14th, including eight
in the Canadian Football League.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 30-something group with quite a few kicks left.
</P>
<P>
   These men have found their own version of a fountain of youth.
They still possess mobility to escape today's mad pass rush. They
have retained arm strength to deliver tight throws. But most of
all, they have seen enough, played enough, read enough coverages
and experienced enough heated game pressures to make quick and
efficient decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It is the decision-making, given any type of pro-level skill,
that is the essential extra ingredient that truly makes a
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling that the Randall Cunnigham that I have now is
a totally different one than the Randall Cunningham that was in
Philadelphia,'' said Brian Billick, Minnesota's offensive
coordinator. ``He is more mature. He is married and has children.
What I have now is a very serene and confident man.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the rookies, Ryan Leaf and Peyton Manning, and
there is no question that those two guys have the physical skills
that match and even pass any of the top-rated quarterbacks today.
But playing quarterback in the NFL is doing a tough job in a very
unique atmosphere. No matter how good of a coach you are, and no
matter how much film you watch, and no matter what the physical
skill of the quarterback is, there is nothing like that game-day
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham replaced the injured Brad Johnson (broken right
fibula) in Week 2 and has thrown 12 touchdown passes and no
interceptions. He is averaging 9.37 yards gained per pass attempt,
by far the best in the league. He has a quality offensive line,
three dynamic receivers and a top running back in Robert Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, he has perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit him in the pocket and give him maximum protection, and
he knows he will have time to throw; he has the arm to make it
happen,'' Billick said. ``I think his experience before in
Philadelphia was different from that. He was scrambling a lot and
tried to make a lot happen on his own. Here, he is part of the
scheme, not the whole scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to Brad. Randall knows that. First we have to
make sure that Brad is fully healed and conditioned. Randall does
have the hot hand and so this is a situation where, when the time
comes, the best decision will be made to not disrupt chemistry and
to also give this team the best chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota is 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are 3-3 and excited after showing the nation on Monday
night that Testaverde is not a backup-turned-starter who cannot
produce. Testaverde passed for three touchdowns in the Jets' 24-14
victory over New England, and he is leading the league in a
noteworthy category: red-zone completion percentage. In the red
zone, Testaverde is 71.4 percent (10 of 14 for 78 yards and 7
touchdowns). His closest competitor is Mark Brunell of Jacksonville
at 59.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Young is rolling. In each of the 49ers' six games, he has passed
for 300 or more yards, the first NFL player to accomplish that
feat. O'Donnell has thrown 1 interception in 165 pass attempts.
Elway is averaging 8.40 yards gained per pass attempt. Flutie beat
previously unbeaten Jacksonville last Sunday with his legs as much
as with his arm, on a 1-yard broken-play bootleg run for the
winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Flutie, each of the top passers is at least 6 feet 2
inches and weighs at least 214 pounds. Size matters. But experience
and decision-making matter more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care much about how we finish each year in total
offense,'' Billick said. ``We want at the end of the year to rank
in the top 10 in rushing and in passing. If you have that kind of
balance, you have an offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same goes for all of these quarterbacks. You are talking
about some guys who have a great deal of pride and professionalism,
who have played the game for a long time and who expect to play at
a certain level. When they get to the point that they can't, they
won't be there. They will make sure of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
