<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8218 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ROQUES-LADN     10-21 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROQUES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROQUES COMING THROUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ryan Roques' surname might be pronounced `rock,'
yet in his first three years at UCLA he'd been anything but.
</P>
<P>
   He was a baseball player who'd gone an entire season without a
hit. In football, he gave upon the idea of playing tailback. And
when it came to playing defense, well, it seemed like anawful lot
of work.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, halfway through this season, Roques, a fourth-year junior,
has stepped from the shadows of the UCLA depth chart to play two
prominent roles: starting cornerback and punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   Count UCLA head coach Bob Toledo among the surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never made a commitment to football before,'' Toledo
said. ``He's kind of done this,done that; a little football, a
little baseball; and he's never done well in either of them.He
hasn't been an effort guy. We had two guys who didn't make the
commitment to work reallyhard in the summer one of 'em isn't with
us (Damian Allen) and the other is Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like all of a sudden a light switch went on that said,
`Hey, I'm tired of being abackup. I'm tired of not playing. I'm
going to go out and compete and go out and show theseguys I can
play.'''
</P>
<P>
   Roques was handed the left cornerback job, ironically enough,
when someone else MarquesAnderson displayed a lack of effort. He
shows no sign of handing it back, either, as hisfour interceptions
lead the Pac-10 and are fourth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Roques became the punt returner last week, returning four kicks
for 38 yards (9.8 average),when DeShaun Foster sprained knee
ligaments that will keep him out at least two more weeks.The job
originally belonged to Freddie Mitchell, who broke his leg against
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It's the type of play UCLA expected out of the 6-foot,
190-pounder when he was chosen theCIF Division IV Player of the
Year after leading Moreno Valley Canyon Springs to a CIF title.
</P>
<P>
   Roques, after redshirting in '95, was given a crack at running
back in the '96 opener atTennessee, but soon found himself buried
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fumbled at Tennessee and he didn't play hard,'' Toledo
said. ``He didn't carry theball well and then he proved he didn't
want to play offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Roques asked Toledo after the season to move to defense. By
playing baseball anoutfielder with excellent speed, he has been
used primarily as a pinch runner the past twoseasons there was
little time to learn his new position in football.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he played in only three games in the secondary last
year all in garbage time of routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel if I just focused on one sport, I'd improve
a lot faster,'' Roques said.``It's not something I have to do it's
something I chose to do because I like playing both sports and I'd
like to keep my options open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to get better, but last year it was really
difficult to make the transition from running back to cornerback so
quickly. I was probably improving with each practice, but it wasn't
at a level where you could really notice it because I was so far
behind in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no press conference or klieg lights when Roques was
given the starting job in the third game against Washington State,
but word got out quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and Oregon have made it a point to test Roques. The
Ducks, in fact, threw five consecutive passes at him in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens,'' said UCLA free safety Larry Atkins.
``If you have a sub or a new guy, the next few plays you're going
toward that guy. If he keeps coming up with big plays,teams will
learn to stay away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of Roques' four interceptions have indeed been big plays.
</P>
<P>
   His 19-yard return for a touchdown against Houston put the
Bruins comfortably ahead, 35-14.
</P>
<P>
   His first-quarter pick against Washington State set up a UCLA
touchdown that put the Bruins ahead, 21-0, less than 11 minutes
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Roques' 39-yard return of an interception against Arizona set up
Chris Sailer's 41-yard field goal that gave UCLA a 24-21
third-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   His interception of Akili Smith's fourth-down desperation heave
killed Oregon's chance in overtime and the Bruins won on their
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really feel like you'repart of the game until you
get apass breakup or a nice tackle orsomebody might hit you,'' he
said.``Then it's like, `Now, I'm ready to play.'''
</P>
<P>
   And for that, the Bruins couldn't be more thankful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
