<HEADER>
A8221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      10-21 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: CORPORATE AMERICA CUTS BACK; THE PENINSULA
REOPENS; SINGAPORE AIRLINES SCORES AGAIN; BARGAINS IN FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also filed in ``t'' category) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN MCDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business travelers can take some comfort that the typical
domestic business fare rose only 3 percent in the 10 months ended
in August, to $458, according to the latest American Express
Business Airfare Index. By contrast, comparable fares increased 16
percent in all of 1997 compared with 1996. Typical business fare
generally means the lowest fare available with the least
restrictions. But business fares last August, the latest month for
which data were available, were 9 percent higher than in August
1997, when the comparable fare was $421.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent survey, the Air Transport Association
reported on Monday that the average fare, which includes economy
and first-class fares, fell 1 percent in September, compared with
September 1997, and rose only 1.8 percent from January through
September 1998, to $138.74
</P>
<P>
   But whether because of the rise in business fares the last few
years, because of the recent economic downturn or both, corporate
America has begun to rein in spending on business travel. A survey
of 450 Fortune 1,000 companies by the National Business Travel
Association found that 56 percent have cut back the number of
employees who travel, 53 percent have replaced some travel with
video conferencing and teleconferencing and 40 percent have altered
corporate travel practices and policies to save money. On average,
the corporations surveyed will reduce overall domestic and
international travel by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Update
</P>
<P>
   With New York City hotels jammed practically every night, the
242-room Peninsula New York hotel at Fifth Avenue and 55th Street
will reopen on Nov. 1, 10 months after closing for a $45 million
overhaul. Room rates are $535 a night, a junior suite is $800 and
the Peninsula suite is $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Managed by the hotel and marketing arm of the ultra-upscale
Hongkong and Shanghai Hotels Ltd., the Peninsula, as those rates
suggest, is hardly your ordinary hotel. Amenities include built-in
remote-controlled televisions that can be viewed from the tub;
three telephones in the bathroom, including a hands-free unit at
the tub that automatically mutes the radio and television;
double-glazed windows and a personal fax number for the machine in
a nearby credenza.
</P>
<P>
   There are other specialties of the house, including a control
panel that displays up-to-the-minute temperature and humidity
readings from the hotel's own rooftop weather station.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast Winners
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines has done it again. The November issue of
Conde Nast Traveler rates the airline the best international
carrier for the 10th time in the 11 years the the magazine has
conducted its readers' choice awards. The best U.S. carrier was
Midwest Express, the rare airline that actually leaves a few inches
between passengers' knees and the seat back in front. Other winners
included the Windsor Court Hotel in New Orleans, voted the best
hotel in the world; Crystal Cruises and Silversea, the best large
cruise line and small cruise line, respectively; Sydney, Australia,
the top foreign city, and San Francisco, the top U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
   Airline News
</P>
<P>
   Americans who buy the Europe Flight Pass can now add Paris,
Prague, Venice, Vienna and 25 other European cities for $90 a
flight. That is the result of three more airlines joining: Cityjet,
based in Dublin; Alpi Eagles, a regional carrier based in Venice,
and Croatia Airlines of Zagreb. Other airlines in the network
include Icelandair, Virgin Express and Spanair, a Spanish carrier
that for almost a year has been operating nonstop flights between
Washington Dulles International Airport and Madrid. Flight coupons,
sold in packets of three or more, are valid for 120 days. They are
available from travel agents or by calling (888) 387-2479.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate a year of flying to the United States, Spanair has
a $299 round-trip fare between Dulles and seven Spanish cities,
including Madrid, Barcelona and Palma de Mallorca. The round-trip
fare to the Canary Islands is $369. Travel must be completed by
Dec. 14 and other restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Sabena Belgium World Airlines also has a bargain fare: $750 a
couple to Brussels from New York, Newark, N.J., Boston, Chicago or
Atlanta. The price includes round-trip fare, departure taxes and
two nights at the Brussels Hilton International or a similar hotel.
The package is good only over Thanksgiving weekend, Nov. 26-29, and
restrictions apply. In a refreshing break with the airline
tradition of never disclosing the number of seats available to
frequent fliers or in fare sales, Sabena said it was limiting the
number of seats for this promotion to 350, or 50 for each of the
seven flights _ including two flights each from New York and
Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0021 </DOCNO>
