<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL ON THE MENU  
 WHITNEY JEWELRY BRINGS HIGH BIDS  
 EXPENSIVE TEDDY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with C.J. Satterwhite 
   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The guests were handing the book to the author to autograph.
Squiggle, squiggle and flourish. Squiggle, squiggle and flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Then Michael Reiss, 14, approached. He was carrying not the
book, but a basketball. Bill Bradley autographed that, too.
</P>
<P>
   The party for Bradley's just-published ``Values of the Game''
was at a restaurant with a basketball connection: Michael Jordan's
Steakhouse on the balcony in Grand Central Terminal. And Bradley
was easy to pick out. He was the tallest guy in the crowd _ until
the 6-foot-10-inch Willis Reed arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bradley, a former forward for the Knicks and a former U.S.
Senator, and Reed, a former center, some of the other guests have
the word ``former'' in their titles, whether they made their names
in sports or politics. Red Holzman, the former coach of the Knicks,
was there. So were Geraldine Ferraro, the former representative who
ran for vice president in 1984 and for the Democratic nomination
for the Senate this year, and Sal F. Albanese, the former City
Councilman who ran for mayor last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's publisher, Peter Workman, said something into a
microphone about being a Knicks fan. But Grand Central's
public-address system was louder (``The 6:35 to North White Plains,
track 19'').
</P>
<P>
   Later Bradley wished Workman a happy birthday. How many candles
on his cake?
</P>
<P>
   `Oh, I wonder if I'm supposed to say,'' a Workman worker said
later. ``I may be killed for telling you. He's 60.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Jewelry Brings High Bids
</P>
<P>
   As celebrity auctions go, the sale of the late Betsey Cushing
Whitney's jewelry at Sotheby's on Monday made for a low-voltage
evening, befitting a woman who was herself not given to extravagant
display, even though she had plenty of earrings, necklaces and
rings to show off.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone in the room was a dealer of one sort or other
(diamond, antiques, etc.) or a Whitney relative of one sort or
other. In the second category were two nieces of Mrs. Whitney's
late husband Jock, Payne Middleton and Sandra Payson. They smiled
when the auctioneer, John Block, declared, ``This is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   This was after the bidding on a gold-and-enamel snuffbox had
reached $30,000, $5,000 more than Sotheby's top estimate. It
eventually sold for $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   The next lot, another snuffbox, must have seemed like more fun:
it sold for $200,000, nearly six times the top estimate.
</P>
<P>
   A platinum cultured-pearl-and-diamond bracelet by Verdura went
for $60,000 to a man on the aisle. When asked for his paddle
number, he called out, ``I don't have one.'' Block said, ``That's
okay. I think we know you.'' The bidder was Ward Landrigan, the
president of Verdura in New York and the former head of Sotheby's
jewelry department.
</P>
<P>
   John and Margo Catsimatidis walked in midway through the
auction. Mrs. Catsimatidis said later that her husband had wanted
to buy her something for their 10th wedding anniversary (``and who
am I to say no to that?'').
</P>
<P>
   But Catsimatidis, the chief executive of the Red Apple Group, a
supermarket chain that includes the Gristede's and Sloan's stores,
left empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't find exactly what he was looking for,'' Mrs.
Catsimatidis said.
</P>
<P>
   Expensive Teddy
</P>
<P>
   The $100,000 teddy bear is headed for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The handmade Gund with fur that ranges from mocha brown to
``warm mahogany'' was auctioned Tuesday at the William Doyle
Galleries. Gund, which said that money from the sale would go to
four children's charities, identified the buyer as Yoshirio
Sekiguchi, the founder of two teddy bear museums in Japan. He
wanted the bear for his third museum, scheduled to open next August
in Hakone.
</P>
</TEXT>
