<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS EPITOMIZES YANKEES' EMPHASIS ON PLAYING AS A TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ To adopt the sentiments of a banner displayed at
Yankee Stadium over the weekend:
``SupercalifragilisticexpialiBROSIUS!''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' underrated third baseman Scott Brosius sucked the
air out of Qualcomm Stadium with a shocking three-run homer off
Padres closer Trevor Hoffman in the eighth inning last night, and
in the ensuing sounds of silence, you could have heard a friar's
frock drop.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius' hope-crushing home run, his second of the game, lifted
the unstoppable Yankees to a 5-4 victory in Game 3 of the 1998
World Series and a 3-0 lead in the best-of-seven matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat after me: No team has ever been down three games to none
and come back to win the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen have tried. Nobody's done it.
</P>
<P>
   The poor Padres, like every other team before them, are frozen
in the path of a machine as powerful and inexorable as a locomotive
under full steam. Even when the Yankees do something wrong, which
is rare enough, they find a way to come back and win.
</P>
<P>
   That it was the unassuming, workaholic Brosius, the Yankees'
hottest hitter in the postseason, who would provide the big blows
last night epitomizes a Yankees season marked by team effort.
</P>
<P>
   This is truly a team that is greater than the sum of its parts
and a blueprint for clubs with championship aspirations to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the thing that, as a kid, you dream about,'' Brosius
said. ``I've done it in my backyard a thousand times.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a little bigger than that. This was in the World
Series, in front of 64,667 screaming Padres fans. This writes his
name in the history books alongside Ruth and DiMaggio, Mantle and
Berra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enough of a student \Rof baseball history\S to know that
my name doesn't belong with theirs,'' Brosius said. ``Maybe
somewhere underneath them. I just feel fortunate to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   So, by the way, should the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   With their Southern California cool, their wonderful climate,
their beautiful beaches and their own vaunted pitching staff, the
Padres have been little more than a fish taco _ a San Diego
epicurean staple _ on the Yankees' dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   Tasty. Interesting. But gone way too fast and not very
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Padres will send out their weary ace, the
always-sick-in-late-October Kevin Brown, on three days' rest in
hopes of stemming the Yankees tide, at least for a night, but they
must now win two in a row just to return the Series to Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the most pleasant of propositions, even if they can
somehow pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   That it was Hoffman who served up the game-losing home run after
the Padres had finally broken through off Yankees starter David
Cone for a 3-0 lead demonstrates the frustration of Padres manager
Bruce Bochy, who has been unable to find a way bridge the gap
between his starting pitchers and his closer.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, he tried to shorten that gap, by bringing in Hoffman
for his first appearance of the Series after Randy Myers walked
leadoff batter Paul O'Neill and the Padres clinging by their
fingernails to a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Great teams _ and this is one _ make pitchers pay for walking
leadoff hitters with a one-run lead, and the Padres paid dearly.
</P>
<P>
   Backed against the wall, Bochy waved in Hoffman, who hadn't
pitched in six days, since closing out Game 6 of the National
League Championship Series against Atlanta. Now Bochy was asking
him to get six outs. The rust showed.
</P>
<P>
   Some 64,667 fans held their breath when Bernie Williams' fly
ball backed Tony Gwynn to the fence in right field. Bochy gulped,
sensing that Hoffman might not have his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez walked, moving O'Neill into scoring position and
bringing Brosius to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In a game in which both starting pitchers _ David Cone and
Sterling Hitchcock _ took no-hitters into the fourth, there was no
question that Brosius had been getting the best swings of anyone on
either team all night.
</P>
<P>
   He'd flied out to the warning track in center in the second,
singled sharply to left in the fifth and homered to left center
leading off the seventh, right after the Padres had broken through
for three runs off Cone in the bottom of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   With the tying run at second, all Brosius wanted to do was find
a way to get O'Neill home. He did.
</P>
<P>
   ``A home run is not something you go up there thinking about,''
he said. ``I wasn't trying to do anything in particular. I was just
trying to do my best not to jump out too fast because \RTrevor\S
has a great changeup.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, bouncing his breaking ball and changeup in the dirt,
fell behind 2-1 and then got a pitch a little too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fastball, out over the plate,'' Brosius said, ``and I
got a good swing on it and got it up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres center fielder Steve Finley tracked it to the 405-foot
mark in dead center, then watched helplessly as the ball
disappeared over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   When it left the ballpark, the Padres' last chance to come back
and win this Series vanished, too.
</P>
<P>
   You suppose the Yankees' celebration champagne will go with fish
tacos?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
