<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY MIGHT BE SOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy players learned at a team
meeting Tuesday morning that Los Angeles Kings co-owner Philip F.
Anschutz is negotiating to join the Major League Soccer team's
operating group.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy chairman and lead investor-operator Marc Rapaport made
the announcement, acknowledging to players and coaches that rumors
of the team's impending sale had merit.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known whether L.A. Soccer Partners,
headed by Rapaport, is seeking to relinquish ownership of the
Galaxy or if Anschutz is merely interested in investing in the
team. Rapaport and team president Daniel Villanueva were involved
in a five-hour meeting Tuesday afternoon and did not return
numerous telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Rapaport and Villanueva) brought that issue (selling the
team) up today,'' Galaxy captain Dan Calichman said. ``We had heard
rumors of Anschutz thinking of buying the team, but we didn't know
for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if that means Rapaport and Villanueva will be
out, or if they would remain. We just don't know other than
something's going on. Hey, anyone that can come in and bring us a
training facility, instead of practicing in Lot H (of the Rose
Bowl), is OK by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the organization, who asked not to be
identified, said a deal could be finalized in a day to a week.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz, a 58-year-old Denver billionaire, already has a
significant stake in Major League Soccer. He is the lead
investor-operator of the Colorado Rapids and Chicago Fire.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Fire defeated the Galaxy, 2-0, in the Western
Conference Finals and will meet the winner of Wednesday's D.C.
United-Columbus Crew match in Sunday's MLS Cup at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Fire defeated the Galaxy, 2-0, in the Western
Conference Finals and will meet the winner of Wednesday's D.C.
United-Columbus Crew match in Sunday's MLS Cup at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   An influx of Anschutz' money could pay dividends to the Galaxy.
The team has long coveted a state-of-the-art training facility,
such as the one Anschutz proved for the expansion Fire. The Galaxy
currently practices in Area H, which is used as a parking lot at
the Rose Bowl, or Occidental College, which lacks a locker room
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz and Edward Roski bought the National Hockey League's
Kings in October 1995. Anschutz's Denver-based The Anschutz
Corporation has its main interests in natural resources,
transportation, real estate and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz serves as chairman of the board of Quest Communications
International, vice chairman of the board of Union Pacific
Corporation and is on the boards of Forest Oil Company, the
American Petroleum Institute and the National Petroleum Council.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Lamar Hunt, who heads franchises in Kansas City and
Columbus, Anschutz is the only investor with a stake in more than
one MLS team. If he joins the Galaxy's operating group, he would
become the first to invest in three.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other major professional sports leagues, MLS features a
unique ownership and operating structure -- a confederation of
individual franchise owners. MLS is structured as a single-entity
liability company. As such, each team operator owns a financial
stake in the league, not just their individual team. In addition,
player contracts are owned by the league, rather than by individual
teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
