<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-CRACKDAD-1stLd-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY ABANDONED IN DAD'S SEARCH FOR CRACK BACK WITH MOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 
(Adding 2nd name in byline) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 and KAREN RUBIN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Eight-month-old Bianca Luna was reunited with her
mother after her father was arrested on suspicion of leaving the
infant with a stranger so he could hunt for drugs, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A relieved Francesca Rosales embraced her child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy she is back,'' said the 24-year-old suburban
West Covina resident as she bounced Bianca on her lap. ``It is a
really great feeling to have her back. It is something I can't
describe.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from her home for more than a day, it was clear that the
child missed her mother and grandmother after spending a night in
foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bianca was really happy. When Bianca saw us she was touching
our faces and pulling our hair,'' said Rosemarie Romero, the
child's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca's father, 27-year-old Ray Luna, was arrested at 3:25 a.m.
Tuesday after officers say they found him driving near Columbus
Avenue and Parthenia Street -- a notorious neighborhood for drugs
-- in suburban North Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Luna was arrested on suspicion of child endangering and is
expected to be arraigned today or Thursday in San Fernando
Municipal Court, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to express to everybody, especially his family, how
sorry he is,'' said Detective Cynthia Dragun.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal for Bianca and her mother began Sunday when Luna
dropped off Rosales at work and was supposed to take his daughter
to her grandmother in West Covina. Luna had told Rosales he was
going to make arrangements to get a truck so the couple could move
in with his parents in suburban Sylmar, police said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last Rosales knew of the whereabouts of her child
until late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police said Luna drove with the child to North Hills
in a desperate search for drugs. Out of money, the unemployed
27-year-old sold his food stamps and child restraint seats, leaving
his baby daughter unsecured in the back seat, Dragun said.
</P>
<P>
   Luna continued cruising the area police refer to as the suburban
San Fernando Valley's drug supermarket, reportedly looking for
money to buy more rock cocaine. ``When he got low, he desired
more,'' Dragun said.
</P>
<P>
   He met a stranger at a minimart at about 11 p.m. Sunday and
began talking about drugs, police said. ``They briefly talked and
agreed to go to another location to obtain drug paraphernalia,''
Dragun said.
</P>
<P>
   While Luna drove for about an hour, the baby lay in a blanket in
the back seat, without a child restraint device, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get any money, Luna asked the stranger to care for his
daughter for 15 minutes while he searched for rock cocaine, police
said. When the father did not return after 20 minutes, the stranger
called police, who later turned Bianca over to Child Protective
Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugs became more important to this individual than the
welfare of his own offspring,'' said Capt. Joe Curreri of the Los
Angeles Police Department's Devonshire Division.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rosales had filed missing-person reports after she
did not find her husband and daughter at her parents' home as
agreed earlier in the day, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She began a frantic search for her child and Mr. Luna,'' said
Detective Gary Barthelmess, who supervises the Devonshire
Division's major assault crimes unit.
</P>
<P>
   After the infant's face appeared on televised newscasts, a
neighbor of Rosales' parents recognized Bianca, police said.
Rosales confirmed with police that the baby is hers.
</P>
<P>
   When Luna was arrested, no drugs were found and he displayed no
obvious signs of being under the influence, Barthelmess said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosales and Luna also have a 3-year-old son, who was with Luna's
parents during the ordeal, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Children and Family Services is conducting an
investigation and will hold a dependency hearing later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the facts in this case and we are recommending that
this child be with her mother, (who) is going to live with
Grandma,'' said Schuyler Sprowles, a spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   Luna was being held at the Devonshire Division jail in lieu of
$50,000 bail on suspicion of child endangerment. But he also was
being held on no bail because of a nondrug-related parole hold from
a previous prison term, police said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
