<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-POSTNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART SAYS CLOSER LACKED HIS BEST PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 and 
JOE HAAKENSON 
San Gabriel Valley Tribune 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SAN DIEGO _ San Diego pitching coach Dave Stewart didn't like
the approach closer Trevor Hoffman was taking when he entered
Tuesday's game in the eighth-inning. The reason? Hoffman, who saved
53 games this year, couldn't throw his usually nasty changeup for
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The first batter Hoffman faced was Bernie Williams, who flied to
the wall in right. The second, Tino Martinez, walked. The third,
Scott Brosius, hit a game-winning two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't getting his changeup over, but he kept going to
it,'' said Stewart, who went to the mound just before the home run.
``To be successful, he has to work off his fastball. Everytime he
needed to get ahead, he went to the change and got burned.''
</P>
<P>
   The walk to Martinez was particularly painful to Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys (the Yankees) aren't going to swing at bad
pitches,'' Stewart said. ``They laid off the changeups in the dirt
(Hoffman) was so successful with this season. That is a mark of
their team. They never beat themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Pettitte hopes to clinch: Left-hander Andy Pettitte, bumped
from a scheduled Game 2 start due to recent struggles, is all set
to close out the Series tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will sleep great,'' Pettitte said. ``There is no reason to
have this go another game than we have to. And I want to be the one
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte will be facing the Padres' best in Kevin Brown, who
comes back on three days rest despite the flu. There is no reason
to hold him back.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte returned to the Yankees on Monday after spending a
couple days with his father, who underwent heart-bypass surgery
outside Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte struggled the last six weeks of the regular season,
pitched well in the division series against Texas, then was rocked
in Game 3 against Cleveland in the American League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   That game prompted manager Joe Torre to go with right-hander
Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez in Game 2. He allowed one run in
seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   During his time in Texas, Pettitte threw at his high school. He
also pitched off a mound during Monday's offday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Streaking Rivera: Yankees closer Mariano Rivera allowed
three hits in 12/3 innings but upped his scoreless innings streak
to 12 in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre doesn't like to bring in Rivera
to pitch in the eighth inning, but after Quilvio Veras doubled with
one out, Stottlemyre thought it was time even though left-handed
hitting Tony Gwynn was next.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually is better on left-handers,'' Stottlemyre said.
``His arm was strong and he was our best option. If we have to use
him tonight, I know he will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; No Bronx cheer: Padres owner John Moores made his first
visit to Yankee Stadium last weekend for Games 1 and 2 and came
away with mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little like a cathedral,'' he said. ``I went out and
looked at the monuments and got goose pimples and my eyes got
moist. At the same time, when your eyes clear you look around and
see that Yankee Stadium is not adequate. The aisles are too small,
it's hard to get around, the concessions are just awful. I think
(Yankees owner) George Steinbrenner badly understated the problem.
Unless there's massive redevelopment in the South Bronx, I could
see them relocating in Manhattan or New Jersey. I hope George gets
something done sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Election update: The citizens of San Diego who vote Nov. 3
will decide whether or not to pass Proposition C, which would allow
the Padres to build a downtown ballpark as part of a redevelopment
project in the city. But contrary to widespread belief, the
proposition does not call for the citizens to pay for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be no tax increase,'' said Padres president Larry
Lucchino. ``It's being done as a part of the downtown-redevelopment
project. It is a function of the completion of the project. By
transforming downtown San Diego, we create new revenue streams to
help finance the new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Home again: San Diego native Shane Spencer got the start in
left field for the Yankees over Chad Curtis on Tuesday, even though
Curtis was 5 for 12 against Sterling Hitchcock, the Padres' Game 3
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough not to put Chad Curtis in the lineup because he's
done so much for us in the last year and a half,'' Yankees manager
Joe Torre said. ``I just felt Shane was more of a power threat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
