<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-21 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ This is how the heroes of baseball often come to
October, jumping out from behind a tree or hiding around an
unexpected corner like one of the goblins who haunt the end of the
month at Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   You don't know who they are until they sneak up from behind and
tap you on the shoulder and make you jump right out of your skin.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes! Scott Brosius!
</P>
<P>
   He came to New York one year removed from the Yankees' most
recent World Series title and just months removed from the worst
year of his life in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He came to them from Oakland, a place that the writer Gertrude
Stein once summed up quite nicely by saying, ``There is no there,
there.'' And he came into a situation with the most famous team in
the game in the toughest town in which to play and knew there would
be no place there for him if he didn't quickly find a way to turn
it all around from the previous season, when he hit just .203.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know exactly what Scott Brosius was all about,''
admitted Yanks manager Joe Torre. ``He came into spring training,
and it was a time when we wanted to find out what was there. Could
he hit home runs? How was his defense?''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months later, what has been there is everything. As this
Yankees team that is already being called in some corners the
greatest ever has opened up a commanding 3-0 lead in the World
Series, it has been Brosius, back from the brink himself, who has
boosted them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night inside the rock 'n' roll fantasy land that is
blaring, jumping Qualcomm Stadium, he grabbed the microphone and
belted out the loudest song of them all, belting back-to-back home
runs in the seventh and eighth innings to carry the Yankees to a
5-4 win over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   So far in this series that is loaded with big-name Yankees
performers like Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams and Tino Martinez,
it is Brosius who has been the hammer pounding away on the Padres'
anvil.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius' 3-for-4 effort in Game 3 raised his World Series
batting average to .538. He is hitting a scorching .418 overall in
the postseason with 14 RBIs. And for a guy who didn't know if he
would even be able to earn a regular place on the team, you wonder
how the Yankees would even manage to get along without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a force,'' Torre said. ``Guys on this team may not
have known a lot about him. But now, they look up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only for the way Brosius has bounced back from his nightmare
season of a year ago, but for doing it while dealing with the
personal burden of knowing that his father, Maury, has been
fighting a battle with colon cancer, the same disease that has
sidelined celebrated teammate Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Through the long, brilliant season of the Yankees, Brosius
rarely talked about the situation at home, and during his rare
slumps at the plate, he never used it as an excuse. Of course,
there wasn't much need for excuses in a year when he rebounded to
hit .300 with 19 home runs and 98 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He played defense at third base with abandon, diving to gobble
up balls and reminding many in New York of former great Graig
Nettles. Jeter went so far as to call Brosius the Yankees' MVP this
season.
</P>
<P>
   And that was all before he got to October and really turned up
the heat. He has been hitting most everything thrown his way. He
launched a three-run homer off Charles Nagy in the third inning of
Game 6 in the ALCS that gave the Yankees a 6-0 lead and sent them
on to the Series. He made spectacular diving stops on the Indians'
Omar Vizquel and Enrique Wilson to preserve that final win.
</P>
<P>
   Now on baseball's biggest stage, Brosius has taken his game to
yet another level. There does not seem to be a member of the
Padres' pitching staff who can get him out.
</P>
<P>
   After their first two losses in New York, the Padres wistfully
talked about how things would be different if their wretched middle
relief pitching could somehow get them to their iron-fisted closer,
Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they got there in Game 3. But not before Brosius blasted a
fastball from Sterling Hitchcock over the center-field wall in the
top of the seventh. That came just moments after San Diego had
taken a 3-0 lead in the bottom of the sixth, and it was another
example of how New York keeps coming at you. The Yankees are
slipperier than eels in a bucket of Jell-O, and no lead is ever
safe. It was only 3-2 when Brosius came back to the plate in the
eighth after Paul O'Neill and Martinez had walked ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he was facing Hoffman, who had entered the game to
the sound of the mission bells ringing and to blaring screams of
AC/DC's Hell's Bells.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the bells tolled for Hoffman, who struggled with
his changeup and eventually delivered Brosius a 2-2 fastball. It
landed 424 feet away, over the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' Brosius said. ``This is the type of thing that
as a kid you dream about. As a kid in my back yard, I probably did
that 100 times in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was in the World Series and Maury, his father, now
recovering, had made the trip down from Oregon and was in the
stands to see his son take this night by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, when I hit .200, I didn't know what went wrong or
how I did that,'' he said. ``I've told people that I think it might
have been harder to actually hit .200 than to hit .300. Now, the
batting stroke seems to be back. I'm seeing the pitches and making
good swings. It's one of those things; it kind of snowballs.''
</P>
<P>
   A snowball named Scott Brosius who is becoming a part of October
lore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
