<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PARTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING SCOURS PRODUCTION LINES FOR POSSIBLE DEFECTIVE PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE
 &HT;     c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Already struggling to meet its year-end production
forecast and turn a profit after last year's financial disaster,
the Boeing Co. is scrambling to find possibly defective parts in
airplanes now in production, the Seattle Post-Intelligencer has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   No planes with suspect parts are in service, the company said.
Officials reached Tuesday night could not say how many planes in
production are affected.
</P>
<P>
   Except for classic model 737s, all Boeing airplanes in
production at Renton and Everett _ including those completed but
not yet delivered to customers _ are being inspected and the
suspect parts replaced when found.
</P>
<P>
   The part in question is called a ``Burndy block'' and serves as
a connection for various electrical wiring. It can be used to
transmit power voltage or as a ground.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Burndy blocks in a Boeing plane varies widely,
depending on the model. A 777, for example, has 380 Burndy blocks.
A 747 has only 10 and a 767 has six. But the next generation 737
has 570 Burndy blocks.
</P>
<P>
   In an internal communications that went to several Everett
managers last week, Kevin Gould a wiring manager, said, ``I think
we have a severe problem with several lots of bad Burndy blocks.
... I am alerting you because I think this could have some
widespread production implications.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview last night, Wolf Glende, Boeing's chief
engineer for 777 systems, said the problem has resulted only in a
production ``disruption.'' Many planes have already been inspected
and the suspect parts replaced, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not know how many planes must still be inspected.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued last night in response to questions about
the parts problem from the Post-Intelligencer, Boeing said no
airplanes with the suspect Burndy blocks have been delivered to any
of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The statement read, in part: ``The Boeing Commercial Airplane
Group has received a formal disclosure of a defective part from an
approved Boeing supplier. ... All suspect parts are contained
within our production system and our investigation to date
indicates no suspect parts have been delivered to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokeswoman Yvonne Leach said the company has not
experienced any late deliveries to customers as a result of having
to inspect planes and replace the suspect parts where necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that might result in Boeing not being able to meet its
delivery schedule would be a serious setback to the company's
ongoing efforts to fix its production woes and return to
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said it expects to deliver 550 airplanes this year,
but it has fallen behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   It delivered only 123 in the third quarter, about 14 fewer than
most analysts had expected. It delivered 368 planes in the first
nine months, including 137 in the second quarter. It will need to
deliver a record 61 planes a month for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will release its third-quarter earnings tomorrow morning,
and Chairman Phil Condit will give industry analysts and the media
a look behind the numbers at how well Boeing is is doing in meeting
its delivery schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Burndy blocks apparently was discovered
only in the last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing received a shipment of 18,000 of the blocks from its
sole-source supplier, and some of the parts failed testing in the
wiring shop before they were installed, Glende said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem involved cracking of a conductive plate inside the
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing later decided not to use any of the parts from the
suspect lot, but some had already been installed on planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of those 18,000, all have been quarantined,'' Glende said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Boeing is that it does not know which planes got
parts from the suspect shipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to inspect every plane to make sure parts from that
shipment were removed,'' Glende said. The first to be inspected, he
said, were those already out the factory door and undergoing flight
testing.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated it takes about about five hours to inspect a 777
with its 380 Burndy blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspection process has gone well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact so far is not that great. ... The key thing is that
each plane is scheduled to be inspected. We are going to inspect
every plane and pull out the parts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
