<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-21 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES' BEST IS NOT GOOD ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ To the San Diego Union-Tribune religion writer who
proposed that baseball and the Padres' success have ``saved us''
from the plagues of White House scandal and Wall Street collapse
and ``the horrors of genocide abroad'':
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but doomsday dawns at 5:20 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   To the storekeeper who was already advertising half-price Padres
merchandise Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   It's no time to get greedy.
</P>
<P>
   To Padres fans who waited 14 years for this:
</P>
<P>
   Hey, 2012 really isn't that far away to an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, did somebody really write that the Padres had a chance
to win the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   He must have assumed a lot of things would go right.
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is, Tuesday night EVERYTHING went right for the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   They got the pitchers' duel they wanted, the kind of game they
thought would favor them.
</P>
<P>
   They got the breaks that eluded them in New York.
</P>
<P>
   They got the ball to Trevor Hoffman with the lead in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are too good. They won 5-4 after Hoffman, the major
leagues' saves leader in the regular season, gave up Scott Brosius'
second home run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Padres are down 3-0 in the series. Wait 'till next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Devastating? somebody asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the least,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game,'' manager Bruce Bochy said, ``reaches in and grabs
your guts out.''
</P>
<P>
   This game was just what the Padres were hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   Not a slugfest like the 9-6 and 9-3 losses in New York. They
knew they couldn't hang with the Yankees in games like that.
</P>
<P>
   They believed they could win if one of their starting pitchers
could match one of the Yankees' starting pitchers long enough to
keep the ball out of the shaky hands of the Padres' middle
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't really been our starters,'' general manager Kevin
Towers had been saying near the batting cage, talking about the
defeats in New York. ``It's been the middle relief, the sixth,
seventh, eighth innings.''
</P>
<P>
   They turned to Sterling Hitchcock, who'd beaten Cy Young Award
winners Randy Johnson, Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine in the National
League playoffs, and asked him to beat Cy Young Award winner David
Cone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He did his part.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock delivered the game's first pitch at 5:22 amid the last
shafts of 72-degree sunlight. He needed barely 40 more minutes to
put himself in the upper echelon of Padres World Series pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   When he completed his third inning, having faced just nine
Yankees, Hitchcock had already done more than five of the seven
Padres to start World Series games before him, dating back to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock held the Yankees to a pair of singles through five
innings and stopped them with the bases loaded in the sixth,
battling just the way he'd learned by watching Cone when both were
Yankees a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was scoreless until the sixth, when the Padres made it 3-0
thanks to a Hitchcock base hit and a Yankees fundamental lapse.
</P>
<P>
   A hit by the pitcher. A Yankees blunder. Was everything going
San Diego's way or what?
</P>
<P>
   Count the breaks:
</P>
<P>
   __ Center fielder Steve Finley bobbles but catches Chuck
Knoblauch's leadoff blooper in the first inning _ catches it in his
lap while on his back.
</P>
<P>
   __ Yankee Paul O'Neill's hard one-hopper goes for a double play
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   __ Brosius' first swing of the game sends Finley to the
center-field wall in the second inning. Three more feet and it's
gone.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shortstop Chris Gomez is breaking to cover second base with
two Yankees runners going in the seventh, and Derek Jeter's
hit-and-run line drive goes right to him, causing Homer Bush to be
doubled off.
</P>
<P>
   This sure was different than New York, where an umpire missed a
strike call and the next pitch went for Tino Martinez's Game
1-breaking grand slam, where a Wally Joyner drive fell 18 inches
short of giving the Padres a 3-0 lead in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   This was one the Padres had to win and should have won.
</P>
<P>
   They had their fans, 64,667 of them, on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The fans got what they came to hear, AC/DC's ``Hell's Bells,''
Hoffman's anthem.
</P>
<P>
   He came in with O'Neill on first, representing the tying run,
and none out in the eighth. An out later, struggling with his
changeup, he walked Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one to Brosius, he bounced a slider, a pitch Hoffman
later called the pivotal one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That put him in a hitter's count,'' said Hoffman, calmly
facing questions at his locker 15 minutes after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Boom: Fastball up, and Brosius clears the 405-foot sign in dead
center, heavy night air and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was (just) a fly ball, to be honest with you,''
said Tony Gwynn, who watched from right field. ``You just don't see
too many guys go out to center field (at Qualcomm Stadium).''
</P>
<P>
   The world needs a new savior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
