u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-PADRES-YANKEES-BO     10-21 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PADRES-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS, YANKEES PUT PADRES IN DEEP HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ ``Hell's Bells''?
</P>
<P>
   For Scott Brosius and the New York Yankees, San Diego's
head-banging paean to closer Trevor Hoffman wound up sounding like
``Ode to Joy.''
</P>
<P>
   And after Brosius's crushing three-run homer off the San Diego
reliever in the eighth inning Tuesday night lifted the Yankees to a
5-4 win over the Padres _ and a 3-0 lead in the 94th World Series _
there was only one tune left to play before they turn out the
lights.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same one that's been on top of the charts since April,
an oldie but goodie. Some might even call this year's version the
best rendition of a classic ever.
</P>
<P>
   Start spreading the news ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't seen them in person, only on TV, but once you see
them firsthand, you see,'' said Tony Gwynn, the 38-year-old prince
of Padres, who may be watching his last, best chance at playing for
a World Series winner disappear in a pinstriped haze. ``Man,
they've got a great ball club. You can understand why they've won
so many games this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who have lost just twice in a dozen postseason
games, all but assured themselves of their 24th World Series title
by maintaining a champion's composure in a crucible of
knee-buckling intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Stoked by the cheers of 64,667 fans in Qualcomm Stadium urging
them to stave off extinction in the best-of-seven series, the
Padres seized a 3-0 lead in the sixth against Yankee starter David
Cone, who had a no-hitter through five until opposite number
Sterling Hitchcock singled after pitching out of a bases-loaded jam
in the top of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were no-hit for five innings, finally put a hit up on the
board, and get three runs,'' Gwynn said. ``It was ugly, but we'll
take it. But it still wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius led off the seventh against Hitchcock with a home run,
and the Yankees added another run on Shane Spencer's double, a
passed ball by Jim Leyritz, and third baseman Ken Caminiti's second
killing error in two games, making it 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   When the third San Diego pitcher, Randy Myers, walked Paul
O'Neill to open the eighth, the Padres went to Hoffman, who had 53
saves in the regular season and a win and three saves in the
postseason. Hoffman had been Tom Gordon, West Coast version, but
just like the Red Sox closer, he lost his aura of perfection when
the stakes were highest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the World Series. This isn't a good situation to come
out on the short end of the stick,'' said Hoffman, who several
times bounced his changeup, his best pitch, but refused to blame a
six-day layoff for his blowup. ``I could have saved this game and
tomorrow you all would be asking better questions.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bernie Williams flied to the warning track in right,
Hoffman walked Tino Martinez before Brosius hit a 3-and-2 fastball
over the 405-foot sign in center, his second home run of the game
and fourth of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shock?'' Gwynn said. ``It's never a shock. Anything can
happen in this game, and I've seen a lot of it firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep saying, `It can't happen,' but you see tonight. I've
said before there are no guarantees in this game. As good as
Hoffman has been, and he's been unbelievable, you see what can
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brosius had an unbelievable at-bat. That was a great piece of
hitting, and he hit a good pitch. And all you can do is tip your
cap to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Gwynn did. He took off the cap he was
wearing backward, tipped it to the absent Brosius, and put it back
on, bill forward.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius is batting .395 (17 for 43) with a team-leading 14 RBIs
in the postseason. That kind of performance, someone mentioned to
Brosius, puts him in the company of the Ruths and DiMaggios. Was he
enough of a student of history to realize that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enough of a student to know my name doesn't go there,'' he
said. ``It goes somewhere under there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Brosius sucked the air out of Mission Valley, the
Padres did not go gently into the night. With one out in the
eighth, Quilvio Veras doubled off Ramiro Mendoza, prompting Yankees
manager Joe Torre to go to his closer, Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, whose single _ plus a subsequent throwing error by
outfielder Paul O'Neill _ had fueled the Padres' three-run rally in
the sixth, blooped a hit to left that sent Veras to third, and Greg
Vaughn hit a drive to right that was caught by O'Neill but was deep
enough to score Veras.
</P>
<P>
   Singles by Carlos Hernandez and pinch hitter Mark Sweeney with
two outs in the ninth gave them a final chance. But Andy Sheets,
who had entered in the seventh inning as part of a double switch,
struck out to end it. John Vander Wal, the Padres' best pinch
hitter, had been used the inning before as a pinch runner for
Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. ``This game
reaches in and grabs your guts out. When you lose games like this,
sure, it's tough to take. But it's the hard part of this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is great, but losing, especially in the World Series,
it's tough. And now our backs are to the wall, we know that. The
only thing we can do is go and play our hearts out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
