<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS UNLIKELY HERO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The 64,667 fans sat in their seats like children who
had just been scolded.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Sad.
</P>
<P>
   Humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Excited and loud throughout most of Game 3 of the World Series
between the San Diego Padres and New York Yankees, the fans at
Qualcomm Stadium slumped to their seats in stunned disbelief after
Scott Brosius belted a three-run homer off Padres closer Trevor
Hoffman in the eighth inning to lift the Yankees to a 5-4 win and
three-games-to-none Series lead.
</P>
<P>
   No team in major league history has lost a seven-game series
after leading 3-0. Game 4 is tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius both started and finished the Yankees' comeback from a
3-0 deficit, homering off Padres starter Sterling Hitchcock to lead
off the seventh inning, then smacking Hoffman's 2-2 pitch over the
center-field wall with two baserunners aboard with one out in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius was asked after the game what it will be like having his
name alongside such Yankee greats as Babe Ruth and Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enough of a student of the game to know that my name
really doesn't go there,'' Brosius said with a smile. ``It's kind
of underneath somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to do anything particular,'' Brosius said of
his at-bat. ``Just get something to hit and see it for a long time
because I know how good his changeup is.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius got a good look at a fastball that Hoffman left up in
the strikezone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He crushed that ball,'' Yankees teammate Chili Davis said.
``You can hit home runs down the line in this place, but to hit it
to straight-away center, you've got to get all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Brosius was the hero Tuesday typifies the Yankees
season. He had 98 RBI during the regular season, hitting mostly in
the eighth spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back to the old Celtics, and you thought about all
those guys averaging 16, 18, 19 points a game, and they'd always
win as a team,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``But this
ballclub, they're going to take MVP votes away from each other.
They don't care who gets the winning hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman was stoic after the game and made no excuses. He said he
felt good. When told Brosius recalled facing him in the All-Star
game this season, Hoffman shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struck him out on a curveball,'' he said. ``I guess he got
his revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took a 3-0 lead against Yankees starter David Cone (6
innings, 3 runs, 2 earned, 2 hits) in the sixth after Cone had
pitched five hitless innings. But the Yankees responded in the top
of the seventh with two runs and trailed, 3-2, heading into the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Hamilton had relieved Hitchcock (6-plus innings, 2 runs, 1
earned, seven hits) and handed the ball over to Randy Myers to
start the eighth. Myers walked Paul O'Neill, prompting Padres
manager Bruce Bochy to summon Hoffman, who had not made an
appearance in the first two games of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams flied out to right, but Hoffman walked Tino
Martinez, setting the stage for Brosius, whose homer made it 5-3.
Hoffman, who saved 53 of 54 chances during the regular season, has
now blown two save opportunities in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say he did a good job with the pitch he got,''
Hoffman said. ``I won't say he hit my best pitch. I would have
liked to put it in a different spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres got to within 5-4 in the bottom of the eighth after
Quilvio Veras doubled and later scored on a sacrifice fly by Greg
Vaughn. In the ninth, the Padres got two-out singles by Carlos
Hernandez and Mark Sweeney. But with the tying run on third base,
Andy Sheets struck out to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down three games,'' Bochy said. ``The odds are against
us, and there's not much else to say but go out there and play your
hearts out. This club will do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
