<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8253 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-WHITESIDECOLUMN-B     10-21 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WHITESIDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE ALMOST CLOSED AFTER HOFFMAN BLOWS SAVE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ He spoke with his head held high. But the pain
raging inside San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman was obvious. He blew
the big one, and there is nobody to blame but himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was reminiscent of the Red Sox' Tom Gordon, who suffered a
similar fate in the American League Division Series. With San Diego
holding a 3-2 lead in the eighth inning Tuesday night, Hoffman
surrendered a three-run homer to the Yankees' Scott Brosius that
sent the Padres down to defeat, 5-4, and left them on the verge of
being swept in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pitch that you live and die with,'' said Hoffman of his
high fastball. ``It's gotten me a long way. So I'm not going to
overanalyze what happened. We played good baseball in Game 1 and we
played good baseball tonight. Once again, the bullpen just let the
team down. It was my turn tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger brother of former Red Sox shortstop Glenn Hoffman
had hoped to escape the curse that seems to follow anyone remotely
connected to Boston. He hadn't been needed in Games 1 or 2, which
the Padres lost, 9-6 and 9-3. He hadn't worked for six days but
took the ball from manager Bruce Bochy in the eighth inning
convinced that the layoff wouldn't make a difference. He had blown
only one save in 54 opportunities this season. All he had to do was
get six outs.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he did.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and a runner on first, he walked Tino Martinez. At
that point, he had a conversation with pitching coach Dave Stewart,
who had a simple message for him: Your changeup isn't working
because the Yankees are patient. Be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius hit a fastball over the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   New ball, please.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was a home run at first,'' said Hoffman.
``But it had that certain crack off the bat. He hit it well. The
pitch was up in the zone. And he drove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and say it was a bad pitch or a
mistake. He did a good job of hitting in that situation. He made
something happen. I would have liked to have it down and away more,
but it wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Hoffman stood his ground while wave after wave of
reporters asked essentially the same questions. His answers were
consistent, as were those of Bochy, who chided those who suggested
he panicked by bringing Hoffman in an inning early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a case of too much rest,'' said Hoffman. ``I warmed
up plenty in the bullpen. I used my changeup, but it wasn't very
good tonight. Unfortunately, it was Game 3 of the World Series, and
people will remember this for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to hang my head. It takes a lot of work to get
in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy said he wanted to use lefthander Randy Myers against the
two lefthanders who were coming up _ Paul O'Neill and Martinez. But
a walk by O'Neill forced his hand. The call went for Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone this long without pitching before,'' said Bochy.
``We'd talked before and he said he'd rather come in to pitch in
his regular situation. Afterward, it was obvious that he didn't
have his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only human. But in a game like this, you had to win. This
was a huge game for us, and it just got away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said a quick visit to the mound does not guarantee that
the pitcher will make the necessary correction. Hoffman did try to
be aggressive, but his location was off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes with relief pitching,'' said Stewart. ``The Yankees
are a team of patient hitters. The thing that hurt us as much as
the home run was the walk by Myers. That's what made us bring in
Hoffman when we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this mean we've lost confidence in the bullpen? On the
contrary. I still have confidence in the guys who brought us to the
dance. We've got one dance left. We can't worry about coming back
from three down. We've got to worry about winning one game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-HNS &LR;      10-21 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN DIEGO _ The San Diego Padres are not quite done, but they're a
little brown on both sides, and it has nothing to do with the sun.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Yankees poured rain on San Diego's biggest baseball
day in 14 years, and one particular raindrop kept falling on their
heads. There was plenty of thunder in Scott Brosius' bat, not to
mention the lightning bolt that struck down the Padres in the
eighth inning of Game 3 of the World Series on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius' second homer of the game _ a three-run blast to center
field off Trevor Hoffman _ propelled the Yankees to a 5-4
come-from-behind win over the Padres before a stunned crowd of
64,667 at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of thing you dream about as a kid,'' Brosius
said. ``That's something I've done a hundred times in my back yard.
You never know if you're going to get the opportunity to do
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees increased their lead to 3-0 in the best-of-seven
series and can wrap up their second World Series title in three
years tonight. There hasn't been a sweep in the World Series since
Cincinnati beat Oakland in 1990. Andy Pettitte will start for the
Yankees; the Padres plan to pitch ace Kevin Brown on three days'
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win now,'' Padres right fielder Tony Gwynn said.
``There are no ifs, ands or buts about it. Our backs are against
the wall, and all of you guys (the media) are writing us off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have an explanation for why we haven't been
able to win a game other than the Yankees have just outexecuted us.
If (Yankees manager) Joe Torre had made a list of all the things he
wanted to see his team do before the World Series started, they
would be doing everything on that list. Those guys have done
everything they've needed to do to win these three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, who is hitting .538 in the World Series, was 3-for-4
and drove in four of the Yankees' runs. Mariano Rivera pitched the
final 1 innings for his second save of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Sterling Hitchcock held his ground against a mound
opponent with Cy Young credentials. He locked up with David Cone
and left with a lead in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock's gritty effort wasn't enough to get his team a
win. The Padres had been waiting for a chance to use Hoffman, who
hadn't pitched in six days. But this was hardly the way they
imagined his first World Series appearance would unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman has converted 80 of his past 82 regular-season save
chances. But Tuesday, he was no more productive than any of his
relief mates have been in the Series. The Padres' bullpen, which
posted a 3.49 ERA during the regular season, has allowed 10 earned
runs in 11 innings in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to get outs, and I didn't do it,'' Hoffman said. ``I
didn't get the pitch (to Brosius) where I wanted it, and it cost us
the game. I didn't do my job. But give Brosius credit _ he put the
bat on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who singled to lead off the sixth, got a hit before any
Padre did. Chuck Knoblauch moved Cone to second with a bunt single
before Hitchcock struck out Derek Jeter for the first out of the
inning. Paul O'Neill singled up the middle, but third-base coach
Willie Randolph held Cone at third. Hitchcock struck out Bernie
Williams and got Tino Martinez to pop out to second to end the
Yankees' first scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real gutsy job of pitching by Hitchcock,'' Padres
manager Bruce Bochy said. ``He's done a good job for us throughout
the postseason, and he pitched another good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock broke up Cone's no-hit bid with a leadoff single in
the bottom of the sixth. After Cone walked Quilvio Veras, Gwynn
singled through the right side of the infield, scoring Hitchcock
from second. O'Neill's errant throw from right field cut across the
infield and into the Yankees' dugout, allowing Veras to score and
Gwynn to take third. Gwynn scored on Ken Caminiti's sacrifice fly
to the warning track in center field to give the Padres a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a dominating performance for me,'' Cone said. ``I
just made enough good pitches at the right time to get through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps all the running took a toll on Hitchcock, who served up
a leadoff homer to Brosius in the seventh. Shane Spencer followed
with a double, prompting Bochy to motion Joey Hamilton in from the
bullpen. Spencer moved to third on a passed ball and scored when
pinch hitter Chili Davis' grounder to third rolled under Caminiti's
glove.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and runners on first and third, the inning looked
promising for the Yankees. But Padres shortstop Chris Gomez made a
fantastic leaping catch on a line drive by Jeter and flipped to
second base for an easy double play.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthanded reliever Randy Myers opened the eighth inning for the
Padres and walked O'Neill before Hoffman entered. Williams flied
out and Martinez walked to set the stage for the biggest hit of
Brosius' career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like that all season long,'' Jeter said. ``If we've
got a runner on base, he (Brosius) is a tough guy to get out. He
gets big hits all the time. We have a very resilient team. We don't
think we've lost until we've made our 27th out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres pulled to within a run on Greg Vaughn's sacrifice fly
in the eighth, and they had runners on the corners in the final
inning, but Rivera struck out Andy Sheets to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game reaches in and grabs your guts out,'' Bochy said.
``Winning is great, but losing _ especially in the World Series _
is tough. The only thing we can do is play our hearts out
(tonight), and I know this team will do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
