<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      10-21 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET SCOUTING REPORTS; YANKS SHOW NO WEAK LINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ As a team partial to palm trees and a warm breeze,
the Padres' take on the first two games of the World Series was
that New York was a mean, icky place.
</P>
<P>
   Not a scoop, really. But the excuse is a lot easier to deal with
than the aggravating reality of the greatness of the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Like a bunch of California tourists trembling in their first
visit to the Bad Apple, the Padres wrote off the pair of weekend
losses as a freakish scene awkward to the uninitiated and unlikely
to be duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about going home and playing in front of the home
folks,'' said Padres All-Star Tony Gwynn before the game. ``I can't
remember being called so many different names out in right field.''
</P>
<P>
   Added teammate Ken Caminiti: ``It's definitely a hard crowd. It
will be kind of nice to get away from, `Caminiti, you suck,' every
few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rude, yes. But it is hard to fault the accuracy of the New York
fans regarding Caminiti, the Padres' cleanup hitter who in Game 3
Tuesday night delivered only a sacrifice fly and made two errors.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Gwynn's claim of virtue in playing in front of the
home folks, well, the song lyrics don't say, ``If I can make it in
San Diego, I can make it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres aren't making it, here or in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who would against these Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   At least the Padres made it close. If you could have heard the
sound that 64,667 fans at Qualcomm Stadium made with their their
hands over their mouths, you would know how much being close was
worth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks' 5-4 victory in Game 3 was as close as the series 3-0
gap is wide. Just to prove that they can win in ways no team can
scout for, the lineup's lowest-profile guy, veteran third baseman
Scott Brosius, the pride of Oregon's Linfield College, came up
Ruthian.
</P>
<P>
   His two home runs, four RBIs and .538 Series batting average are
merely the latest bits of evidence that the Yankees are a complete
team of quality players that doesn't require a massive, Reggie
Jackson-sized ego to stir their drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all want to get the winning hit, but they don't really
want to talk about it,'' said Yankee manager Joe Torre. ``In all my
years in baseball, it's a very unusual club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back to the old Celtics, you go though about all those
guys averaging 16, 18, 19 points a game, and they'd always win
games as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The pre-game contention was that if the Padres could just get
some quality innings from a starting pitcher, matters would turn.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Hitchcock provided, going six shutout innings to slow a
team that had scored nine runs in each of its last three playoff
games. He was the first left-hander the Yankees had faced in the
postseason, and every bit the stud he was in earlier playoff
matchups against Randy Johnson, Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Once called a ``fat boy'' by his first baseball boss, Yankee
owner George Steinbrenner, Hitchcock had the privilege of letting
his play say, ``Eat this.''
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Mariner-turned-good even had the audacity to break up the
no-hitter of his counterpart, David Cone, with a sixth-inning
single, offering one of the most articulate arguments against the
designated-hitter rule.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's primary task was to get a lead to Trevor Hoffman,
saver of 53 of 54 regular-season chances and perhaps the National
League's premier pitcher this season. Deed done, even if Hitchcock
did surrender Brosius' first home run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Padres' most formidable strength that came
up weak. Against his third batter in the eighth, Hoffman was first
in the dirt against Brosius, then fat over the middle of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent three-run homer and 5-3 lead can't be blamed on
the flu, or bellicose fans, or Yankee history or any of the other
pre-Halloween goblins the Padres have offered up to explain how
their otherwise magnificent season has been stopped cold.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of creating at least a hotfoot for the Yankees, one
swing relegated the Padres to a mere footnote in one of the great
single-season achievements in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of thing that as a kid you dream about,''
Brosius said after he fried the Friars. ``It's something I've done
in my backyard a hundred times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know if you're going to get the opportunity to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no one in the baseball universe would have envisioned
Brosius as even having an opportunity, much less exploiting it. He
hit .203 last year for the wretched Oakland A's, yet the Yankees
offered up for him lefty pitcher Kenny Rogers and cash last
December.
</P>
<P>
   As a team whose success is frequently ascribed to unlimited
funds, the Brosius acquisition is an example of talent shrewdness
and development that has no source in cash. As a Yankee, he hit
.300 and was named an All-Star for the first time. Barring a highly
improbable Yankee collapse, he seems destined to be the Series'
most valuable player, an honor unique _ this is said without
research, yet with no fear of contradiction _ for a resident of
McMinnville, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   He even comes with his own personal-drama story _ his father,
Maury, flew in from Oregon yesterday after surviving a bout with
colon cancer, to witness his son become a Yankee World Series hero.
</P>
<P>
   One more story like this, and the Yankees graduate from a sports
team to a force of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
