<HEADER>
A8277 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-SPI &LR;      10-21 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES STUN PADRES FOR 3-0 LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Even the most automatic game-saver in the National
League during the regular season could not prevent the World Series
from taking a giant step closer to a four-and-over washout for the
San Diego Padres Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   They are a team gone overboard.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning eighth-inning at-bat that gave a loud Qualcomm
Stadium crowd instant laryngitis, Scott Brosius reversed a Trevor
Hoffman fastball and rocketed it over the center-field fence for a
game-deciding, three-run homer as the New York Yankees shocked the
Padres 5-4 before 64,667 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been the best team in the major leagues all
season and are on the verge of their second sweep this postseason.
One more win clinches the franchise's 24th World Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are on life-support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the history of the teams who were down three games to
none,'' San Diego right fielder Tony Gwynn said. ``No one has ever
come back from being three games down and won, but we can either
roll over or come out fighting. I plan to come out fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   But you have to wonder how much fight is left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game reaches in and grabs your guts out,'' Padres manager
Bruce Bochy said. ``When you lose games like this, sure it's tough
to take.''
</P>
<P>
   With better relief pitching, the Padres would be up 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   They blew a three-run, seventh-inning lead and lost Game 1
without getting to Hoffman. But when they turned to their save
master with a one-run lead and a runner on base in the eighth
inning Tuesday night, the automatic switch seemed to be turned on.
</P>
<P>
   Though he hadn't pitched in six days, Hoffman said he felt
great.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling turned sour in a New York minute.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring Bernie Williams on a fly ball that drove Gwynn to
the fence, the command Hoffman almost always had when he saved 53
regular-season games in 54 opportunities deserted him. He bounced
pitches into the dirt. His fastball, usually in the low 90s, peaked
at 89 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander walked Tino Martinez, putting the go-ahead run
on base, and two pitches after bouncing another ball in the dirt,
this time with Brosius batting, Hoffman fired a fastball that had
more zip going out than coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1-and-1 pitch that I threw about 50 feet bothers me more
than the pitch he hit out,'' Hoffman said. ``That put him in a
hitter's count.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius fouled off one pitch, then clobbered the next one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to do anything in particular,'' said the
Yankee third baseman, who became only the third player this season
to hit a home run off Hoffman. ``Against Trevor, I was just looking
to try to get something to hit. Because of his changeup and how
good it is, I didn't want to jump out and spin off the ball. So I
was really just thinking, `Stay up the middle with him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The home run gave New York a two-run lead, and three Yankee
relievers maintained the cushion despite allowing a run in the
bottom of the eighth on Greg Vaughn's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres threatened in the bottom of the ninth, putting
runners on first and third bases before Mariano Rivera struck out
former Mariner Andy Sheets for the game-ender.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 19th time in history that a team has grabbed a 3-0
lead. Fifteen of those Series ended in a sweep. Only three teams
have forced a Game 5, and they were eliminated in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will just give it our all, that's all we can do now,''
Bochy said. ``The odds are against us, and there's not much else to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy and the Padres got the kind of starting pitching from
Sterling Hitchcock that they needed to win Game 3. The left-handed
postseason star was superb, holding the Yankees scoreless through
the sixth inning and escaping a bases-loaded, none-out mess in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   He was surprising with the bat.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Mariner broke up David Cone's no-hitter with a leadoff
single in the bottom of the sixth and scored the game's first run
as the Padres took a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Quilvio Veras walked, Gwynn lined a run-scoring single to
right field, and Veras also scored when Paul O'Neill uncorked a
wild throw to the plate, missing the cutoff man and catcher Joe
Girardi. Gwynn reached third base on the errant toss and scored on
Ken Caminiti's long fly ball to center.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees retaliated immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, who hit 19 homers during the regular season, led off
the seventh inning with a towering drive into the seats in
left-center field ib a full-count pitch, and Shane Spener doubled
into the left-center field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   A passed ball and Caminiti's second error of the Series cut San
Diego's lead to a run before Derek Jeter lined into an
inning-ending double play to shortstop Chris Gomez, who leaped high
to deflect the ball, grabbed it on the rebound and doubled
pinch-runner Homer Bush off second base.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the scantest of leads, when Bochy handed the ball to
Hoffman, almost everyone in the park, and probably a few in New
York, felt this game was history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anytime it doesn't work out with Trevor on the mound,
sure you're surprised,'' Bochy said. ``But he's human. The guy has
had a tremendous year, and I'll take my chances with him out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But there aren't many chances left. Maybe only one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
