<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8278 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-SFCHR     10-21 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT FIGHTS BACK WITH DEFENSE OF CHAIRMAN GATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Microsoft blasted the Justice Department's
antitrust charges Tuesday as an effort to ``demonize'' its
chairman, Bill Gates, and charged that rival Netscape
Communications elected to seek refuge in a government lawsuit
rather than compete for consumers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the second day of the momentous antitrust trial of the
software giant, lead Microsoft litigator John Warden described the
company as a tough but fair competitor that spends $3 billion a
year on research to maintain its edge.
</P>
<P>
   Warden belittled the government's case as ``long on rhetoric and
short on substance'' and chastised the Justice Department for its
focus on Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A personal attack on a man whose vision and innovation have
been at the core of the benefits that people are reaping from the
Information Age is no substitute for proof of anticompetitive
conduct and anticompetitive effects,'' Warden said in his opening
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Warden also began his cross-examination of the Justice
Department's key witness, Netscape chief executive officer Jim
Barksdale, arguing that Netscape itself once had a monopoly on
Internet browsers _ it held 90 percent of the browser market in
1995 _ and that the company instigated the government's
investigation when it saw its own dominance threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence will show that the government's charges turn
antitrust law on its head,'' Warden said. With deep sarcasm, he
added, ``Netscape had what the government would consider a monopoly
in the market for Internet browsers until the great Satan,
Microsoft, came along.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft trial is the biggest monopoly case since the
breakup of AT&AMP;T and could shape not only the future of Silicon
Valley and the high-tech industry, but the lives of millions of
consumers who increasingly rely on computers and the Internet in
their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   The government accuses Microsoft of illegally exploiting its
dominant Windows computer operating system to promote its own
products, particularly its Internet Explorer browser, and kill off
competitors like Netscape's Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Warden said the core of the government's case _ that Microsoft
``bundled'' Internet Explorer for free with Windows to drive out
Netscape _ amounts to ``semantic games.'' He said Internet Explorer
is ``not an add-on, like a flash on a camera or a car radio,'' but
an integral part of Windows, like ``a shutter on a camera or a
car's transmission.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Ordinary consumers who buy personal computers at Wal-Mart
have no interest in piecing together an operating system from a
grab bag of separately marketed components,'' Warden said.
``Consumers want their new machine to come out of the box and just
work, and our position is that it's our right to provide consumers
what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale calmly took the stand after submitting his written
testimony, often taking long deliberative pauses, parrying with
Warden and making wry jests.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Barksdale conceded that Netscape had
hired Palo Alto attorney Gary Reback in the spring of 1995 and that
Reback had provided what Warden called a ``detailed chronology of
Microsoft's dealings with Netscape'' to the Justice Department by
July of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Warden introduced an internal Netscape memo titled ``The
Situation'' that said the ``DOJ (Department of Justice) and court
actions create opportunity for Netscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the statement, Barksdale replied that the government
antitrust action was ``a way of protecting an opportunity we had
all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden and Barksdale sparred over one of Netscape's key
accusations: that Microsoft bullied computer giant Compaq Computer
into dropping Navigator and adding Internet Explorer to its
machines by threatening to cancel Compaq's license to use Windows.
Losing Windows would effectively destroy any computer maker's
market.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale said Netscape ``learned that Compaq no longer intended
to put Navigator on the desktop shortly after Microsoft threatened
to cancel Compaq's Windows license.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden asked whether Microsoft threatened to withdraw its
license because Compaq wanted to remove Internet Explorer from
Windows _ and not because Compaq simply wanted to add Navigator.
Barksdale replied, ``as an original statement, that would probably
be correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden asked Barksdale whether he had ``any basis whatsoever''
for suggesting that Microsoft threatened to cancel the license with
Compaq because the company included Navigator, and Barksdale
replied, ``No, that's not what I say here.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, lead government attorney David Boies said Barksdale
did not back off his testimony on Compaq, but ``said exactly what
he said in his statement. . . . The witness said all along that
Compaq tried to substitute Navigator for Internet Explorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray insisted that the Compaq dispute highlights ``a
fundamental point. . . . Microsoft never attempted to withhold
Windows from Compaq or any computer manufacturer if it wanted to
ship Navigator.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden painted Netscape as a ``ward'' of the government that
chose to turn to the Justice Department to save its market share.
</P>
<P>
   Warden also suggested that the government is applying two
different rules, one for Microsoft and another for everyone else.
To make his point, he noted that Netscape added features demanded
by customers, such as e-mail, even if it drove stand-alone products
made by other companies off the market. Drawing the comparison to
Microsoft, Warden said the software giant created and marketed its
browser because it was ``forced to respond to competitive
challenges. The government cannot seriously come to this court and
contend that Microsoft should have its hands tied behind its back,
unable to respond to changes in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   In his written testimony, Barksdale credited Netscape co-founder
Marc Andreessen and a team of colleagues with inventing a
user-friendly Internet browser in 1993 while at the University of
Illinois National Center for Supercomputing Applications. Barksdale
said Netscape's commercialization of the browser set off the
Internet boom.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale suggested that ``had Netscape not been willing and
strong enough to look Microsoft in the eye and bring the browser to
market, we would not have browsers (or anything like browsers) in
the marketplace at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden ridiculed that assertion. ``You don't really believe that
but for Netscape, Web browsing wouldn't exist,'' Warden asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that from the bottom of my heart,'' Barksdale
retorted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
