 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 407 - October 21, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 407 -- Oct. 21, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. DANCING IN HITLER'S SHADOW It's as unlikely an Oscar
candidate as they come : A comedy set in a German concentration
camp, written by, directed by and starring an Italian comedian. But
Roberto Benigni's ``Life is Beautiful'' has beaten the odds,
winning the Grand Prize at the Cannes Film Festival and is touted
for Oscar consideration. In this interview Benigni talks about the
new movie, why he doesn't worry that it will be taken in bad taste,
how Holocaust survivors have received the film and how his father's
grimly humorous tales of prison-camp life during World War II
provided the seeds for the film. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words +
photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
FACE VALUE: CAMP HUMOR - ROBERTO BENIGNI Artist Ricardo Castaneda
offers an intriguing cartoon of Roberto Benigni in ``Life is
Beautiful,'' his unique concentration camp comedy.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
THE FUNNIEST ITALIAN YOU'VE PROBABLY NEVER HEARD OF Roberto Benigni
is Italy's Robin Williams, but he has never caught on big in
America. Maybe his new comedy, ``La Vita Bella'' (Life Is
Beautiful) set during the Holocaust, will do the trick. It is
already being mentioned as a prime candidate for Best Foreign Film
in the Academy Awards. By Alessandra Stanley. New York Times
Magazine. Full-length (3,100 words) + edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
WELLES AND THE 'WAR OF THE WORLDS' It was 60 years ago this month
that the world's most influential radio broadcast first aired :
Orson Welles' Mercury Theatre production of ``The War of the
Worlds.'' People panicked, believing that Martians were actually
invading Earth. This article examines the broadcast's impact and
discusses its effect on Welles' first film, ``Citizen Kane.'' By
Lige Rushing. From Diversion magazine. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
THE NOT-SO-SECRET LIFE OF PETER GALLAGHER Peter Gallagher has
appeared in a lot of hit movies - ``Sex, lies and videotape''
(1989,) ``The Player'' (1992,) ``While you Were Sleeping'' (1995) -
but he insists that his new TV series, ``The Secret Lives of Men,''
(about divorced men in Manhattan) is the most fun he's ever had. In
this interview Gallagher talks about the new show, why grim
subjects such as divorce make for the best comedies, and why men
will say things to one another on a golf course that they would
never tell the women in their lives. By Stephen Cole. From Canadian
TV Guide. 1,100 words + photo. 6. OPRAH GOES FOR THE OSCAR GOLD
Oprah Winfrey struggled for 10 years to bring ``Beloved,'' (the
Toni Morrison story about slavery) to the screen. In the process,
she says, she discovered ``the real meaning of life.'' By Ivor
Davis. 1,000 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.)
____________________________________________________________ 7.
JAMES WOODS, VAMPIRE FIGHTER James Woods has played heroes,
villains, lovers and lawyers, but in John Crow, the sardonic
vampire fighter in ``John Carpenter's Vampires,'' he says he has
found one of the most enjoyable roles of his career. The film is a
cross between a Western and a horror film and Crow is ``the baddest
guy ever.'' Woods talks about the film, colleagues such as Clint
Eastwood and Oliver Stone, why he is as quick to do TV movies or
quirky independent films as he is to do Hollywood blockbusters, and
why ``Hercules'' may be the most mportant film he ever made. By Ian
Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
TURN TV INTO A POSITIVE INFLUENCE For most people, television is a
big part of family life. Here is advice on how to make it a more
positive influence in the home. By Kathy Sena. 900 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
HOLLYWOOD'S APT PUPIL Bryan Singer directed the crime thriller
``The Usual Suspects.'' Following the success of that film, the
young director found himself travelling in Hollywood's highest
circles. But finishing his next movie proved anything but easy. In
``Apt Pupil,'' based on the novella by Stephen King, an American
teenager discovers that his next-door neighbour is a notorious
former Nazi. The film, starring Sir Ian McKellan, has become almost
as controversial as its subject. ``The movie is about the
pervasiveness of evil and corruption,'' says Singer. By Joshua
Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
THE DEVIL AND DEREK JACOBI Francis Bacon, one of the greatest
artists of the 20th century, led a life almost as harrowing as his
dark and violent paintings. In ``Love Is The Devil,'' Sir Derek
Jacobi gives a phenomenal performance as Bacon. The film focuses on
Bacon's long-term, often destructive relationship with his male
lover, the subject of his most famous paintings. To play Bacon,
Jacobi says he employed the same acting technique he would use to
portray Shakespeare's Richard III, as they both had a streak of
cruelty. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo.
