<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLD-SERIES-GAME-3-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CLOSE IN ON CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. Sullivan 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The San Diego Padres aren't eliminated, but they
have nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   There are no weapons unused or bullets unfired. Manager Bruce
Bochy has tried everything, but the New York Yankees have taken the
Padres best shots, scoffed at the Padres and just kept on trouncing
their hopelessly outclassed National League opponent.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was Trevor Hoffman, who was almost as invincible as
a reliever in the National League as the Yankees were as a team in
the other league. Bochy brought his All-Star closer into the game
in the eighth inning to protect a 3-2 lead, but, just like almost
every move he has made in the World Series, it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hoffman gave up a three-run homer to Scott Brosius that
carried the Yankees to a 5-4 victory against the Padres in Game 3.
A Qualcomm Stadium crowd of 64,667, whose screams reached
bloodcurdling levels when Hoffman trotted in from the bullpen to
the heavy metal sounds of ``Hells Bells'', left heartbroken as the
Padres fell behind three games to none.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius also led off the seventh with a home run, which
kick-started the Yankees' offense and allowed them to overcome the
Padres' 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of thing you dream of as a kid,'' Brosius
said. ``It's something I've done 100 times in my backyard as a
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres will send Kevin Brown to the mound for Game 4
tonight, but, as they remember after winning the first three games
of the NL Championship Series against Atlanta, no team in
major-league history has come back from a 3-0 deficit to win a
best-of-seven playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   It would take an immediate and total collapse by a team that won
a league-record 114 games in the regular season and 10 of 12 games
in postseason. More likely scenarios would seem to include the
Yankees moving to Vermont, owner George Steinbrenner moving toward
total revenue sharing or the Dodgers moving back to Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we have to face,'' Hoffman said. ``We just
have to pick it back up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres thought they had done that when they broke up a
scoreless pitchers' duel between Sterling Hitchcock and Yankees
starter David Cone with a three-run outburst in the sixth.
Hitchcock started the rally with a single to right, breaking up
Cone's five-inning no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees came back in the seventh when Brosius led off
with a homer to left-center and Shane Spencer doubled. Bochy
brought in Joey Hamilton to pitch, but Spencer, who moved to third
on catcher Jim Leyritz's passed ball, scored on third baseman Ken
Caminiti's error on pinch hitter Chili Davis' grounder.
</P>
<P>
   That set up the dramatic events of the eighth, an inning that
started with Padres reliever Randy Myers walking Paul O'Neill.
Bochy then brought in Hoffman, who was making his first appearance
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman got Bernie Williams to fly out, but Tino Martinez walked
to bring up Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not something I wanted to do, but I put myself
in a hole by not making quality pitches,'' Hoffman said. ``I paid
for it. What's so disappointing is the team battled so hard. We had
a lead, and I didn't do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment of truth was a 2-2 fastball that Brosius crushed over
the center-field fence, giving the Yankees a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the clubhouse icing my arm and I jumped so high I
almost went through the roof,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only thing was trying to pick the ball up,'' Brosius said.
``I wanted to see him \RHoffman\S as good as I could and get a good
swing on the ball. As it was, it was a fastball over the plate, and
I hit it hard in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres made a valiant effort to come back, getting one run
in the eighth when Quilvio Veras doubled, then later scored on Greg
Vaughn's sacrifice fly. They also had runners at first and third
with two outs in the ninth before Mariano Rivera closed it out by
striking out Andy Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Padres' best chance, but against the best team in
baseball, nothing has worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
