r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DASH-FOR-CASH-TEX     10-21 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DASH-FOR-CASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF THE RIDE: QUARTER HORSE'S OFFSPRING STILL DASHING FOR
CASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Legendary quarter-horse breeder B. F. Phillips Jr. knew it from
the start. Moments after the newborn foal hit the ground on April
17, 1973, at Phillips Ranch in Frisco, he went into the house and
informed his wife that he had witnessed the birth of a special
horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no question he was going to be a great horse,''
Phillips later said. ``There was no mistaking him.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he strutted his stuff on the track, Dash For Cash made
believers of everyone else. And after he was retired to the
breeding shed, his reputation only grew.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it is fitting that Dash For Cash was foaled only
weeks before Secretariat began his famed sweep of thoroughbred
racing's Triple Crown. In the world of quarter-horse racing, Dash
For Cash's legacy has surpassed even that of his thoroughbred
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   At Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie, that legacy is honored this
week with two races in his name: The Dash For Cash Derby for
3-year-olds Friday and the Dash For Cash Futurity for 2-year-olds
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dash For Cash died May 20, 1996, but his presence is clearly
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Six of 10 qualifiers for the Dash For Cash Futurity are his
great-grandsons. The Derby field includes five grandsons or
great-grandsons. One Derby qualifer, Four Six Dash, is his son,
from his next-to-last crop of offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Dash For Cash ``was the best runner I've seen,'' said his
trainer, C. W. ``Bubba'' Cascio of Weatherford. ``And he's
obviously the best sire ever, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As a racehorse, Dash For Cash won 21 of his 25 starts, finishing
second three times.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only horse to twice win the Champion of Champions _ an
important December race at Los Alamitos near Los Angeles. He was
voted world champion in 1976 and 1977, and was the first quarter
horse to earn $500,000 without benefit of victories in the rich
All-American Futurity or All-American Derby at Ruidoso Downs in New
Mexico. ``The thing I remember most about him is that I didn't have
to sweat many photo finishes,'' Cascio said. ``He beat good horses
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Cascio said Dash For Cash's stride was measured at 32 feet,
among the longest ever recorded. And like most champion horses, his
stride appeared fluid and effortless.
</P>
<P>
   Another ingredient in his success as a runner _ and later as a
sire _ was his temperament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got into the gate, he'd stand there and never move,''
Cascio said. ``He'd never bat an eye. You'd think the horse was not
gonna break, and then he'd explode.''
</P>
<P>
   With his career winding down in the fall of 1977 while residing
in the Southern California barn of then-quarter-horse trainer D.
Wayne Lukas, Dash For Cash was syndicated for stud duty for $2.5
million. Forty shares were sold for $62,500 each, with two
breedings allowed per share.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who died in 1987, set the price-per-share over dinner
one evening, and asked Cascio how well the shares might sell. When
Phillips visited Cascio's barn at 11 a.m. the next morning, the
answer was clear: Cascio already had a dozen signed contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Dash For Cash's first crop was a test breeding of fewer than two
dozen mares, and the results were conclusive. One became a
champion, a second was a major stakes winner, and several others
were talented runners.
</P>
<P>
   Dash For Cash quickly become such a hot commodity that ownership
of a single breeding share became as valued as Wal-Mart stock.
Within a few years, one of the shares was sold for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, Cascio brokered a deal in which California
quarter-horse breeder Liston Aluminum Brick Company wanted to buy a
breeding share. Cascio found a seller, but told the Liston
representative that the asking price was an unheard-of $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cascio, the immediate response was, ``Who do I make
the check out to?''
</P>
<P>
   That selling price for a single quarter-horse breeding share,
Cascio said, ``is a record that will never be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Such financial support proved justified.
</P>
<P>
   Dash For Cash has sired five world champions, and 17 divisional
champions that collected a total of 39 titles. One of his
daughters, Dash For Speed, co-owned by Bob Blakemon of Fort Worth,
took seven titles.
</P>
<P>
   Cascio later trained one of Dash For Cash's daughters,
Dashingly, who earned $1.7 million and won 21 of 24 starts. She is
the only quarter horse to earn a million dollars without winning
one of the All-American races.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20 all-time leading money-winning quarter horses before
the 1998 season, seven are sons of Dash For Cash and another is a
grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Further down that list at No. 33 is First Down Dash, a son of
Dash For Cash who won 13 of 15 starts and became the pre-eminent
sire of the 1990s. Now 14, First Down Dash is the primary flag
carrier for the Dash For Cash bloodlines. He has sired five
All-American Futurity winners from only eight crops of offspring.
Five of the top 20 sires of 1997 are his sons, and last year's
world champion SLM Big Daddy is his grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after his birth, Dash For Cash's family tree
has so many branches that on any given day, numerous runners with
``Dash'' and ``Cash'' in their names are seen at quarter-horse
tracks around the country.
</P>
<P>
   And that is one trend that won't soon be changing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-     10-21 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRETT'S EXPLOITS SHOULDN'T BE EDITED OUT OF SEASON'S FINAL REEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The eighth week is the natural midpoint of an NFL season. And
with the Cowboys' bye week coming after seven games, this is as
good a time as any to assess the first part of the 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond running back Emmitt Smith's resurgence, defensive tackle
Leon Lett's dominating play and cornerback Deion Sanders' utter
greatness, the best story of the first half was backup quarterback
Jason Garrett, who lived out a made-for-television movie right
before our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Disney couldn't have scripted it better.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Sunday's loss to the Bears took some of the luster off
Garrett's performance. But that's what makes it better than some
hokey movie fantasy. The Jason Garrett Show was authentic, because
it came with the highs and lows of real life.
</P>
<P>
   What's funny is that some people are actually disappointed that
the 4-3 Cowboys finished ``only'' 3-2 with Garrett at the controls
in place of Troy Aikman. And they are right. The Cowboys should
have beaten the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett, who is the NFL's third-ranked quarterback and is in
front of last season's Pro Bowl quarterbacks, Brett Favre and Trent
Dilfer, was performing that well. So well, in fact, that people
took a few things for granted. Think about it for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Here, we had a little-used and supposedly flawed backup, making
a minimum-wage quarterback salary of $300,000, being called on to
replace a $50 million hero in Aikman. Did we already say that
Garrett went undrafted out of Princeton, was slight of build and of
arm strength?
</P>
<P>
   Did we also say that Garrett was cut by the Saints, the
now-defunct World League San Antonio Riders and CFL's Ottawa
RoughRiders before being signed by the Cowboys in 1993. And in the
past five seasons he had never been more than a third-string
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   If you knew before the season that Aikman would go down with an
injury and the basically unproven Garrett would be handed the keys
to the Cowboys' season for five games _ including road matchups
against the defending NFC East champion Giants, Redskins and Bears
and home games against the Raiders and Panthers _ what would your
expectations have been?
</P>
<P>
   2-3? 1-4?
</P>
<P>
   Most people would have been happy _ no, ecstatic over a 3-2
mark.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard now to be satisfied with 3-2 because the two losses
were each by one point and Garrett's shortcomings played large
roles in the outcomes of both games.
</P>
<P>
   However, considering this crazy season _ in which the almighty
Packers have lost back-to-back games and the 49ers lost to the
Bills _ there is no guarantee that the Cowboys would have gone 5-0
or even 4-1 during that same stretch with Aikman at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that when Aikman returns from his broken
collarbone after the bye for the Philadelphia game, the Cowboys'
preseason goals remain intact. The Cowboys stand atop the NFC East
by one game and the possibilities are endless.
</P>
<P>
   And Garrett is a big reason why. He combined a sharp knowledge
of the game and his own limitations with a bombs-away flair; he
can't throw the 15-yard out, but he can throw the deep ball. And
when he played mistake-free, as he did in victories against the
Giants, Redskins and Panthers, Garrett was surprisingly the best
quarterback on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping that if/when the Cowboys do realize their
potential and return to the playoffs after a year's hiatus,
Garrett's contribution won't be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clint Longley's legendary relief job for Roger Staubach
on Thanksgiving Day in 1974, which was called by one teammate as
``the triumph of an uncluttered mind,'' Garrett's play was not born
of luck or happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   His improbable five-game run was the story of a lifelong
football junkie and the son of a football coach, who was not
blessed with great physical skills. However, Garrett loved the game
and prepared himself every day on blind faith for an opportunity
that was never promised.
</P>
<P>
   Nine long years after graduating from Princeton and at mature
age of 32, Garrett finally got his chance and made the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy'' was a fantasy. The Jason Garrett story was genuine.
Kevin Smith standing strong
</P>
<P>
   It's been well documented that cornerback Kevin Smith is having
a tough time. What's not been told is how Smith _ though hurt by
criticism _ has not shied away it.
</P>
<P>
   Some players outright duck the media when they have bad games.
But not Smith. He faces the music like a man, answering every
question whether he agrees or not.
</P>
<P>
   It's that attitude that gives defensive backs coach Mike Zimmer
hope that Smith will bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people that believe in him are the people in the
defensive locker room,'' said Zimmer, who pointed out that Smith is
the same guy that the Cowboys used to hang out in single coverage
during the Super Bowl seasons of 1992, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just lost his confidence,'' Zimmer added. ``I believe in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer added that the Cowboys are also going to stop giving
Smith a lot of safety help and just trust that he will get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were screwing everybody else up,'' Zimmer said. ``That's
why we were getting the long balls thrown on us. He's just going to
line up and cover the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   To know Smith _ he has tangled with former defensive end Charles
Haley in the past _ is to know that he won't go down without a
fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
