<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEHOUSE21-COX     10-21 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEHOUSE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After census, statehouses to reapportion Congress seats
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ With legislative reapportionment likely to
determine control of Congress in the new millennium, some of the
fall's most competitive and expensive elections are unfolding in
state legislatures around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Well beneath the radar of the congressional campaigns, the two
national parties are spending millions of dollars in about a dozen
states where a gain or loss of a few seats could give one party
control of the state house or senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hand-to-hand combat out there,'' says Kevin Mack,
director of the Democratic Legislative Campaign Committee.
``Partisan control is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Term limits, creating an unprecedented number of open seats in
some states, is also feeding the frenzy. Here in the Razorback
State, half of the 100-member House is open because of term limits,
giving Republicans the best opportunity to pick up seats in the
Democratically controlled Legislature ``since Union troops left
Little Rock and allowed the former Confederate soldiers to vote
again,'' says Arkansas GOP director Richard Bearden.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, where Democrats are clinging to a four-seat
majority in the state House, 64 of the state's 110 House seats are
open this year because of term limits. The state parties and
related committees there are spending ``millions and millions of
dollars'' for control of the chamber, says Mark Brewer, chairman of
the Michigan Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans, of course, have immediate objectives
in wanting to control state legislative chambers. But the
overarching impetus at the national level is the redistricting that
will take place in 2001 as a result of the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   The parties that control the legislatures and the governor's
offices after the 2000 elections will redraw the district
boundaries for Congress. How the lines are drawn can determine
which party will be able to send more of their members to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The national parties aren't waiting until 2000 to launch their
offensives on legislatures, figuring that it will be easier for
their members to win in 2000 if they are running as incumbents
elected this year.
</P>
<P>
   Three states that send the most members to Congress _
California, Illinois and Texas _ all have legislative chambers that
could change hands with the gain or loss of a few seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm spending a ton of money in California,'' says Rep. John
Linder (R-Ga.), chairman of the National Republican Campaign
Committee, which spearheads the House GOP campaign effort.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Linder's NRCC is spending nearly $2 million in state
legislative races. Linder sums up the reason for the investment:
reapportionment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be huge to control one or both bodies and even
better if we control the governors' offices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who coordinates the Democratic Party's effort from
Washington, declined to disclose what the DLCC is spending this
year. ``People are just working as hard as they can to keep these
legislative chambers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're basically talking about setting the rules of the game
for the next 10 years,'' says political scientist Gary Moncrief at
Boise State University, who teaches state legislative politics.
``Whoever controls that has really got a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who control a majority of the nation's legislative
chambers, have the most at stake. With the GOP now controlling both
houses of Congress and 32 of 50 of the nation's governor's offices,
state legislatures are the last repository of Democratic strength.
</P>
<P>
   And that strength has been eroding steadily, thanks in a large
part to the huge Republican gains in the South. In 1974, Democrats
controlled 68 percent of all state legislative seats. Now they
control just 53 percent. In the South, the erosion has been even
more dramatic. In 1974, Democrats controlled 86 percent of all
legislative seats in the region. Today, they control 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also facing some bad precedent. The party of the
president has lost legislative seats in every midterm election in
the past 20 years except one.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Republicans have a realistic chance of gaining
control of a majority of the nation's 7,424 legislative seats for
the first time since 1952, says Tim Storey, research analyst for
the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the final act of realignment,'' says Storey.
``Democrats really dominated state legislatures if you look at the
last 20 years. Now you have a number of states where Republicans
are optimistic and have realistic shots to take state chambers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the NRCC is spending about $100,000 to erase the
Democrats' 10-seat majority in the state Senate. ``We've got a real
shot,'' says state GOP chairman Rusty Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is a good example of another trend that is reshaping the
way state legislative battles are fought. In the past, strategic
planning and fund-raising was a largely parochial affair, with the
respective party leaders from the House and Senate calling the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Now, legislative campaigns have become centralized in the state
parties, with strategic advice and money flowing directly from the
national parties. This year in Georgia, for example, the state
Republican Party is coordinating statewide television advertising
for its candidates for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   The result are campaigns that are far more professional than the
candidates could have ever undertaken on their own, Paul says.
</P>
<P>
   The DLCC, founded in 1993, this year is providing professional
support to 37 legislative chambers, from polling to fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened in the past is these have been lackluster
operations with legislative leaders raising $10,000 to $15,000 and
passing out $500 checks to incumbents,'' Mack says. ``Now they are
$500,000 to $1 million efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BALANCE OF POWER
</P>
<P>
   Control of one or both chambers of many state legislatures is up
for grabs in the November election. A gain or loss of a few seats
in many cases will mean a change of partisan control. The number in
center column indicates how many seats the minority party must win
to gain control.
</P>
<P>
   SeatsParty
</P>
<P>
   Stateneeded in power
</P>
<P>
   California Assembly 4Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Senate2Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Senate 6Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Illinois House2Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Senate 2Republicans
</P>
<P>
   Indiana House 1Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Maine Senate3Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Michigan House4Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota House4Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Missouri House6Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Senate3Democrats
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina House2Republicans
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Senate2Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Senate2Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Texas Senate2Republicans
</P>
<P>
   Washington Senate2Republicans
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Senate1Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Minority party already controls the other legislative chamber.
</P>
