 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Itty-bitty video great for enclosing in e-mail 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A company called AVerMedia has given me a new way to bedevil my
friends. Now I can send them little movies of my dog, my guinea
pigs, my wife or myself (I may be mean but I'm not a sadist).
</P>
<P>
   The AVerMedia InterCam kit consists of a peripheral card, a
microphone and stand, and a little camera the size and shape of a
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up this little video system is about as easy as it can
get. The card requires a PCI slot. If you have a Pentium computer
of fairly recent vintage, it will have plenty of available PCI
slots unless you have been buying some very sophisticated stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Once the card is installed, all that remains is to plug the
camera into it and the microphone. If you want talkies, plug into
the mike input on your sound card, and install the software, which
is automatic.
</P>
<P>
   One does not expect much from a video camera the size of a
baseball that comes in a $120 package. The key to enjoying InterCam
is having fun.
</P>
<P>
   The InterCam camera has two controls: an on-off switch and a
focusing ring that surrounds the lens. When you call up the
InterCam program, it presents you with a video box about 2 inches
wide and an inch and a half high. You can enlarge this all the way
to full screen, but you don't want to. It becomes extremely fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with the camera is its shape. It sits in a
depression in a soft plastic support, and the cable tying it to the
capture card is annoyingly stiff, fighting you every time you
adjust the camera's position.
</P>
<P>
   When you turn the camera on, it gives you a view of what it
sees, but it doesn't begin recording until you click the record
button in the software. When you turn off recording, you can view
the video you just recorded. Once you save it to disk, however, you
can no longer view it through the AVerMedia software.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The video is saved as an AVI file, and you can
view it just fine through the Video for Windows or the Active Movie
feature found in Media Device in the Accessories group of Windows
95.
</P>
<P>
   If you have no experience with digital video, you need to know
that these files can be huge. They have to be compressed, and the
software allows a selection from among a number of video
compression formats. I chose the Microsoft decompressor, on the
theory that everybody to whom I would send a video would have it,
and set the quality to 75 percent. Choosing 100 percent quality
greatly increases file size.
</P>
<P>
   I also selected 50 frames per minute in the software, rather
than the default 20, which tends to be rather jerky.
</P>
<P>
   A video 10 or 15 seconds long is going to be about 10 megabytes
in size. You won't make any friends sending 10-megabyte e-mails.
But trying to make two- to three-second videos is extremely
difficult in some cases, such as making videos of my piggies. I put
the camera down in their enclosure and waited for them to come
around.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to handle this, since the AVerMedia software has no
editing features, is to keep your videos to a reasonable length _
15 seconds or so _ save them to disk, and then call them up in the
Video for Windows feature mentioned above. Using this, you can make
a selection of a few seconds from anywhere in the video and copy it
into a file.
</P>
<P>
   This way you can get a file down into the 200K range, attach it
to an e-mail message and send it out without becoming Attila the
Geek.
</P>
<P>
   As these things go, $120 is pretty cheap, and AVerMedia's
InterCam is the best cheap thrill I've had in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
