 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Let your Mac do the Windows 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtual PC is one of the most amazing pieces of software I've
ever seen. Apple Computer should include it on every G3 model it
sells.
</P>
<P>
   Why the enthusiasm? Because Virtual PC delivers as advertised.
It seamlessly simulates a Windows computer on your Mac.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though this hasn't been tried before. Insignia
Solutions still sells its Windows emulator called SoftWindows. But
SoftWindows is a clunker compared with Virtual PC.
</P>
<P>
   With Virtual PC, you can run anything from Microsoft Office to
the latest multimedia game on your Mac.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Virtual PC will run PC games. I tested it with a
very demanding one called ``Sid Meier's Gettysburg.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, a real-time simulation of the famous Civil War battle,
ran fine. There was a slight loss of speed, and the video and sound
were jumpy at times. But I played the game on a G3 PowerBook for
hours without a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual PC is easy to install and use. Switching back and forth
between operating systems is a breeze. Just click on the desktop,
and you jump back to the Apple Computer's operating system. You
click inside the Virtual PC window to go back to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, running Windows 95 and Apple Computer's operating
system side by side really showcases the Mac. Windows 95 seemed
awkward and unintuitive compared to the Mac operating system. But
that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   What's amazing about Virtual PC is it's all software. In effect,
Virtual PC is tricking the Mac into believing it's a PC. Virtual PC
emulates not only Windows 95 but Windows 3.1 and DOS. You can also
buy a version that handles Windows 98, Microsoft's latest operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   While Virtual PC emulates any PC operating system, it won't work
on just any Mac. You need one with a powerful microprocessor.
Developer Connectix, for example, recommends Apple Computer's new
G3 models.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but Virtual PC will not work on Macs with chips
pre-dating the PowerPC microprocessor. Its performance is sluggish
on early models of the PowerPC.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual PC is a storage and memory hog. You need at least 32
megabytes of RAM and 150 megabytes of storage to run Windows 95.
Despite its requirements, Virtual PC is worth the money. It retails
for $149.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
