u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-REUNION-INTERNET-     10-21 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-REUNION-INTERNET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN REUNITED WITH FATHER SHE FOUND ONLINE AFTER 50 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By SONIA GIORDANI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. -- Since Sharon Sylchak found her long-lost
father through the Internet recently, she's waited anxiously to
complete the puzzle of her life _ to meet him in person.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the 53-year-old Simi Valley woman's wait ended as she
watched her father, Earl Papkie, enter the terminal at Los Angeles
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I felt like I had half an identity. Now that I've
found my father, I feel like I can know who I am _ the whole
story,'' Sylchak said.
</P>
<P>
   She was a little girl, not quite 4, when she last saw him.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowded airport terminal, 75-year-old Papkie embraced his
only child as tears streamed down their faces. With their own eyes
welling with tears, spectators watched as Sylchak introduced her
father to the grandchildren and great-grandchildren he had never
known before.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in an airport wheelchair with his 2-year-old
great-granddaughter, Miranda, in his lap, Papkie said he still
couldn't believe his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have known I have all these beautiful kids?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Sylchak had dialed up operators in Michigan, where
she was born and thought her father might still be living. When
nothing turned up, she tried writing to the Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   She had nearly given up when she received an America Online
start-up disk in the mail and hooked up to the Internet. It was
there she would track down her dad's phone number in St. Helen,
Mich., and leave him a message on his answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard it, I thought, you've got to be joking. I tried
for 30 years to find her,'' said Papkie, a former rancher who wore
a black cowboy hat and boots to look his best for the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Before even making it to the car to go home, Papkie couldn't
resist opening up his carry-on bag and digging out an armful of
photographs of Sharon as a little girl and showing off the
portraits of her he has kept in his wallet all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Papkie and Sylchak's mother had been married for less than two
months when their relationship ended. When Sylchak was born, her
mother gave the baby to Papkie's parents because she already was
raising two children from a previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Papkie _ then in his early 20s _ helped his own
parents raise the child. But Sylchak's mother reclaimed custody of
the girl, and Papkie never saw her again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so excited about this moment. He talked about her the
whole flight,'' said Edie Mazurek, a resident of Northbrook, Ill.,
who sat next to Papkie on the flight to Los Angeles. ``He was also
very nervous _ this was his first flight, and I think he knew what
would be waiting for him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Local television stations as well as ``Inside Edition'' had
their cameras rolling when Papkie arrived, trying to catch every
moment of a touching story about Sylchak's family and about the
persistence it took for their reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never knew he was alive,'' said David Boyer, one of
Sylchak's four children who, with his two daughters and brothers
George and Charlie, met Papkie at the airport. ``My grandmother
died when I was young. So this is exciting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members would spend the rest of the day in Sylchak's
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he must be exhausted, so we'll let him rest. But then
we'll get around to telling our tales from the last 50 years,''
Sylchak said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-19-98 0000EDT &QL;
