<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBADS-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB ADVERTISERS GET NEW TOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By CAROL EMERT   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A top consumer research firm is launching a service today
designed to give Web advertisers highly detailed, statistically
significant data about who is seeing their ads.
</P>
<P>
   Thus a bottled water company advertising on the Web will be able
to figure out how many of the ads it sent into cyberspace were
viewed by its target audience _ for example, women aged 35 to 44
who drink bottled water and live west of the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The service, Millward Brown Interactive's Voyager Profile,
recruited 50,000 consumers who filled out a lengthy questionnaire
on the Web detailing their demographic information and consumption
habits.
</P>
<P>
   These volunteers received an electronic identification tag that
identifies them as Voyager panelists. When they visit a Web page,
ad servers _ companies that broadcast ads to various Web sites _
recognize them as Voyager panelists and keep track of which ads
they've seen.
</P>
<P>
   That information is sent back to Millward Brown, which can tell
the advertiser the demographic profile of all the panelists who've
seen their ads.
</P>
<P>
   The servers are not privy to the personal information disclosed
by the panelists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something Internet advertisers have been crying out
for,'' said Michael Tann, a vice president with AdForce of
Cupertino. ``This fundamentally brings the same kind of credible
market research that's used in the established media into the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   John Mracek, vice president of marketing for AdKnowledge, an ad
server in New York, said he sees the service as an adjunct to
ratings services such as New York's Media Metrix, which uses a
panel of 40,000 computer users to project the demographics of
visitors to different sites.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix tracks visitors to sites, but they don't know which
ads every visitor sees because people visiting the same site at the
same time may see different ads.
</P>
<P>
   Voyager is designed to make up for that anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   Once an ad campaign runs, planners can use Voyager to fine tune
the mix of sites where they buy ads.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if 60 percent of the people who viewed the campaign
are women and the advertiser was trying to reach 75 percent women,
planners will know to buy more ad space on female-oriented sites
the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   Millward Brown will charge advertisers $1,500 to $2,000 per
report.
</P>
<P>
   One other service, NetRatings of Milpitas, is attempting to
measure ad audiences. But that company, which also provides site
ratings a la Media Metrix, uses a panel of only 3,500 consumers,
which is not big enough to provide statistically valid data about
many Web ads.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Meadows, vice president of marketing for NetRatings, noted
that Voyager reports are largely limited to ads that have been
distributed by ad servers that are working with Millward Brown,
including AdKnowledge, AdForce and industry leader DoubleClick,
which serves about 30 percent of Web ads.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Briggs, a Millward Brown Interactive vice president, said
the sample of panelists is large enough to provide statistically
significant data on the vast majority of Web ad campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The panel represents about 1.5 percent of the total Web
population of 61 million, which is a larger percentage than most
samples used by ratings services in other media, Briggs said.
</P>
<P>
   Voyager panelists are recruited by random telephone calls and
don't receive anything except the chance to win free prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Millward Brown is based in Chicago; its interactive division is
based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-19-98 0009EDT &QL;
</P>
