<HEADLINE>
COMPULSIVE COMPUTER USERS TURN THEIR BACKS ON THE REAL WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By CAROLYN POIROT  
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe, like one addict, you believe your $400 phone bill must be
paid before the $40 water bill.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you don't have time for the people you love but who just
seem to take so much effort, and you'd rather connect with new
friends on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's simpler. Maybe you just find your fingers
anxiously making typing movements when you're away from your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   If any of this is true, it may be that you're addicted to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some people find themselves sneaking online in the middle of the
night or calling in sick so they can stay home and surf the Net,
says Jim Landers, a counselor with Family Service in Fort Worth.
Still, they don't recognize that what has gotten hold of them is a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get called mostly for relationship problems,'' Landers
says. ``They don't come in for help with an Internet addiction, but
when they call for help with a relationship problem, we sometimes
find an addiction to the Internet behind it. I've talked with men
who say they spend 10 hours a day on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet addiction is a psychological dependence on the Internet
or compulsive computer use to the point that it causes family and
relationship problems, job loss, physical exhaustion or failure in
school.
</P>
<P>
   With more people gaining access to the Internet daily,
increasing numbers of people are becoming involved with strangers
they ``meet'' in chat rooms, sometimes throwing away the lives they
have for a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, people are simply becoming so mesmerized by the
Internet that they are neglecting other areas of their lives, such
as their families or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kimberly Young, assistant professor of psychology at the
University of Pittsburgh at Bradford, Pa., and director of the
Center for Online Addiction, presents workshops to train counselors
to deal with Internet addicts. Her book, ``Caught in the Net''
(John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $22.95), offers information on how to recognize
signs of Internet addiction and strategies for recovery. (Addicts
note: Young can be reached through her Web site
www.netaddiction.com.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Use of the Internet can definitely disrupt one's academic,
social, financial and occupational life,'' Young says.
</P>
<P>
   Although Internet Addiction Disorder is not yet listed in the
Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, counselors
say it is often linked with other addictions, especially sex, work
and gambling addictions.
</P>
<P>
   Young conducted an online survey that found that, in well over
half the cases, Internet junkies suffered from prior addictions.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, says Landers, what we call an Internet
addiction is really a sexual addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty to ninety percent of the time it's a sexual addiction.
The Internet amplifies the problem. You can act out your fantasies
and not have to deal with the shame you would feel otherwise
because no one knows who you are. You do things you wouldn't do
otherwise. There are no checks and balances,'' Landers says.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy relationships are easy, he says. You think, ``I've found
my soul mate.'' The problem is that you've really just found a
superficial connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look up someone to meet online with the exact
inclinations and quirks you are looking for _ but you might be
getting a woman who is really a man or something else you don't
bargain for and are not expecting,'' Landers warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say they are addicted to the Net, it's not to
their computer or the information highway itself, but to some way
they can use it for satisfaction they are not finding elsewhere,''
the counselor says. ``Usually there are relationship problems they
are not dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, some people who say they recognize their addiction
turn back to the Net for solutions, a measure critics liken to
Alcoholics Anonymous groups meeting at a bar.
</P>
<P>
   Online support groups, such as Webaholics and Interneters
Anonymous, say they'll help Net surfers who want to overcome their
addictions to cybersex or information overload. Virtual clinics
promise assistance for those who need immediate help.
</P>
<P>
   Critics warn that these kinds of computer-centered resources may
simply gratify the same need for undemanding, unrealistic
connections that are the basis of many Internet-born relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Landers cautions that one danger of the Web is that people who
don't make friends well in person may suddenly start to feel
falsely connected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is about connections,'' he admits. ``But most of
the problems I see are about disconnections.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact her at: (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-20-98 1607EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
