<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-HOTLIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH THE WEB TO KEEP UP WITH THE TWISTS AND TURNS IN THE MICROSOFT
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems only fitting that one of the best ways to keep up with
what's been dubbed the ``Tech Trial of the Century'' is via the
Internet. Hotlist, the topic-based collection of Web sites that
appears in the Houston Chronicle, offers a few ways you to get an
online antitrust fix.
</P>
<P>
   Hotlist Extra: United States vs. Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft _ www.microsoft.com/presspass/trial/ Though there's a
decided Microsoft spin on the daily coverage offered at the
company's Web site, you'll also find a chronology of events, the
complete text of Microsoft's legal filings and opinion pieces from
those friendly to the software giant. More antitrust-related links
are also at www.microsoft.com/presspass/doj/doj.htm
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Justice _ www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/msindex.htm
The Justice Department doesn't have a crack team of spinmeisters on
its side, so you get just the facts, ma'am. Here you'll find the
depositions from witnesses in the case _ posted the afternoon
before they take the stand _ and the government's legal filings.
You'll find orders and rulings entered by the judge at
www.dcd.uscourts.gov/district-court.html
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Mercury News _
www.sjmercury.com/business/microsoft/trial/ The Mercury News,
considered the newspaper of Silicon Valley, has created a ``virtual
courtroom'' online. Click on the defendant's table to read about
Microsoft's point of view. Clicking on the plaintiffs see the
government's case. Hit the file cabinets for background and
documents. Or click the judge for a profile of Thomas Penfield
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   News.com _ www.news.com CNet's News.com offers minute-by-minute
coverage of the Microsoft trial, acting like a wire service for
technology junkies. The site also has created a single page where
it has archived all its past DOJ vs. Microsoft stories.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet _ www.zdnet.com/zdnn/special/msdojtrial.html ZDNet, the
online site for computer magazine publisher Ziff-Davis, offers both
ongoing news coverage and plenty of opinion, with the staff of its
Anchor Desk weighing in on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Times _ www.seattletimes.com/news/business/microsoft/
How are they viewing the proceedings in Microsoft's own stomping
grounds? The Seattle Times is archiving its stories in a special
area on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   CNNfn _ cnnfn.com/specials/antitrust/ CNNfn has dubbed these
proceedings ``Microsoft Trial 2.0,'' since this is the second time
the government has gone after the company on antitrust charges.
Read a timeline of events, profiles of the participants and CNNfn
and CNN's past stories.
</P>
<P>
   NewsLinx _ www.newslinx.com/newstopics/renovsgates.html This
site provides links to news publications across the Web, and has
set up a special area just to deal with Microsoft trial coverage.
Read reports from sources as diverse as Wired, Reuters, Bloomberg
Business News, the Washington Post, the Associated Press, PC Week
and the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! Full Coverage _ headlines.yahoo.com/FC/Tech/Microsoft/
Finally, if you just can't get enough, Yahoo! Full Coverage offers
an exhaustive set of links to just about any site that has to do
with the Microsoft trial.  &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-20-98 2018EDT &QL;
</P>
