<SLUG> BC-GADGETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER ROBOT: NOT EXACTLY LOST IN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Telephone numbers are CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the soccer mom whose offspring is also a technophile, the
MIT Museum Shop catalog, offering wares found at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, has the Soccer Robot.
</P>
<P>
   The six-legged walker, 3-inches high by 5-inches long, runs
forward, backward and turns a full 360 degrees. Each
build-it-yourself kit comes with Soccer 'Bot, control box (the
machine is connected by a wire) and a soccer ball. The only
disappointment: You have to provide your own field and mini-goal to
make your set-up look like the catalog picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Soccer Robot kit, suggested for ages 10 and older, requires
basic tools for assembly. One robot costs $42.95, or $79.95 for
two. Call 617-253-4462 to order or to request a Museum Shop
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AS THE WORLDS TURN: Globes are cool. We've recently been
thinking about and looking at different kinds of globes because,
well, we like them.
</P>
<P>
   Two of our recent favorites are a black globe with a Machine
Age/Art Deco metal base, from the Levenger (``Tools for Serious
Readers'') catalog and the wowing World of Gems Globe, in the
holiday issue of The Smithsonian Catalogue.
</P>
<P>
   Levenger's black globe is simple and striking; the equally
striking gems globe (pictured), as you might imagine, isn't simple.
Each country is hand-cut from precious materials, such as jasper,
jade and mother-of-pearl, and inlaid in a sea of lapis, all atop a
lapis stand. The 12-inch-diameter black globe costs $149; call
800-544-0880 to order.
</P>
<P>
   The gems globe, 8 inches in diameter, costs $2,800, on sale from
$3,200; call 800-322-0344 to order.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINE STEWARDS: Whimsy wins out over wine snobbery when you
present your favorite vintage with the Bottle Butlers.
</P>
<P>
   The humorous, hugging helpers, clad in formal wear, are a
variation on those simple wine holders that use gravity to balance
a bottle horizontally a few inches above the tabletop. Simply stick
the neck of a bottle into the butlers' arms and they stand up,
proffering the wine. Because they're only 8-inches tall and made of
plastic polymers, it's not quite the same as having hired help to
attend to dinner-party duties.
</P>
<P>
   But go ahead and promise guests that ``our butlers will be
serving the wine'' and watch their laughter bubble up when they see
the dapper dudes. Call the International Wine Accessories catalog
at 800-527-4072 to order the $25 Bottle Butlers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
