A8813 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-ANTHEM-HN     10-21 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-ANTHEM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANTEHM' IS A ROAD TRIP BEST AVOIDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the long history of meandering, self-centered, badly written
books about being on the road, you will be hard put to find one
that's more meandering, self-centered and badly written than
``Anthem: An American Road Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the book, by Shainee Gabel and Kristin Hahn
(Avon Books, New York, $14, 394 pages), was to take to the road to
explore the question, ``What does it mean to be an American
today?'' The two Hollywood women, both 26 at the time, would
crisscross the country, writing a book and making a film about
their findings. The film has already come out, to lukewarm reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The initial concept wasn't bad _ search for the answer through
interviews with a broad section of interesting Americans, including
filmmaker John Waters, author Studs Terkel, journalist Hunter S.
Thompson, novelist John Irving, former Sen. George McGovern, rap
artist Chuck D, actor Robert Redford, singer Willie Nelson,
desegregation champion Charlayne Hunter-Gault and former vice
presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   But the book needed an editor and didn't get one. The writing
veers between insufferable prattling and schoolgirl giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the book is given over, not to interviews, but to
the authors talking about how hard it was to get the interviews, or
the trouble they had in finding an address, or how a nagging
stomach ache wouldn't go away. Reading ``Anthem'' is like sitting
in the waiting room of a doctor's office, listening to someone blab
on about liver troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing _ nothing _ is so insignificant that Gabel and Hahn
leave it out. Want to know what they ate on a newsless night?
They'll tell you. Want a description of how hard it was to get an
audience with Thompson? OK, how about half a dozen pages worth?
Want to know how stoked Gabel and Hahn were when they met Thompson,
or Redford, or Jimmy Santiago Baca, or Ferraro? They'll tell you,
moon eyes shining.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a road book. This is the diary of two
celebrity-stricken women who had enough chutzpah to arrange
interviews with people worth listening to, then decided their views
on things were just as important as the people they were
interviewing.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, uneven as it is, offers considerably less horseradish
than the book. You're better off renting the movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS22-COX     10-21 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio Reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar, Doug Hamilton, and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Gershwin's World''
</P>
<P>
   Herbie Hancock. Verve. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   American vernacular dressed up as tuxedo music, this spiffy
songbook threatens to choke the listener in its high-concept
cologne. Jazz great Herbie Hancock's contribution to the George
Gershwin centennial boasts as many guest stars as a Puff Daddy
production. Though it could have wobbled under the weight of all
those egos, serendipity reigns. Joni Mitchell and Stevie Wonder
rhapsodize along with Wayne Shorter's soprano on ``Summertime''; a
corps of percussionists led by Cyro Baptista stir an Afro-Caribbean
undertow on ``It Ain't Necessarily So'' and ``Here Come De Honey
Man,'' to which trumpeter Eddie Henderson also lends a muted,
Milesian air. Orchestral interludes, a stride duet with Chick Corea
and a Kathleen Battle cameo complete a ritzy package.
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Prolonging the Magic''
</P>
<P>
   Cake. Capricorn. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you talk to, California combo Cake is a prime
example of what's good or what's bad about the alternative music
scene. Gleefully non-cerebral, the group sets smirky,
centimeter-deep lyrics to seemingly tossed-off grooves augmented by
trumpet and occasional theremin. Critics scoff, but the college
party brigade scarfs this stuff up like so much ... well, let's
just say the band's nutrition-free name is perfect. If Cake
sometimes sounds as if it's coasting on its third album, there are
enough angst-free ditties and goofy sing-alongs (``Sheep Go to
Heaven,'' ``Never There'') to keep the frat houses rockin'.
</P>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ```Slam' The Soundtrack''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   Immortal/Epic. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The movie this soundtrack accompanies took top prizes at
Sundance and Cannes, and the album comes appropriately loaded with
rap stars (Q-Tip, Pras). But it's newcomer Black Rob _ the first
Bad Boy artist not afraid to talk violence since labelmate
Notorious B.I.G. was killed _ who's sure to hit the charts with a
bullet. And if there were a trailer for this album, it would be
smart to tout the couplings of Goodie Mob and Esthero (``The World
I Know'') and Big Pun and Next (``Sex, Money &AMP; Drugs''), the
dynamic duos in an otherwise only decent set.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
