 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release THURSDAY, OCTOBER 22, 1998 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MCCOY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The story of Margaret Garner _ the
slave woman who killed her 2-year-old daughter in 1856 in
Cincinnati rather than let her be taken back into slavery _ lit a
match in the souls of three very different women, in three very
different ways. The first two women are famous. They are Toni
Morrison and Oprah Winfrey, and Garner's story provided the seed
for Beloved, the 1987 Pulitzer Prize-winning novel and the current
movie. The third woman _ Joanne Caputo of Yellow Springs _ is
hardly famous, but her obsession with the case led to the discovery
of the Boone County, Ky., farm where Garner worked as a slave.
(McCoy, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The other day a friend's
four-year-old grandson climbed onto my lap, took my face in his
hands, and declared: ``You're going to die pretty soon, you know?
You're really getting old.'' Fortunately for the kid and my
relationship with his grandmother, I overcame the urge to dump him
on his head. Instead, I suggested he go climb another person. But
I've been thinking. A lot. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Here it is, just three days after
the winner was announced, and acrimony and discontent have rocked
this newspaper's Tallest, Truest Texan Contest. Eric ``Tex''
Simonsen thinks Mark McLendon, the winner, is too much of a
``redneck'' to hold the title. Simonsen thinks somebody else should
have won: him. McLendon's qualifications for winning the contest
included being in the Too Damn Friendly Bar in Johnson City every
night last year and having once done his Christmas shopping at a
truck stop. Simonsen, who entered the contest, thinks he would have
been a better choice. ``I know in my heart that I truly am the
'Truest Tallest Texan,' '' Simonsen wrote. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ VAL D'ISERE, France _ Even if I die on this
mountain, it still beats traveling through Europe on a Eurail
Flexipass. After that last train trip from Barcelona, Spain to
Nice, France, I knew that I would crawl back to Texas on my hands
and knees beating myself with a mesquite branch before I suffered
through another train ride in Europe. (Nethaway, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ State Rep. Lois
Frankel has gone country on us, a shocking development.
</P>
<P>
   I've always thought of Frankel as more lox than Loxahatchee.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw her latest political ad. It's a glossy photo of Lois
. . . now get this . . . posing with a horse. Really. The big black
horse is standing there, wide-eyed next to Frankel, who is smiling
broadly as her left hand nestles affectionately under the horse's
muzzle. Given the current political climate, my first impression
was that the photo was some tawdry smear campaign by her Republican
challenger, Rick Heers. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
