<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCOY-COLUMN22-COX     10-21 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Beloved'' a story of the unimaginable
 &HT;    By Mary McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The story of Margaret Garner _ the slave woman
who killed her 2-year-old daughter in 1856 in Cincinnati rather
than let her be taken back into slavery _ lit a match in the souls
of three very different women, in three very different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The first two women are famous. They are Toni Morrison and Oprah
Winfrey, and Garner's story provided the seed for Beloved, the 1987
Pulitzer Prize-winning novel and the current movie.
</P>
<P>
   The third woman _ Joanne Caputo of Yellow Springs _ is hardly
famous, but her obsession with the case led to the discovery of the
Boone County, Ky., farm where Garner worked as a slave.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison's inspiration came from a brief reprinted article about
the case. The novelist learned only the barest facts: On Jan. 28,
1856, as white federal marshals burst into a shack near
Cincinnati's Mill Creek, the 23-year-old pregnant mother gripped a
knife and shouted that she would rather see her children dead than
returned to slavery. Before she could be subdued, Garner slit the
throat of her daughter, Mary, and attempted to kill her three other
children.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison intentionally avoided further research. She told the
New York Times in 1987, ``The rest is sheer novel writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Caputo, 43, had never read Beloved when she came across a brief
mention of Margaret Garner's story in 1994 while conducting
research for another project. Caputo couldn't rest until she
learned everything she could about Margaret Garner.
</P>
<P>
   `` Beloved is a novel,'' says Caputo, who is working on both a
screenplay and a non-fiction book about Margaret Garner. ``I was
real compelled by the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Compelled, but also baffled. The tragedy was far from the
reality of this mother of two boys and president of the Yellow
Springs PTO. ``Because I was a mother I couldn't understand how she
could do it,'' Caputo said. Over the next several years, her
research brought her to a very different feeling. ``Margaret
symbolizes maternal love,'' she says, ``because of the depth to
which she is willing to go to protect her children from slavery. .
.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the daughter who died was her special child, her
favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Caputo began by searching the Cincinnati Enquirer archives in
the public library in downtown Cincinnati. She squinted over a
flurry of microfilm until she found something that gave her
goosebumps: the Jan. 29, 1856, edition of the Enquirer with the
headline : ``Stampede of Slaves: A Tale of Horror!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city was thrown into much excitement yesterday morning by
the information that a party of slaves, sixteen in all, had made a
stampede from Kentucky to this side of the river. Other
circumstances, however, which afterward transpired, have imparted a
degree of horrible interest to the affair different from that which
usually attends a stampede of negroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The story in the 1856 pro-slavery Enquirer goes on to relate
federal marshals' pursuit of the Garner family, including Margaret,
known as Peggy, her husband Simon, their four children, and Simon's
parents. Simon fired a revolver from the window of their hideout,
nearly severing the finger of one marshal.
</P>
<P>
   The marshals burst in and seized the weapon, the story
continues, ``But a deed of horror had been consummated, for
weltering in its blood, the throat being cut from ear to ear and
the head almost severed from the body, upon the floor lay one of
the children of the younger couple, a girl three years old, while
in a back room, crouched beneath the bed, two more of the children,
boys, of two and five years, were moaning, the one having received
two gashes in its throat, the other a cut upon the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Beloved, the Garner case went largely unnoticed in the
20th century, but it attracted national attention, and considerable
controversy, in 1856. In January of that year, the Garner family _
slaves on the Maplewood farm of Archibald Gaines in Boone County,
Ky. _ escaped across the frozen Ohio River and hid in the home of a
freed slave in Cincinnati. After their capture, abolitionists
argued that Garner should be tried in Ohio for murder, but as a
free woman. Instead she was tried on federal charges of being a
runaway slave.
</P>
<P>
   An article from the Cincinnati Gazette describes Garner's
demeanor during the trial: ``The child in her arms is a little
girl, about nine months old, and is much lighter in color than
herself _ light enough to show the red tinge in her cheeks. Her
eyes, during the trial, were generally cast down. She would look up
occasionally, for an instant, with a timid, apprehensive glance, at
the strange faces around her. The babe, with its little hands, was
continually fondling her face, but she rarely noticed it, and her
general expression was one of extreme sadness. Only once, when it
put its hand to her mouth, we observed her smile upon it, and
playfully bite its little fingers with her lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the left side of her forehead, just above the outer
extremity of her eye-brow is an old scar, and on the cheek bone of
the same side, another. We asked her how those scars came there.
She said, 'White man struck me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beloved is set in Reconstruction-era Cincinnati, and the main
character, Sethe, is haunted by the ghost of the daughter she
killed two decades earlier. In real life, Margaret Garner lost her
infant daughter less than two months after the trial, and lived
only two more years, dying of typhoid fever in Mississippi in 1858.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Garner been convicted and sent back to Kentucky
than Ohio governor Salmon P. Chase (later chief justice of the U.S.
Supreme Court) issued a warrant for her arrest on murder charges.
Gaines, probably tipped off by Kentucky authorities, spirited the
slaves away the night before the warrant was to be served.
</P>
<P>
   The Garner family was on board the New Orleans-bound Henry Lewis
when it collided with another steamer along the Ohio River near
Troy, Ind. Fifteen of the 40 passengers drowned _ among them
10-month-old Silla, the rosy-cheeked infant described in the
newspaper accounts of the trial. ``The mother exhibited no other
feeling than joy at the loss of her child,'' reported the March 11,
1856, edition of the Cincinnati Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   The more Caputo learned, the more she empathized with Garner.
Her screenplay won an Ohio Arts Council fellowship and praise from
one judge who called the story ``America's Sophie's Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Caputo searched for months through Kentucky court records and
old newspaper clippings. At last a local historian directed her to
an undeveloped 15-acre farm that was part of the original 200-acre
estate. She came to the designated intersection and there it was: a
landmark plaque declaring the property ``the home site of Major
John P. Gaines.'' Caputo knew John Gaines was Archibald's older
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Goosebumps again.
</P>
<P>
   A cook house and smokehouse still stand on the property.
Officials with Kentucky's historic preservation agency have
confirmed the farm is the site where Garner worked, although
they're not sure the buildings date to the1850s.
</P>
<P>
   Caputo feels sure. She has erected an impromptu altar in the
hollow of a tree she says is shaped like a woman with her arms
upraised, her skirts lifted. There she has placed symbols of
mothering _ baby blankets, a bowl of rice, a bar of soap _ as well
as a pretty handkerchief (''Margaret never had anything nice'') and
a photo of Martin Luther King, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Caputo knows she can only imperfectly place herself in Garner's
world. ``All parents know that panicked feeling when you're in a
department store and you can't spot your child,'' she says. ``Her
sons were close to the selling age. Imagine what it would be like
if your child could be sold or raped or whipped until the skin was
bleeding, right in front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   None of us can imagine it, really. It's a tribute to the story's
enduring power, its profound symbolism, that such soaring
imaginations have made us try.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
