</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The can-dos outweigh life's utter impossibilities
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The other day a friend's four-year-old
grandson climbed onto my lap, took my face in his hands, and
declared: ``You're going to die pretty soon, you know? You're
really getting old.'' Fortunately for the kid and my relationship
with his grandmother, I overcame the urge to dump him on his
</P>
<P>
   head. Instead, I suggested he go climb another person.
</P>
<P>
   But I've been thinking. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   Have you seen those T-shirts that, in a fit of cute announce:
``I'm not 30, I'm 29.95?'' There's one for 40, one for 50, and one
for 60...and then there are no more. Is that an omen? Is someone
suggesting that folks over 60 are too old to advertise? Life is
tough enough without some twerp of an entrepreneur reminding me
that I'm ready for the next T-shirt _ the one that's stamped:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 65 and I'm turning into my grandmother'' which, when you
think about it, is not all that bad, considering the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   But I have begun to ponder my future. Time's a wastin' and
before it runs out completely, I have to decide what I'm going to
be when I grow up. Funny how these little decisions sneak up on us
when our backs are turned.
</P>
<P>
   First, I had to cull my list of possibilities and separate the
``HU (highly unlikely)'' from the ``UI (utterly impossible because
either my feet are too big or I was born 20 years too late or 50
years too soon).'' Following are the results:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ballerina (so full of graceful moves that the audience would
throw flowers rather than fruit and I would be the toast of at
least two rural counties) _ UI.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid I was so clumsy my father nicknamed me ``Grace,'' and
my mother was forever running interference between me and the
breakables hollering, ``Watch out! The furniture!'' I even went to
dancing school for a couple of years until the teacher closed her
studio and moved away. My mother said it was fate. My father
labeled it self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blues singer (known for my tear-wrenching rendition of ``I
Loves You Porgy'' while draped over a piano in some disreputable
waterfront dive) _ HU.
</P>
<P>
   One late evening last week, a rude friend informed me that my
voice, the one I've always thought of as sultry, kind of a Marlene
Dietrich-like baritone, is highly irritating to anyone not
profoundly hard of hearing and/or drunk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fighter pilot (carrier based) _ HU.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's been many years since I've flown an airplane, I
clearly remember the odd behavior of my instructor, particularly
during landings. I wasn't sure, but I doubted that all pilots
clapped their hands over their eyes and rattled off a ``Hail Mary''
just before touchdown. Later, I began to suspect he drank.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe my grandmother Parker's impeccable UDC (United Daughters
of the Confederacy) credentials could land me a spot in the CAF
(Confederate Air Force) if war between the North and South ever
breaks out again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playboy bunny _ HU.
</P>
<P>
   Ever worn a push-up bra?
</P>
<P>
   _ President _ UI.
</P>
<P>
   My unspectacular past would hardly support an investigation by
independent counsel. The nation would be faced with four long years
of uninterrupted business as usual. Except maybe for that one time
in Peoria. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Astronaut _ HU.
</P>
<P>
   Even though John Glenn has paved the way for non-traditional
astronauts (geezers in space), I couldn't make it. Motion sickness
... unless maybe they'd let me ride in the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   Upon reflection, chances of accomplishing more than one or two
items on my list seem remote, so I've decided to add a third
category: CD (can do).
</P>
<P>
   _ Sit in the front pew and blubber as I watch my son marry the
lovely lady it took him 30 years to find.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marvel at the wonder of a grandchild who will knock my socks
off with his or her beauty and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ride trains.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finish the book.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spend time with my friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hire a new flight instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Even though my son has a problem with the last item, life is
looking good. I think I'm really going to enjoy this old-age
schtick.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher in Gibonsburg, Ohio, writes for Cox
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
