<HEADER>
A8822 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN22-COX     10-21 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Does boxing need Mike?
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ America can breathe a sigh of relief. Mike Tyson
has been ruled mentally fit to fight, which I'm sure has kept you
up nights.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that decision means he is mentally capable of
delivering a maelstrom of fury on another human being, or sub-human
being, for that matter, in a controlled environment _boxing ring,
not a fender-bender on a street corner _ for millions upon millions
of pictures of dead presidents.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he was judged to have full grasp of all his
faculties even as he prepares to relieve opponents of theirs. Only
in boxing is logic totally illogical. We can presume, then, that if
he were judged mentally unfit to box, Tyson would have to change
careers and become, what, a librarian?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Monday's ruling by the Nevada State Athletic
Commission puts him in a category with any guy who's ever laced up
a pair of gloves and sparred in a dimly lit gym, every red-blooded
American postal worker, and me. I'm as mentally fit as the next
sportswriter (insert own joke here), but I'd get in a ring with
Tyson for $20 million. Wouldn't you? I'm still relatively quick for
my age, emphasis on the relatively, and I can certainly take a dive
as well as Roberto Duran.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Troy Aikman's had his skull beaten in time after time,
and he still has the majority of his cerebral powers.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, just who is unfit to fight?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson didn't get a second chance. He got a second hundredth
chance, which made it all the more comical when he pleaded with one
commissioner to stop torturing him. Excuse me? Did that lone voice
of dissent use Evander Holyfield's ear for an appetizer and then
the main course? Where was the accountability, the deeply felt
humility? This was charade, total and irrefutable, played out on a
national stage. Tyson's camp wisely trots out the perfect PR folks
_ Muhammad Ali, the greatest boxer ever, and Magic Johnson, the
worst talk show host ever _ to speak on his behalf. I can only
assume Billy Graham was tied up.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson may have been credited with his best assist. But if he
and Ali are really to help this troubled man, maybe they should
convince him to take full responsibility for his actions and quit
blaming others. All Tyson really needs to do is take a long, hard
look at the trembling Ali and see the ravages of this vicious sport
on a man sadly inflicted with Parkinson's Disease.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a career hoodlum, an admitted wife-beater, a convicted
rapist, a notorious bad guy telling a commissioner to quit
humiliating him. What else should we expect from a fellow who
claimed he was misquoted in Playboy magazine when he said he could
explode at any time? Misquoted in a Q&AMP;A article. Who does he think
he is, Charles Barkley?
</P>
<P>
   For several million reasons, the former two-time heavyweight
champion had his boxing license restored. According to Bloomberg
News, Vegas tourists spent $9 million on housing and meals the
weekend 16 months ago when Tyson gave boxing a black eye and a
bloody ear.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Tyson gave a weak apology. With Clintonesque remorse,
Tyson sounded as if he were sorry he had to be there, not sorry for
biting Holyfield. After all the psychological testing, Tyson said
he was being humiliated by this process. That's like blaming his
orthodontist for inflicting the damage on Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, however. Mike Tyson is boxing. No name is a
bigger draw in the profession now, no name brighter on Las Vegas'
marquees, even with the erosion of his once considerable skills.
There likely has been no fighter before or since Tyson with the
same inner demons, the uncontrolled fury, the anger that spills
into the ring. You get the distinct impression Tyson is fighting
his neglectful father, his alcoholic mother, his greedy,
electric-haired promoter, his greedier handlers with every blow he
delivers.
</P>
<P>
   But for every cheeseburger-inhaling George Foreman and low
blow-throwing Andrew Golota, there is but one Tyson. Boxing needs
Mike Tyson. It needs more than that _ like stronger restrictions,
better medical safeguards, and a scoreboard without subjective
judges _ but if boxing has any hope of regaining its feet, a
rejuvenated Mike Tyson is essential.
</P>
<P>
   But what does Mike need? He even said he's not sure if he will
fight again, a premise no one believes, particularly the IRS, which
says Tyson owes it millions. Does Tyson need boxing to survive?
Without it, will he spiral ever downward, sink further into the
mental depression that he apparently cannot escape and finally meet
an untimely end? Does anyone really care about Mike Tyson? Should
anyone?
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada Athletic Commission gave him yet another chance.
Let's see if Tyson gives himself one.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
