<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frankel's a little bit country
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ State Rep. Lois Frankel has gone country
on us, a shocking development.
</P>
<P>
   I've always thought of Frankel as more lox than Loxahatchee.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw her latest political ad.
</P>
<P>
   It's a glossy photo of Lois . . . now get this . . . posing with
a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Really. The big black horse is standing there, wide-eyed next to
Frankel, who is smiling broadly as her left hand nestles
affectionately under the horse's muzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current political climate, my first impression was
that the photo was some tawdry smear campaign by her Republican
challenger, Rick Heers.
</P>
<P>
   I like Lois, and so naturally, I was prepared to defend her.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look at the print advertisement revealed that this
mailing was even more bizarre than I had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   It was Frankel herself who had distributed the horse photo to
voters in House District 85.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Friend,'' it said. ``On Sunday afternoon, October 18, I
will be riding through your area with some of your neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois Frankel on a horse! Riding!
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's the daughter of a Brooklyn mother and Bronx father.
She grew up in Long Island, where horses are considered only by
riot-control policemen and gamblers trying to hit the trifecta.
</P>
<P>
   I called Frankel on the phone, thinking maybe I had missed
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, what kind of experiences did you have with
horses?'' I asked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry-go-rounds,'' Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   Just what I thought.
</P>
<P>
   It's not her fault. She didn't know that Georgetown Law School
would lead to playing buckaroo down washboard roads in Palm Beach
County's rural suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   If only she would have known that one day she'd grow up to be a
politician who would find herself in a district that includes, not
only condos packed with aging former New Yorkers _ her bread and
butter _ but also rural communities, where voters live in homes
that have horses as lawnmowers.
</P>
<P>
   If only she had known, she might have made sure she had more
experience with horses of the non-Calliope variety.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't have to suddenly, at middle age, enter a rushed and
awkward cowboy phase.
</P>
<P>
   Her Lois L'Amour period.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Frankel was square dancing with the Loxahatchee
Groves Landowner's Association, and Sunday she was riding a horse
through the Acreage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My knees hurt,'' she said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She was talking about the riding, not the dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever been on a horse before?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my son was younger, we tried doing the cowboy thing,''
she said. ``I took him to a dude ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to be on the safe side, Frankel wore a helmet for Sunday's
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Her equestrian antics made her challenger, Heers, compare it to
him showing up at ``bingo parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel had to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't play bingo in the condos,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No, the poor guy would have to learn mah-jongg if he wants to
make headway there. That's even worse than riding a horse.
</P>
<P>
   The election is on Nov. 3, which means that Frankel has two more
weeks before she goes from horseback to horseradish.
</P>
<P>
   If Frankel's knees don't heal soon, she'll have to give up her
riding and come up with other country-styled campaign events.
</P>
<P>
   So, if I were you, I'd start looking for her to show up at
Moroso Motorsports Park with a mouth full of chaw and a mottled
hound on a short chain. Frankel will be the one wearing the Dixie
T-shirt, eating beef jerky, and riding the big-wheeled mud buggy
with the gun rack on the back and Hank Jr. on the stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
