</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's Magic thinking, trying to replace sorcery in Tyson camp?
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Quick, somebody, find something for
Magic Johnson to do with his time.
</P>
<P>
   To see him in Las Vegas, acting as Mike Tyson's adviser,
promising Nevada boxing regulators that Iron Mike will make them
proud if only he's allowed to pummel people professionally again
instead of as a hobby, well, it's just about the most misguided and
muleheaded use of celebrity sparkle since a young Jane Fonda went
to Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Magic's influence cuts across the whole of American culture,
touching people in ways as unpredictable as they are unprecedented.
Who else could contract the HIV virus and tell the world about it
with a smile? Who else could admit to sleeping around
indiscriminately with female groupies during his days as an NBA
superstar and still retain the more pleasing popular image of a
devoted family man? Who could invest huge amounts of risk capital
in the heart of our nation's crime-ridden inner cities, as Magic
has with his downtown movie and entertainment centers, and make it
work?
</P>
<P>
   Throwing in with Tyson now raises a disturbing question, one
that eventually must be faced by all such wizards. Has Magic grown
bored using his astounding powers only for good, and not evil?
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali can be forgiven his participation in the tawdry
``Free Iron Mike'' crusade. In recent years Ali has come to
represent harmony and healing on an international scale. Even
Saddam Hussein agreed to see the champ on the eve of the Gulf War,
sending 15 U.S. hostages home safely with Ali before the shooting
started. That's the kind of pull that makes a man believe he can
change the world, one obnoxious bully at a time, just by showing up
and making a personal appeal for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Magic should know better, especially when it comes to Tyson.
There is no demonstrated capacity here for learning from life's
mistakes. If there were, one chunk of Evander Holyfield's ear would
have been enough. Tyson lives in a tumult of his own creation and
the only way he knows to come out of it is fighting mad. Call it an
instinct, identified and nurtured by all the bad apples who
overflow boxing's putrid barrel, and perhaps it is a nobler
instinct that draws Johnson near. Magic, after all, specializes in
lending his strength and optimism to seemingly hopeless situations.
He might actually feel sorry for a high-school dropout so
ill-equipped for the demands of a superstar athlete's lifestyle
that he couldn't even keep himself out of prison, much less money
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Merely mixing with this crowd, however, impugns Johnson's
integrity. Proposing to lead them, with all the boxing business
above board and Tyson as the appropriate object of Magic's
boundless energy, is lunacy. This is Don King's court. Magic
doesn't even have next.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed here is another mission for Magic. Something
spectacular and specially suited to his powers of persuasion, like
a seat at the Mideast peace talks, with autographs aplenty to charm
the principals. Or a national bus tour to remind people that the
NBA still exists and hopes to be back in action before the WNBA.
Maybe a space shuttle shot, generating valuable research on the
effects of zero gravity on the immense.
</P>
<P>
   Anything, anything at all, would be preferable to this Tyson
farce. Magic may be enjoying a second life, churning on in robust
health seven years after HIV detection, but he's only got one
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
