</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No longneck, no redneck: Mr. Congeniality
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Here it is, just three days after the winner was
announced, and acrimony and discontent have rocked this newspaper's
Tallest, Truest Texan Contest.
</P>
<P>
   Eric ``Tex'' Simonsen, 28, who grew up in Northwest Hills,
thinks Mark McLendon, the winner who keeps his snuff in his denim
shirt pocket, is too much of a ``redneck'' to hold the title.
</P>
<P>
   Simonsen, who is working on a master's degree in business
administration at the University of Texas at Dallas, thinks
somebody else should have won: him.
</P>
<P>
   McLendon's qualifications for winning the contest included being
in the Too Damn Friendly Bar in Johnson City every night last year
and having once done his Christmas shopping at a truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   Simonsen, who entered the contest, thinks he would have been a
better choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in my heart that I truly am the 'Truest Tallest Texan,'
'' Simonsen wrote in an e-mail to me after McLendon was named the
winner on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Simonsen's favor, no one ran harder to win the coveted title
than he did. Several relatives and friends sent e-mail in
Simonsen's behalf. Shortly before the contest deadline, Simonsen
went to the trouble to send me, by overnight mail, a fancy
promotional kit about himself.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity packet pointed out that Simonsen is ``known as Mr.
Texas, Tex and Texas Boy.'' It included color photos of himself
dressed in western clothing at various spots around the world.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite picture is the one of Tex standing in front of the
Sphinx, and I'm not talking about the professional wrestler. I'm
talking about the actual Sphinx in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In the photo, Tex is the one in the cowboy hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appalled at your choice for the winner of the 'Truest
Tallest Texan' contest,'' Tex wrote in his e-mail. ``I can
understand why you might have picked Mr. McLendon as the biggest
redneck in Texas, but how can someone like that truly represent
Texas and the great things this state stands for?
</P>
<P>
   ``While I don't want to appear to be a sore loser, I do feel
extremely slighted. I have done more throughout the world to
promote the 'Great State of Texas' than any of the people you gave
honorable mentions to. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of people all over the world that have been
made aware of the great things Texas has (to) offer thanks to my
zeal for sharing Texas culture. I feel that not only have you
degraded me personally, you have also degraded the thousands of
Texans that are truly proud of our state and the great place it is
to live in. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   So, OK, Tex has done a passel to spread Texas culture hither and
yon. While a student at Brigham Young University, he started a
barbecue place called Texas Pride Barbecue in Provo, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was up there I realized there was no barbecue, and
that's one of my favorite things about Texas,'' Tex told me Tuesday
over the phone from Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Also while in Provo, Tex promoted the Lone Star State by
throwing an annual Texas block party. Even though it was dry, it
attracted upwards of 350 people.
</P>
<P>
   No beer? That's not a block party. That's a congested area for
no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   Tex says that whenever he travels, he serves as a Texas
ambassador by telling people what a great place Texas is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always talk about Texas and tell them that it's not a
desert,'' he said. ``That's the biggest misconception people
have.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an honorable thing to do. And we don't want anyone to go
away mad because of this contest, which was supposed to be fun. We
want everyone to walk off into the Texas sunset with big ol' smiles
on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   So because of all the trouble Tex has gone to to win this
fandango, I've decided to name him Mr. Congeniality of the Tallest,
Truest Texan Contest.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that if McLendon is unable to perform his
duties as the winner of the Tallest, Truest Texan Contest, Simonsen
will take over and perform them for him.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, I'd like to name Simonsen the contest's
official designated driver.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
