<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX     10-21 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanity _ or the lack thereof
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAL D'ISERE, France _ Even if I die on this mountain, it still
beats traveling through Europe on a Eurail Flexipass.
</P>
<P>
   After that last train trip from Barcelona, Spain to Nice,
France, I knew that I would crawl back to Texas on my hands and
knees beating myself with a mesquite branch before I suffered
through another train ride in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In Nice, I rented a new 5-speed Renault and launched European
Trip Plan Two, which was to explore the back roads and mountain
villages in the European Alps.
</P>
<P>
   For months, I had been looking forward to Plan One, which was to
travel around Europe on a first-class Eurail pass with a long-time
friend, colleague and experienced world traveler. As a child, I
enjoyed riding American passenger trains and sleeping in Pullman
beds. European trains are nicer, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   To better enjoy our first train ride from Paris to Madrid _ a
13-hour overnight trip _ we paid an extra $100 apiece to upgrade
our $500 Eurail passes so we could kick back in our own private
sleeping compartment.
</P>
<P>
   There was no kicking back. We sat shoulder to shoulder in two
seats that faced a beige plastic wall inches from our knees. I've
been in outhouses with more room. We had the bunk beds unfolded so
we could straighten our legs.
</P>
<P>
   The day-trip from Madrid to Barcelona was better. The train was
not sold out, the scenery was interesting and I was learning to
accept rude treatment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the next train trip, from Barcelona to Nice, that put me
in a car in a shrieking blizzard on a narrow, ice-covered mountain
pass in the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
   The first leg of that trip was on a packed, smoke-filled,
rattle-trap commuter train. With no accommodations for travelers
with luggage, simple survival required constant fist-fight
brinkmanship.
</P>
<P>
   The second leg was supposed to be on a first-class, non-smoking
coach with reserved seats. Our reserved seats had been sold at
least twice, which led to more unpleasantness.
</P>
<P>
   After the conductor disappeared, I watched through the glass in
the locked doors that separated first-class from economy class as a
middle-aged man jimmied the locks. This, I thought, must be how the
Romanovs felt when angry, starving peasants breached the palace
walls.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately all empty first-class seats were taken. The doors
were propped open. The new arrivals yelled, joked and filled the
coach with cheap cigarette smoke. By the time we arrived in Nice, I
had not slept in more than 27 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The car gave me back my freedom. I went where I wanted to go and
stopped when I wanted to stop. In mid-October, the hardwood trees
in the French, Italian and Swiss Alps are decked out in yellows,
reds and oranges. Back-road villages and farms appear little
changed from the Middle Ages. Farmers drive cows with big, musical
bells around their necks down the middle of roads. No one is rude.
</P>
<P>
   Small, twisting Alpine roads are a blast to drive, until I got
to this one that became little more than a paved mule trail that
winds its way up over a mountain pass next to a glacier.
</P>
<P>
   A villager on the south side of the pass said I could make it if
I drove slowly. No snow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Near the top, snow blew horizontally so hard that it threatened
to push the car off the tiny icy road with no guard rails. I could
see only a few feet in front of the car. I plowed through snow
drifts and inched around switchbacks.
</P>
<P>
   I unbuckled my seat belt to make it easier to jump if the car
started to go over the side.
</P>
<P>
   But even at it's scariest worst, which was slipping down the
north side of the pass, I knew that I would rather lose my life on
this mountain than my mind on another European train.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas. E-mail: RNeth(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
