<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LINEMAN NOW TRIES TO TACKLE COLLEGE BINGE DRINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It wasn't as if Carl Eller had never been knocked
down before. When you're a defensive lineman, you routinely find
yourself on your back, your butt or your belly.
</P>
<P>
   You get up, though. That's what you do when you play defensive
end. And few men _ maybe no one, actually _ ever played that
position as well as huge, hulking Eller.
</P>
<P>
   He has 134 career sacks; 23 fumble recoveries and nine blocked
kicks. Rookie of the year. Six times all-pro. Twice the National
Football League's most valuable lineman. Four Super Bowl
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but he'd been part of what some football nuts _
including this one _ feel was the best defensive line in NFL
history. Eller, Alan Page, Gary Larsen, Doug Sutherland and Jim
Marshall were the Minnesota Vikings Purple People Eaters.
Collectively, they sacked the quarterback 400 times, recovered 70
fumbles and won 176 games.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Steel Curtain? The New York Giants' goal line squad
of Robustelli &AMP; Co. of the early 1960s? The Deacon Jones-Merlin
Olson combo in Los Angeles? Too Tall Jones, Randy White &AMP;
Associates in Dallas 15 years ago. All good. All very, very good.
But the Purple People Eaters were, quite simply, the very best
ever.
</P>
<P>
   And then 16 years in the NFL had passed for Eller. He'd lost a
few steps, which is all it takes. It all ended for him. Booze and
coke had him by the throat. And then Eller was really down, and he
didn't have a clue as to how to get up. And, after contemplating
suicide, Eller finally found a way to stand on his own two feet
again.
</P>
<P>
   Through sheer force of will, he got clean and sober and has
stayed that way for 18 years. Tuesday, he sat in front of me in a
little office on the campus of the State University of New York at
Albany, his inch-thick fingers folded on the table before him,
grayer and thicker at 56 than when he'd been playing. But still
Carl Eller. Still as big as a milk truck. And, now, a smarter,
calmer, more serene Carl Eller than ever.
</P>
<P>
   He was on one of the two dozen or so visits he makes every year
to college campuses across the country. You might not have heard,
but these college kids have huge booze problems. According to the
Harvard School of Public Health, only one in five of them stays
dry. Two in five are blind drunk at least one night a week.
</P>
<P>
   No other cohort in the population drinks so recklessly, and
college administrations fret over this. This is Alcohol Awareness
Week, and the administration of SUNY-Albany hopes that some of
their kids, at least, pay attention to what Carl Eller has to say.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially that's this: If it can happen to him _ a
disciplined, elite athlete living a severely regimented life _ then
it can happen to anybody. He worries that college kids seem to
believe that drinking on this monumental scale is harmless, merely
a rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   But Eller can tell them from painful experience that serious
boozing _ any substance abuse, really _ has a corrosive effect on
virtually everybody. He knows that he's in an uphill fight, that
he's dealing with young people who feel they're simply entering
into adulthood and partaking of its myriad pleasures. He knows that
the popular conception is that drinking is normal and that
teetotaling is deviation.
</P>
<P>
   But these are smart kids, Eller was saying. Some will get the
point that eluded him until he was 38. Because he came here to warn
them, some will escape the agony he endured.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe _ just maybe, if they listen _ they won't get knocked
down to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
