<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORK-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH VOTE PLAYS KEY ROLE IN TIGHT NEW YORK SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the hotly contested race for U.S. Senate in
New York, incumbent Alfonse D'Amato and his Democratic challenger,
Rep. Charles E. Schumer, are both actively soliciting the Jewish
vote.
</P>
<P>
   In political circles, Jews are courted as a large and powerful
constituency who can make or break candidates in the state.
</P>
<P>
   And in this year's race, which could cost a combined $40
million, every vote counts; polls show D'Amato and Schumer neck and
neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important,'' pollster Lee Miringoff said of the
Jewish vote. Miringoff works at the Marist Institute, an
independent college polling organization in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been in close races before and has eked out
victories because of Jewish support. Six years ago, the senator
edged former Attorney General Robert Abrams, who is Jewish, by a
slim 80,000 votes, garnering 40 percent of the Jewish vote. Any
substantial shift in Jewish voting would have cost D'Amato
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Schumer is carrying the bulk of the Jewish
support, according to the independent Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute in Connecticut. A poll showed Schumer ahead 65 percent to
28 percent among Jewish voters, up from 57 to 34 in mid-September.
Schumer has the advantage of being a Jewish member of Congress from
a Brooklyn district rich in Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Schumer) is doing more of what he ought to be doing,''
said Maurice Carroll, Quinnipiac's polling director. ``He's Jewish.
He's from Brooklyn. He's liberal _ not terribly liberal, but
liberal enough. The Jewish vote tends to be from New York City and
liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, no member of the Senate is more pro-Israel
than D'Amato, who fought hard for the return of assets stolen from
Jewish victims of the Holocaust and deposited in Swiss banks. The
3-term incumbent has long counted on the Jewish vote to repeatedly
defeat Democrats in a state where Republicans remain heavily
outnumbered, particularly in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator D'Amato needs to hold the traditional upstate
Republican vote,'' said Republican consultant Thomas Slater. ``At
the same time, he needs to find constituencies among enrolled
Democrats to vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's downstate ads feature former Mayor Ed Koch endorsing
him. Koch, a Democrat, touts the Republican senator as a ``real
mensch,'' praise meant to draw support from the millions of Jewish
voters in New York City and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``D'Amato has been visible in our community,'' said Rabbi
Matthew Cutler, president of the Capital District Board of Rabbis
in Albany. ``I hear more about this race than any, head and
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Cutler said there was ``a great feeling of distrust
with Alfonse D'Amato ... a degree of skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   While D'Amato's downstate ads focus on the Koch endorsement,
some of the upstate ads with which he is associated have turned off
some Jews. Upstate ads run by D'Amato and the GOP characterize
Schumer and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, also a Jew, as
money-grubbing New York City liberals who have different values
than those outside the New York metropolitan area. The ads, which
run only outside of New York City, exploit tensions between upstate
and downstate.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say the ads deliver an anti-Semitic message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's subtle for the non-Jew, hard to prove for the real Jew,''
said Stephen Silberfarb, deputy executive director of the National
Jewish Democratic Council. ``It feeds into the stereotype of the
New York (City) Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Chartock, a political scientist and commentator in Albany,
doesn't find the ads _ particularly one that suggests Schumer
should stay in heavily Jewish Brooklyn _ in the least bit subtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say `go back to Brooklyn' to a Jewish candidate, it
has to have some repercussions that these very smart people
(Republican political operatives) are aware of,'' Chartock said.
``Those kinds of tactics will always be effective among certain
people.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's aides and Republican powers deny there is an
anti-Semitic intent to the ads. They contend, and some observers
agree, that they are meant only to cast the downstate Democrats in
a liberal light upstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to isolate him as a downstate politician,''
said Miringoff, a Jew. ``I assume the intent of the ad is to deal
with a clear regional difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Jewish Coalition, a pro-Republican group, points
out that D'Amato is the biggest booster of military spending for
Israel. The group is convinced that a senator so friendly to their
interests would not allow his name to be associated with bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Israel isn't the only issue of interest. Jews traditionally are
also interested in support for education, reproductive rights, gun
control, social justice and other issues that have long been high
on Schumer's agenda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
