<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-COMMUNISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG STRUGGLE OVER COMMUNISM IN ITALY ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The long struggle over communism's challenge for power
in Italy ended this week when a former Communist Party leader was
asked to become premier and form the next government in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The naming of Massimo D'Alema marked a milestone not only in
Italian but also in European history.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the premier-designate, who will head Italy's 56th
government since World War II, appointed a 25-member Cabinet that
includes eight holdovers and doubles the number of women to six.
The parliament is expected to vote its approval on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, widely regarded as one of his country's most
intelligent politicians, no longer calls himself a communist. He
heads what is called the Party of the Democratic Left, composed of
remnants of the old Communist Party and some extreme left-wing
socialists.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, he has been the real power behind Prime
Minister Romano Prodi's socialist-leaning government although
holding no cabinet post. Prodi fell Oct. 9 after a parliamentary
vote of no-confidence in a budget dispute.
</P>
<P>
   It had long been thought that D'Alema's communist background
precluded him from leading the government. But Italy's president,
the moderate Oscar-Luigi Scalfaro, who is responsible for choosing
the prime minister subject to parliamentary approval, decided
otherwise. And Pope John Paul II's audience with D'Alema Tuesday
gave him the church's seal of approval.
</P>
<P>
   The new leader is not, of course, about to impose a Marxist
regime on Italy. He couldn't even if he wished to.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, his coming to power ends the postwar saga in which
the United States expended huge financial and political resources
to block a communist takeover in Rome and even prevent the
communists from becoming members of the government. However, for
decades they formed Italy's second most powerful party and were the
largest communist movement in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The communist-anticommunist duel raged almost to the end of the
Cold War in 1991. It deeply damaged Italian society since the
ruling Christian Democrats, who were guaranteed unconditional
American support because of the communist threat, became hopelessly
corrupt and wholly unresponsive to the country's pressing social
needs.
</P>
<P>
   The situation grew so drastic that by the early 1990s, the
Christian Democrats and the other mainstream parties finally
collapsed. Since then, Italy has been struggling to regain
political equilibrium _ with only scant success. It remains the one
major western nation lacking a satisfactory political system.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema's ascent also recalls a far more important piece of 20th
century history.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Benito Mussolini's Fascist movement and its eventual
seizure of power in 1922 was largely in response to the menace of a
communist revolution in Italy after World War I. Mussolini's most
assiduous admirer and imitator was Germany's Adolf Hitler who based
Nazi ideology mainly on the Italian dictator's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   So the story of communism in Italy goes back a long way. It has
now reached its denouement with the coming to power democratically
and undramatically of the mild-mannered, former trade unionist
D'Alema.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
