<SLUG> BC-BUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998, A VINTAGE YEAR FOR BUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's been a banner year for bugs in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   And now there's a good chance that these creatures have been
wriggling, crawling and boring into your home.
</P>
<P>
   Chillier temperatures and shorter days have signaled that it's
time to hole up for the winter. Most of the invaders swarm to the
sunny side of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge is the 19-spotted Asian ladybird beetle, or
Harmonia axyridis, sometimes dubbed the Halloween ladybug.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bartholomew, consumer horticulturist with the Cornell
Cooperative Extension of Albany County, said he received 50 calls
within the last two days of people complaining about another pair
of pests: box elder bugs and western conifer seed bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insects apparently use the siding as a place to rest and
soak up the sun, which brings their body temperature up to where
they are active enough to fly and crawl,'' said Michael Birmingham,
a New York Department of Environmental Conservation forest
entomologist.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them are leaving their mark. ``The box elder bugs have
been terrible this fall. They get stepped on and body fluids create
stains on rugs and flooring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beverley Lyon began noticing the grayish-black bugs with red on
their backs in the spring, but she paid little attention to them
until recently hundreds showed up at her house in Scotia, a town
north of Schenectady, N.Y. Now, getting rid of them stinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you kill them, they smell horrible,'' she said. The
Halloween ladybug is a mercenary of sorts. The U.S. Department of
Agriculture brought the strain into the country as early as 1916 in
the fight against aphids, one of their favorite foods. The beetles
didn't seem to take hold, however, until the last few years when
they have become abundant in the Albany area. The mild winter and
summer gave all bugs a boost in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Barnes, a curator of the insect collection at the New
York State Museum, said it's nearly impossible to give a precise
head count. ``I don't want to give an impression that there has
been a population explosion,'' he said, ``but we have had real
appropriate conditions for great survivorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladybugs are welcomed by those who hold to the old superstition
that they bring good luck. But these creatures also can leave a
stain and stench when you swat them into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes suggests people try to get rid of the ladybugs by
catching their sharp legs on a tissue or vacuuming them up.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, heated houses are less than ideal habitats for
bugs. They need to slow down and hibernate, but the warmth of the
interior instead speeds their metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally they would overwinter in tree cavities or rock
crevices, and that's where the successful populations will end
up,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that enter homes are ill-fated,'' Barnes added with a
chuckle. ``They generally find not only irate homeowners but
unfavorable conditions in heated homes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
