   ``Odgen Nash was onto something when he observed that progress
might have been all right once, but it has gone on for far too
long,'' begins Glicksman in this humorous essay. She fondly recalls
the days when ``a laptop was where you sat a child'' and ``a
compatible interface was what you hoped for on blind dates.''
Echoing the frustration of many a PC user, she wonders, ``Why can't
they write a decent manual, given the thickness of a Russian
novel?'' (slugged:
BC-A-TECHNOPHOBE'S-LAMENT-(HOME-BUSINESS-WEEK)-NYTSF, priority code
r, category code l and b)
