<HEADER>
A8944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-NEWSQ&AMP;A-TWO     10-21 1795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NEWSQ&AMP;A-TWO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS -- SECOND OF TWO PARTS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I understand that only eight states do not have a hate crimes
law of some type. What are those states?
</P>
<P>
   A: Arkansas, Georgia, Hawaii, Indiana, Kansas, New Mexico, South
Carolina and Wyoming have no hate crimes laws for anyone, according
to the Washington-based Human Rights Campaign. Laws in Maryland,
Texas and Utah are ``unclear,'' the organization says. The District
of Columbia and 21 states have hate crimes laws that include sexual
orientation, and 18 states' hate crimes laws do not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: President Clinton recently flew to California on Air Force
One to raise money for Democratic candidates and to visit daughter
Chelsea. How much did this cost, and who pays?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Clinton White House, like those before it, doesn't
calculate or publicly disclose the full scope of the operations _
military, security, transportation, communication and political _
involved every time a president goes on the road. But the White
House has said previously that Air Force One costs $35,300 an hour
to operate. So a 10-hour round-trip flight between Washington and
the West Coast would cost $353,000. The president's trips basically
are federally funded, which means U.S. taxpayers foot the bill, but
when trips such as the one to California include official business
on behalf of the Democratic Party and local political campaigns,
they share some of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned last year about the propriety of partisan
fund-raising tours, Democrats countered by saying they are proper
and even helpful. ``I think it's part of being president,''
Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, said. ``That's just a necessary part of
American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans occupied the White House, the GOP followed a
similar practice using Air Force One, and also encountered
questions. In April 1992, for example, Sen. Dennis DeConcini
(D-Ariz.) said he saw ``something wrong'' about President George
Bush using Air Force One to mix politics with official business.
But Bush's budget director, Richard Darman, pointed out that even
when traveling for political purposes, Bush couldn't escape his
duties as commander in chief, requiring a coterie of security and
other personnel as well as communications, transportation and other
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ricky Williams, the terrific running back for the University
of Texas, pays homage publicly to the late Doak Walker. Can you
give us a history of Walker's athletic accomplishments?
</P>
<P>
   A: A great fan favorite at Southern Methodist University in
Dallas, Walker was a 5-foot-11, 170-pound single-wing tailback who
was named a consensus All-American three years in a row, starting
in 1947. He won the 1948 Heisman Trophy as college football's
outstanding player. The ``Doaker,'' as he was called, was so
popular at SMU that a deck of seats was added to the Cotton Bowl,
SMU's home field, to accommodate all the fans who wanted to watch
him play. His coach, Matty Bell, said of him, ``Some called it
luck, others called it destiny, but Doak has a natural knack for
pulling off great deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker joined the NFL's Detroit Lions in 1950. Despite his size,
he promptly led the league in scoring with 128 points and was named
both rookie of the year and an All-Pro at halfback. A remarkably
versatile player, he scored 534 points during his six-year NFL
career, during which the Lions won two NFL championships. Although
the Lions offered Walker a big contract to return in 1956, he chose
to retire to pursue business interests in his native Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Williams honored Walker by wearing his No. 37 Oct. 10 in the
Texas-Oklahoma game at the Cotton Bowl. Williams and Walker became
friends last season when Williams received the Doak Walker Award,
which goes to the nation's best running back. Just weeks after the
two met, Walker was seriously injured in a skiing accident in
Colorado that left him paralyzed. He died last month at 71 from
complications from those injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the Bilderberg group? The New York Times refers to it
as ``the most elite of the establishment clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   A: The Bilderbergers include about 100 of Europe and North
America's most influential bankers, economists, politicians and
government officials. They meet yearly for a three-day conference,
always conducted in a rigid atmosphere of security, that
occasionally gives rise to various conspiracy theories about the
group's aims. But the Bilderbergers say the required pledge of
delegates not to discuss what goes on at their meetings is simply
to provide a private, informal environment in which those who
influence national policies and international affairs can get to
know each other and discuss, without commitment, their common
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The conferences were initiated by Prince Bernhard of the
Netherlands in 1954. Meeting locations vary. This year's session
was held in May at Turnberry resort in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there an address where we can send donations and messages
of condolence to the family of Matthew Shepard, the gay student
from Laramie, Wyo., who died after being savagely beaten?
</P>
<P>
   A: Donations can be made to: Matthew Shepard Fund (1926083), c/o
1st National Bank, P.O. Box 578, Fort Collins, CO 80522. Poudre
Valley Hospital in Fort Collins, where the student died, has set up
an e-mail address for Shepard's family: mshepard(at)libra.pvh.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article mentioned an apparition in Portugal in 1917 in
which the Virgin Mary told three secrets to some children. Is it
known what the secrets were?
</P>
<P>
   A: The secrets, revealed by the Virgin Mary to three Portuguese
cousins in a series of visions while they were tending sheep in
Fatima, Portugal, were written down by Lucia dos Santos _ the sole
survivor of the three and now a 91-year-old nun _ and passed to the
Vatican in 1944. They are held in the Vatican and have never been
published.
</P>
<P>
   But a report last year in The Times of London offered some
information, saying the Vatican was seeking to reassure Italians
about widespread fears that Umbrian earthquakes presaged a
premillennial disaster, possibly the end of the world. That
apocalyptic doom was said to be the third secret of Fatima, to
which only the pope and his closest advisers have access.
</P>
<P>
   The Times went on to disclose speculation about the first and
second secrets. The first is said to offer a hellish vision of
``charred bodies in an ocean of fire,'' a possible forecast of
World War II, coupled with a message to the world to repent. The
second, disclosed in 1942 by Cardinal Ildefonso Schuster of Milan,
Italy, was that Russia, which was in the grip of its Marxist
revolution at the time of the visions, would ``spread her errors
throughout the world, causing wars and persecution,'' but ultimate
disaster would be averted if Russia reconverted to Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last Oct. 21, Loris Francesco Capovilla, the
former secretary to Pope John XXIII, said the third secret
contained no ``deadline of doom,'' adding that it is not linked to
the end of the millennium as people have claimed. He told the
Italian newspaper La Stampa that he couldn't reveal what the third
secret was, but talk of ``millions of deaths'' was inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that Georgia ranks as one of the
worst states in the nation in a survey on the amount of ozone
pollution. What states have the least ozone pollution?
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. Public Interest Research Group in Washington
analyzed air quality data from most states and the District of
Columbia and ranked them by the number of ``unhealthy smog days.''
Nine states were not included because there's little or no publicly
available data; 14 other states were included, even though only
partial data was available. Of the remainder that were ranked,
these were found to have the fewest violations of the stricter
ozone pollution standard issued last year by the Environmental
Protection Agency: South Carolina (lowest), followed in order by
Oklahoma, Illinois, Vermont, Rhode Island, New Hampshire, Colorado,
Maine, Massachusetts and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported that food stamps can be used only for food or
food products for human consumption. I once overheard a grocery
store manager saying they could be used only for foods grown or
processed in the United States. Virginia ham was acceptable, for
example, but canned Polish ham was not. Is that still true?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are no restrictions on the origin of the foods that can
be purchased with food stamps, said Susan Acker of the Department
of Agriculture's Food and Nutrition Service. But that wasn't always
the case. When the food stamp program was a pilot project between
1961 and 1964, the stamps were restricted to foods or food products
either grown or processed in the United States. However, when the
program officially started, that restriction was dropped and
recipients could use stamps for foods from anywhere: Caviar from
Russia or peanuts from Georgia were equally acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there an e-mail address for the national Democratic party?
</P>
<P>
   A: To contact the Democratic National Committee by e-mail, go to
its Web site _ www.democrats.org/contact.html _ and sign the guest
book form.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Rose Mary Woods, the personal secretary
for Richard Nixon who was involved in the infamous Watergate tape?
</P>
<P>
   A: Woods, 80, who remained on Nixon's staff until 1976, has
lived in Alliance, Ohio, since retirement. Her biggest claim to
fame involved a mysterious gap of 18 1/2 minutes in a crucial
Watergate tape recording. In testimony before Chief U.S. District
Judge John J. Sirica on Nov. 8, 1973, Woods reacted angrily to
suggestions that she might have accidentally altered or erased any
of the conversation on the tapes she was making transcripts from.
</P>
<P>
   But in testimony soon afterward, she had a different attitude,
explaining that when the telephone rang while she was transcribing
from the tape, she ``must have pushed the record button, which is
right next to the top button (on the recording machine).'' The
result was a gap of four or five minutes. She always denied that
she could have caused the full 18 1/2-minute gap, but White House
files made public in 1995 indicate that Nixon White House lawyers
blamed her for the full gap, and believed she caused it
intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Articles last year tracing the whereabouts of a number of
Watergate figures included only a brief mention of Woods, who
apparently doesn't talk to reporters. She said only that she
doesn't get asked about Watergate much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
