<HEADLINE>
SEMINARY REVISES FACULTY GUIDELINES: TEACHERS MUST SIGN SUBMISSION
STATEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Board members of Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary have changed a bylaw to require faculty
members to sign the updated version of the denomination's statement
of faith that includes a passage stating that women must ``submit
graciously'' to their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Tuesday endorses an administrative move made weeks
ago that has brought strong opposition from some faculty members.
Some are concerned that the seminary is changing the rules of
employment, others worry that being required to sign the statement
could be a move toward curtailing academic freedom and others fully
support signing the updated statement, said Dan G. Kent, a
professor who specializes in the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue has caused a great deal of heartache and concern,''
he said. ``The faculty has been carrying a terrible burden for the
past several weeks. I hurt for them. I wish there was some way it
could have been avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent, who has taught at the seminary for 19 years, said he would
not sign the updated statement. Friday, he handed in a letter
announcing his retirement, but he declined to discuss his reasons
for retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think something that significant is ever based on one
issue,'' Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's vote came without discussion as the board, meeting for
its biannual session, approved an amendment to a section of bylaws
referring to the statement of faith that faculty members must sign.
Instead of calling it the 1963 Baptist Faith and Message, the rules
now identify the document as the Baptist Faith and Message, which
includes an article on the family that was approved by the Southern
Baptist Convention in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of conviction and conscience, as an SBC
institution, we gladly teach according and not contrary to the
Baptist Faith and Message,'' seminary President Ken Hemphill said
in a prepared statement. ``We are under the patronage, general
direction and control of the SBC which established the Baptist
Faith and Message and amended in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   The request for faculty members to sign the updated statement
came from the seminary administration in September, seminary
spokesman David Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   Porter said that there is no deadline for faculty members to
sign the statement and that the administration will not seek out
professors for their signatures.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who cannot teach according to the statement will be
expected to contact the department dean and may have to step down,
Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our faculty manual specifies that when a faculty member can no
longer subscribe to the seminary's articles of faith, he or she
would voluntarily sever relations with the institution,'' Hemphill
said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   The family addition to the Baptist Faith and Message states that
``the husband and wife are of equal worth before God.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also includes a section stating that ``a wife is to
submit graciously to the servant leadership of her husband even as
the church willingly submits to the headship of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the statement was approved by convention delegates, there
are some in the Southern Baptist community who have concerns about
the updated message, said Joe E. Trull, professor of Christian
ethics at New Orleans Baptist Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Some fault the process by which the document was developed.
Others are concerned that the added article represents only one
interpretation of certain passages of the Bible, Trull said.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist Faith and Message is not a creed, said Jeff B. Pool,
a former seminary professor who is a lecturer in theology at Brite
Divinity School in Fort Worth. It is ``a guide in interpretation,
having no authority over the conscience,'' he said, quoting the
preamble of the faith statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that the practice of the seminary and the
convention itself of enforcing these things as creeds contradicts
the very document they are using to do the enforcing,'' said Pool,
who left the seminary in part because of a conflict with the
administration over the Baptist Faith and Message statement.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
