<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGING WAR, IN AND OUT OF THE RING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   BENJAMIN NETANYAHU: American pundits and politicians seem to be
in near-unanimous agreement that the slow pace of
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks is the fault of Netanyahu. The
Israeli prime minister is too rigid, they say, too reluctant to go
the extra mile in his dealings with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is looking out for the best interests of his people _
and those interests do not include giving away the farm just to
create the illusion that peace has been achieved. Arafat and the
Palestinians have vowed to destroy Israel and there is no reason to
believe they won't do it if given half a chance. Here's hoping
Netanyahu hangs tough in the face of Palestinian hostility and
American meddling in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: Meddling? Did I say meddling? Surely, the
president of the United States wouldn't compromise Israel's
security for the cynical purpose of pressuring Netanyahu into an
agreement that the White House PR machine could trumpet as a
foreign policy triumph. Would he?
</P>
<P>
   As long as Clinton has this impeachment cloud hanging over him,
darn near anything he does in the arena of international relations
will look like some sort of ``Wag the Dog'' scenario. It may not be
fair, but it's what can happen when a president squanders his
credibility _ and this president is a charter member of the
Credibility Squanderer Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   MIKE MCCURRY: Clinton's former press secretary made his debut on
the lecture circuit the other night and promptly capitalized on his
newly won independence _ McCurry quit the White House Oct. 1 _ by
taking a shot at his ex-boss.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``is an enormously gifted and richly qualified leader
for our nation but someone who is exasperatingly stupid in his
personal life,'' McCurry said in a speech at the University of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: ``exasperatingly stupid.'' A CNN news anchor
quipped that McCurry must have already cashed that White House
severance check.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN KASICH: Most of the political deep-thinkers who've been
speculating about the 2000 presidential race list Texas Gov. George
W. Bush as the front-runner for the Republican nomination. And they
figure his toughest competition _ if any _ will come from the likes
of Steve Forbes, Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle ...
</P>
<P>
   You know, the usual suspects, a lackluster covey of proven
losers and assorted retreads.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if Bush runs he will win and none of the has-beens or
never-weres will make him break a sweat. The only Republican who
might be capable of giving Bush an anxious moment or two is Ohio
Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee and
Congress' most dynamic crusader for balanced budgets. Kasich is an
emerging star of the Republican Party and could very well lead the
pack of also-rans as Bush cruises to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, Kasich would be a terrific running mate for
Bush. A Bush-Kasich ticket could set up the GOP to control the
presidency for 16 years _ maybe enough time for the Democrats to
live down Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   MIKE TYSON: The Nevada Athletic Commission made the right
decision Monday when it voted to give the ex-heavyweight champion a
license to box. The commission had revoked Tyson's license in July
1997 after he bit Evander Holyfield's ears in one of the most
bizarre spectacles in the history of the bizarre sport of prize
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The biting incident shocked and horrified the nation _ an
interesting reaction in view of Tyson's well-established reputation
as a bloodthirsty head-hunter in the ring and a violent sociopath
on the street. How could anyone be surprised that the most brutal
of sports is populated by the most brutal of humans?
</P>
<P>
   Thank heaven for the occasional gentleman fighter _ Holyfield
being the most admirable example these days _ but the truth is,
plenty of professional boxers are just plain thugs. Tyson has as
much right as any other thug to pursue a livelihood in the Sport of
Thugs.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
