<HEADER>
A8988 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAZZLEDPARENT-COLUMN     10-21 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLEDPARENT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SAY KNOW ... 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I guess I always knew that, someday, everything I learned in the
pursuit of my liberal arts degree would become completely useless
when it came to helping my kids with their academic development. I
suspected that this would happen during their high school years as
they delved into logarithmic equations and beyond-DOS computer
programming. But now I see I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know that it's all over by second grade.
</P>
<P>
   In second grade, a child enters a stage of inquisition. Lying in
wait on his lips at all times are those dreaded words: Who, What,
When, Where and _ most irritating _ Why.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 years of age my son, Jack, became an intellectual
velociraptor, devouring the knowledge he ripped out of my mind,
leaving me exhausted in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   I learned to dread the signs of his reasoning mind.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it began with a deceptively simple question. But as
Jack considered my response, his eyebrows would furrow together and
then one would rise slowly, cynically, and I would know it was
coming.
</P>
<P>
   I was about to learn that I didn't know a thing.
</P>
<P>
   To the best of my recollection, Jack's Age of Reason began one
Independence Day. On the way to a parade, I made some comment about
how much fun it was to celebrate the nation's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean by birthday, Mom?'' asked Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, on this day, in 1776, the leaders of our country signed
the Declaration of Independence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who were they, Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Thomas Jefferson. And John Hancock, and....'' My voice
started to trail. Did he expect me to remember more? He did.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Washington, Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ummmmm...'' Uh-oh. I was an American history major, true, but
couldn't we talk about societal patterns between the two world
wars?
</P>
<P>
   ``What did the declaration say, Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   My mind started to reel: Four score and seven years ago ... no,
that wasn't it. We the People. ... No, no. Anyway, he didn't need
the exact wording. Just the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said,'' I said with confidence, ``that we were no longer
going to be ruled by England. That's what started the Revolutionary
War...''
</P>
<P>
   Wait, what about Lexington and Concord, I wondered. Did the
Declaration come during the war? While I was feeling stupid, Jack's
brow was furrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't they like England, Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   The phrases ``tea party'' and ``taxation without
representation'' floated through my mind, but the details weren't
there. Luckily, though, the parade was. So we dropped the
discussion and launched into flag-waving.
</P>
<P>
   Matters grew worse in the fall. This questioning-and-thinking
thing seemed to be actually encouraged in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does a microchip work?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What time is it in China right this now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does Pluto change places with Neptune?''
</P>
<P>
   I began to wonder just what it might be that I do know.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how to form my letters in the D'Nealian style. I
don't know how many books Eric Carle has written. I don't why
koalas are not bears.
</P>
<P>
   After one particularly agonizing afternoon, I told Jack I was
going to seal his mouth shut with duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's duct tape, Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   Ah-ha. An easy one. I had just heard a radio program on the very
topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Jack, it was a brown tape invented for soldiers who
needed a tape that wouldn't get weaker when it got wet. They called
it `duck tape' because water ran right off it, like water runs off
a duck's feathers. After the war, they changed the color to silver
and used it to repair air-conditioning and heating units. The name
was changed to `duct tape.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jack's brow furrowed. I was ready for the ``What's a duct?''
question. I got this: ``Which one is powerfuller, duct tape or red
tape?''
</P>
<P>
   When, in the course of human events a man or woman should decide
to rear a child, accept this truth to be self-evident: You'll never
know as much as a second-grader.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
