<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9009 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HN     10-21 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Oct. 21, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file or has filed these
stories for Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)    For Thursday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICAN-REVOLT _ (Washington) _ A surprising number of Senate
Republicans rebel against their party's leadership to oppose the
colossal $520 billion spending package approved by the Senate. The
renegades complain that the 40-pound document represents a failure
of Congress to follow its own rules. Most senators, they say, knew
little about the budget's contents when they voted. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-VISAS (Washington) _ The $520 billion spending bill
approved by Congress Wednesday includes a big bonus for Silicon
Valley _ a provision that would almost double the number of
employment visas for foreign computer programmers and others with
high-tech skills. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-DRINKS (Washington) _ Americans consume twice as much soda
pop as they did 25 years ago, says a new study by the Center for
Science in the Public Interest. The result _ especially for
teen-agers, who typically down two to three 12-ounce cans a day _
is more medical problems including obesity and tooth decay. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-COMMUNISM (Paris) _ already filed _ The naming of Massimo
D'Alema, a former Communist Party leader, as Italy's new premier
marks a milestone not only in Italian but also in European history.
By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Fulton, Mo.) _ Through a strange convergence of
events, this college town in central Missouri has attained a
symbolic status in the saga of the Cold War that for more than 40
years divided East and West. It was here that Winston Churchill
coined the term ``iron curtain.'' By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
