<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNERS LACK DIRECTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As the spring 1999 ready-to-wear collections spin from
one ``arrondissement'' to the next, hither and yon across this City
of Light, the view of fashionable women in the year before the
millennium grows dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Often, figuring out fashion is like looking through a
kaleidoscope, then putting the bits and pieces together to form the
image of a woman a la mode for the next six months. But here, now,
the pieces do not connect. Each designer has his or her own vision
and, except for a few loose trends, the twain not only don't meet,
they don't even exchange e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chanel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there is a direction, it might be the fuzzy one found in Karl
Lagerfeld's collections for Chanel. They left editors and buyers
scratching their heads _ surely a signal that fashion is indeed in
flux.
</P>
<P>
   Held at the Opera National de Paris Bastille (many call it the
``new opera''), the show consisted of models winding their way down
multiple stories in the foyers. Guests on the lower levels heard
end-of-show applause before laying eyes on two-thirds of the
garments.
</P>
<P>
   Those they could see were bound to have been confusing. Only one
ensemble, the white woven wool suit with tiny cropped jacket and
hip-hung skirt that began the show, bore any resemblance to a
traditional Chanel suit. The model carried a cute, coral miniature
version of the ergonomically shaped 2005 bag.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a coral suit, with ribbons of glittering metallic
threads woven through its wrap-and-shrug jacket and plastic cuff
bracelets stacked up the model's arm.
</P>
<P>
   There was a backless blouse; an orange leather jacket; shiny
nylon pants; a large group of silvery, pearlescent Space Age
sportswear separates; and chiffon-hooded sweat jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts and pants trailed ribbons and panels. Finished seams on
lacquered cotton garments were turned to the outside. Chiffon tops
were worn over denim pants and skirts. And beige was dotted
throughout the collection _ not basic beige, in which a woman could
seek security, but a buff tone, more like a pale flesh color.
</P>
<P>
   Evening wear might be a different matter, however. Taffeta
skirts in purple, brown or navy, with panels sewn to overlap like
petals, were some of the more pleasing designs (but the same
executed in white tulle looked too young for the Chanel customer).
But then, with music that ran from ``Disco to Disco'' to ``Funk
Soul Brother,'' who is to say what woman will begin saving her
francs to buy into a new Chanel image?
</P>
<P>
   Sequins in black, coral, baby blue and white dripped down a
skirt like paint, making a piece so nice you might want to hang it
on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld has shaken fashion to its roots in the past, and he is
sure to do it again. Is this collection a bellwether or only a
blip? Lagerfeld's greatest asset is his unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Givency &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other designers also sought the emerging modern woman, trying to
take their designs past the Space Age modernity of the '60s _ some
with greater success than others. Alexander McQueen, fresh from
rave reviews of his signature collection in London, cut some ersatz
modern shapes, including draped cape-back jersey dresses and
black-gray-white cubist sequined-top dresses and tunics.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen did a fine job of turning out pieces more fluid than the
stiff suits he has produced for Givenchy so far. But the collection
lacked direction and the sense of importance one might expect of
the label.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Thierry Mugler &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thierry Mugler's collection, on the other hand, flew straight as
an arrow. There were dramatic single batwing sleeves, jersey
sheaths, a half yellow dress-half white pantsuit ensemble, and
pants with huge bites taken out of the front legs. Froufrou and
colorful ruffled chiffons, which closed the show, were fun to watch
but a tad young for the Mugler customer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
