<HEADLINE>
MISUNDERSTOOD BATS MYSTIFY, HORRIFY, ... POLLINATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAI HUYNH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If there's an animal that could use an image
consultant, it's the bat. Hollywood hasn't helped, portraying the
winged critter as a bloodsucking vampire and a dark, moody
superhero.
</P>
<P>
   But the world would be very different without these creatures of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Benson of the Austin-based Bat Conservation International
detailed the economic and ecological importance of bats as the
first speaker in the Zoological Society of Houston's 1998-99 Shell
Oil Co. Foundation Lecture Series on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Without bats, many plants would not get pollinated, Benson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bats are also one of Mother Nature's best pest controllers: A
small brown bat can catch up to 1,200 mosquito-size insects in just
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In his lecture, titled ``Champions of the Night: The Amazing
World of Bats,'' Benson dispelled popular misconceptions about
bats.
</P>
<P>
   One common fallacy is that bats are filthy; in reality, they're
among the cleanest of animals and very resistant to disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bats are definitely among the most misunderstood animals,'' he
said. ``Like ... snakes, spiders and sharks, there are a lot of old
myths and stereotypes associated with bats.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
