<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY LOSSES FORCED BANKER TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Analysts believe the sudden resignation Tuesday
of BankAmerica Corp. President David Coulter was prompted by losses
due to speculative investments, and that he was not forced out by
the bank's new chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in its first earnings report since its merger last
month with NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C., the new BankAmerica
startled investors by writing off $372 million of a $1.4 billion
loan to the D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co. in New York, a hedge fund that makes
speculative investments. The bank also took a $238 million loss on
Russian government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, a big supporter of the hedge fund, ignored warnings
from his risk-management executives and stayed loyal to the hedge
fund, one investment manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coulter promoted and oversaw the D.E. Shaw transaction, and
when it blew up in his face, he's the one responsible for it,''
said Brian Edgar, director of research for the Sife Trust Fund in
Walnut Creek, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to start off on a bad note like this. There has
always been speculation as to whether Coulter would remain, but no
one expected him to leave within 30 days of the merger,'' Edgar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter said he would remain at the bank through Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts interviewed for this story doubt that Coulter, a
22-year veteran of BankAmerica, was forced out by Hugh McColl, the
bank's new chairman and the chief executive of NationsBank before
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, Coulter and the new bank's board of directors had a
powerful, vested interest in making the merger of equals work, the
analysts say. Furthermore, they say, Coulter commanded respect in
the industry as a hands-on executive who oversaw several successful
sales and acquisitions and division makeovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was imperative for both sides to succeed and blend their
strengths into a universal bank,'' said Jay Tejera, a banking
analyst at Dain Rauscher in Minneapolis. ``That was the spirit of
the deal, and how it came together.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief resignation statement released Tuesday from
Charlotte, Coulter said: ``The decision was extremely difficult for
me, both personally and professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter praised BankAmerica as ``a strong, stable and sound
financial institution'' with a rich heritage and thousands of
``talented and dedicated'' employees.
</P>
<P>
   McColl called Coulter ``a man of the highest integrity.'' He
added: ``It is very painful for me personally to accept his
resignation. We wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   During a shareholders meeting last month to vote on the merger,
McColl defended Coulter's actions. NationsBank announced earlier
this year that it was acquiring San Francisco-based BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   According to one angry BankAmerica director, McColl misled the
old BankAmerica board about Coulter's future earlier this year. In
private meetings before the merger agreement was signed, McColl,
63, vowed that he would retire in two years, so Coulter, 51, could
succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad situation,'' the board director said Tuesday.
``Dave is a great guy, a very good strategic thinker who knows the
business. You can't find a better CEO than that. But perhaps he
trusted a guy by the name of McColl whom he shouldn't have
trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter's pink slip stunned BankAmerica employees. Just last
month, Coulter had reassured workers in a companywide voice mail
that he wouldn't abandon the bank in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked about the market turmoil in Asia and a couple of
other matters,'' said one veteran bank executive who asked not to
be named. ``But the key thing was he indicated his intention to
stick around for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and fund managers said that Coulter was well-regarded
in banking circles for reigning in the big, slow-moving
BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has enormous respect throughout the industry,'' Tejera
said. ``He really got the ball rolling after a long period of
stodgy profitability and growth for BankAmerica.''
</P>
<P>
   While Coulter will depart with a golden parachute of $29
million, he also was due to be awarded 300,000 BankAmerica shares
over a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the losses were announced, BankAmerica was sued by
shareholders, who alleged that the bank failed to disclose its
hedge-fund exposure while shareholders were voting on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., called for an
inquiry into whether the Office the Comptroller of the Currency
encouraged BankAmerica to delay disclosure of a multimillion-dollar
loss to a hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Tejera said the hedge fund issue wasn't the only problem for
BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a quarter for the banking Hall of Fame,'' Tejera
said. ``There are a number of smoking guns you can point to:
Securities trading. Investments in emerging markets. Mortgage
banking issues. All of those played a part in the weak quarterly
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts anticipate more writeoffs in the coming fiscal quarters
for BankAmerica. The bank had estimated $1.6 billion in
merger-related charges, including severance pay for executives,
writing off old software, paying for new advertising, and
stationery costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
