<SLUG> BC-BAT-MAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATS IN YOUR BELFRY? CALL A BAT MAN  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAI HUYNH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Phillip Lindhurst is a bat man.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't look anything like Hollywood's Michael Keaton or
George Clooney, though. More like Tim Allen's ``Tool Time'' helper,
moonlighting in the bat exclusion business.
</P>
<P>
   While most bats prefer safe havens such as trees, caves or the
undersides of bridges, as a last resort they may inhabit attics or
walls, getting in through tiny crevices in roofs or eaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This occurs more frequently than people think,'' Lindhurst
said. ``Chances are the bats have been in the homes for years, but
the people don't know they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   A general contractor by trade, Lindhurst excludes bats in his
spare time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't get rich,'' he said. What he does get is a lot of
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bats are so misunderstood,'' said Lindhurst, 44, pointing out
their importance as pest controllers and pollinators. ``They're
beneficial, but you don't want them living in your house.''
</P>
<P>
   There are six species of bats found in the Houston area,
including brown bats and the Mexican free-tails. Although bat guano
makes a great fertilizer, it can bring tears to the eyes from its
overpowering and earthy ammonia scent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be very offensive, but I'm used to it,'' said
Lindhurst, who is one of only a few bat excluders in the Houston
area.
</P>
<P>
   Bat excluders ``are the people who are knowledgeable about ways
to get bats out of buildings that don't harm the bats,'' according
to Barbara French, information specialist for Bat Conservation
International. To find a bat excluder in your area, call the
Austin-based group at 800-538-2287.
</P>
<P>
   October is a busy time for Lindhurst. Baby bats, which are
usually born in June, are now grown and able to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't exclude them until then,'' he said, explaining that
the mothers would be unable to return, and the babies would die
from starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Lindhurst uses no chemicals, and the bats suffer no physical
harm thanks to a simple exclusion technique that he demonstrated
one afternoon on the roof of a southwest Houston condo.
</P>
<P>
   Using a utility knife, he cut soft wire mesh to size, then
draped and stapled it over a hole the size of a golf ball in an
angle of the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can stick your pinky in the hole, the bats can get
in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun sets, the bats will crawl out for food, but the
wire mesh will prevent them from flying back in. Later, after all
the bats have vacated, he will caulk the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Along with excluding bats, Lindhurst wants to build a large bat
house that would accommodate thousands of the creatures. He's
currently rallying support for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, all we're doing is just chasing them from house to
house. My goal is to see a refuge for the bats established in a
nonresident area within the city. This way we can enjoy the
benefits of bats, but without the inconveniences they cause in the
home.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
