<SLUG> BC-BAT-QUIZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S FACT, WHAT'S FICTION? TAKE THE BAT TEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAI HUYNH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bat quiz
</P>
<P>
   To find out what's fact and fiction, take this bat quiz. Items
1-12 are true or false statements; 13-20 are multiple choice. The
answers are from Bat Conservation International. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. All bats are blind and use a sonar system to fly and catch
their prey.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bats are rodents, similar to mice.
</P>
<P>
   3. A colony of 150 big brown bats can protect local farmers from
up to 33 million or more rootworms each summer.
</P>
<P>
   4. In Texas, it's against the law to kill bats.
</P>
<P>
   5. All bats are blood suckers.
</P>
<P>
   6. The Chinese view bats as symbols of good luck, prosperity and
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   7. About half of all rain forest mammal species are bats.
</P>
<P>
   8. Some bats feed on the nectar and pollen of night-blooming
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   9. All bats are rabid.
</P>
<P>
   10. Bats can become entangled in people's hair.
</P>
<P>
   11. Bat droppings are mined and used on cereal.
</P>
<P>
   12. Bat houses provide a much-needed artificial habitat for
bats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   13. &UR;  &LR; How many different kinds of species are found in the world?
</P>
<P>
   A. 100
</P>
<P>
   B. 200
</P>
<P>
   C. 500
</P>
<P>
   D. 1,000
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   14. &UR;  &LR; The world's smallest mammal is thought by many to be the
bumblebee bat of Thailand. It weighs less than:
</P>
<P>
   A. A feather
</P>
<P>
   B. A penny
</P>
<P>
   C. A banana
</P>
<P>
   D. A hockey puck
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   15. The world's largest bat species have wingspans of nearly how
long?
</P>
<P>
   A. 3 feet
</P>
<P>
   B. 4 feet
</P>
<P>
   C. 6 feet
</P>
<P>
   D. 8 feet
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   16. What type of alcohol is produced from the agave plant, whose
seed production drops without bat pollinators?
</P>
<P>
   A. Gin
</P>
<P>
   B. Scotch
</P>
<P>
   C. Tequila
</P>
<P>
   D. Vodka
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   17. What percentage of American bat species are in severe
decline or are already listed as endangered?
</P>
<P>
   A. 10 percent
</P>
<P>
   B. 15 percent
</P>
<P>
   C. 30 percent
</P>
<P>
   D. 50 percent
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   18. Vampire bats represent less than one-third of 1 percent of
bat species. Where do they live?
</P>
<P>
   A. Australia
</P>
<P>
   B. North America
</P>
<P>
   C. Transylvania
</P>
<P>
   D. Latin America
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   19 &UR; . &LR;  Among the oldest mammals on Earth, bats have been around
for:
</P>
<P>
   A. 2 billion years
</P>
<P>
   B. 50 million years
</P>
<P>
   C. 1 million years
</P>
<P>
   D. 100 years
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   20. Of the 45 species of bats in the United States, how many can
be found in Texas?
</P>
<P>
   A. 10
</P>
<P>
   B. 21
</P>
<P>
   C. 33
</P>
<P>
   D. 18
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANSWERS:
</P>
<P>
   1. False. Not only can bats see, but they also use echo-location
to detect objects as fine as human hair. 2. False 3. True 4. True
5. False 6. True 7. True 8. True 9. False. About half of 1 percent
of all free-flying bats around the world may have contracted
rabies. 10. False 11. False 12. True. 13. D 14. B 15. C 16. C 17. D
18. D 19. B 20. C. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
