<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-MITCHELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL BELIEVES PEACE WILL ENDURE IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After more than three years spent brokering a
historic peace accord in Northern Ireland, George J. Mitchell had
not fully comprehended the courage of the Irish people until he met
15-year-old Claire Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mitchell accompanied President Clinton and Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain to meet grieving families who lost
loved ones in an August bomb blast in Omagh that killed 29 people
and wounded more than 200 others.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell told the story to a hushed, sold-out crowd of 1,200
people Tuesday night in the gymnasium of the College of Saint Rose
in Albany. He said the gym reminded him of the one in Omagh where
he tried to comfort yet more innocent victims of a three-decade
cycle of sectarian violence that has pitted Protestants against
Catholics and claimed 3,500 lives in British-ruled Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallagher girl was ``tall, gangly and lovely,'' Mitchell
said. She is an aspiring pianist who had both of her eyes blown out
in the blast and she wore ``two large patches where her eyes had
been.'' And still the disfigured girl ``poignantly, trying to be
courageous, spoke of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Senate majority leader and Northern Ireland
peacemaker always returned to the touchstone of ordinary people as
the bedrock of international diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the May 22 public referendum on the Good Friday
peace accord was the first all-island vote in 80 years, and that 85
percent of those who voted _ both Catholics and Protestants _
supported peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have spoken,'' said Mitchell, who represented Maine
in the Senate from 1980 to 1994. ``The people do not want to go
back to the bitterness and violence of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   He said splinter groups that seek to derail the peace process _
such as the offshoot of the Irish Republican Army, the Real IRA,
that planted the Omagh bomb _ had no broad support. ``The Real IRA
was not speaking for their communities,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Mitchell told the editorial board of the Albany
Times Union he remains ``cautiously optimistic'' that the fragile
peace will move forward and that disputes will arise in the coming
months and years, but ``compromise and cooperation'' will carry the
day.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the notion that the outstanding issue of disarming
the IRA will destroy the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he did not take it as a personal slight that he
was not named a winner of the Nobel Peace Prize for his involvement
in the Northern Ireland peace process. The prize was awarded to two
other players in Northern Ireland, David Trimble, Protestant head
of the Ulster Unionist Party, and John Hume, head of the Catholic
Social Democratic and Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   But he would have liked to make Nobel recipients out of the
leaders of all eight political parties involved and the Irish and
British governments, too. ``It made sense to me to include
everybody who took the risk for peace,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
