<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9029 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAVORS-FOOD-2TAKES-H     10-21 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAVORS-FOOD-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAVORS OF FALL TITILLATE TASTE BUDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're younger than 25, you may never have eaten a turnip, a
rutabaga or a beet. But new generations are discovering these and
other somewhat obscure vegetables thanks to adventurous cooks and
restaurants. And they're learning just how delicious root
vegetables can be with pures, baked and roasted vegetables, slaws
and salads.
</P>
<P>
   October signals the beginning of the fall harvest season. Many
crops were affected by the drought earlier in the year and the
devastating floods that followed, especially in West Texas and the
Rio Grande Valley, but there will be a good supply of squash,
turnips, rutabagas and carrots, says Michael Marx, assistant
produce merchandiser for Kroger in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   David Asher, produce category manager for Randalls in Houston,
says many drought-plagued farmers didn't plant seasonal crops
because of water restrictions. Since grocery chains fill in with
produce from other areas, especially California and Florida, and
Asher doesn't foresee shortages.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that prices should be about the same or a
little cheaper because of last year's bad winter, which drove
prices up. Because the hot weather has extended into October, many
recently planted winter crops are already sprouting. That may mean
they will peak earlier and that some will be harder to find around
their normal time, the holidays, so prices may rise.
</P>
<P>
   Look for good buys in hard-shell squash and locally grown greens
and herbs, Marx said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small but consistent demand for turnips, rutabagas
and beets, generally in October and November, Marx said. People
often ignore root vegetables because they require more preparation
and cooking time than convenience products such as packaged carrots
and salad mixes.
</P>
<P>
   Before old-fashioned vegetables become an endangered species,
give them a try. Roast turnips, rutabagas and potatoes for a
vegetable platter. Add beets to a salad. Make carrot soup. Stuff
squash or bake a sweet potato for a vegetarian entree. Enrich a
comforting stew with chunks of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Turnips, rutabagas and beets should never be boiled vigorously.
Put them in cold water to cover, bring to a boil, cover, reduce
heat and simmer until tender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEETS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beets, which come in different sizes, varieties and colors, are
a love-hate vegetable. You either love them or hate them. They can
be roasted, steamed, boiled or microwaved. Beets also can be cooked
whole, sliced, cut in chunks or pickled.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy beets with greens attached, remove much of the greens
if you plan to store them in the refrigerator more than two days,
but leave about 1 inch of greens attached.
</P>
<P>
   Basic cooking: Cut off greens, leaving about 1 inch of stems
attached. (If you cut off stems completely, beets will ``bleed.'')
Place in pan, cover with cold water, bring to a boil, reduce heat,
cover pan, and simmer 20 minutes (for baby beets) to 1 hour or
until they can easily be pierced with a sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, add water to keep beets covered as they cook. When
done, drain, cool until you can handle them, and slip off the peel
or pare with a paring knife. Cut off the root. To microwave beets,
see the recipe that follows. To peel baby beets, scrub with a brush
before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sliced cooked beets provides 26 calories, 5.7 grams
carbohydrates and 42 milligrams sodium. Key nutrients: Vitamin C
and folacin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TURNIPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Vegetables'' (William Morrow, $35), author James Peterson
said that he so dreaded turnips growing up _ their reputation had
preceded them _ that he never tried them until he was in his 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't discover that a turnip could be something good until
I lived in France,'' Peterson said of the food he once loathed and
feared. At a famous restaurant in the French countryside, he
discovered turnips were a great delicacy when served a plate of
sliced ones that had been gently caramelized in port wine and
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Turnips seem to be best when served with meat or cooked in meat
juices, Peterson said. Avoid turnips with wrinkled skins or those
that are beginning to sprout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To store turnips with greens in the refrigerator, place in
perforated plastic bags. They will keep for several days. For
longer storage, remove greens about 1 inch above the turnip.
</P>
<P>
   Basic cooking: Remove wax if any; peel. Cook small turnips
whole, or dice, quarter or cut in strips. Place in cold water to
cover, bring to a boil, reduce heat, cover and simmer 15 to 20
minutes, until tender. Drain and season as desired.
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup mashed turnips provide 21 calories, 5.6 grams
carbohydrates and 58 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUTABAGAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutabagas look like giant turnips and can be cooked the same
way,'' Peterson said in ``Vegetables.'' Turned vegetables are
carved with a knife into large garlic clove shapes. Store unwrapped
in the refrigerator as long as two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup mashed rutabaga provides 41 calories, 1.3 grams
protein, 9.3 grams carbohydrates and 22 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SWEET POTATOES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes are not related to white potatoes or yams. Look
for potatoes of uniform shape that taper from the middle and have
smooth skin. They bruise more easily than white potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Basic cooking: Scrub well; dry. Pierce skin with a fork or
skewer to allow steam to escape. Bake whole sweet potatoes in their
skins in a 400-degree oven 40 to 45 minutes or longer. Bake in a
shallow pan to catch sticky juices.
</P>
<P>
   To microwave: Pierce potato once or twice and microwave on high
(100 percent) 5 to 8 minutes. Turn over once; turn a quarter-turn
twice if microwave has no turntable. Let potatoes rest after
microwaving to allow them to finish cooking and soften. To cook 4
medium potatoes, pierce, arrange in a circle and microwave 13 to 17
minutes, turning as instructed.
</P>
<P>
   One medium sweet potato, baked in skin, provides 118 calories, 2
grams protein, 27.7 grams carbohydrates and 12 milligrams sodium.
Key nutrients: Vitamins A, B6, C and beta carotene.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CARROTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carrots add color, crunch, sweetness and flavor to everything
from soup to cake.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid carrots that are limp or have cracks along the sides. Buy
fresh carrots with green tops, but remove tops (2 inches above
carrot) before storing in the refrigerator. In a tightly sealed
plastic bag, carrots may be stored for weeks. Peel them or not,
depending on the use and the esthetics of the dish. As an
alternative to peeling, scrub carrots with a nylon scrubber or
vegetable brush.
</P>
<P>
   Basic cooking: Wash well with a stiff vegetable brush or
scrubber; trim ends. Cook whole, slice into rounds, cut diagonally,
or in strips or sticks. Boil, covered, in a small amount of water.
Remove cover a few minutes near end of cooking time. Cook until
tender.
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sliced boiled carrots provides 25 to 30 calories,
8.2 grams carbohydrates and 52 milligrams sodium. Key nutrients:
Vitamin A, betacarotene and potassium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SQUASH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winter (hardshell) squash, such as acorn, buttercup, butternut,
Hubbard, Kabocha, spaghetti and turban, make delicious soups and
vegetable entrees _ plain or with stuffing or sauces. Hardshell
squash can be baked, steamed or microwaved.
</P>
<P>
   Basic cooking: Wash; cut in half; discard seeds. Bake, cut side
down, in a shallow baking dish at 400 degrees until fork-tender, 30
to 60 minutes depending on size. To microwave, place halves, cut
side down, on microwave platter and cook on high (100 percent)
until tender, 5 to 15 minutes. Let sit about 5 minutes and test for
tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   For large whole squash, such as Hubbard, pierce in several
places with a skewer or ice pick so steam can escape. Microwave 6
minutes per pound. Let stand 5 minutes, then peel. Or cut squash
into large pieces and microwave with a little water, covered, 10 to
12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup baked cubed winter squash provides 44 calories, 8.9
grams protein and 2.9 grams fiber.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
