<SLUG> BC-MICROWAVE-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAZELNUTS ENHANCE AUTUMN VEGETABLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN STEINER 
and CICI WILLIAMSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bit of crisp in the air signals harvest time for apples,
winter squash and hazelnuts. Like the basil and fresh tomatoes of
summer, fall's flavors meld tastefully.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, food editors and writers from across the country
converged in Portland, Ore., for the Association of Food
Journalists' annual conference. There we toured some of Oregon's
hazelnut groves that produce 99 percent of the U.S. crop.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnuts found their way to Oregon with a Frenchman who planted
a grove of 50 trees in the lush Willamette Valley. Cultivation of
these flavorful nuts began more than 4,500 years ago in China.
According to an ancient Chinese manuscript, hazelnuts were one of
five sacred nourishments God bestowed to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from their role as a snack, hazelnuts can be made into
pesto, combined with honey to make a filling for fruit, chopped and
scattered on the surface of soup, and used in many other creative
ways. For fall soups, hazelnuts and squash are a natural marriage
of flavors. Apples, too, benefit from being paired with hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   As desirable as the nutmeats are, the skins are not. To roast
hazelnuts in the microwave, spread a layer of shelled hazelnuts in
a glass pie plate and microwave on high 3 to 4 minutes, stirring
midway through roasting. To remove skins, rub the hazelnuts while
they are warm with a rough cloth or between your hands. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
