<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANON-SIDE-AZR &LR;      10-21 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANON-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITTIER IS OUT, BUT MILES DAVIS IS IN  
 (WITH CANON) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The cultural canon should prepare us to better and
more deeply understand the times we live in. It should provide
context and background for our understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Each piece of literature we read, each dramatization we see has
in it the reflection of the thoughts that have gone before it, like
a great hall of mirrors down which we walk and see ourselves a
thousand times on each side. We have to remember that when we read,
we are also reading everything that author ever read. When we
recognize that, the literature becomes more meaningful, speaks more
complexly _ and hence more truthfully _ to us.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the canon is the list of those things we ``should have
read.'' No one can read all of it, but a familiarity with it
enlightens our lives and makes us more satisfied inhabitants of the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not a list of deified heroes: These are not gods. The
list needs constant pruning. I'm willing to chuck ``Mill on the
Floss.''
</P>
<P>
   The dropping of dead wood is necessary to make way for new
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the PC crowd, I'm not willing to drop Homer. But I'm more
than willing to add Jane Austen, Edith Wharton, Willa Cather,
Gertrude Stein.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not ready to give up Whitman, but I'm there pushing John
Greenleaf Whittier out the door to make room for Sylvia Plath and
Derek Walcott.
</P>
<P>
   Let's add Matsuo Basho to the canon; let's add Richard Wright,
Ralph Ellison and James Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks I'm talking about lowering the standards for
entry has not read these authors.
</P>
<P>
   You still need to know Beethoven's symphonies and Mozart's
``Marriage of Figaro,'' but you had better also know Louis
Armstrong playing ``Struttin' With Some Barbecue,'' Charlie
Parker's ``Cherokee'' and Miles Davis' ``Kind of Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to make a short version of my own canon, I came up with
this minuscule list. This is not a list of the ``best,'' but of the
most influential, the things without which you cannot understand
what followed.
</P>
<P>
   It is very short. Too much worthy is not here for lack of space.
But these are things I could not do without. Everything on this
list gives me great pleasure. It's a place to start. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fiction &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Dostoevski's ``Brothers Karamazov'' &QL; 
2. Tolstoy's ``War and Peace'' &QL; 
3. Joyce's ``Ulysses'' &QL; 
4. Cervantes' ``Don Quixote'' &QL; 
5. Voltaire's ``Candide'' &QL; 
6. Jane Austen's ``Emma'' &QL; 
7. Melville's ``Moby Dick'' &QL; 
8. Kafka's ``The Trial'' &QL; 
9. Swift's ``Gulliver's Travels'' &QL; 
10. Twain's ``Huckleberry Finn'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Poetry &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Homer's ``Iliad'' and ``Odyssey'' &QL; 
2. Wordsworth's ``Intimations Ode'' &QL; 
3. Milton's ``Paradise Lost'' &QL; 
4. Dante's ``Divine Comedy'' &QL; 
5. The ``Mahabharata'' &QL; 
6. Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales'' &QL; 
7. Goethe's ``Faust'' &QL; 
8. Eliot's ``The Waste Land'' &QL; 
9. Whitman's ``Leaves of Grass'' &QL; 
10. Sappho's odes &QL; 
11. The ``Epic of Gilgamesh'' &QL; 
12. Ovid's ``Metamorphoses'' &QL; 
13. Baudelaire's ``Flowers of Evil'' &QL; 
14. Neruda's ``Odas Elementales'' &QL; 
15. A boatload of lyrics by Emily Dickinson, W.B. Yeats, Coleridge,
Keats, Auden, Borges, Rilke, Sylvia Plath, G.M. Hopkins, W.C.
Williams, John Skelton, Archilochus, Petrarch, Horace, Rimbaud _
pretty much anyone you can get your hands on. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Plays &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Aeschylus' ``Oresteia'' &QL; 
2. Sophocles' ``Oedipus Rex'' &QL; 
3. Shakespeare's ``Hamlet'' &QL; 
4. Shakespeare's ``King Lear'' &QL; 
5. Kalidasa's ``Shakuntala'' &QL; 
6. Beckett's ``Waiting for Godot'' &QL; 
7. Ibsen's ``The Doll House'' &QL; 
8. Sartre's ``No Exit'' &QL; 
9. Euripides' ``Medea'' &QL; 
10. Brecht's ``Mother Courage'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Belle Lettres &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Boswell's ``Life of Johnson'' &QL; 
2. Thoreau's ``Walden'' &QL; 
3. Suetonius' ``Lives of the 12 Caesars'' &QL; 
4. Longinus' ``On the Sublime'' &QL; 
5. Marx and Engels' ``The Communist Manifesto'' &QL; 
6. Emerson's ``Nature'' and ``Self Reliance'' &QL; 
7. D.H. Lawrence's ``Twilight in Italy'' &QL; 
8. Basho's ``Journey to the North Country'' &QL; 
9. Shelley's ``Defence of Poetry'' &QL; 
10. Castiglione's ``The Courtiet'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scriptures &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. The Bible &QL; 
2. The Koran &QL; 
3. Tao Te Ching &QL; 
4. Upanishads &QL; 
5. Tibetan Book of the Dead &QL; 
6. Egyptian Book of the Dead &QL; 
7. Analects of Confucius &QL; 
8. Sayings of Chairman Mao &QL; 
9. I-Ching &QL; 
10. The Vedas &QL; 
 &QL; 
Music &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Beethoven's Ninth Symphony &QL; 
2. Miles Davis' ``Kind of Blue'' &QL; 
3. Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde'' &QL; 
4. Mozart's ``Marriage of Figaro'' &QL; 
5. Duke Ellington's ``Koko'' and ``Harlem Airshaft'' &QL; 
6. Haydn's ``Creation'' &QL; 
7. Bach's ``Well Tempered Clavier'' &QL; 
8. Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring'' &QL; 
9. Bessie Smith's ``Shreveport Blues'' &QL; 
10. Messaien's ``Quartet for the End of Time'' &QL; 
11. And a selection of Chinese opera, African tribal music, Andean
flute music, the ragas of Ustad Ali Akhbar Khan, Australian
aboriginal music, Tibetan Buddhist chant, the Apache Mountain
Spirit Dance, Japanese Noh flute music and koto music, and
``Sergeant Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Painting, Prints and Photographs &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Leonardo's ``Mona Lisa'' &QL; 
2. Botticelli's ``Birth of Venus'' &QL; 
3. Pollock's ``Autumn Rhythms'' &QL; 
4. Picasso's ``Damoiselles d'Avignon'' &QL; 
5. Lascaux cave paintings &QL; 
6. Hiroshige's ``53 Stations of the Tokaido'' &QL; 
7. The Limbourg Brothers' ``Tres Riches Heures of the Duke of
Berry'' &QL; 
8. Michelangelo's Sistine ceiling &QL; 
9. Bosch's ``Garden of Earthly Delights'' &QL; 
10. ``Toreador Fresco'' from the Palace of Minos &QL; 
11. Rembrandt's ``Night Watch'' &QL; 
12. Poussin's ``Rape of the Sabine Women'' &QL; 
13. David's ``Death of Marat'' &QL; 
14. Copley's ``Watson and the Shark'' &QL; 
15. Goya's ``Third of May'' and ``Disasters of War'' &QL; 
16. Gauguin's ``Where Do We Come From? What Are We? Where Are We
Going?'' &QL; 
17. Duchamp's ``Nude Descending a Staircase'' &QL; 
18. Edward Weston's ``Peppers'' &QL; 
19. Van Gogh's ``Starry Night'' &QL; 
20. Mu-Ch'i's ``Six Persimmons'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sculpture &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Rodin's ``Burgers of Calais'' &QL; 
2. Elgin marbles &QL; 
3. Michelangelo's ``David'' and ``Pieta'' &QL; 
4. Bernini's ``Ecstasy of St. Teresa'' &QL; 
5. Brancusi's ``Bird in Flight'' &QL; 
6. Terra cotta army of the emperor Qin Shi Huangdi &QL; 
7. Venus of Willendorf &QL; 
8. Head of Queen Nefertiti &QL; 
9. Myron's ``Discobolus'' &QL; 
10. Laocoon group &QL; 
11. Great Amida Buddha of Kamakura &QL; 
12. Shiva Nataraja, Lord of the Dance &QL; 
 &QL; 
Architecture &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Chartres Cathedral &QL; 
2. Frank Lloyd Wright's Falling Water &QL; 
3. Chrysler Building &QL; 
4. Michelangelo's St. Peter's &QL; 
5. Jefferson's Monticello &QL; 
6. The Great Pyramids &QL; 
7. The Parthenon &QL; 
8. Hagia Sophia &QL; 
9. The Alhambra, Granada, Spain &QL; 
10. The Taj Mahal &QL; 
11. Brooklyn Bridge &QL; 
12. Gaudi's Sagrada Familia &QL; 
13. Mies Van Der Rohe's Seagram's Building &QL; 
14. Pyramid of the Sun, Moon, Teotihuacan, Mexico &QL; 
15. Macchu Pichu, Peru &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
