<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS SAY BEERS ADS TEMPT CHILDREN TO DRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lively advertisements inspire young Americans to
drink beer, but experts attending a medical conference here say
there are ways to inoculate children against the influences of
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Grube, of the Prevention Research Center in Berkeley, told
the American Academy of Pediatricians Tuesday that his research
established a direct relationship between awareness of beer
commercials on television and the propensity to drink among 470 San
Francisco-area students in grades seven through 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids who said they liked the ads that they saw and paid more
attention to the alcohol ads were more likely to drink,'' Grube
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two attributes that seemed to be getting kids' attention
were humor and ads that had youth-oriented music _ rock,
country-western or, in one case, hip hop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter DeBenedittis, of the New Mexico Media Literacy Project in
Albuquerque, told the pediatricians that alcohol advertising
``targets children and encourages them to be alcoholics.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``the whole point of alcohol ads is to make them believe
that it's perfectly normal to be a binge drinker. This is why you
see small dogs and frog puppets and comedians.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBenedittis, who said he has lectured more than 10,000
schoolchildren on how to ``deconstruct'' advertising and see how
they use symbols to lure children, contended that such teaching can
reduce the tendency to drink.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a Washington State University study that he said showed
``media training for third-graders significantly reduced their
intention to drink'' and made them less likely to collect
promotional products, like clothing, that advertise alcoholic
beverages.
</P>
<P>
   The beer industry has consistently denied that it aims
advertising at under-age drinkers, a topic currently under
investigation by Congress. The Federal Trade Commission, at the
request of Congress, is studying whether alcohol advertising and
consumption of booze by minors are related.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the FTC ordered eight major alcoholic beverage
companies to turn over information on their advertising practices.
The FTC plans to review the alcohol industry's self-regulatory
codes on advertising to under-age consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Beer Institute, a Washington-based lobbying organization for
beer manufacturers, features a lengthy segment on its World Wide
Web site titled ``Beer Industry Initiatives to Address Under-age
Drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web page cites industry-sponsored programs for home, school,
college campuses and retailers purportedly designed to prevent
minors from abusing alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our critics tend to assume an awful lot about the power of
advertising when, in fact, the reality is quite different,'' Beer
Institute spokesman Jeff Becker said. ``Over the last 10 years,
we've seen a decline in beer sales of 6 percent. Advertising
clearly isn't effective in getting people to drink more beer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grube said tricks such as using cute mascots _ the talking
frogs used by the maker of Budweiser beer, for example _ are
effective in establishing brand identification with young
television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to one study by a Berkeley researcher that found
grade-school children ``were more familiar with the Budweiser frogs
than they were with Tony the Tiger,'' the symbol of a cereal
marketed to children.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published in 1993, Grube discovered a similar
awareness of Spuds Mackenzie _ a canine mascot for Budweiser _
among fifth- and sixth-grade students. That research indicated a
correlation between awareness of beer ads and ``positive beliefs
about beer drinking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBenedittis noted that characters in beer ads ``are all young
adults _ you don't see crusty old people drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``the main message (is fulfillment of) the adolescent
male fantasy: All these beautiful babes that will come to me if I
just get sloppy drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Grube nor DeBenedittis called for a ban on televised
beer commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to be looking at what to be doing about the
ads so they don't appeal to kids,'' Grube said. ``Get them in time
slots where the kids are not exposed to them, and let the alcohol
advertisers take a little more responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
