 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, October 22,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday,
October 22, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ As the Middle East peace summit
trudges into its seventh day amid faltering expectations, can
President Clinton finally broker an agreement between Israeli and
Palestinian leaders? (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ITALY _ ROME _ Like shipping rice to China, coals to
Newcastle, steel to Pittsburgh .... Viagra to Italy. Viagra in
Italy? What use could there be for the little blue ``love pill'' in
a country renowned for its romantic ardor and sexual prowess? This
is the land that bred the likes of Casanova, Marcello Mastroianni
and Alberto Tomba. Trying to sell Italians on the need for Viagra
must be like trying to convince them to drive slower. Wait a
minute, just below the front-page story in my Rome newspaper about
Viagra's October debut is this headline: ``Drivers Urged To Slow
Down.'' In the country that gave us the Lamborghini and the
Maserati, a new public-service campaign wants motorists to ease off
the pedal. Check the plane tickets, did I land in the right
country? (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Oct. 20 in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ Coverage of 2 p.m. meeting between White House lawyers
and House Judiciary Committee members. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)..
</P>
<P>
   PORK _ WASHINGTON _ The Congress that boasted of balancing the
budget may be more remembered for divvying up the pork projects in
the huge catch-all spending bill to be passed Wednesday by the
Senate. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SCHOLARSHIPS _ WASHINGTON _ The new visa legislation that
allows employers to hire more foreign high-tech workers will also
establish new job training programs for American workers and
scholarships for low-income students. Here's how the programs will
work. (Monroe, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Netscape chief executive James
Barkdale, the lead prosecution witness, continues his testimony in
the Microsoft antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BANK-BILL _ WASHINGTON _ Congress appeared poised this year to
dismantle a Depression-era law that has prohibited consumers from
one-stop shopping for banking, insurance, stocks and bonds. But
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, with his objection to a tiny piece of the
overhaul, stalled a reform that had been 20 years in the making.
His beef: the Community Reinvestment Act, a federal law that
requires banks and savings and loan associations to report the
gender, race and income of loan applicants. (Harlan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD _ Following on the flooding. Most action is down south in
Victoria, where the historic downtown is underwater. Around Central
Texas clean-up continues. We're trying to get more precise damage
estimates. (Shah/Lindell/Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-DEADLIST _ List of the dead in Texas floods. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE _ Following investigation into the deaths of three men
slain in their hotel room in downtown Atlanta. (Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-BLANCA _ Who are the three men who will decide one of the
state's most controversial environmental issues? The Texas Natural
Resource Conservation commissioners vote Thursday morning on
whether Texas will build a low-level radioactive waste site near
Sierra Blanca, and everybody involved wonders what the three men
appointed by Governor Bush are thinking. (Haurwitz, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ANDREWS _ With the TNRCC expected to cast its long-awaited vote
on the planned radioactive waste site in Sierra Blanca, folks in
Andrews County are waiting in the wings in case it gets shot down.
Waste Control Specialists has operated a hazardous waste storage
facility in the West Texas county for years, and some county
leaders say they would welcome Texas' low-level radioactive waste.
They say the company could make it happen in about a year. But a
lot of wrinkles would have to be ironed out first. (Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   UT-RACISM-HIGHER-ED _ A panel discussion and teach-in on race,
racism and higher education are being held Wednesday as part of the
National Days of Action being observed at UT, UC-Berkeley and the
University of Michigan. Affirmative action has been banned at
Berkeley and Texas and is under attack in Michigan, prompting the
campus events. Faculty and students at UT are involved, and a rally
and other events also are scheduled for Thursday. We'll mention
those in this story. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas papers.
</P>
<P>
   TX-SUPREME-COURT-RACE _ Rose Spector holds the last position on
Texas Democrats' Maginot Line in the 1998 elections. If a
Republican sweep of statewide offices occurs, Spector _ with one
term as a state supreme court justice one of the court's most
experienced jurists _ will fall. Her opponent is a capable Houston
state appeals court judge. These days Spector fights what recent
history shows is an almost foregone conclusion, that if you run for
the supreme court as a Republican you'll be elected. At the bottom
of the ballot, the theory goes, voters tend to mark a straight GOP
ticket in an evermore Republican state. In many respects, the
Spector- Harriet O'Neill race frames the awkwardness of a state
that elects its judges on a partisan basis. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas papers.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS _ A look at the Arkansas senate election. (Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STATEHOUSE _ Amid this lackluster year for federal campaigns,
the most aggressive and hard-fought battles are being waged in
state Capitols around the nation, particularly in the South.
Republicans and Democrats are battling for control of legislative
chambers from North Carolina to Georgia to Texas. The fierce
competition is an extension of the transformation that swept
Congress in the early 1990s, when Republicans gained control of
most of the Congressional delegations in the South. The off year
elections unfold in the shadow of the 2000 census, making
statehouse races _ and the 36 governors' races _ especially
important since the ground is being laid for the 2001
reapportionment. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30'. WITH
DT LIST (showing majority in southern state legislatures). MOVED
</P>
