<HEADLINE>
TYSON SHOULD BOX AGAIN, FOR HIS SAKE AND FOR THE SPORT'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before I tell you why boxer Mike Tyson deserves to be back in
the ring, I have a confession to make.
</P>
<P>
   Because I've long been a pacifist, and have a general reputation
of being against violence, people tend to be very surprised when
they learn two things about me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a fan of boxing, and I love bullfights.
</P>
<P>
   Don't say it, because I've heard it all. And animal lovers,
please don't send any literature because I've seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   Although I don't want to go into detail about either pastime, I
can tell you that I've followed prize fighting (as it used to be
called) ever since a young guy named Cassius Clay won an Olympic
gold medal in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   I would become an even bigger fan of the man and the sport nine
years later after meeting the then-banned Muhammad Ali during his
visit to North Texas State University. The next day, the Supreme
Court ruled in Ali's favor, saying he had the right to refuse
military service because he was a minister in the much-maligned
Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   It felt so good to be that close to history and to a real-life
hero.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I became a fan of bull fighting shortly after local
Channel 39 first signed on the air and its major sports programming
_ maybe its ``only'' sports programming _ was the Sunday night
replay of the bullfights from Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've made numerous trips to Mexico's capital city,
primarily for the culture and the history, although I've always
gone during bullfighting season. (Even trips to El Paso usually
coincide with a weekend when the fights are scheduled in Juarez's
bullring.)
</P>
<P>
   But, so much for true confessions. Well, maybe just one more.
</P>
<P>
   I like Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I know it is fashionable to be on the anti-Tyson bandwagon,
to call the fighter some of the worse names you can think of and to
make jokes about ``getting an earful'' of something. But he's been
punished enough for that hair-raising, ear-biting bout with Evander
Holyfield last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know he's been convicted of rape, has been known to say
crude things, has been accused recently of physical assault and,
since the ``ear-rie'' Holyfield bout, has been deemed ``crazy'' by
many people in this country.
</P>
<P>
   While not dismissing Tyson's past, I also know of his troubled
childhood, his love for his adoptive parents, the positive changes
he made in his life (even in prison) and what he did for the
heavyweight division of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what most people say, including the Nevada State
Athletic Commission, they don't care about Tyson's troubles or
reputed character flaws or Holyfield's ear.
</P>
<P>
   They care about the money. And when Tyson is fighting, a bunch
of folks make a bunch of money.
</P>
<P>
   Surely no one expected the commissioners to do anything other
than restore the fighter's license this week. They had to _ for the
sake of boxing and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember in Tyson's early career when I was standing in
line to get into Dallas' Memorial Auditorium to watch a
closed-circuit bout featuring Tyson. Before I could get to my seat,
Tyson had knocked his opponent out.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one expects that kind of fight out of the boxer
today, they do expect him to put on a great show and bring some
pizzazz back to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   There are some people who want to see the fighter banned for
life, constantly humiliated and, in fact, destroyed, as if his
destruction would somehow bring honor to a sport that has little
honor left.
</P>
<P>
   I want to see Tyson back in the ring partly for his own
self-esteem. He will always have something to prove to someone, of
course, but the most important person he needs to please is
himself.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at: bobray(at)star-telegram.com,
or call: (817) 390-7775. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
