A9104 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLES-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      10-21 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLES-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORSON WELLES' VISION SHARPER IN RE-EDITED `TOUCH OF EVIL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON RENFROE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - He's a man who had it all. Admiration. Respect. Looks.
Professional success. And downfall.
</P>
<P>
   So, what happened? What quirk of personality led him down from
such heights?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. This story is not about President Clinton. It's
about the director of what's long been considered the finest movie
ever made, years before the American Film Institute declared it so
on its Top 100 list.
</P>
<P>
   Orson Welles was 25 when he directed ``Citizen Kane.'' He had
already conquered the stage with the Mercury Theatre repertory
company, formed with actor John Houseman and some of the best
actors from across New York.
</P>
<P>
   He had also become the most popular voice on the era's most
popular medium _ radio. He had become known to millions across the
country, starring in and directing plays, guest-starring on variety
shows and pitching soap.
</P>
<P>
   Every radio network wanted him because the shows he produced had
drama, impact and class, drawing on great works of literature such
as ``Arrowsmith'' and ``Beau Geste.'' A typical day in New York
would find him rushing from the Mutual network offices to CBS and
back again.
</P>
<P>
   His realistic ``War of the Worlds'' (1938) caused sensation and
panic among listeners who thought Martians were landing in their
back yards. In 1939, he directed a staggering 39 radio plays. There
was something about his steady, distinctive voice that kept
Americans listening.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood was listening, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ever on the lookout for fresh talent for its films, RKO Radio
Pictures could see the potential box office of this very popular
star. Although not exactly the biggest fish in the Tinseltown pond,
RKO was well respected and had made milestone films such as ``King
Kong'' (1933) and ``The Informer'' (1935). It managed to tempt
Welles ahead of the bigger, more successful companies.
</P>
<P>
   He first thought about accepting the role of Quasimodo in ``The
</P>
<P>
   Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' but decided to wait until he was
offered a chance to direct a film. He considered many projects,
including Joseph Conrad's ``Heart of Darkness,'' but he eventually
had the chance to use what he called ``the biggest goddamn box of
toys any boy ever had'' in directing a story about a newspaper
tycoon, ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything was going great guns. Welles couldn't have known that
in just a few years Hollywood would become disillusioned with him
as a director. After ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' (1942), it would
be 16 years before his movie career hit another directing peak with
``Touch ofEvil'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   Both ''Citizen Kane'' and the re-edited ``Touch of Evil,''
coming soon to theaters, show Welles as the master of the craft of
filmmaking. He reinvented the language of film through photographic
and sound techniques such as deep focus overlapping dialogue in
``Citizen Kane'' (1941) and brought them back again for ``Touch of
Evil.'' Even his worst critics admit he was a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Those films provide the two highest points in Welles' Hollywood
career. Although he had many memorable acting roles _ Harry Lime in
``The Third Man'' (1949) and Will Varner in ``The Long, Hot
Summer'' (1958) come to mind _ when it comes to directing, he never
did better than these two classics.
</P>
<P>
   What bothers many Welles biographers and lovers of cinema is
that the boy genius had so much potential, yet so seldom attained
the heights he was capable of. As Welles himself put it in an
interview late in life, ``I began at the top and have been making
my way down ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Some filmophiles make note of what amounts to Welles' fear of
success. Others point out that he wouldn't finish what he started,
stretching himself too thin in far-flung places around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after shooting ended on ``The Magnificent
Ambersons,'' a drama about a well-to-do family unable to adjust to
changing times at the turn of the century, Welles tried to conduct
the editing long-distance while simultaneously shooting a
pan-American State Department-funded goodwill film in Brazil,
``It's All True.'' Talking through an edit, rather than using the
hands-on approach, would prove impossible even for Welles. Imagine
trying to teach someone to drive over the phone, without the
benefit of actually (begin ital) showing (end ital) him: Disaster
was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Frank Brady writes in his ``Citizen Welles'' that the
director felt ``the film art itself did not end when the actors
performed a scene and it was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was merely the preparation, the rough notes or unarranged
words of filmmaking,'' Brady wrote. ``The film was made when the
director, through his editor, combined the shots and elements
together in various combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is indeed how Welles felt, why did he leave Hollywood to
party in Rio when such important work was left to be done?
``Ambersons,'' only his second film, was edited through phone
calls, cables and letters to Robert Wise, who would later direct
``West Side Story'' and ``Sound of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the quality of communication networks in those days
confounded Wise's ability to do a good job editing, according to
Brady's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what was going on half the time,'' Wise
recalled. ``We often tried for clarification (with Welles) by
telephone, and the problems were enormous, just getting through.
Then, when we reached him, we usually could not hear him because of
the connection. It was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Welles stayed in Brazil, and when ``Magnificent
Ambersons'' was test-screened, the results were predictable.
Audiences laughed in the wrong places, had trouble following the
characters' relationships to each other and thought the movie was
self-consciously ``arty.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Ambersons'' nevertheless ranks high with today's
critics, it could have been as good and as well received as
``Citizen Kane'' if only Welles had taken the time to stay at the
task, in person, through the editing process. (begin ital) What
could have been (end ital) is a phrase that keeps popping up when
studying Welles' life.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably Welles' antics and setbacks during the shooting
of ``It's All True'' that finally turned the Hollywood
establishment against him. He behaved badly, drinking too much and
throwing tantrums, and he had a hard time making the
pseudodocumentary on the lives of Rio peasants.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, although he shot lots of film (375,000 feet of
Technicolor), not much of it made much sense. RKO had had enough.
The studio's hoped-for golden boy was dragging it down, financially
and creatively. He was undisciplined and out of control, and the
studio wanted no more to do with him, at least not as a director.
As a result, ``It's All True'' wasn't seen by the public until it
was released as a sort of curio in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of ``It's All True'' and the lukewarm reception of
``The Magnificent Ambersons'' forced Welles to become a free agent,
acting in films mainly to fund his own pictures through the rest of
his career. Great director, sure, the studios seemed to say, but
dependable director, no.
</P>
<P>
   He made only a handful of studio-funded pictures during the late
1940s. Before ``Touch of Evil,'' his last studio film, under the
auspices of Western-maker Republic, was a 1948 treatment of
``Macbeth''which, although innovative in some ways, was savaged by
critics.
</P>
<P>
   How then did it come about that Welles was chosen to direct
``Touch of Evil'' at Universal? He had been chosen to play corrupt
police officer Hank Quinlan, but the studio had no director in mind
when it approached Charlton Heston to star as good cop Mike Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Heston claims it was he who suggested that Welles direct the
film. He told the ``Orange County Register'' earlier this year that
he wanted Welles because he admired ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he would turn a plain old cop story into something
special,'' Heston said.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, an up-and-coming star who portrayed Moses to great
success in 1956's ``The Ten Commandments,''won the day.
</P>
<P>
   Welles, Heston, Janet Leigh, Marlene Dietrich, Dennis Weaver and
others made a fascinating film. Then, the editing process began,
and once again, because of Welles' delays and broken promises, the
studio stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welles was his own worst enemy,'' Heston said in a recent
Phoenix interview. ``He would deliberately alienate the men in
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the stories surrounding the re-release of ``Touch of
Evil'' vilify Universal Pictures, which supposedly took the film
away from Welles. However, Welles shares responsibility for what
happened. He was given opportunities to make suggestions and
re-edits, but he chose to procrastinate and leave town at a
critical time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike what happened in the early '40s, however, this story has
a happy ending. Producer Rick Schmidlin and editor Walter Murch
have re-issued ``Touch of Evil,'' using a 58-page memo Welles sent
to the studio during the editing process. The result is a film that
should come closer to Welles' vision.
</P>
<P>
   For once, ``(begin ital) what could have been'' (end ital)
became reality. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
