<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCASTANEDA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CASTANEDA: THE SORCERER'S WIFE  
 (NOTE TIME ELEMENT) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED- They were improbable lovers. For decades, he denied she
even existed.
</P>
<P>
   She was a tall Southern belle with Cleopatra bangs and a
seductive patter; he, short and serious, recently immigrated from
Peru in hopes of becoming a successful artist in America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, their paths crossed in Los Angeles during the mid-'50s, and
in 1960 Margaret Evelyn Runyan married the man who would become the
most famous literary sorcerer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Castaneda, author of ``The Teachings of Don Juan,'' ``A
Separate'' ``Reality'' and eight other bestselling books on the
enigmatic world of Mexican shamans, passed away last April in Los
Angeles of liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda's works, which sold 8 million copies in 17 languages,
captured the spirit of the drug-bent, psychedelic '60s and helped
launch the New Age era with vivid accounts of spiritual and
pharmacological adventures with a white-haired Yaqui Indian
``nagual,'' or shaman, Don Juan Matus.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda wrote that, as a UCLA graduate anthropology student,
he met Don Juan at a Greyhound bus station in Nogales, Ariz., in
the summer of 1960 while researching medicinal plants used by
Indians of the Southwest. An unexpected apprenticeship with Don
Juan followed in which Castaneda, under the influence of peyote and
other psychotropic plants, saw giant insects, flew like a crow,
spoke with cactus and was chased by inorganic beings in the pursuit
of seeing pure energy and breaking away from ``ordinary reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Admirers then and now see his work as a compelling spiritual
quest. Critics view it all as a metaphor at best, more likely an
out-and-out hoax.
</P>
<P>
   And now the skeptics are clucking again as a multimillion-dollar
estate hearing over Castaneda's will begin Thursday (Oct. 22) in
Los Angeles. The adversaries? Castaneda's corporation vs. the
legally adopted son of his old love.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda always denied being married. Records prove
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Margaret Castaneda, 76, lives on in Charleston, W.Va.,
where she leads an active life among friends and family. And
despite her famous ex-husband's refusal to publicly acknowledge her
existence during the last two decades of his life, Margaret still
carries the torch for Carlos, whom she calls ``a genius'' and ``the
most wonderful human being'' she has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Margaret said the truth about
Castaneda and his books is like reality itself, an amalgam of
elements with varying degrees of resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no Don Juan,'' Margaret said. ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   As an anthropology student, Margaret said Castaneda did spend
years in Arizona and Mexico doing fieldwork on aboriginal people.
But she believes the bulk of material for his books came from his
childhood in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret said Castaneda grew up in the small Peruvian village of
Cajamarca, not the more cosmopolitan country of Brazil as he
claimed. As a child, he walked the square where herbs were sold,
listening to magical stories told by local ``curanderos'' and
Quechua Indians.
</P>
<P>
   She believes she may have inspired the creation of Don Juan
through a conversation with Castaneda about Plato and his Socratic
dialogues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that Plato didn't have anyone to discuss the other
side of what he thought so he wrote his ideas as dialogues with
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret said Castaneda most likely came up with his teacher's
name, Don Juan Matus, from Mateus, the bubbly Portuguese wine the
couple favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He once held up a bottle of Mateus and said, `This is where
real knowledge comes from.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Margaret said it doesn't matter; what's important are the
teachings, which she believes are the most trenchant of this
century.
</P>
<P>
   As far as being an actual sorcerer, Margaret said Castaneda
(begin ital) did (end ital) have the knowledge and capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   She believes she once spent a weekend in New York with
Castaneda's energy double, and that glass mysteriously shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day when I see a crow I say, `Carlos, is that you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret believes Castaneda's denial of their marriage was an
inevitable consequence of becoming a sorcerer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indians called it becoming a man of knowledge, and it
entailed a complex process of erasing one's personal history,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was that, and there was what Margaret calls ``fear'' on
the part of Cleargreen, the corporation that handled all aspects of
Castaneda's career, that she might reveal a personal side to him
that could puncture his carefully woven mystique. For most of his
public life, Castaneda refused interviews, refused to have his
picture taken and refused to have his voice recorded.
</P>
<P>
   So it came as no surprise when Cleargreen sued her over the
publication and distribution of her 1997 book ``A Magical Journey
With'' ``Carlos Castaneda,'' a 185-pager written with affection and
erudition about Castaneda before his fame and before the ``shedding
of his human form.''
</P>
<P>
   There are wonderful personal details in the book, such as how a
penniless Castaneda worked for the Mattel Toy Co., drove a cab and
did a shift at a liquor store in order to finance his education and
research for his doctoral dissertation, which eventually became his
first book, ``The Teachings of Don Juan: A Yaqui Way of
Knowledge''.``''
</P>
<P>
   But foremost, ``Magical Journey'' is a love story.
</P>
<P>
   As Margaret tells it, she met Castaneda in 1955 through her
dressmaker, a Costa Rican woman named Lydette Maduro. They began to
date despite Maduro's warning that Castaneda had ``powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda was a marginal artist. Margaret worked in management
for Pacific Telephone in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret said Castaneda loved foreign films, especially those of
Ingmar Bergman, and enjoyed getting together with friends over
Mateus to share intellectual banter.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda's focus became retooled when Margaret introduced him
to ``The'' ``Doors of Perception,'' Aldous Huxley's account of his
controversial mescaline experiments and scholarly dissection of
altered states of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``On first reading, Carlos was hooked,'' Margaret said.
</P>
<P>
   He abandoned art and enrolled in social-science classes, first
at Los Angeles City College and later at UCLA. He was especially
taken with phenomenology curricula.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Margaret said, they were married in Mexico. Six months
later, they separated because he spent too much time in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their personal problems, Margaret said, they remained
good friends, and when she pressed him for a divorce, he drove her
back to the same little Mexican town to undo the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Castaneda told her they weren't really
divorced. It had all been a charade, something to appease Margaret
while he was doing fieldwork. This was especially upsetting news as
she had married another man after the fake divorce and bore his
child.
</P>
<P>
   The other man disappeared, but Castaneda remained and developed
a strong, spiritual attachment to Margaret's son, originally named
Adrian but renamed Carlton Jeremy Castaneda, or C.J., after
Castaneda legally adopted him.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. lives in Atlanta. He is married and owns a chain of
drive-through gourmet coffee shops. He said Castaneda treated him
as if he were his own.
</P>
<P>
   David Christie, owner of Millenia Press, publisher of Margaret's
book, said he has known Margaret for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margaret was a significant force in Castaneda's life,''
Christie said, ``including talking him into using Castaneda as his
last name, rather than Aranha. She was also a very beautiful
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis L'Amour thought so, too. Margaret said she met him in a
Los Angeles drugstore three years before Castaneda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to marry me, too,'' Margaret said. ``But I took him
to meet my aunt, and she said she didn't want her beautiful niece
marrying that lounge lizard who would never amount to a hill of
beans.''
</P>
<P>
   The same aunt didn't care for Castaneda, either.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret and C.J. lived several years in Tempe in the mid-'70s
after her real divorce from Castaneda. C.J. attended Marcos de Niza
High School; Margaret owned a phone answering service called the
Apache Sun, which she said Castaneda bought for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona was the most spiritual place I've ever lived,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret said that in 1978 Castaneda came to Tempe for C.J.'s
graduation from high school. Afterward, he took them to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't see him again until 1993 _ for the last time _ at a
bookstore in Santa Monica, Calif., for the signing of his book
``The Art'' ``of Dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried when I saw him,'' Margaret said. ``His hair had turned
gray. I couldn't imagine Carlos as an old man. It still upsets me
to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda's estate was reportedly worth $20 million to $50
million when he died. A few days before his death, Margaret said,
his will was changed under ``very suspicious circumstances.'' She
said she and C.J. were left nothing even though their names were
mentioned at the top of the will. Castaneda's entire estate, she
said, was left to his corporation.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. has contested the will. If it turns out the way he hopes,
he and his mother, the sorcerer's wife, could benefit handsomely
from Castaneda's adventures in ordinary reality. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
