<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS IN MAINE HAVE TROUBLE ON THEIR HANDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ It has come to this: The Democratic Party in
Maine is within a hair's-breadth of being decertified as an
official political party if struggling gubernatorial nominee Tom
Connolly doesn't get at least 5 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Red alert! Connolly polled at only 6 percent four weeks before
the vote. Governor Angus King, the popular Independent incumbent,
siphoned off 61 percent in the poll by Strategic Marketing, versus
13 for former US Representative Jim Longley, the Republican. The
Green Party's Pat LaMarche (4 percent) and the Taxpayers Party's
Bill Clarke (2) left 15 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   As the Democrats organized a resuscitation team, King's
spokesman, Dennis Bailey, cracked: ``I think they could run a
canned ham and get 5 percent.'' Elsewhere around the nation there's
more pork than ham at work in the 36 governor's races. Huge leads
for incumbents, mostly Republicans, reflect the strong economy, the
lack of many or even any galvanizing state-level issues, and the
pragmatic approach of most governors, who tend not to be as
ideologically polarized as the GOP Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Perusing a state-by-state polling survey by the National Journal
Hotline you find 22 Republican candidates for governor leading by
more than the margin of error, only four Democrats comfortably
ahead, and six races in the tossup category _ closer than 6 points
or less. Since the GOP has 24 of the 36 seats at stake and the
Democrats only 11, the Republicans seem to be holding much of their
tight grip on statehouses, which should help the GOP in the
congressional redistricting required in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One GOP wag jibed that the Republicans will control more land
than the National Park Service. But California _ where Lieutenant
Governor Gray Davis, a Democratic, leads Attorney General Dan
Lungren, a Republican _ is the big prize because the Golden State's
electoral votes give you the biggest chunk of what you need to win
the White House. If Davis loses and if Scott Harshbarger falls
short in Massachusetts, the Republicans will likely control the
governor's chair in the 11 largest states, a shift with awesome
import.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is up 6 and 8 points in two October polls, and
Harshbarger seems to have begun to move here, where the outcome is
likely to be a single-digit win one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Brothers Bush have huge leads; Governor George W. was up by
70-24 in Texas, and Jeb is running in the mid-50s in Florida, to
Lieutenant Governor Buddy McKay's high 30s. This gives the Bushes
the inside track on the second- and third-largest blocs of
electoral votes for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   New England incumbents _ save the Bay State's acting guv and
Rhode Island's Lincoln Almond, who is tied with Democrat Myrth York
in recent polling _ seem solidly ensconsed. Vermont's Howard Dean
polls at 64 percent, GOP Governor John Rowland of Connecticut is at
60 or 62, and Democratic Governor Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire
had a 20-point comfort zone over Republican Jay Lucas, who has
outspent her by almost 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents in danger of being axed include Republican Fob James
in Alabama, a God squadder whose politicizing of matters Biblical
finds him trailing Democratic Lieutenant Governor Don Siegelman,
and Maryland, where Democrat Parris Glendening is neck and neck
with Republican Ellen Sauerbrey. In heavyweight industrial states
like Pennsylvania and Michigan, Republican incumbents rule, but in
New Mexico and South Carolina, the GOP faces stronger-than-expected
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Lewinsky imbroglio, with its impeachment
connotations, seems not to be much of an issue here, but in New
Hampshire, Republican Lucas has flayed Shaheen for not being
sufficiently anti-Clinton. No one is sure how turnout nationally
will be affected by Washington's perpetual scandal machine, but
most tea leaf readers see it helping Republicans in the South,
West, and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   I have developed my own Iodine Theory, to wit: In places that
border on saltwater, where the iodine content is higher, voters
tend to be more tolerant of Clinton's sins than in the interior,
where AM talk radio harangue-masters fill the role that hurricanes
and ocean-spawned storms play along the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently 32 GOP governors, the highest number the
party has held for 76 years. It was Lyndon Johnson who confided to
Bill Moyers that advancing the cause of black Americans might cost
the Democrats control of the White House for 30 years, so resentful
would become white voters. National politics has become transformed
in ways no one foresaw, though Richard Nixon's infamous Southern
Strategy has stood the test of time, more's the pity. Congress is
dominated by Sun Belt conservatives; the only Democrats elected
president in 38 years were Southerners; the North's political clout
is at its lowest ebb ever. And if Davis and Harshbarger lose,
Republicans will control the 11 largest states. Whew.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
