<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-VOTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS AIMED AT GETTING WOMEN TO VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two women's organizations are using advertising
campaigns to topple the conventional wisdom that President
Clinton's sexual infidelities will keep women away from the polls
on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media keeps reporting that women won't be voting and that
message is a very disempowering message for women to continue to
hear,'' said Margot Magowan, a co-founder of the group, Women
Count. ``It has the potential to be a self-fulfilling prophecy.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonpartisan organization's advertising campaign, which began
Tuesday in many major California daily newspapers, comes as
Democrats fear a low turnout by women voters will hurt their
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats have had success at the polls in the 1990s
by relying on a ``gender gap'' in which women by large margins have
voted for the party's candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Emily's List, a national organization that raises
money for women candidates who support abortion rights, is
spearheading its own ``Women Vote'' project.
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List began the Women Vote project in 1994, when Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., was struggling in her campaign against
Republican Michael Huffington, who poured millions of dollars from
his personal fortune into the race. The group sought ``drop off''
women voters _ those who voted in presidential elections but not in
off-year elections.
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List spokeswoman Stephanie Cohen said the project
targeted 900,000 women voters with direct mail and follow-up calls
urging them to vote _ and 415,000 did. Cohen said the vote clearly
helped Feinstein. Her victory came in an election in which,
nationally, 16 million fewer women voted than in the presidential
election of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is making sure that people realize that this
election and going out to vote has an impact on their lives and
their families,'' Cohen said. ``It's not about scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   Women Count was launched earlier this year by Esprit Corp.
co-founder Susie Tompkins Buell and several friends who were
frustrated by news media reports saying that the Clinton scandal
would alienate women and lead to voter apathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so discouraged that women have let their right go,'' Buell
said Tuesday. ``If you think about what suffragettes did and how
they sacrificed and paved the way for all of us, we've just taken
it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The print ads by the group include an image of a woman flexing
her biceps along with the text: ``They used to say women couldn't
vote. Now they say we won't. Vote Tuesday, November 3rd.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Madrid, political director for the California Republican
Party, praised the group's effort to increase women's participation
in politics, but questioned how nonpartisan its goals are. Buell,
who is spearheading the effort, was one of the top 10 California
donors to the Democratic Party in 1996, giving $138,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me this group sees the same thing we are seeing:
that Barbara Boxer is going to lose unless she can use scare
tactics to get women to vote,'' Madrid said. He said supporters of
Boxer, the incumbent senator who faces a tight re-election, ``are
wrong to use a nonpartisan group to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buell said the vote campaign wasn't about re-electing Boxer,
although she personally supports the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about women taking responsibility for their concerns and
getting out and voting,'' Buell said. ``If you don't vote, don't
complain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
