<HEADER>
A9175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      10-21 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Bringing Hibiscus Indoors &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two beautiful Hibiscus plants in pots outdoors. How do
I prepare them for the long Northeast winters, when I know they
must be brought indoors. I heard they should be placed in a
basement with little light and watered only occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   A. Wintering over large, flowering tropical plants like Hibiscus
rosa-sinensis is always a challenge. They never thrive in the
living room the way they do outdoors. Leaves turn yellow and drop,
flowers seldom appear. Assorted pests DO appear, in droves. No
wonder gardeners dream of exiling these shrubs to the basement,
where they can be out of sight and out of mind until spring.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of Hibiscus never sleeps, however, and if you try to
store yours as though it were dormant, you may get a rude
awakening. If you want to try it all the same, keep the plants
cool, 45 to 50 degrees. Expect them to drop all their leaves. They
will likely get bugs. And they will still need to be brought into
light well before summer planting time.
</P>
<P>
   A better choice is a room that gets lots of light and is cool
enough to slow growth _ 60 to 65 degrees. If you must put hibiscus
plants in the living room, keep them in the sunniest place, away
from direct heat and far enough from the window so they don't
suffer big temperature swings from night to day. There is no point
in misting, but if you don't have a humidifier this would be a good
excuse to get one. Keep soil barely but consistently moist, and
don't feed unless flowers appear. Watch out for aphids, whiteflies
and red spider mites. If you see them, treat promptly with
insecticidal soap.
</P>
<P>
   Hibiscus is tough. The plants will not be glorious inside, but
they will survive. Cut them back in late April, removing leggy
branches and working to create a pleasing shape. New growth should
start almost at once. It is tempting to set the plants out as soon
as the frost is past, but hibiscus is a heat lover that will be
happier inside until it is warm out day and night _ late May or
early June.
</P>
<P>
   Or treat hibiscus as an annual indulgence. While they are still
beautiful, give your plants to a deserving establishment with big
windows and no qualms about getting rid of ailing ornamentals.
Enjoy a carefree winter, and get new ones next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hibiscus are available from Fancy Hibiscus, 1142 S.W. First
Ave., Pompano Beach, Fla. 33060-8706; (800) 432-8332; catalog, $2,
refundable with order, and at Plumeria People, 910 Leander Dr.,
Leander, Texas 78641; (512) 259-0807; catalog, $3, refundable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Keeping Dahlias Cold &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. For the first time ever, I planted dahlias in my garden this
past summer. What a delight! What's the best way of storing them so
I can enjoy their profusion next year? I understand they do not
overwinter well and should be taken up.
</P>
<P>
   A. Dahlias will not winter over in places where the ground
freezes, but they are easy to store _ if you have a cold place to
keep them. Start by making labels now while you remember which
color is which. Cut off the dead foliage, leaving stubs two inches
long. Wait for a dry day, then use a digging fork to lift the
tubers. Turn the clumps upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Let them dry a few hours, then gently remove as much soil as
possible. Don't wash them off, as the last thin layer of clinging
soil will help protect them from shriveling. Line a large box with
a plastic bag; then add a four-inch layer of dry peat moss or
sawdust. Place tubers stem side up on the peat moss, keeping them
well separated. Nestle the labels into the clumps.
</P>
<P>
   Completely surround the tubers with additional peat moss, and
loosely close the bag. Store in a dark place, ideally at 35 to 45
degrees. When storage temperatures climb to the mid-50s, the tubers
start sprouting. Ignore short sprouts; they'll be buried when you
plant. Clumps that come from storage with long, pale stems,
however, should be hardened off for a week or so in the shade
before being set out in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Replanting Peonies &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When and how do I transplant my peonies. I planted them a
year ago, and they have far overgrown their location in my raised
bed garden in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no time to lose. Peonies should be planted at least
six weeks before the ground freezes. Start by choosing a new
location where they can grow undisturbed for the foreseeable
future. Peonies are long-haul plants, not at their best until they
have been in place a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off and discard the spent foliage. Carefully dig up the
roots. If they have been in place only a year, it is unlikely they
will need dividing. Be sure the new planting holes are wide _ the
understructure of peonies tends to be broad. Replant at once,
making sure the budlike eyes are no more than two inches below the
ground. After the ground is frozen at least three or four inches
down, probably after Christmas at this rate, add a layer of mulch.
Do not fertilize until spring, when a generous application of
compost will be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Peonies are available from Klehm Nursery, 4210 North Duncan Rd.,
Champaign, Ill. 61822; (800) 553-3715; catalog, $4, refundable with
order, and at New Peony Farm, P.O. Box 18235, St. Paul 55118; (612)
457-8994; catalog, free.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
