<SLUG> BC-HIGHSCHOOLDROPOUTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY LEFT HIGH SCHOOL WITHOUT DIPLOMAS. HERE'S WHAT HAPPENED NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Agnes Chandler stopped going to high school
in 1940 because her mother couldn't afford to send her. Vickie
Hernandez quit in 1970 because she was pregnant. Boredom and a bad
attitude led Devin Williams to drop out just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to a high school dropout?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler might have been a professional dancer instead of a
cleaning lady.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez might be a psychologist or a teacher, not a grocery
store clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Williams can be whatever he wants. He has gone back to school.
</P>
<P>
   Some dropouts succeed without an education, and some don't. Some
finish their degrees, some don't. But no matter what their age,
race or gender, most regret the single decision that shapes much of
their adult lives _ their jobs, their lifestyles, their
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez recently passed the GED test, 28 years after she quit
school. ``Is it worth it? Yes, it's worth it,'' she said. ``The
result is an open door to better things.''
</P>
<P>
   How can school administrators teach that lesson to all the
headstrong teen-agers who drop out every year?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they can't.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it takes experience to see the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   AGNES CHANDLER
</P>
<P>
   The Diamond Hill Seniors Center is preparing for Tuesday lunch,
and there in the middle of the clamor is Agnes Chandler. At 69, she
is one of the center's most active volunteers. She is program
director and reporter and photographer for the ``Senior Sentinel''
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler retired years ago, after a lifetime of working odd
jobs: cleaning, cooking, waiting tables, baking sweet rolls,
picking cotton, working assembly lines, keeping a church nursery
and cleaning airplanes at Meacham Field in Fort Worth. The job she
wanted, she never had.
</P>
<P>
   She was a little girl growing up outside Temple in Central Texas
when she discovered her family's ancestral dance. Chandler is a
second-generation Czech who dreamed of turning her hobby into a
career.
</P>
<P>
   She was 16 and a good student _ straight-A's, she brags _ from
first through 10th grades. But in 1940, there was one high school
in her county, and it was in town.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents had divorced, and Chandler's mother raised her
alone. The bus did not run to their farm, and Chandler's mother
could not afford to put her daughter in an apartment in town. ``I
did not, did not drop out of school,'' Chandler says.
</P>
<P>
   She married at 17 and got a job. When she divorced in 1960, she
needed more money to raise the two children alone. She took her GED
test, passed it and landed a good job at General Dynamics,
assembling light fixtures for airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she is retired, Chandler thinks about what might have
been. She still dances with a Czech group at festivals and fairs.
She wonders, though, if she had graduated, could she have gotten
into dance school? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler made certain her children finished school. She's
lecturing her grandchildren, too. ``I preach to my granddaughter,
`You drop out of school, I'm going to shoot you, girl. You better
keep your can in school.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't mean maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   DEVIN WILLIAMS
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Chandler, 20-year-old Devin Williams had the opportunity,
but he lacked the desire to finish school. Williams dropped out of
Southwest High School in Fort Worth in 1995, his senior year. ``It
was pretty much the kind of thing where you think you're big and
bad and you think you can take on the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   His situation is not uncommon, and it may be the hardest for
educators to fight. How do you change a bad attitude?
</P>
<P>
   Williams wanted to be in the jazz band, but his teacher demanded
he go through marching band first. Williams said no. Frustrated
with other teachers, he failed algebra, English and geometry.
</P>
<P>
   His parents balked when he brought up the subject of dropping
out. They agreed, eventually, after he agreed to finish his
education. Williams passed the GED test and went to work full time,
cashiering at a barbecue joint, making $5.25 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking out was a relief, and in other ways, you know you're
missing out on something every teen-ager takes part in: no prom, no
homecoming. While I was there, I tried to have as little to do with
it as possible, and in some ways, I don't regret it as much as some
people do. It did slow my educational process. I'm now a part of
real life. I can't have a summer job. I've got to pay my bills and
show up for work.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has settled down in the past two years. He married his
high school sweetheart (she stayed in school and graduated). He
works full time as a butcher. (''The money's not bad, but I'd
rather have the time off.'') He's taking courses at Tarrant County
Junior College and thinking about going into teaching. ``It's more
or less trying to make a difference _ kind of civil disobedience
strikes back,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   VICKIE HERNANDEZ
</P>
<P>
   The year Vickie Hernandez turned 16, she was pregnant. A doctor
wrote a pass that allowed her to finish the 10th grade at O.D.
Wyatt High School in Fort Worth. ``The thing you did back then was
you get married and take care of your children.'' So she did, as
soon as she finished the 10th grade. That was in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   For 28 years, Hernandez did without a diploma. She lied on job
applications, and no one checked. She sold jewelry at Dillard's
until January, when the department store phased out fine jewelry,
and Hernandez was laid off.
</P>
<P>
   This time while job-hunting, Hernandez told the truth. She
looked for other jobs, and, ``They were like, we don't hire
dropouts. We don't hire people unless they're in school or they
have a GED.''
</P>
<P>
   From March through July, Hernandez, 44, sat in a Tarrant County
Junior College classroom, studying for her GED test. After so many
years of telling her two daughters no _ there's no money for
basketball camp, there's no money for a computer, there's no money
for ballet lessons _ Hernandez decided no more living without an
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say I regret everything, because I'm grateful for my
family. But at school, there's nothing like sitting in that
classroom, and that's what I stress to my girls. I wanted my
children to be the opposite of what I was. Life is as rich as you
want it to be, and knowledge is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez passed the GED. She's living with her sister now,
saving her money from the grocery store where she works, and trying
to find a program to help pay for college tuition. A social worker
told her $21,000 annual salary is too much to get government help.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, she has her GED, and for someone who worked two jobs
on the weekend after two jobs during the week, that piece of paper
is as good as a high school diploma. For the first time in years,
she is dreaming again like a teen-ager: What will she be? A
psychologist? A teacher?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that, next to my children being born, that's one of
the greatest accomplishments of my life. Something you want so bad,
and you're almost convinced you can't have it _ just to hold that
paper, I felt as though I had walked across that stage in front of
millions of people. When I saw that, it was like something stirred
in me I didn't know was there. God, I just want to learn more.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
