r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     10-21 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING IS THE TIME TO BUILD A BETTER BIRD _ A TURDUCKEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the cool, fall breezes in the air, you just have to ask
yourself, ``How am I fixed for turduckens?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving is just about a month away, give or take a week,
and if you plan on doing your own turducken, it's time to start.
Actually, if you are doing one for the first time, you might
already be late.
</P>
<P>
   A turducken, for those of you who are staring blankly at this
space, is a chicken stuffed inside a duck, stuffed inside a turkey.
It is the latest rage from ragin' Cajuns, and it is the
Thanksgiving dish that will make obsolete all those portable gas
burners used to fry whole turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turduckens have been real popular back in Louisiana for, I'd
say, the last four years,'' said Kent Vincent of Bayou Boys Cajun
Foods in Lewisville, Texas. ``Believe me, they'll take the place of
the world-famous fried turkeys. The turduckens are better.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent claims the problem with fried turkeys is that you need
to be there when the bird is lifted from the hot grease. It is
then, he says, when the turkey has cooled just enough to eat, that
it is at its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of places fry them, then freeze them,'' he said. ``Then
they ship them out to customers. When you get one, you have to
rewarm it in your oven, and it ends up tasting just like baked
turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Turduckens are baked, but the mixture of meats and spicy
dressings lifts the taste beyond the normal
giblets-and-gravy-covered white meat.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know who came up with this idea, though it
was someone who had a lot of time on his or her hands. A turducken
is completely boned _ turkey, duck and chicken. When you slice
across it, it comes out looking like a jelly roll of meat and
stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Cajun food guru Paul Prudhomme didn't invent them, we know that,
but he has a recipe for one. It includes andouille dressing for the
turkey, corn-bread dressing for the duck, and oyster dressing for
the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Add the time for making all this dressing to that of boning each
bird, and you can see why we might already be late for this year's
Thanksgiving. It's interesting just to look at the necessary tools.
Prudhomme's recipes call for ``1 small hammer, 1 (3-inch) needle (a
packing needle with a curved tip works well), and strong thread for
sewing up the fowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to swing by the hardware store on the way home from the
butcher.
</P>
<P>
   At Bayou Boys, the turduckens are available with rice dressing.
Last year, the company offered them with several different
stuffings, but the overwhelming favorite was the dirty-rice
dressing made with rice, ground beef, ground pork and spices.
</P>
<P>
   For those who fear dirty rice that traditionally has liver in
it, don't worry, the Bayou Boys omit it.
</P>
<P>
   There is another concession they make as well. They don't use
whole duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of domestic duck we have to use has a lot of fat
between the skin and meat,'' Vincent said. ``That was making the
turduckens a little too greasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the best part of the duck is the breasts, so Vincent
and his partners are now using just the breasts. They stuff the
boned turkey with rice dressing, lay two duck breasts on top of the
dressing, pack them with more dressing, place the chicken in, stuff
it, and sew the whole thing up.
</P>
<P>
   It takes these guys, who are turning out 50 to 60 a week, about
25 minutes to bone the birds and stuff them. That's generally about
90 days faster than average.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy one from Bayou Boys, it will run you $65. The
turducken will weigh in at around 13 to 14 pounds, and Vincent
figures a serving is about a pound a person.
</P>
<P>
   There is a cheaper version. You can buy a turken (no duck) for
$55. It weighs about 12 pounds and will serve 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Bayou Boys is cranking them out. Vincent says folks
are buying them right now, not for Thanksgiving, but for Sunday
afternoon football parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do them in advance and freeze them,'' he said. ``But we are
having trouble keeping up. If people want one, they need to give us
at least four or five days' notice, and they can't wait until we
get too close to the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   The turduckens come frozen in a vacuum-sealed bag. Generally, it
takes about five hours to cook one after it has been defrosted _
four hours in a 350-degree oven covered, then one hour uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call Bayou Boys at (972) 434-0353. To do one yourself,
you can find several recipes on the World Wide Web. Just search for
``turducken.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can write him at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web
site: www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
