<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9188 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINEMEDICINE-TEX     10-21 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINEMEDICINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE PATIENT NET ACCESS ENCOURAGED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Afraid and confused, the elderly woman
walked into the Fort Worth library seeking information about a
recently diagnosed disease.
</P>
<P>
   She had just left her doctor, who told her she had neuropathy
and sent her to a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Malone, senior librarian and Internet guru at the central
library, said she remembers the relief on the woman's face when her
research found treatments for the condition, which affects nerves
in the feet and other extremities.
</P>
<P>
   The knowledge came courtesy of the information superhighway,
technology that is changing the way that the newly diagnosed,
chronically worried or sporadically curious learn about medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, public access must be expanded significantly to reach
Americans who cannot afford computers at home, according to a
special issue on computers and medicine published in this week's
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many people out there just surfing for information, we
have to do a better job ensuring that the information that's
provided is accurate and up-to-date,'' said Dr. John Licciardone,
medical director of the International Travel Medicine Clinic at the
University of North Texas Health Science Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   For 14-year-old high school freshman Michelle Waters, the
Internet provides an escape into a world outside the hospital.
Between breathing treatments at Cook Children's Medical Center in
Fort Worth, Waters signs onto a computer and visits with other
children with cystic fibrosis from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about what medicines we take,'' said Waters, who was
being treated last week to clear mucus from her lungs. ``It's
interesting to know what they take and how often they come to the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   The JAMA issue, which includes nearly a dozen studies, reviews
and editorials on Internet-related subjects, also discusses ways
that doctors can expand patient dialogue via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Whether physicians should use the Internet to communicate with
patients is a sticky issue, Licciardone said.
</P>
<P>
   Licciardone's travel medicine Web site fielded 26,129 hits last
year from at least 105 countries, according to statistics. But the
site, he said, no longer includes a section for general questions
and answers because the queries were getting too specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtually impossible to provide more than the most
general information without sitting down and talking to the
person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Virginia Health Sciences Center, the
division of pediatric gastroenterology and nutrition offered free
e-mail consultations for nearly three years. In all, 1,239 requests
were fielded.
</P>
<P>
   On average, physicians needed less than four minutes to answer
each patient e-mail, said Dr. Stephen Borowitz, a pediatrics
professor in Virginia and lead author of a related JAMA study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what I'm doing in a lot of circumstances is answering
those questions that the physician did answer, but the patient
didn't hear,'' Borowitz said. ``Even though you may be in the room
with them for an hour, they don't process all that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Uninsured Americans are doubly penalized if they are locked out
of the information exchange, said Thomas Eng, a study director at
the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``... They don't have the information that can be used to
prevent the need for the health care in the first place,'' said
Eng, who wrote a related public policy analysis in the medical
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, Eng said, public access to the Internet must be
expanded significantly to include shopping centers, post offices
and other community locations.
</P>
<P>
   Malone and her fellow librarians caution eager Internet users to
check the source as they dig for answers.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, they recall, wanted to know whether her husband's
prostate cancer medication would inhibit his ability to work.
Another was trying to learn more about a herbal alternative to
estrogen replacement therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the things that I've read on the Internet are much
more written in layman's language than some of the medical books we
get,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
