<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-SCHOLARSHIPS21-C     10-21 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SCHOLARSHIPS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VISA BILL TO FUND NEW JOB TRAINING, SCHOLARSHIPS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New visa legislation approved Wednesday by Congress
as part of the massive omnibus spending bill will generate about
$71 million for job-training programs and scholarships for U.S.
workers and students.
</P>
<P>
   The H-1B visa measure, sought by the high-tech community, boosts
the number of visas for highly skilled foreign workers from 65,000
to 115,000 next year. Employers argued that a tight labor market
has left them strapped for trained workers.
</P>
<P>
   One way Americans will benefit is from the higher $500 fee
employers must pay for each visa they apply for and renew.
</P>
<P>
   The bill dictates that the Labor Department receive 63 percent
of the fee revenue _ about $47.25 million _ to be filtered through
dozens of existing job-training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Workers or unemployed people can participate in the programs by
applying for an Individual Training Account grant, said Jake
Siewert, communications director for the National Economic Council
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Training account grants give workers money to apply to a program
of their choosing. Those interested can get information on
available programs through their employer or at one of the more
than 800 One-Stop Career Centers that have been established in
nearly every state to provide employment information.
</P>
<P>
   The National Science Foundation will receive 32 percent of the
fees _ about $24 million _ to establish a new scholarship fund for
low-income students studying mathematics, engineering or computer
science.
</P>
<P>
   Associate, undergraduate and graduate students will be able to
apply once the foundation sets up the program, which is not
expected for several months.
</P>
<P>
   David Stonner(cq), head of congressional affairs for the
foundation, said it faces numerous challenges in assuming a new
role as scholarship provider.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation now awards 10,000 new grants and fellowships each
year, but has no scholarship program.
</P>
<P>
   One problem will be with staffing, Stonner said. The bill did
not allocate any money for additional staff, although a deluge of
applications will have to be processed for the expected 10,000 new
scholarships each year.
</P>
<P>
   Stonner said one solution may be to enter a cooperative
agreement with a university or scholarship fund that already
administers scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Other challenges will be in setting up criteria for who will
receive the scholarships and deciding how that money will be
divided among associate, undergraduate and graduate students, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have within Congress a reputation of doing things well and
rising to challenges,'' Stonner said. ``This is going to be a real
challenge, because the parameters have yet to be written and the
fact that it is open to a variety of educational experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 5 percent of the fee revenue from the visas will
be used by the Labor Department to speed up processing of the new
visas and other program expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
