<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDER-CONCERT-REVIEW-H     10-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDER-CONCERT-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BROADWAY POLISH, CONFIDENT LINDA EDER SPARKLES IN CONCERT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Linda Eder made a triumphant homecoming Monday night
with a vibrant and enthusiastically received concert at the Aerial
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   You could call Houston Eder's artistic home, since she made her
stage debut with the Alley Theater's world premiere of ``Jekyll &AMP;
Hyde'' in 1990. She returned for two engagements on that show's
long road to Broadway and performed three solo concerts at the
Alley, attracting a large and avid Houston following with her
stunning looks and sensational voice.
</P>
<P>
   Although she's been in the ensemble cast of the Alley's new
``The Civil War'' since September, Monday's concert marked Eder's
return as a diva with the sort of showcase supplied by her ``J&AMP;H''
role and past concerts. After a year and a half on Broadway, Eder
is a more confident, polished and nuanced entertainer. Since she is
now widely regarded as a major find, Houston and the Alley can take
justifiable pride in having found her first. (The evening was a
benefit for the Alley.)
</P>
<P>
   Attired in a trim black pantsuit for her concert's first half
and a sexy but classically simple black gown for the second, Eder
looked and sounded like a million bucks. Her vocal dynamism was as
impressive as ever, her big voice charged with feeling and
displaying the range to go from powerful belting to a pure soprano
for the gentler ballads.
</P>
<P>
   A key to this equation is that ``J&AMP;H'' and ``Civil War''
composer Frank Wildhorn, who is married to Eder and writes all her
original material, is supplying her with more varied and nuanced
material that plays to her strengths. In songwriting partner Jack
Murphy he has found his sharpest lyricist yet, giving Eder more to
work with, especially in a comic vein.
</P>
<P>
   The concert emphasized numbers from Eder's latest album, ``It's
Time.'' Besides the anthemic ballads that we know Wildhorn can
write and Eder can deliver with a knockout punch, the disc provides
an array of attractively bright big band-style numbers suggesting
1990s equivalents of standards by Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart
or Sammy Cahn and James Van Heusen, with a Nelson Riddle touch in
their brassy arrangements. Led from the piano by music director
Jeremy Roberts, Eder's eight-person band was tight and vivid,
though the Aerial Theater's amplification was unnecessarily
aggressive for most of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   When she eased confidently into the relaxed lilt of ``It's
Time,'' the title song confirmed not only its lyrics' ``time for
romance'' message but also Eder's arrival as a major stylist. She
gave vocal sparkle to the wry humor of ``Don't Ask Me Why,'' a
luckless girl's lament. Among the other new Wildhorn-Murphy tunes,
she made a feminist anthem of the punchy ``I Want More'' and
infused the show-bizzy ``Big Time'' with propulsive drive.
</P>
<P>
   When not singing Wildhorn originals, Eder chooses to perform
standards, even those indelibly associated with famed singers. This
is risky, but Eder has both the chutzpah and the pipes to pull it
off.
</P>
<P>
   She opened with an affectionate ``My Kind of Town,'' the
Cahn-Van Heusen tune forever linked with Frank Sinatra, and in
time-honored tradition changed the ``Chicago is'' line to ``Houston
is.'' She segued into a rousing ``Don't Rain on My Parade'' (from
Jule Styne and Bob Merrill's ``Funny Girl''), meeting the frequent
Streisand comparisons head-on by using the original arrangement and
even emulating Streisand's vocal inflections. The likeness was
almost alarming.
</P>
<P>
   In tribute to an entertainer she has credited as an enormous
influence on her, Eder sang two of Judy Garland's signature songs,
both by composer Harold Arlen. Eder's ``The Man That Got Away'' was
haunting, in an eerie arrangement that began softly and built to
despairing fury to match Ira Gershwin's torchy lyrics. She made
``Over the Rainbow'' her own with a loving, painstaking and
delicate rendition that caught the wistful yearning of E.Y.
Harburg's lyrics. Both songs raised goose bumps.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to two of the finest contemporary theater composers,
Eder did an intently focused ``Losing My Mind'' (from Stephen
Sondheim's ``Follies''), then soared through the wise and
wide-ranging passion of ``Unusual Way'' (from Maury Yeston's
``Nine'').
</P>
<P>
   Eder's biggest gamble was her fiery rendition of the heroic
title song from Mitch Leigh and Joe Darion's ``Man of La Mancha.''
While she may not be as persuasive a Don Quixote as Richard Kiley,
he never looked so glamorous; hers was a disorienting but
theatrical rendition.
</P>
<P>
   Eder pleased the audience with two of her ``J&AMP;H'' favorites, the
mega-ballad ``Someone Like You,'' which still tugs the heartstrings
when she sings it, and her risqu tavern show-stopper ``Bring on the
Men'' (which, as she pointed out, was cut, perhaps unwisely, before
the show reached Broadway). Eder anticipated the next big Wildhorn
project with two promising excerpts from the upcoming ``Havana'':
the lovely ballad ``Why Do People Fall in Love?'' and the rousing
and ambitious title number.
</P>
<P>
   For encores, Eder turned inspirational with her touching
treatment of Simon and Garfunkel's ``Bridge Over Troubled Water''
and closed with the Wildhorn pop anthem ``Something to Believe
In,'' ably backed by a vocal group of her ``Civil War'' colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that her audience believes in Eder. Given the
talent on display, a nonbeliever would be hard to find. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
