<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Despite U.S. efforts to keep the
Israelis and Palestinians talking at an isolated resort in
Maryland, efforts to resolve security issues and revive the peace
process remain uncertain. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICAN-REVOLT (Washington) _ A surprising number of
Republicans rebel against their party's leadership to oppose the
colossal $520 billion spending package approved by the Senate. The
renegades complain that the 40-pound document represents a failure
of Congress to follow its own rules. Most senators, they say, knew
little about the budget's contents when they voted. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ Staff members of the House
Judiciary Committee and the White House defense team meet privately
on procedural matters for upcoming hearings into whether President
Clinton should be impeached for his lying about the Monica Lewinsky
affair. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-VISAS (Washington) _ The $520 billion spending bill
approved by Congress includes a big bonus for Silicon Valley _ a
provision that would almost double the number of employment visas
for foreign computer programmers and others with high-tech skills.
By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-DRINKS (Washington) _ Americans consume twice as much soda
pop as they did 25 years ago, says a new study by the Center for
Science in the Public Interest. The result _ especially for
teen-agers, who typically down two to three 12-ounce cans a day _
is more medical problems including obesity and tooth decay. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-DUMP (Sierra Blanca, Texas) _ On the eve of Thursday's
decisive vote on whether to allow a radioactive waste storage
facility near Sierra Blanca, Mexican officials opposed to the site
stepped up high-level political pressure. There are reports that
the site will be rejected because of geological instability and/or
quiet political pressure from Texas Gov. George W. Bush. By JOHN W.
GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIAN-SUIT (Houston) _ The parents of Olympic gymnast
Dominique Moceanu agree to discuss their side of allegations that
they mismanaged the young athlete's finances. Their attorney says
they plan to fight the lawsuit filed by their daughter, 17, and
they deny the allegations of squandering money. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   TX-FLOOD-VICTORIA (Victoria, Texas) _ Floodwaters from the
swollen Guadalupe River are subsiding, but the authorities have
declared the estimated 850 homes that were evacuated off-limits for
several days. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONOCO-PUBLIC (Undated) _ Conoco, the sixth largest U.S. oil and
gas company, begins trading as a public company, establishing its
independence from parent DuPont. Valued at as high as $3.6 billion,
the deal is the largest initial public offering by a U.S. company
in history. By LAURA DURGIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-COMMUNISM (Paris) _ The naming of Massimo D'Alema, a
former Communist Party leader, as Italy's new premier marks a
milestone not only in Italian but also in European history. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-SERIES (San Diego) _ Coverage of Game 4 of the World
Series, where the New York Yankees could put the finishing touches
on the San Diego Padres with a four-game sweep. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Fulton, Mo.) _ Through a strange convergence of
events, this college town in central Missouri has attained a
symbolic status in the saga of the Cold War that for more than 40
years divided East and West. It was here that Winston Churchill
coined the term ``iron curtain.'' By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
