<HEADLINE>
TURNOUT COULD BE THE KEY IN CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR'S RACE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Henry Adams never walked a precinct nor took a
poll, but he understood voter turnout. The scion of presidents grew
up in pre-Civil War Massachusetts amid Federalist frenzy, Whig
anger, and the stirrings of the Know-Nothing Party. In ``The
Education of Henry Adams,'' he wrote: ``Politics, as a practice,
whatever its professions, has always been the systematic
organization of hatreds.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, hatred still motivates. Millions of Republicans,
prescandal or postscandal, despise President Clinton. Millions of
Democrats hate his court-appointed pursuer, Kenneth Starr. On Nov.
3, one group or the other will organize more systematically at the
polls. Seldom has the role of a president in off-year elections
seemed so murky, but that doesn't stop partisans in the nation's
largest state from guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton stuff seems like eons ago,'' says Paul Maslin,
pollster for Gray Davis, the Democratic lieutenant governor, who is
ahead of Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren in the contest for
governor. ``In a normal turnout in California in an off year
election, a 2 or 3 percentage point bias favors Republicans. The
electorate is always a little bit older, more conservative, and a
little whiter. We expect a Latino uptick in the first real surge of
that vote. A low turnout? I just don't see it. Of the registered
voters, I'd say it will be a 60 percent turnout, in that range.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Schroeder, chairman of the Republican State Committee,
looks at the turnout tea leaves differently: ``If it comes in at 51
percent, as I think it will right now, Dan Lungren's governor, and
we have a Democratic Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP conducts tracking polls, asking 230 Californians
daily for whom and whether they will vote. ``In the last 45 days,
Democratic turnout has dropped 16 points. Our base doesn't appear
to be more motivated, but theirs has declined, according to
absentee ballot requests,'' Schroeder says, pointing to the high
motivation factor (of hatred) in the US Senate race between
Democratic incumbent Barbara Boxer and Republican Matt Fong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fong-Boxer race drives our base but doesn't drive
theirs,'' he says, pointing to a Clinton connection: ``The reason
it's down overall on one side is that Clinton's numbers'' in terms
of voter favorability ``went from 63-30 to 57-38 percent over that
same 45 days. That's in the Field poll, and it correlates to what
we're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Merv Field began his career in polling, California had 2.7
million voters. This year, more than 15 million voters are
registered, but Field warns of ``deadwood'' in the rolls because
some 35 percent of Californians move every year. The Field poll
separates ``likely voters'' from no-shows by asking whether they've
voted in the past several elections and how certain they are to
vote this time.
</P>
<P>
   Field is not as confident as some national pollsters about
turnout patterns. John Zogby was quoted as saying ``Right now,
there is no evidence of a re-energized Democratic voter,'' echoing
the comments of Lydia Saad, the Gallup Poll's managing editor.
``Democratic interest in the election surged over the last two
weeks, where Republican interest stayed the same,'' she said,
adding that ``Republican voters are now showing more partisan
loyalty than Democrats, with party support rates very similar to
1994,'' when Republicans captured Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the level of turnout, but the character of
turnout,'' Field argues. ``Republicans, as well as Democrats, might
say, `A plague on both your houses,''' Mercutio's dying words in
``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   Historical patterns suggest that plagues do not divide evenly.
If discouraged Democrats stay home and turnout dips even slightly,
it could be but a scratch to Clinton, who may eventually evoke
Mercutio's farewell: ``'Tis not so deep as a well, nor as wide as a
church door, but 'tis enough, 'twill serve. Ask for me tomorrow and
you shall find me a grave man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
