<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-21 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HISTORY OF CATHOLICISM IN BOSTON FASCINATES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when 35,000 faithful Roman Catholics would fill
Fenway Park for a rally sponsored by the Holy Name Society; when
hundreds of priests would parade through the streets of Boston in
honor of the Virgin Mary; and when the cardinal's daily radio
broadcast of the rosary commanded a huge audience.
</P>
<P>
   The early to middle part of this century was the heyday of the
Archdiocese of Boston, the period when the Catholic Church emerged
as a political and social force.
</P>
<P>
   It was an era when Catholics, who had long played second fiddle
to Protestants, transformed Boston into a decidedly Catholic city,
dotted with majestic brick churches, monuments to the power and
glory of the church.
</P>
<P>
   This is one slice of the story of Boston's Catholics that Thomas
H. O'Connor, the renowned Boston College historian, captures in his
new book, ``Boston Catholics: History of the Church and Its
People.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, widely regarded as the dean of Boston historians, does
not just tell the story of the princes of the church, but examines
the experiences of the people in the pews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make it a human story, about the people in the
parishes, and not an institutional story,'' said O'Connor, an
affable man who keeps a busy schedule at Boston College, where he
is a professor emeritus. ``It was the people who helped shape the
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor hopes that his book appeals to Catholics and
non-Catholics. After all, he noted, anyone interested in the
history of the city must have some understanding of how an
immigrant, impoverished archdiocese became a power broker.
</P>
<P>
   The easy and most obvious explanation of the ascendancy of the
Catholic Church in Boston can be given in a single word: numbers.
The vast numbers of Catholics, the Irish who arrived in the
mid-19th century followed by waves of eastern and southern
Europeans in the late 19th century, guaranteed the church's rise.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor doesn't buy it. ``Just because you have the large
numbers doesn't guarantee anything, because it could just be an
amorphous, disjointed mass,'' he said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Besides numbers, the archdiocese also has enjoyed astute
leadership, archbishops who have been able to organize far-flung
parishes into a cohesive army of believers. Finally, O'Connor
credits the hard work of the immigrants who filled the churches and
are the backbone of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years it took to produce the book, O'Connor said he
was surprised by what he learned of some of the archdiocese's
little-known leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop John Williams, for example, who led the archdiocese
for two decades following the Civil War, built Holy Cross Cathedral
and St. John's seminary; established the parochial school system;
and inaugarated the St. Vincent De Paul Society. Williams also set
a welcoming tone for the flood of European immigrants arriving in
Boston, establishing national parishes for Italians, French, and
Lithuanians, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal William Henry O'Connell, during a tenure that lasted
from 1907 to 1944, turned a population of lay people still hesitant
about their place in Boston into a confident and empowered group.
</P>
<P>
   ``When O'Connell comes in, Catholics still suffer from a lack of
self-confidence, a sense that they are still kowtowing to the
Yankees,'' said O'Connor, who was born and raised in South Boston.
``But O'Connell comes in and tells them not to try and imitate the
Yankees. He tells them that they've got their own heritage and
roots. He created the CYO (Catholic Youth Organization) so
Catholics wouldn't have to go to the YMCA or YWCA, because those
were Yankee institutions. He made Catholics proud of their
Catholicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cardinal Bernard Law faces a new set of challenges.
Foremost, O'Connor noted, is the declining number of priests and
nuns. Increasingly, the church is relying on lay people, especially
women, to fill key posts.
</P>
<P>
   Law also has had to respond _ and here O'Connor gives the
cardinal high marks _ to a new wave of immigrants from Asia, Latin
America, and Africa. The archdiocese has established apostolates to
act as liaisons to the new arrivals, who have helped revive urban
parishes.
</P>
<P>
   Law also has forged strong alliances and good relationships with
Jewish and black religious leaders to address social and economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Law's authority is much more
diminished than those of his predecessors, O'Connor said. Catholics
today are well-educated, sophisticated, and unafraid to challenge
church fathers and teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laity expect to have a say in determining and shaping''
the archdiocese's future, O'Connor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
