<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KIDS-PAPERS-NYT &LR;      10-21 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-PAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDING HANDS OF YOUNG WEB WRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had my usual nightmare the other night, the one in which I am
stumbling down the halls of my old high school, feeling cold, late
for a biology exam, noticing that other students are staring oddly
at my outfit. Catching sight of my reflection in a window, I see
why. I am naked, except for a pair of men's black nylon dress
socks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the refusal of my subconscious to graduate from high
school partly explained my state of anxiety the next morning, as I
sat on a hard wooden bench outside the principal's office at my
daughter's elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that I was nearly two decades removed from the days
when I had to bend to the implacable rules of public school. No
matter that I was a parent, accompanied by a sleeping baby in a
stroller, here to protest the fact that my 9-year-old daughter had
been put on a waiting list to join the school's newspaper club. I
still felt a chill.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Sean O'Connell, principal of Southdown Intermediate
School in Huntington, N.Y., invited me into his office, I was a
mess. Plus, the baby dumped animal crackers on the floor, another
factor that possibly distracted him from my forceful eloquence, as
I argued that, to be able to accept my daughter, the newspaper club
should move to a larger room or accept help from parent volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Connell bounced the baby on his knee while I teased crumbs
from the carpet pile, he assured me that other students were sure
to drop out of the club to make room _ probably as soon as they got
their first assignment. ``So why are you getting so upset?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it seemed sad to exclude students from a fun activity
that would teach them about writing and, more important, about
having a voice in a community. Collaborating with friends to
express ideas that other people will read is still as powerful a
thrill today as back when, say, Thomas Jefferson took a crack at it
with the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   But the full truth was more complicated, tied up with a
recurring vision of me, helpless in those black nylon socks. ``I
don't want my daughter to grow up thinking it's OK to be thwarted
by bureaucracy,'' I said, finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' O'Connell said, ``why don't you have her start her own
newspaper and hand it out in class?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good idea, but as I drove home I thought of an even
better solution: let her start a newspaper on the Internet. After
all, the Internet is the antidote to the centralized authority of
the public-school classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Forget waiting lists. In the riotously egalitarian atmosphere
that prevails online, anyone is empowered to publish a newspaper,
simply by signing up for a free home page and typing some news on
it.
</P>
<P>
   When my daughter, Zoe, heard the idea, she said, ``Can I call my
friends right now and ask them to come over to help?''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, a fledgling staff of three elementary school
girls assembled at our house, took an immediate break for a snack,
then reconvened in front of the computer, ready to create a home
page for the newspaper. This would have been a good opportunity to
transform our family's moldering free home page on the Geocities
site into something useful, but a failure to update the page for
the past five months had prompted Geocities to reassign our web
address.
</P>
<P>
   No matter; in less than five minutes, we had been assigned a new
member name, password and new Web address at http://www.
geocities.com/EnchantedForest/ Tower/1609/.
</P>
<P>
   Using a basic text editor provided by Geocities, the young
journalists could click back and forth between an editing window
and the actual template of their website. Enamored of such basic
html commands as  &QL; 
p(GT) and  &QL; 
c(GT), they quickly mastered the rudiments of online layout,
creating new paragraphs and centering blocks of text on the page.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, they eschewed the  &QL; 
blink(GT) tag. Best of all, they saw their efforts published online
and updated each time they clicked the ``Save'' button at the
bottom of the text editor page.
</P>
<P>
   But almost as soon as the staff had christened the page
``Southdown Newspaper (NU)2: Interesting News About Southdown
School,'' I started to worry. Perhaps the fledgling news hounds
needed guidance from an experienced online publisher. After all,
with its capacity for disseminating information nearly instantly to
a worldwide audience, the Internet raises issues different from
photocopied sheets handed around a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Peter Owens, the professor of English at the University
of Massachusetts who started a children's interactive news service
at www.kidnews.com in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take extra care to protect kids,'' Professor Owens
said, ``because you've got an unlimited circulation now, which
makes it much easier for unsavory people to find the publication
than if it were just sent home from school on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   He also passed along a few tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not publish bylines that reveal children's last names or
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be sensitive about potentially embarrassing material, using an
`Anonymous' byline to protect the author.
</P>
<P>
   _ Build online archives for readers interested in back issues.
KidNews, for instance, did not accept new submissions for a few
weeks during the past month, while the site changed ownership. But
its archives remained rich with news written by more than 6,000
children worldwide. The site's new owner, Elaine Floyd, began
accepting submissions again this week.
</P>
<P>
   Hewing closely to Owens's advice, the staff of Southdown
Newspaper (NU)2 composed timely dispatches on the recent dispute
over the large number of students in each fourth-grade class _ ``by
Zoe, grade 4,'' the byline read _ results of recent student council
elections, by Natalie, grade 5, and the fourth-graders' weekly
schedule, by Kyle, grade 4.
</P>
<P>
   They came downstairs only once, to ask how to spell
``treasurer.'' I noticed later that they still needed a copy editor
to show them how to spell it. But they did learn a different lesson
that afternoon: how to overcome bureaucracy without breaking the
rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
