<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9268 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WOMEN-(2TAKES)-NY     10-21 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WOMEN-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN WANT IT ALL, AND ITS ALL ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By NINA TEICHOLZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American women are fast closing the Web gender gap. Women 50 and
older are one of the fastest-growing populations online, and women
now make up almost half of all American Internet users. Given the
reams of magazine pages devoted to charting a woman's every body
curve and fashion fetish, Web sites for women were merely a matter
of course.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Pack, founder of the Women.com site, said women and men
functioned differently on the Net. Men are surfers, she said,
whereas women are seekers, going online to get specific information
_ advice on acne or how to do a proper sit-up _ and not spending
hours just looking around. They don't have time, Ms. Pack said, not
with children and careers and mealtime coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have applications and tools that help women get things off
their to-do lists,'' said Jason Stell, a spokesman for the iVillage
Web site. Accordingly, many women's Web sites are short on news
analysis and are instead crammed full of advice. Like women's print
magazines, these sites combine a number of topics (health,
child-rearing, work), while men's publications, online and off,
tend to pick one topic and stick with it (Muscle, Outdoors and
Men's Health magazines). ``Women integrate various aspects of their
lives,'' Stell said. ``Men, not so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the biggest sites aim to be for every woman, like
Working Woman magazine, Good Housekeeping and Vogue all rolled into
one. With strong corporate backing, these sites aim to capture the
entire 25-to-49 age group that advertisers so covet.
</P>
<P>
   Other, smaller sites are presenting an array of information on
topics long considered too delicate for the magazine racks; Web
zines for young women can be positively lurid.
</P>
<P>
   Still other women's sites define their niches more narrowly,
like the travel magazine Maiden Voyages (maiden-voyages.com), the
national sports clearinghouse Women'Sports Wire
(www.womensportswire.com) and a bookstore for women
(www.womenbooks.com).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the traditional women's magazines have online editions,
including Vogue, Cosmopolitan, Elle, Glamour and Redbook. But they
do not have much of a Web sensibility; they have lots of fashion
photos that take too long to download and, in most cases, very
little content. Mainly they are online to woo subscribers for the
print versions.
</P>
<P>
   Not that women on the Web are not interested in fashion and
beauty. Fashion Icon (www.fashion-icon. com), has reports on street
style, designers and fashion news. Fashion Net (www.fashion.net) is
packed with links to stores and products. And dedicated fashion
consumers will want to hit samplesale.com, a site that lists, day
by day, nearly every designer sample sale in the country. For
cosmetics and beauty, try Heather Kleinman's Cosmetic Connection
(www.kleinman.com).
</P>
<P>
   To help you navigate through all these sites, there is Femina
(femina. cybergrrl.com), a Web guide for sites ``for, by and about
women.'' Femina breaks sites into useful categories, like Yahoo's,
and its listings are extensive. And it is worth noting that the
categories include lesbians and bisexuals, and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   While Web sites for women fell behind the curve in the
Internet's infancy, they are quickly catching up. The Web has few
barriers to entry, making it a remarkably egalitarian place, and
thousands of women have responded, drawn by the chance to dictate
their own content. The result is a host of voices and concerns
rarely seen on the newsstand, and well worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   From Fluff To Finance
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WWW.WOMEN.COM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of a woman's age, profession or education, Women.com
aims to inform her. It has such disparate offerings as an
interactive tax planner, climate information for gardeners, a
how-to item on negotiating your salary and a workout personality
quiz.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com is actually a network of six separate Web sites:
Crayola Family Play, Stork Site (for pregnant women), Money Mode,
Beatrice's Web Guide, Prevention's Healthy Ideas and Women's Wire.
</P>
<P>
   There is a remarkable amount of information provided among these
sites, and much of it is presented in a lively, interactive way. At
the Healthy Ideas site, for example, you are not simply admonished
for eating badly; instead, you can reinvent your diet with a
``daily meal planner'' or punch your lunch into an interactive
calorie counter. In the Women's Wire style section, you can create
a virtual wardrobe by taking a style quiz or catch up on beauty
news.
</P>
<P>
   Although Women.com aims to attract the sophisticated, successful
woman, the tone is often chirpy and condescending, treating the
user more like a preteen than a woman. Instead of domestic or
international news, there is Good News, stories of caring and
sharing sponsored by Hallmark. Instead of politics, Women.com
offers For Princess Diana _ On her 37th Birthday. Often, too, the
choice of articles implies an obsession with how men and women
differ _ a male frame of reference that is disheartening to find.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, on the less girly side, there is a great deal of
financial advice in Money Mode, with stock prices and articles from
Bloomberg, and primers on every financial topic imaginable, along
with interactive planners (an education-cost calculator and a
mortgage calculator). Women's Wire has a section for the working
woman, with a job bank, a resume builder, a ``biz shrink'' who
answers questions and a section with profiles of successful women,
including what they think about men. You can also find out about
child care and care for the elderly, and get your work horoscope.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   For mothers, Crayola Family Play offers ``hundreds of activities
to do with your kids.'' Primary colors and building-block graphics
make this site look as though it was designed more for children
than for adults, but it does have enough ideas to keep your kids
busy for a thousand rainy days. (For Halloween, there are recipes
for jack-o'-lantern cookies and spooky slime.) A pregnant woman can
enter the Stork site and check the Babygram, which tracks the
development of her fetus (``this week your baby is beginning to
develop a little fat under the skin'').
</P>
<P>
   Finally, those users of Woman .com who want a male perspective
can write to the site's token guy, Emale.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WWW.IVILLAGE.COM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WWW.UNDERWIRE.MSN.COM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It takes a village to do just about anything at the iVillage
site. Offering support groups, bulletin boards and buddies,
iVillage.com has a community for every interest. Among them are a
community for women trying to conceive children, parents of
multiples, parents of teen-agers, potty-trainers, women with
home-based jobs, wedding-bound women and stay-at-home moms. To
reach a health or fitness goal, you can sign up for an online
``support buddy,'' and if it's group support you seek, you can join
one of the ``community challenges,'' like the Kick Butt challenge
to stop smoking and the Shape Up for Fall challenge. There's even
``cyber-support'' via e-mail, where you sign up with either a
digital coach or a mother _ one berates, the other encourages.
</P>
<P>
   Two experienced business women founded iVillage.com, and their
business acumen shows. The site has big corporate backers,
including General Electric and America Online, and links to buy
clothing, home appliances and other items are sprinkled throughout.
``We're very focused on the fact that the Web is one of the best
mass-marketing opportunities ever,'' said Jason Stell, an iVillage
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the formula is working: more women _ some two million,
according to Media Metrix, a Web-tracking business _ visit iVillage
than visit any other women's Web site. Women have flocked to
iVillage's online communities, where stories of anonymous
camaraderie abound: a single mother of two who has just received a
diagnosis of breast cancer goes online and writes of her fear, and
finds, two hours later, 12 messages in reply. These communities are
monitored by volunteers. ``It's a clean, well-lighted experience,''
Stell said.
</P>
<P>
   The same Women's Day tone found at Women.com pervades iVillage,
in articles like ``Celebrate Yourself!'' followed by ``Six New
Delicious Ways to Make Sweet Potatoes!'' Unlike Women.com, iVillage
offers no information on finances and little on world news. Still,
it does keep an impressive group of experts, available for
consultation on topics like child-rearing, health and fitness,
relationships and careers.
</P>
<P>
   The site sometimes verges on the cute, with items like ``The Joy
of Soy,'' ``Let's Talk Tofu'' and pink screens with daisies in the
``Keyboard Yoga'' section. But as a Web site for women in search of
kindred spirits, iVillage is one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   Underwire, a weekly Web zine on women's issues, has the usual
online advice on fitness and health, money, sex and relationships,
but this exceptionally well-designed site is much easier to
navigate and has more harmonious graphics than its rivals.
Underwire's more serious and sedate tone is also a relief after the
cheerleading of some other women's sites.
</P>
<P>
   While its offerings are narrower, they're deftly chosen.
Lucille's Garage' delivers auto advice, and Miss Manners answers
questions of etiquette. There are regular contributions by the
political humorist Molly Ivans, articles of some depth and a
Related Readings section with mostly Oprah Book Club-type
suggestions. All books are related to Underwire's topic of the
week. A recent subject was race, with articles on the role of anger
in psychological health among minority women, and a
Taiwanese-American woman's experiences with discrimination in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   On the more whimsical side, Novel Idea is Underwire's adventure
in group storytelling. A prologue to a tale was posted and readers
took it from there, weaving a story, one reader picking up where
another left off. Three hundred and nine paragraphs into the
current Harlequin Romance-style story, the stunningly beautiful Kay
has just solicited from the beautiful and rich Natasha the tragic
story of her father, a spy in the Soviet Secret Service who almost
married a woman with strong connections to Czar Nicholas I. The
story is fairly chaste; clearly these authors have not been over to
Estronet.com lately.
</P>
<P>
   Making Women's Votes Count
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMENVOTE.ORG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ifyou want to delve behind the speeches of your senator or
representative, full voting records for all members of Congress are
available on Womenvote.org, the first Web site to publish an
interactive voting guide for women. Select the issues of most
interest to you from a substantial menu including general topics
(international trade and finance, crime) as well as so-called
women's issues (family planning and abortion, children and
families). ``Vote'' on various pieces of legislation from the past
four years and then compare your positions with those of your
representatives in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This nonpartisan Web site does not advocate; instead, it aims to
educate women and connect them with people influencing events.
Included here are many votes that newspapers neglect to cover,
particularly amendment votes and close votes. The site, which
opened in April, has surveyed many of the challengers in November's
elections on how they would have voted on particular issues and
will soon publish the results so you can compare their stands to
the incumbents'. The site plans to offer discussion groups,
candidate forums and news-maker forums after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Womenvote.org hopes to expand eventually to state politics.
Women with an agenda may also want to check out these comprehensive
sites: the Feminist Majority (www.feminist.org) and feminist. com
on the left and www.rightgrrl. com on the right (with links to the
Support Paula Jones and Support Linda Tripp Web sites).
</P>
<P>
   On the Edge (And Over It)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ESTRONET.COM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This hormone-pumped network is not the place to look for thinner
thighs in 30 days or a recipe for chocolate cupcakes. Estronet.com
is one of a half-dozen or so raunchy sites aimed at the
20-something woman interested in, well, sex. (Last week, the
network merged with the Chickclick network, which is oriented more
toward teen-agers, and is now the host for 22 sites.)
</P>
<P>
   An independently minded group of young women is behind an
eclectic group of sites, including Bust, Wench, Gurl, Swanky,
Hissyfit, Skirt and Minxmag. Some sites in the network are aimed
more at teen-agers, but even the presumably more mature sites, like
Bust and Wench, are fairly shallow and obsessed with sex. In the
Obsession issue of Maximag.com, for example, the leading articles
are ``Loving Latex: One Woman's Obsession'' and ``Sex Positive for
the New Millennium,'' which promotes personal liberation through
``great sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the content at Estronet, particularly at Bust.com and
Mousy. com, rival the Starr report for risque material. Scrolling
through Mousy, with features like Don't Call Me in the Morning, you
might wonder if these aren't actually pornography magazines for men
in disguise. But there are no pictures, only personal confessions
aplenty, and no topic is too intimate.
</P>
<P>
   One slight departure is Wench. com, which, contrary to its
perjorative name, aims to explore women's roles in society. The
site admits that it has only a ``vague idea of the direction we're
heading,'' but it's off to a decent start. There are a few articles
on national politics and two on sexism that it discovered in
computer software packaging and cartoons on Bazooka bubble gum
wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the feminist bent in Estronet is not so much
political as anti-high fashion. For example, several sites
criticized Vogue's requirement that Oprah Winfrey lose 20 pounds
before gracing its cover. ``Big whoop,'' Maximag said, to
``conventionally beautiful faces and unconventionally narrow
thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Irwin, Estronet's founder, said the network intended to
get beyond the vapidity of Vogue to address more serious topics
like date rape and menstruation. And although her site has drawn
plenty of contributors who want to share their stories, not too
many people are reading them _ at least not yet. For all the media
hype surrounding Estronet, it had fewer than 100,000 visitors a
month at the time of its merger, said Media Metrix, which tracks
Web usage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
