<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     10-21 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 25) ,
 IN FULTON, MO., LEGENDS OF CHURCHILL AND REAGAN INTERTWINE ,
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULTON, Mo. _ Through a strange convergence of events, this
college town in central Missouri has attained a symbolic status in
the saga of the Cold War that for more than 40 years divided East
and West.
</P>
<P>
   It was from Fulton on March 5, 1946, that one of the 20th
century's greatest statesmen, Winston Churchill, warned the world
that an aggressive communist empire had lowered an ``iron curtain''
across Europe's midsection, severing the communist east from the
democratic west.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic an iron
curtain has descended across the continent,'' declared the eloquent
Englishman. ``Behind that line lie all the capitals of the ancient
states of Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warsaw, Berlin, Prague, Vienna, Budapest, Belgrade, Bucharest
and Sofia, all these famous cities and the populations around them
lie in what I must call the Soviet sphere, and all are subject in
one form or another, not only to Soviet influence but to a very
high, and, in some cases, increasing measure of control from
Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at the beginning of World War II, Churchill and U.S.
President Franklin D. Roosevelt had been about all that stood
between Germany's Adolf Hitler and the freedom of the British
Isles. Without the two leaders, they probably would have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill, stripped of his prime ministership by British voters
in 1945, journeyed to Fulton as a private citizen at President
Harry Truman's invitation. There, he delivered his historic speech,
entitled ``Sinews of Peace,'' at a copy of a magnificent
17th-century London church _ St. Mary the Virgin, Aldermanbury. The
original church, designed by Sir Christopher Wren and gutted by a
German bomb in World War II, was dismantled and reconstructed
brick-by-brick on the campus of Fulton's Westminster College.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill's warning, which signaled the start of the Cold War,
was followed by Truman's monumental decisions to provide arms and
economic aid to deter communist aggression in Greece and Turkey, to
rehabilitate war-devastated Western Europe with the Marshall Plan,
to launch an airlift of 2 million tons of supplies to end the
Soviet blockade of Berlin and to halt North Korea's brutal
incursion into South Korea. Those bold actions saved Western Europe
and South Korea from communism.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades later, Ronald Reagan, another superb communicator
with ties to Fulton, was to serve as president during the
disintegration of the Soviet empire and the last gasps of the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Warner Brothers had released ``Kings Row,'' the movie
version of Henry Bellamann's novel about life, love, insanity and
sadism in small-town Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kings Row,'' which was closely fashioned after Fulton, where
Bellamann was reared, provided the handsome, 31-year-old Reagan
with his greatest role before he became president in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   It was the film in which Reagan, as Drake McHugh, cried out,
``Where's the rest of me?'' when he discovered that his legs had
been amputated by a cruel doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Before Reagan took office, every president since Truman had
sought to contain communist aggression while also seeking a
peaceful way out of the Cold War. But it wasn't until Reagan's
tenure, which coincided with the leadership of Mikhail Gorbachev in
the Soviet Union, that the Soviet empire began to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Capping the efforts of his predecessors, Reagan spent roughly $1
trillion to bolster America's defenses and ordered development of a
space-based missile defense system, known colloquially as ``star
wars.'' He also proposed that instead of limiting their number of
missiles, the United States and the Soviet Union actually reduce
their arsenals of such weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After much negotiation, Gorbachev, realizing that the Soviet
economy was facing disaster and that change was imperative, wisely
agreed to a number of Reagan's proposals and promised to remove
Soviet troops from Eastern Europe and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reagan's last two years in the White House were
tarnished by the Iran-contra scandal, they also witnessed the
beginning of the end for what he once had branded the ``evil
empire.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be an exaggeration to credit Reagan with ending the Cold
War as his supporters do, but he played a major role in bringing it
to a peaceful conclusion by adopting policies that hastened the
demise of the Soviet empire.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years after he retired to California, the Berlin Wall
was torn down, and democracy replaced dictatorship in such
communist satellites as Poland, Hungary and East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   There is no substitute for strong, enlightened leadership. That
is the story in Fulton where the legend of Winston Churchill is
entwined with that of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
