<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9294 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-21 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY TRAVEL, WHEN THE INTERNET GETS YOU THERE QUICKER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as Russell Baker once noted that all real reporting is
investigative reporting, I believe that all real writing is travel
writing. Every good author takes you on a real or fictional voyage
to a place you have never been.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also an important literature of staying at home.
Ivan Goncharov's slothful 19th-century hero, Ilya Oblomov, can
never figure out a reason to leave his bedchamber. In J.K.
Huysman's 1884 novel ``Against the Grain,'' his protagonist embarks
on a trip from Paris to London, but gets sidetracked at a Parisian
pub that serves roast beef and plum pudding. Savoring the British
ambience (``Was he not now even in London, whose aromas and
atmospheres surrounded him?''), our man never makes it to the train
station. ``What is the use of moving,'' he asks, ``when one can
travel on a chair so magnificently?''
</P>
<P>
   What use indeed? Why spend hours bouncing around in some
ill-riveted, flying cattle car only to be gunned down by local
soreheads at the foot of the Pyramids? Now, thanks to modern
technology, you will soon be able to go everywhere, without having
to travel anywhere at all.
</P>
<P>
   I first learned about the Virtual Heritage movement at a flashy
demonstration of Silicon Graphics' Infinite Reality computers.
Using software developed by Italy's Infobyte, I ``toured'' St.
Peter's basilica, and even flew to the ceiling of the Sistine
Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   A similar installation is now in place at the new Getty Museum
in Los Angeles, where visitors can take a virtual reality tour of
the Emperor Trajan's forum, digitally ``reconstructed'' by
archaeologists from UCLA and Northwestern University
(www.aud.ucla.edu/ &QC; 
bill/trajan.html). As it happens, this is the only chance you will
have to visit Trajan's famous meeting place, which was mostly
flattened by an earthquake in AD 850.
</P>
<P>
   One of the purposes of Virtual Heritage is to restore sites that
have been lost, like the forum. But another aim is to keep people
away from monuments deemed ``at risk'' from human visitation.
Infobyte (www. &QC; 
infobyte.it/catalogo/uk/vr/titoli.html) is now working to re-create
the pharaohs' tombs, which can no longer accommodate the hordes of
tourists who want to tramp through them. A company named Connected
PC (www.connec &QC; 
tedpc.com) &UR;  &LR;  can take you on a fly-around tour of Virtual
Stonehenge _ and simulate solstice sunrises _ saving you the cost
and the discomfort of the trans-Atlantic flight.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, another joyless tourist ritual, the annual
``leaf-peeping'' pilgrimage, has gone digital. Yankee magazine,
headquartered in terminally quaint Dublin, N.H., operates a Web
site called Foliage Central (www.neweng &QC; 
land.com/foliage/leaves.html), quite handy for the Oblomovs among
us who rarely set foot beyond the bedroom door. The Yankee site
features an impossible-to-read map indicating that the very best
foliage to be seen today is in Providence, R.I., a city somewhere
south of Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   For complicated meteorological reasons best explained by the
Weather Channel's Web site (www.weather.com/fall), which also
tracks peak color trends, Vermont and New Hampshire are finito for
foliage. Of course, that's not the impression you'd get from those
states' tourism Web sites (www.visitnh.gov, www.tra &QC; 
vel-vermont.com/), &UR;  &LR; virtually aflame in leafy hype. Perhaps some of
those British barflies we quoted in the Sunday paper _
``Color-Starved British Flock to New England for Foliage Display''
_ can be duped into traveling up there.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there will be a Daily Leaf Cam that allows you to
``see'' the resplendent colors digitally. This one
(www.boston.sidewalk.com/ &QC; 
link/34310) purports to be a view of the village green in Dorset,
Vt., as viewed from the Dovetail Inn. Lately, it's been the village
gray, looking more like the view from a state-run hotel in
pre-glasnost Bratislava than a scene from the Green Mountain state.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like my reality to be a little more virtual, please.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(AT)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERGUSON-ARCHITECTURE     10-21 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERGUSON-ARCHITECTURE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECT OF THE NEW GRANDEUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla., Mass., Okla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEWATER, Conn. _ For every architect there is an ideal
client.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when Mark Ferguson met his patron of a lifetime,
the client's estate consisted of a simple gray saltbox house on 11
acres overlooking a valley and mountain here in western
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson wasn't the King of Limestone then. He was a young man
fresh from Parish-Hadley, the interior design firm, setting up
practice with two others as Traditional Architects; men who
believed firmly in the vocabulary of classical times, who reveled
in architraves and arches, fan windows and dentil molding and
crotch-mahogany veneer.
</P>
<P>
   The client, Peter May, asked only for a small library addition
alongside the 1960s saltbox. He was the first of a series of
well-to-do men and women to seek out Ferguson, though this first
commission would hardly compare to the grandeur of the architect's
later designs: the Spanish haciendas in Palm Beach, Fla.; the
English Tudor manor houses in Tulsa, Okla.; the McKim, Mead &AMP;
White-style beach bungalows on Martha's Vineyard. And it certainly
didn't compare to Ferguson's most monumental effort, the
Sagaponack, N.Y., home of the investor Ira Rennert, a
59,000-square-foot columned villa now under construction _ probably
the largest American house to be built during the second half of
this century.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferguson was content to start out small, at least in square
feet. The little library for May, paneled wall-to-wall in knotty
pine to match an 18th-century mantel with rosettes found at an
antiques show, was so magnificent that May soon grew dissatisfied
with the rest of the house. He bought another 60 acres and asked
his architect to design an exercise room behind the library.
Eventually, they cut french doors across the back wall, opening to
a new terrace.
</P>
<P>
   But it still didn't feel right. ``It was never going to be the
ultimate house,'' May recalled, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   So he ordered the saltbox house ripped down and commissioned
Ferguson to design an elegant Georgian country house, with Roxbury
fieldstone, a Doric portico and a hipped roof with a cupola and
widow's walk. Outside, Ferguson designed courtyards, terraces, a
sunken garden and a pool casino with a columned pergola. But just
when Ferguson thought the complex was perfect, his patron has
decided he wants something more: a kind of separate loggia off the
front, a shady place to sit and look at the view and garden;
something with more openness than the screened-in porch, but less
than the pool pergola.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ferguson is drafting that, May, whose company, Triarc,
last year snagged Snapple at a bargain price, decided it was time
to tear down the three-car garage with the fan panels and classical
details, and design one for four cars, with a luxurious sitting
room and, overhead, a few bedrooms for guests. Oh, yes, and a large
porch big enough for chaise lounges and tables, so the guests can
relax.
</P>
<P>
   Who said the '90s were washed up?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ferguson, 43, met with May. They pored over the
latest set of plans around the antique French kitchen table chosen
by Bunny Williams, Ferguson's friend, who decorated the house.
</P>
<P>
   Tomato-red metal scaffolding had been set up outside, with raw
wood planks at varying levels, one with a Chinese Chippendale-style
chair on it, ready for decisions about the best level to set the
patio floor for viewing the mountains and the 4,000-square-foot
greenhouse the architect had designed, next to the farm pond the
owner had dredged.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson pondered the kind of clients attracted to his firm.
</P>
<P>
   Would he consider doing, say, a $200,000 house?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to do something for a client with modest means,'' he
replied, his voice tinged with regret. ``The problem is to support
the kind of labor, the details we specialize in, our expertise in
custom design.''
</P>
<P>
   Take one door in the Connecticut house. It's over eight-feet
tall and looks like something out of Castle Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find this door in a lumberyard,'' Ferguson began.
``It's mahogany with figured veneer on the panels, and then it's
French polished. It's hung on unlacquered 5-by-5-inch ball-bearing
hinges with acorn finials. Then, you have the casing:
five-and-a-half-inches wide, made of one-and-three-quarter-inch
poplar painted to imitate the faux limestone that lines the
hallway's walls. This is not stock molding. It's milled with a
blade cut to a profile we designed, and it doesn't just go down to
the floor, it sits on plinth blocks. The threshold is made of oak
and, again, milled to a profile we designed. The latch is Baldwin;
the knobs are W.C. Vaughn Company.'' He took a breath.
</P>
<P>
   The price? About $6,000 for the door and door surround.
</P>
<P>
   There are 50 doors in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're journeymen,'' said Ferguson, a soft-spoken man with a
shock of blond hair, a perfect male-model type except for his ears,
which stick out just enough to make him look interesting. ``We're
architects with a small following. Not like the men who are doing
what we call `critical architecture,' people like Peter Eisenman.
They're interested in beauty and taste and the conventional things,
too. But at the same time, they're working really hard at being
inventive.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Ferguson continued wryly, is that, ``If you're
trying to re-invent architecture with every project, well, not
everyone's talent is up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or everyone's education. Classicists like Ferguson (whose
architecture degree is from Princeton University) and his two
partners, Oscar Shamamian and, notably, Donald Rattner, a founder
of the Institute for the Study of Classical Architecture in New
York, bemoan the fact that few architecture schools teach anything
pre-Bauhaus.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Prince of Wales' Institute of Architecture, a London
group, has more or less collapsed _ Rattner says it has now
``turned away from its roots to include something more synchronized
with current tastes: modernism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a cabal,'' Ferguson said, with good humor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the classicists admit they are in the minority, their
work often evokes strong feelings. But to Samuel White, a
great-grandson of Stanford and the author of a new book on the old
firm, there are both good and bad things about the new
mega-mansions designed to look as if they had been built 100 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Flipping through Ferguson's portfolio, he shook his head
admiringly. ``This guy is good, very good; these buildings are
beautiful,'' said White, an architect who also draws on classical
forms, but so far has stuck to smaller homes, perhaps 6,000 square
feet _ not 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   But to spend the kind of money involved _ Ferguson's Rennert
house has been estimated at $100 million _ makes a lot of people
nervous, even a descendant of Stanford White.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only bothers me because I think there are some original,
wonderful big houses in need of restoration,'' White said. Beyond
that, he worries what will happen to these pipe dreams of
billionaires. ``Imagine trying to resell a 60,000-square-foot
house!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Often, these giant homes _ too big for anyone but the men who
built them _ have found new lives as schools or museums. But that
is exactly what Rennert's neighbors in the Hamptons fear; in fact,
some worry that there is a secret agenda to immediately turn the
new mansion into a school _ an agenda the Rennerts' representatives
have denied, pointing out that if the house is turned into
something other than a single-family residence the town can revoke
its occupancy permits.
</P>
<P>
   The defenders of what others denigrate as excess ask what is
wrong with a man who creates his own fantasy _ whether classical,
modern or postmodern. After all, White pointed out: ``Stanford
White did the same with the Grand Trianon; he copied it as
Rosecliff for Tessie Oelrichs.'' The key is in the landscaping, he
added. ``These things become a joke if they're out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   While this kind of slavish attention to classical details and
proportion has been sneeringly labeled ``replicative'' (by the
architect Charles Gwathmey) and worse (by others), White wondered
if the clients are happy with what they have created. ``I would
have to ask the owners if they're comfortable in the houses,'' he
concluded, ``and if they are, then God bless 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   May, the man who hired Ferguson to design and redesign his
estate in Connecticut, said he is comfortable not only in the
house, but with the architectural style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like classical architecture,'' he said. ``It's an issue of
details. I like details. I have friends who appreciate the more
clean-lined architects: total form over function.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in having a house by Charles Gwathmey or
the latest Frank Gehry,'' he concluded. ``It's just not what I want
to live with. I'd get bored with ultra-simplicity.'' He shrugged.
``Besides, I just love projects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
