<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY NOT WEAR SNEAKERS TO THE BALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if Cinderella wore sneakers to the ball?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's a crazy thought. But fashion is supposed to make you
ask ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Just look at Giorgio Armani. This fall, he has introduced a
revolutionary sneaker that he wants women to wear to formal
functions and on their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. His $195 numbers are meant to be worn with long
evening dresses and skirts and business pantsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The sporty lace-up sneakers come in charcoal gray, olive, and
black. The fabrics include satin, wool flannel, neoprene, and
suede.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds too outrageous for Boston, think again. A
spokeswoman for Emporio Armani, where the shoes are sold
exclusively, reports the sneakers are hot with corporate types and
students.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for sure. The sneakers run circles around stiletto
heels ... and glass slippers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oilily established itself years ago as a fun clothing chain for
children. Its funky, brightly colored garments are memorable
because of extras like animal ear flaps, angel wings, and a fat
cartoonish character image named Blap.
</P>
<P>
   Some mothers started squeezing themselves into the kids'
clothing, so Oilily started a women's line eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those clothes are now so hot that this month Oilily opened its
first exclusively women's shop in the nation at 32 Newbury St.
</P>
<P>
   The company _ based in the Netherlands and with stores from
Switzerland to Indonesia _ is selling casual clothes and work wear
to women who want to branch out from wardrobes filled with solids.
</P>
<P>
   At Oilily, you'll find floral prints, plaids, stripes, and rich
designs in colors like bright orange, blue, yellow, and red. Prices
range from $75 for a blouse to to $350 for outerwear.
</P>
<P>
   So amid the sea of gray this season, now there's color.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Rose is probably the most famous model/actress you'd never
recognize. That's because she's a hand model who's appeared in more
than 5,000 television commercials and print ads since 1954. She's
soaked in Palmolive with Madge, held a coffee mug for Taster's
Choice, and iced a cake for Pillsbury.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old's hands are so soft and unwrinkled that Madison
Avenue has used them as stand-ins for Cybill Shepherd's, Candice
Bergen's, and Lauren Hutton's for various commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who lives in South Pasadena, Calif., used to apply heavy
creams and sleep in gloves to get her hands camera ready. But she
says, ``I kept wishing someone would make a simple hand product
that achieved the same results as my complex regimen.'' Finally,
Rose decided to invent one herself.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's introducing the Linda Rose Hand Care System, which
includes a hand cream and protective gel for $45. There's also a
$30 nail and cuticle serum. They're all designed to keep hands
looking young and they're available at Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Palmolive as hand softener.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
