<P>
   MOVIES _ Cinemark, a Dallas movie chain, plans to expand into
the Atlanta area. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NOLO _ On a stage set in Texas, but in a free-speech/free press
drama amounting to book banning in the computer age, a Berkeley,
Calif., publisher of how-to legal materials will defend itself
Wednesday against charges that it is illegally practicing law in
Texas. The Texas Bar has said California's Nolo Books's sales of
self-help legal books and computer software in Texas is tantamount
to practicing law without a license. The case, to be heard by the
Surpreme Court beginning today, is expected to set precedent in the
continued development of computer legal guides and has major
national and free speech implications. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ Dell Computer Corp. will always have its headquarters in
Austin, though it probably, at some point, have another factory
campus elsewhere in the United States. Q&AMP;A of highlights of
interview with Mort Topfer, the company's vice chairman.
(Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   ISS-ALLIANCE _ ISS unveils a new open alliance that means more
than 40 companies that sell hardware and software will integrate in
such a way that security issues are communicated, in real-time,
between the products. This takes the human error and human response
time out of the equation for the companies using these products.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISS-EARNINGS _ ISS group releases its earnings today. (Clothier,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ATLANTA-LAYOFFS _ Scientific-Atlanta laid off another 65
full time employees in its satellite unit as overseas sales have
tanked. No other layoffs in that unit are expected. ( Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
