<SLUG> BC-CIRCUITS-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've heard about off-site data storage. How does it work?
</P>
<P>
   A. Think of off-site data storage as a safe deposit box for
backup copies of your computer's files. While safeguarding against
typical crises like hard drive failures, destructive viruses,
accidental file deletion or a power surge from a storm or faulty
electrical system, off-site storage also insures the safety of
files from environmental disasters like floods and fires, as well
as from computer theft and vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Off-site storage companies have various services and methods of
handling files. Backing up files over the Internet is fast becoming
the most popular method of off-site storage. Most online backup
companies store your data by copying files from your computer to
one of theirs via modem and the company's special software of
choice. The software can automate the entire process, scheduling
the sessions and dialing the phone for you. Files copied over the
phone lines can also be retrieved in the same way for quick
restoration in the event of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   There are several companies that will also offer to make a
CD-ROM of your data and mail it to you on a regular basis so you
have fairly recent copies of your files on hand. If you are
concerned about confidentiality, make sure the off-site service you
choose offers password protection and encryption of your files.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have Internet access and still want off-site
storage, there are places that will provide you with postage-paid
mailers to send in your own backup tapes and disks. The company
will store them safely for you and nag you when it is time to back
up again, and in the event of a crisis, will send back the files
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Off-site storage prices start at about $20 a month. A Web search
will turn up a selection of companies that offer the service,
including Offsite Data Management Services (www.odms.com),
Connected Online Backup (www.connected.com) and Mailsafe
(www.cyberhost9.net/msoffsit).
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
