<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-CATALOGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIL ORDER: THE MORE, THE MERRIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the holiday season approaches, postal bags are
swelling to Santa-size proportions with mail-order catalogs. This
week, there will be two new arrivals in the mail _ both from small
downtown design stores that are new to the mail-order business.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, David Shearer and his wife, Gail Schultz, opened
Totem, a TriBeCa store that sells contemporary furniture and
accessories by young European and American designers. When they
kept hearing from out-of-town customers that there was that nothing
like Totem where they lived, the couple decided to do a catalog.
They will mail 10,000 copies of DSGN, their magalog, as they call
it, all over the country. In addition to products _ from Umbra
plastic wastebaskets to Scandinavian upholstered furniture _ DSGN
includes brief articles about interior design and designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun,'' Shearer said, ``and we're already
planning the next issue for spring.''
</P>
<P>
   To order a catalog, call (888) 519-5587. For shoppers who prefer
browsing on the Web to perusing a catalog, www.totemdesign.com is
up and running.
</P>
<P>
   This week's other catalog debut is from Troy, a shop on Greene
Street in SoHo that sells '60s, '70s and contemporary home design.
Troy Halterman, the owner, isn't mailing his holiday gift brochure
outside New York City, though. The first 5,000 copies are for
``sophisticated New Yorkers,'' Halterman said. ``This one is a
test. If the response is good, there will be others.''
</P>
<P>
   The catalog can be folded into a little box, with graphics that
recall the gift box the store had made specially for mailing
fragile objects. ``We think our new gift box is itself worth
keeping,'' Halterman said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Mxyplyzyk, the Greenwich Village shop known for
well-designed furniture and gifts will mail out its first catalog.
Kevin Brynan and Kevin Terpstra, the co-owners, are hard at work on
the venture. They, too, have had frequent inquiries from
out-of-towners who assume the store already has a catalog. Hang in,
shoppers: something to look forward to after the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
