<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-EVANS-BOS &LR;      10-21 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-EVANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED EDITOR HAROLD EVANS NOW HAS BOOK TO HIS CREDIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tan, trim, impossibly dapper, Harold Evans does not
defeat expectations. Opening the door to the Sutton Place duplex he
and Tina Brown, his wife and fellow famous editor, share with their
two children, Evans is the very model of a modern media general,
right down to his suspenders (red), cuffs (French), and accent
(British).
</P>
<P>
   He's just back from London and slightly jet-lagged, but the
whirlwind vigor that helped gain him one of the most glittering
resumes in journalism and publishing is soon evident. Evans may be
70, but he looks closer to 50. And talking about his new book,
``The American Century,'' he sounds more like 20, such is his
enthusiasm for this phone-book-size ``history for browsers,'' as
Evans calls it, that chronicles the United States in the years
between 1889 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   It makes perfect sense that Evans should be eager to talk about
the new book. Clearly, ``The American Century'' is a labor of love,
a work 12 years in the writing, and 40-plus in the contemplating.
``As early as 1956,'' Evans says, recalling his first visit to the
United States, ``I wanted to write a book about America and freedom
and the romance and the nearness of the history ... to put my arms
around it.''
</P>
<P>
   His eagerness to discuss the book makes sense for another
reason: It means Evans is talking about something other than what
he dismisses as ``the small change of Grub Street,'' which has
dogged him for much of the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he surrendered one high-powered post, president of
Random House, for another, editorial director for Mortimer
Zuckerman, the real estate tycoon who owns US News &AMP; World Report,
the (N.Y.) Daily News, The Atlantic Monthly, and the Boston-based
business journal Fast Company. (The publisher of Evans's book,
Alfred A. Knopf, makes it a condition of this interview that he not
be asked about his departure from Random House.)
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, Evans has focused on US News, which is currently
running a 10-part series drawn from the book, and the Daily News.
By design, Evans's duties have remained vaguely defined. ``The job
of the editors is to edit the papers,'' Evans has said. Is his job,
then, to edit the editors? ``You know,'' he replies, ``(Walter)
Bagehot said of the monarchy: The job is to advise, warn, and
encourage.''
</P>
<P>
   When it's pointed out this analogy carries an implicit
assumption _ for that matter, Evans would seem to have the makings
of quite a good sovereign _ he barks out a laugh and shakes his
head. ``The commoner who would be king,'' he mutters, then changes
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of it in terms of prime ministers or presidents
or what-have-you,'' says Zuckerman of his longtime friend's role
(Zuckerman is godfather to Evans's daughter Isabel and was among
the dozen or so guests when he married Brown). ``We're just all
working together to improve the editorial product.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,19 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `Invisible man'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At Random House, Evans enjoyed perhaps the highest profile in
book publishing. Now he's a self-described ``invisible man''
working behind the editorial scenes. ``If people say, `Harry's
doing nothing,' that's fine with me,'' he told The New York Times
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later he got back some of his old visibility, courtesy
of the highly messy firing of US News editor James Fallows. Fallows
told the staff he'd been dispatched by Zuckerman. Evans quickly
released a statement saying the decision had been his, telling The
Washington Post, ``I have not been known simply to be a lap dog.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it was his aggressive independence that had
established Evans's reputation. He grew up in the north of England,
the son of working-class parents. One can still hear a hint of
Yorkshire and Durham in his u's. ``When I was young,'' he says, ``I
was very conscious of the fact I spoke with a northern accent and
my father drove a train and I hadn't been to the right school.''
After 15 years working as a reporter and editor at several
provincial papers, he was hired in 1966 as chief assistant to the
editor of The Sunday Times of London. Within a year, he was editor,
a post he held until 1981. Evans put such a premium on
investigative reporting and crusading journalism that the paper was
sued 250 times (the Times won all but one of the suits). When
Rupert Murdoch purchased both the daily and Sunday Times, he put
Evans in charge of the former. Evans's struggle with Murdoch for
editorial control got Evans fired after 13 months _ and made him a
journalistic hero on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to the United States in 1984, serving concurrently as
editorial director of US News and editor-in-chief of Atlantic
Monthly Press (at the time, owned by Zuckerman). In 1986, he became
founding editor of the magazine Conde Nast Traveler, before taking
over Random House four years later.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that Evans was a high-wire act there. Publishing
insiders marveled at both his mastery of showmanship and relaxed
attitude toward the bottom line. A $6.5 million advance to Colin
Powell for ``My American Journey'' paid off handsomely. A $5
million investment in Marlon Brando's memoirs barely broke even.
Spending $2.5 million on a book by disgraced Clinton political
adviser Dick Morris proved a costly error.
</P>
<P>
   What is in dispute is why the act ended when it did. Was it that
an opportunity to return to journalism was irresistible to a
bred-in-the-bone newsman (Evans's line)? Or did a shaky balance
sheet mean he had to jump before being pushed (the consensus view
on Publishers Row)?
</P>
<P>
   Evans has been assiduous in promoting the former view, going so
far as to threaten suit against an English magazine, The Spectator,
that had portrayed him as having been forced out. And according to
The New York Observer, when Vanity Fair assigned a profile of Evans
that promised to be unflattering he refused to talk to reporter
David Margolick.
</P>
<P>
   Even his wife's much-publicized departure from The New Yorker in
July might be seen as having its uncomfortable aspects for Evans.
Being married to Brown, 44, has unquestionably added to his cachet.
With them as Zeus and Hera atop media Olympus, no other couple need
apply. Harry and Tina stand where once stood Henry and Clare Booth
Luce, then Ben Bradlee and Sally Quinn (Evans and Brown were wed at
the latter's Hamptons summer home in 1981).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,19 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Freedom fighter
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the couple's balance in editorial throw weight
has shifted. In ``Good Times, Bad Times,'' Evans's 1983 memoir of
Murdochian double-dealing, the index entry for Brown reads, ``see
Evans, Tina.'' Things have changed a good deal since then. Both his
leaving Random House and her leaving The New Yorker were Page 1
stories in The New York Times. Only she made it above the fold,
though. (The one other interview condition is no questions about
Brown's new magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   Asked about events of the past year generally, Evans is
characteristically upbeat. ``I'm very happy professionally,'' he
says. He professes amusement when it's pointed out he's now entered
his eighth decade. ``I can't conceive of leading `a life of
leisure,' heading out to the golf course each morning, that kind of
thing,'' he laughs. ``I just have to stay intellectually engaged or
I wouldn't be able to function. Perhaps this is a character defect,
that one has to keep going. I suppose I can't relax really, except
in my work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Century'' is a case in point. ``I am
persistent,'' Evans says, describing a regimen of rising each
morning at 5 to work on the book till 9 a.m. (with time out for a
daily swim), and devoting weekends, holidays, and vacations to it.
</P>
<P>
   Even when socializing he did research _ though what he learned
was dismaying to a self-confessed ``immigrant in love with the
romance of America.'' What had started out as an exercise in
self-improvement _ among Evans's hobbies, Who's Who lists ``boning
up on US history'' _ became what he hopes will be a contribution to
general civic education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go out to a dinner party and try to pump somebody about
their views on, say, FDR's court-packing plan or the Great
Depression, and finally it would come out that they didn't really
know what it was all about. It might sound simplistic to say this,
but coming here in '56 and then as a newspaper editor from England
where I'd faced many, many (legal) restrictions, I came to a more
vivid realization of the nature of American freedom than many
Americans who take it for granted do.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans regards ``the power of freedom'' as his book's ``essential
thesis.'' It's a power he has come to appreciate all the more,
presumably, since November. Or at least, when asked about the bad
press he's gotten over the past year (a fairly novel experience for
Evans), it's freedom he adverts to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the free exchange of ideas. I think back on
what I wrote (in his new book) about Near v. Minnesota. It was a
case where a racist newspaper, a vile sheet, really, was being
prosecuted. The Supreme Court, ruling in its favor, said that
freedom is not confined to the virtuous, and you have to believe
that. Free speech doesn't mean just things you like. I take a
completely philosophical view of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He delivers these words impressively, as an oration almost.
(Hearing Evans discuss his book, one suspects he could do for a PBS
version of ``The American Century'' what Shelby Foote did for Ken
Burns's ``The Civil War.'') Such eloquence makes a guest feel
somewhat awkward when he expresses puzzlement at these remarks. It
was Evans, wasn't it, who threatened to sue The Spectator?
</P>
<P>
   Evans's voice tightens, his warm manner disappears. ``I don't
want to go into that. It's small beer, simply a question of fact.
If you're dealing in fact, try to get the facts right, that's
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
