</P>
<P>
   Live story from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CONCORD _ Covering a prayer service for Glenn at 7 p.m. EDT
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY OCT. 27
</P>
<P>
   Live story and possible sidebar
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY OCT. 28
</P>
<P>
   Live story and possible sidebar
</P>
<P>
   PERSONALS _ Each astronaut gets to carry a small amount of
personal items of their choosing. Not essentials like toothpaste or
even music, but any old thing they want from teddy bears to
security blankets. But it all must fit in a container about the
size of a shoe box. What's Glenn taking? We try to find out.
(Montgomery, Cox News Service). 10.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY OCT. 29
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ After a 36-year hiatus, space pioneer John Glenn is set
to return to orbit today. The Space Shuttle Discovery is scheduled
to blast off at 2 p.m. EDT, launching Glenn and his six crewmates
on a nearly nine-day science mission that includes experiments to
study the aging process. Glenn became the first American to orbit
the Earth on Feb. 20, 1962, when he flew his Mercury capsule
Friendship Seven on a four-hour, 55-minute mission that circled the
earth three times. This mission will mark the first space shuttle
flight by one of America's original seven Mercury astronauts and
will make Glenn, at age 77, the oldest person to fly in space by 16
years. Glenn has emphasized the importance of his aging experiments
since NASA announced his selection for the flight in January. But
science is likely to take a back seat today to the sheer wonderment
of outer space. Despite Glenn's previous flight, retired space
shuttle pilot Joe Engle says Glenn is in for the experience of his
life. Glenn was strapped tightly into a tiny capsule on his first
flight, and his views of earth and space were limited to a small
window and a periscope. This time, Engle says, he will be able to
float out of his seat and drift up to the orbiter's large overhead
windows. When aimed at the earth, the two big windows ``are like a
glass bottom boat,'' Engle said. Engle said that moment, which he
experienced as pilot of the second space shuttle flight, stands out
above everything else he has done. ``It made the hairs stand up on
the back of my neck.'' So it's likely to be for Glenn, but don't
count on hearing him talk about it, etc. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily
News). 30-40.
</P>
<P>
   NEWCONCORD _ The scene in New Concord as John Glenn prepares for
his return to orbit. Perhaps get some longtime locals to talk about
what they did the last time, too. Also wrap in the prayer vigil
that starts Wednesday night and lasts until 7 a.m. EDT Thursday
morning. (Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THESE GRAPHICS:
</P>
<P>
   CANAVERAL -- A guide to Cape Canaveral's Kennedy Space Center.
Just a simple layout of buildings and launch sites that illustrates
where Glenn's launch pad is, where the VIPs sit, where the press
sits, where the closest spectators are.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE _ How the space shuttle deploys in stages after the
launch. (By the Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
