<HEADLINE>
HAVE A LAUGH OVER CELL-PHONE NATURALISTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At long last, for the modern outdoorsperson who has everything,
there is a camouflage cell phone shaped like an ancient
moss-encrusted tree root and capable of linking one to imperiled
rain forests and wetlands round the planet.
</P>
<P>
   OK, not really. But it's the kind of thing that comes to mind
when reading David Brooks's very funny piece, ``Cell Phone
Naturalists,'' in the Oct. 26 issue of  &UR; The Weekly Standard &LR; . The
article examines how the perennial war between nature lovers and
technology lovers may be gradually eclipsed by the _ dare we utter
it! _ compromise politics of a new generation of Cell Phone
Naturalists. These are the folks who believe in technology as much
as the nature they profess to love, the engineers and programmers
who may rarely venture into the wilderness, but head to work
dressed as though they just wandered off K1. The CPN doesn't so
much want to preserve nature. He wants to conquer it with Gore-Tex
and Polartec and water purifiers and, of course, his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks makes his observations from the throbbing heart of Kevlar
Kulture itself: the REI outdoors store in Seattle. Like any normal
person who wanders into such a place, Brooks is as daunted by the
myriad chemically engineered clothing options as by the humongous
calves of the salespeople. In the end, he cites a few cases in
which environmentalists and capitalists have found common cause of
late, without quite saying whether this is good or bad. But it's an
interesting piece, worth a read if only for its riotous beginning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton's unique method of curing cigars seared
in our memory, we rushed to this month's cigar press to see if the
presidential peccadillo had triggered a surge in cigar sales or
caused the Cuban economy to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, there was not a single mention of Monica,
although there were many sultry-eyed brunettes suggestively
fingering stogies. We did, however, stumble upon a gripping story
in the October  &UR; Cigar Aficionado  &LR; about a man called Aram Setian, a
testosterone-fueled individual who road-tests Mercedes-Benzes by
hurtling across the American terrain ever in search of craggier
peaks and more brutal temperatures. They call him the Benz Breaker.
</P>
<P>
   His is an astounding job, a road warrior fantasy come true _ if
you don't mind sitting on your fanny for 14 hours at a stretch.
Setian, a defector from the Bulgarian Red Army who looks
disappointingly like a vacuum cleaner repairman with a bad haircut,
spends his days ricocheting across the Southwest pushing his luxury
V-12 to speeds above 100 mph. Sometimes he is part of a convoy of
as many as 25 prototypes. Why don't we ever see these automotive
avalanches hurtling by on the highway? Because they're concealed
from consumers by screwed-on sheet metal camouflages, of course.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the driving day, the road warriors unwind big time
over amber liquid and, of course, cigars. Aficionado that he is,
Setian keeps a couple of Upmanns in his computer case and
occasionally sneaks across the Mexican border for replenishments.
And what do the boys do after coffee? Our story does not let on.
Suffice it to say that there is presumably not a lot of road dust
left on them by the time they are done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the flock of new magazines that has appeared on the
newsstands in recent years,  &UR; DoubleTake  &LR; has always seemed
something of a conundrum. A glossy quarterly featuring photography,
features, fiction, and poetry, the three-year-old magazine often
seemed to be groping for an identity. Sometimes it worked,
beautifully. Sometimes it was self-important and annoying. Either
way, one always wondered just who was reading all those terribly
literate pieces, not to mention paying the $10-per-issue newsstand
price.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever they are, they'd do well to buy the fall issue, which is
rumored to be its second to last. Of several very good articles,
the best is a short, low-billed gem about a botanist in Ecuador who
hits the homicide beat with a tabloid newspaper reporter to see if
he can't learn a ``trick or two about reporting extinctions.'' He
does. Sort of. He witnesses his first corpse, a man who choked on
his potato soup at a bar, lying in a field. The botanist watches
some women in baseball hats watching the dead man. He makes note of
the plants growing about the cadaver. (He is a good writer and not
just for a botanist.) He goes with the reporter to a couple of
funerals. He goes to a press conference. And then he gets on the
bus back to the forest where he works and reflects upon how when a
tree dies, how very quiet it is.
</P>
<P>
   It is a colorful bit of writing and just the kind of piece that
may go homeless in a world without DoubleTake. Also in the issue is
an interesting interview with Cambridge filmmaker Frederick
Wiseman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Halloween is right around the corner and if you happen to be
wondering what are the deadliest things in the world, the October
issue of the men's magazine  &UR; Maxim  &LR; is here to tell you. The list
includes: The curse on the Hope Diamond. Washington D.C. Fugu, a
Japanese dish prepared from puffer fish and from which the natural
poison is not always entirely removed. Working as a keyboardist for
the Grateful Dead (three have already died.) Candy apples don't
even make the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
