<SLUG> BC-HIRING-FINANCIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S MUTUAL FUNDS INDUSTRY WAITS FOR OTHER SHOE TO FALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A chill has descended over Boston's financial district, where
the heart of America's mutual fund industry is warily watching Wall
Street's downsizing and quickly readying itself to cope with life
in a volatile market.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of almost uninterrupted expansion, Boston asset
management firms are bracing for aftershocks from the global
financial crisis. &UR;  &LR; Despite a mini-rally in recent days, the
domestic stock market is off about 10 percent from its July peak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Putnam Investments, a mutual fund giant that nearly tripled in
size over the past five years, is about to implement a hiring
freeze, industry sources say. Massachusetts Financial Services, a
smaller firm that also grew explosively, has already done so.
Scudder Kemper Investments Inc., the New York investment firm with
Boston-based operations, has called off all hiring until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Wall Street-size cutbacks here.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's multitrillion-dollar asset-management industry has a
different structure than New York's money culture. Whereas
investment whizzes here make their living overseeing mutual fund
assets that generally tend to stay put over the long term, New
York's wheeler-dealer stockbrokers, traders and investment bankers
live in a transaction-oriented culture that lives and dies by the
market each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With mergers and stock offerings down, Wall Street companies are
taking hits to their bottom lines. By contrast, most
money-management firms have generally maintained strong revenues
despite the market downturn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That difference affords Boston some protection from layoffs of
the kind announced last week by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. The nation's
largest stock brokerage will ax 5 percent of its work &UR;  &LR; force, or
3,400 jobs, due to global economic uncertainty. Other investment
banks and brokerages are following suit, though not as drastically.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when depressed stock markets slash the value of assets
managed by a mutual fund firm, thereby reducing money-management
fees, revenues suffer _ and cost cutting comes to the fore. The
picture becomes worse if investors hand fund firms less new cash by
pulling back on purchases.
</P>
<P>
   So far that has not happened; investors are by and large simply
buying different kinds of mutual funds. But firms nestled in
downtown Boston are battening down the hatches just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the country's biggest mutual fund firm,
with 13,000 employees in Massachusetts, says it is still hiring.
</P>
<P>
   But in a twitchy market that since summer has flirted between a
10 percent correction and a 20 percent bear turn, industry
specialists speculate that layoffs are imminent.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent skittish staffers from preemptively jumping ship,
Fidelity recently blocked employee access to a popular Internet job
site geared to financial services, one fund industry source said.
Company insiders say staffers are increasingly spending their lunch
hours surfing the Web for job postings.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pioneer Group Inc., the mood is grim. ``All additional
hiring I would characterize as under very critical review and
intense justification,'' said spokesman Timothy T. Frost. ``We are
going to look very, very closely at expenses.'' Pilgrim Baxter &AMP;
Associates, the Wayne, Pa.-based mutual fund firm that is owned by
United Asset Management Corp. of Boston, plans to lay off 50 people
in its marketing division.
</P>
<P>
   At State Street Corp., the giant back-office processing and
asset management company, executives are preparing for a slowdown.
``Clearly, we are hiring less,'' said chief financial officer
Ronald L. O'Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's financial services firms grew furiously this decade,
becoming a bulwark of the state economy with around 60,000
employees. Investment firms have swallowed up a third of the
downtown commercial real estate leased or sold so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The global economic downturn looming on the horizon could change
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see a de facto hiring freeze across
the board in the industry,'' said Joseph C. Haberman, an executive
search consultant at A.T. Kearney in New York. He also predicted
layoffs of 5 &UR;  &LR; to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That causes fear among investment professionals, especially
after a wretched third quarter for stock funds that for many
signaled the bull market's end. ``The general mantra out there is,
`This is a chance to get rid of some of our laggard performers,'''
Haberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Many asset management firms, including Fidelity, are privately
held, so they don't have to tighten the belt after one bad quarter
to appease shareholders. Contrast that with other financial
services players that are publicly traded. BankBoston Corp., for
example, is laying off 111 staffers worldwide after a miserable
three months for emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In theory, Fielity cannot let off people in droves for the
long term because of a $40 million state tax break the local fund
industry received in 1996 in exchange for hiring pledges. Under the
deal, Fidelity must boost state employment by 5 percent a year, or
about 500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Most cuts in the asset-management industry will likely come in
areas that are contracted out to third parties, such as back-office
processing and consulting. Advertising and marketing expenditures
will also be reined in if there are fewer investors to woo in a
soft market. MFS has already cut its advertising budget for the
fourth quarter by 13 percent, spokesman John F. Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, people are scaling back pay expectations. Money
managers to whom hefty six figure bonuses are the cake, not the
icing, could be left with crumbs for the first time this decade.
``The bonus could be thin or nonexistent this year,'' said Jim
Lowell, publisher of the independent Fidelity Investor newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   With many companies now planning budgets for 1999, expenditures
are getting a once-over. At MFS, Poland Spring bottled water has
been replaced with the cheaper Atlas filtered system _ a move that
saves the company $60,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at many Boston firms, there's not much fat to trim in the
creature comforts area. Chalk it up to Boston's legacy of
austerity: Compared to flashy New York investment bankers, with
their minibars, shoeshine men, and no-holds-barred entertainment
budgets, Boston money men are a no-frills lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ned Johnson comes from a good strain of Puritanism and is lean
and efficient,'' said one fund industry source, referring to
Fidelity's chief executive. ``You see a lot more mahogany and
marble at Merrill than you do at Fidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson preferred wall-to-wall carpeting, plug-in shoe shiners
in the men's rooms, and plain Arabica coffee, not flavored
varieties, for the staff, the source said. Unusual for the
industry, Fidelity has a purchase-order system in which staffers
must justify an expense before they incur it. Most Fidelity
employees fly coach class.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there isn't room to trim. Fidelity spends
hundreds of millions on pet projects; it recently alloted $20
million to test an experimental technology base. Such efforts are
likely to be sliced in any downturn, said Louis Harvey, president
of Dalbar Inc., a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, fund companies are looking less at the stock
market's rally of recent days and more at the longer-term trend.
``A lot of people are going to be surprised,'' Haberman said.
``People don't realize the industry can react as fast as it does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
