<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAMM FACES DOWN FINANCIAL SERVICES REFORM LAW
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress appeared poised this year to dismantle a
Depression-era law that has prohibited consumers from one-stop
shopping for banking, insurance, stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, with his objection to a tiny piece
of the overhaul, stalled a reform that had been 20 years in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   His beef: expansion of the Community Reinvestment Act, a 1977
federal law that requires banks and savings and loan associations
to record the gender, race and income of loan applicants and report
each year whether those applicants received loans.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said the CRA has been turned into an Mafia-like extortion
device by groups representing consumers and minorities. These
``professional protest groups,'' Gramm charged, use the publicly
available data about lending practices to pressure banks and S&AMP;Ls
to set quotas for lending and hiring and to financially support the
protesting groups.
</P>
<P>
   The CRA, originally designed to ensure that banks were making
loans in communities where they receive deposits, ``has become a
rich source for extortion and kickbacks,'' Gramm said in an
interview last week. Asked why banks don't complain, he explained
that ``the merchants being shaken down by the Mafia don't complain
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's objection, shared by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala. and a
handful of other senators, stopped the legislation from coming to a
vote in the Senate. Even if the bill had passed, Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin and other presidential advisers had enough doubts
about the bill that a veto from President Clinton was considered a
good possibility. Still, Gramm played a big enough role in stopping
the financial-services overhaul that he was blamed by some for
killing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came closer to passing comprehensive financial services
reform in the 105th Congress than we have in a generation,'' said
Dean Sackett, a vice president of the National Association of
Professional Insurance Agents. ``Unfortunately, turf battles within
the Clinton administration, the looming threat of a presidential
veto, opposition by key senators to Community Reinvestment Act
requirements and the narrow interests of a small minority prevailed
over the interests of the country at large and those affected by
the legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's willingness to scuttle the overhaul of financial
services because it could expand the CRA beyond banks was the most
recent example of his lack of compunction about delaying or even
killing widely supported bills that contain items he opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, for example, he delayed for weeks a popular
agriculture-research bill because he objected to a provision that
restored food stamps to legal immigrants, including children, whose
aid had been cut off under the 1996 welfare reforms. The
agriculture bill eventually passed, unlike the financial-services
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's willingness to do in the bill also gives a hint of what
might be in store if Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., loses his
re-election bid Nov. 3 and Gramm succeeds him as chairman of the
powerful Senate Banking Committee, which oversees banks as well as
securities and federal housing policy.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill _ primarily the trade associations for
banks, insurance companies and securities firms _ had hoped until
last week that their lobbying efforts and campaign contributions to
key members of Congress might keep the bill alive as part of the
giant federal spending plan that wrapped up other unfinished
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the trade groups conceded defeat in a joint
statement, pledging to work together for passage next year and
thanking ``those members of the House and Senate leadership who
worked so hard to achieve legislation that could enjoy such broad
support.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was released the same day that the Center for
Responsive Politics reported that the industry groups together had
contributed $30 million to congressional campaigns since January
1997. Gramm, who is not up for re-election this year, was not among
the top beneficiaries of the group's money.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The ease with which Gramm blocked the bill, known as H.R. 10,
also illustrates continued uncertainty in Congress about undoing
the Glass-Steagall Act, written in the Depression to prevent the
concentration of banking, insurance and securities in mammoth firms
whose failures could wreak untold havoc.
</P>
<P>
   After many failed attempts at rewrites, Congress thought it got
it right this year, but H.R. 10 squeaked out of the House in May by
only one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needed some more fixes to be a really good bill,'' said
Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, a former investment banker and a
member of the House Banking Committee. Bentsen voted against H.R.
10, saying he was concerned about the assignment of regulators for
the new multi-purpose entities that the bill would create. He also
said he thought the bill short-changed small banks.
</P>
<P>
   Similar concerns kept the bill on hold in the Senate until
September, when D'Amato finally brought it before the Banking
Committee. It emerged from committee in mid-September and was
headed for a full Senate vote with the blessing of the banking,
insurance and securities industries, all of whom overcame historic
rivalries to back the Senate's version of H.R. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gramm took to the Senate floor Sept. 30 and declared: ``I
intend to do everything in my power to impede this bill ...to use
all of the rules of the Senate, no matter how long it takes, no
matter how difficult it may be.''
</P>
<P>
   He laid out his concerns that the bill expanded the Community
Reinvestment Act and ``literally set up the vehicle for billions of
dollars to be extorted from financial institutions in America by
people who are professional protesters.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gramm said he was thinking of groups such as
the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN),
a consumer group that often stages protests of businesses it
considers unfriendly to the elderly and poor.
</P>
<P>
   On hearing Gramm's charges, ACORN policy analyst Patrick Woodall
in Washington said, ``We must be the worst extortionists and
kidnappers in America.'' The group filed objections with the
Federal Reserve to three of the five big bank mergers this year;
not one was disallowed, Woodall noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that community groups have an incredibly
difficult time with lenders who are in theory the lifeblood of the
community,'' Woodall said. ``We do end up exerting pressure because
that's what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   ACORN and other groups also seek and receive financial support
from banks _ a practice Gramm said he would have moved to outlaw if
the bill had come to a vote. Woodall said the financial support
helps ACORN screen loan applicants for the banks; Gramm called the
practice extortion.
</P>
<P>
   The banks themselves said they have noticed ``some heavy-handed
tactics'' by groups wielding lending records under CRA, but the
banks have learned to deal with both the pressure and the paperwork
that the law creates, according to Pattie Cinelli, spokeswoman for
the American Bankers Association. The association supported H.R.
10.
</P>
<P>
   Was the bill worth killing over CRA? ``Not for the American
Bankers Association members,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
