<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GARDEN-AGNELLI-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN NOTEBOOK: THE BLURRY IMAGES OF A FAMILY HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo advisory.)  
 (ATTN: Italy)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new book, ``The Agnelli Gardens at Villar Perosa'' (Harry N.
Abrams, $75), is filled with fuzzy pictures of very beautiful
gardens in the Piedmont region of Italy, virtually secret gardens
that have never been opened to the public. They cover 25 acres
surrounding the Agnelli family seat in the village of Villar Perosa
30 miles north of Turin.
</P>
<P>
   Why are the pictures so fuzzy? Because the photographer, Marella
Caracciolo de Castagneto Agnelli, 71, the wife of Gianni Agnelli,
head of Fiat SpA since 1966, wants them that way, said her niece,
Marella Caracciolo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caracciolo, 33, and Mrs. Agnelli wrote the text for the
book, a history of the family as seen through its gardens. The
beautiful but impressionistic pictures hint at more than a taste
for witty abstraction. They underline a consistent attempt to
gauze-wrap any critical focus on a family that, in Italy, is seen
as comparable to the Kennedys _ that is, if the Kennedys controlled
the press, held the reins of society and ran the largest business
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Italian the film ``The Silence of the Lambs'' had to be
retitled (``Agnelli'' means ``lambs'').
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italian collective unconscious wants them to be royalty,''
Ms. Caracciolo said. ``In the completely disruptive Italian
republic, they represent some kind of unifying force.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Agnelli, a photographer for Vogue in the 1950s, is perhaps
best remembered from a legendary 1950s Town &AMP; Country photograph by
Richard Avedon of her swanlike neck and fine Neapolitan nose.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades ago, she began shaping the villa's gardens. What
she had to start with were straggly terraces laid out in the late
18th century (before her husband's great-great-great-grandfather
bought the villa), a 19th-century limonaia, or orangery, a
neo-Gothic memorial chapel, a great lawn with Victorian specimen
trees _ and unlimited funds.
</P>
<P>
   She removed flower beds shouting with red salvias in favor of
features like an English woodland walk and a kitchen and cutting
garden.
</P>
<P>
   The late great English garden designer Russell Page _ creator of
the smaller garden in the courtyard of the Frick Collection in New
York and of hundreds of luxurious private gardens in Europe _ made
a series of lakes where there had once been a mountain ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Gae Aulenti, the Italian architect, designed a pool and pavilion
in the 1980s. A sculpture garden focuses on works by Henry Moore,
Max Ernst and Rene Magritte.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the almost-too-perfect gardens relate to the polished
public image created by Gianni and Marella Agnelli, Ms. Caracciolo
said, ``They have managed to make themselves into what they wish to
be, what they appear to be.''
</P>
<P>
   She insists the gardens are not Byronic. ``This is the
antithesis of the romantic garden,'' she said. ``It's not about
melancholy at all, or about nature. It's about man as the master of
the landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   As a favored niece, Ms. Caracciolo had access to write the book,
but was under an obligation not to betray the family. All the
family mistakes have been kept within the family fortress, its
exterior smoothed by money and tight-lipped stoicism.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, it says, ``Villar Perosa had to remain an oasis
apparently untouched by the events of reality.'' The book alludes
only in passing to the Allies' bombing the villa during World War
II, and the Agnelli hankerings for ``fast cars, gambling, beautiful
women.''
</P>
<P>
   A garden history of Villar Perosa might not be the place to air
the Agnellis' documented collaboration with the fascists. But it
seems too much of a gloss to say, as the book does, that ``after
1940 and Italy's entry into the war, the family lived through a
period of separation'' and that the period was marked ``by
political and social tensions.'' Ms. Caracciolo said her aunt toned
down her first draft to fit a more discreet and stately vision.
</P>
<P>
   The sprightly Ms. Caracciolo is good-natured about this
intervention. When she interviewed various Agnellis for the book,
she found that their stories were as different from one another as
petunias from peas. Just as gardens are constantly replanted and
revised, so is family history. What doesn't work gets edited out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Caracciolo was a journalist for Epocha, a newspaper that is
one of the few in Italy not owned by the Agnellis. She is the
author of three books, including a history of another fabled
Italian garden, Ninfa. She lives in New York with her husband, the
painter Sandro Chia (who did the murals at the New York restaurant
Palio), and their two children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caracciolo is half Canadian, but her Italian side is
Caracciolo, a princely Neapolitan family. Still, she said, she is
not an Agnelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am of them but not of them,'' Ms. Caracciolo said carefully.
Within the pages of the book at least, Villar Perosa is perfection,
what Page called ``my Shangri-La.''
</P>
<P>
   But like the others of her generation in this family, Ms.
Caracciolo does not want the regimentation of perfection, the
striving for Shangri-La that was the old Agnelli way. ``I avoid
it,'' she said, sitting on an undistinguished yellow plush sofa.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from her loft apartment, however, her life is casual,
expensive and spare. But a little taste for Shangri-La lingers. On
the wall above her hangs a beautiful, tattered 17th-century Italian
tapestry that shows a Renaissance garden with figures.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, Ms. Caracciolo and her two children visit Villar
Perosa to see the generations of cousins, the aunts and uncles.
What better place to learn about the changing nature of gardens and
families and the often necessary fictions they so beautifully
maintain about stability and order and beauty?
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 28 at 6 p.m., Ms. Caracciolo will deliver a slide
lecture about Villar Perosa in New York to benefit the New York
Horticultural Society. Tickets are $350. Information, (212)
757-0915.
</P>
</TEXT>
