  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR OCT.
21, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- BUDGE. Bay Area's congressional delegation was
divided over the huge $500 billion spending bill Congress passed
Wednesday, even though the project contains tens of millions of
dollars for transportation and education projects in the region.
Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- BUDGET. It's 4,000 pages long, weighs nearly 40
pounds and is filled with more pork than a barbecue festival. But
the $500 billion federal budget bill passed by Congress Wednesday
contained a myriad of Colorado projects, including funding for both
the Southeast and Southwest light rail corridors, expansion of the
Federal Courthouse in Denver, the University of Colorado Health
Sciences Center at Fitzsimons, and funding for the cleanup at Rocky
Flats. But the thing is so big, Colorado's delegation doesn't know
exactly what's in it. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- HEFLEY. (Probable.) Saying it was too bloated, had too much
pork, and was given to Congress too late, Rep. Joel Hefley,
R-Colo., voted against the $500 billion budget plan. Still, the
bill contained many projects for Colorado Springs and the state.
Zaret
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- CANAL. The Augusta Canal National Heritage Area is
$500,000 richer as a result of the massive spending bill approved
by the Senate Wednesday. Williams
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. (Working.) Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- BUDGET. Northwest Indiana is slated to get nearly $34
million for five projects from the $500 billion federal budget
passed by Congress this week. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- BUDGE. Western Louisiana will receive millions of
dollars in education, transportation and health funding, as
Congress approved a huge $500 billion catchall spending bill
Wednesday. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- WRAP-UP. Nevada's two congressmen and two senators
reflect on the 105th Congress, and look forward to the 106th.
Preston
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- DEWINE-CLOSING. Ohio Republican Mike DeWine gave the
closing remarks as the U.S. Senate concluded the 105th Congress
Wednesday. DeWine spoke about the impeachment process, foreign
crises and the attack of a gay college student in Wyoming. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- OXLEY-COPA. Facing opposition from the Department of Justice
and the American Civil Liberties Union, Rep. Mike Oxley's Child
Online Protection Act, which was tacked onto the Omnibus Spending
Bill, passed through the House and Senate Wednesday. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- STEEL. Members of the steel industry on Wednesday urged
federal officials to take action to stop the illegal dumping of
cheap foreign steel. (Possible.) Gorman
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- SCHOOLS. Every child has been told breakfast is the
most important meal of the day, and Brownsville high schools are
making sure their students get the day started right. ``Breakfast
in a Bag,'' a program started in Pace High School by Principal Tim
Coyle, was such a success that several other schools in the
Brownsville district adopted it. On Tuesday, the Food Research
Action Center (FRAC) held the Brownsville program up as a model for
the nation's schools. Brown
</P>
<P>
   -- FEC. Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Clarendon, continued his trend of
out-raising and outspending his opponent, Texas Tech professor Mark
Harmon, by more than $100,000, according to reports filed with the
Federal Election Commission (FEC). Brown
</P>
<P>
   -- CAMPAIGN. An overview of the race in the 15th congressional
district of Texas, where freshman Rep. Ruben Hinojosa faces
perennial candidate Tom Haughey. Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- OMNIBUS-REACT. With the exception of Rep. David
Obey, the entire Wisconsin delegation was among the 95 members
voting against the Omnibus Spending Bill, which passed the House
Tuesday night. Sens. Herb Kohl and Russ Feingold also voted against
the measure in the Senate on Wednesday. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
