A9628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ANTIPASTO-COX     10-21 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ANTIPASTO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Array of Italian appetizers a colorful, creative way to start
meal
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My, my how we've grown.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Italian food, we're no longer a nation stuck on
spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   We rarely say noodles anymore. We say pasta. We buy olive oil _
cold-pressed, extra-virgin. And balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   We've begun to learn the pleasures of risotto, biscotti and
focaccia (anybody catch Cindy Crawford demonstrating her herbed
focaccia on a recent ``Rosie O'Donnell Show''?). And we've
certainly adopted sliced tomatoes with fresh basil, mozzarella and
drizzles of olive oil as a choice summer appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   So why not take another step up to the plate?
</P>
<P>
   Autumn is a perfect time to dive into the deep riches of
antipasti, Italy's array of satisfying appetizers made with simple,
fresh ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   A well-planned antipasto assortment can jump-start an otherwise
all-too-predictable holiday party (by Christmas will you really be
able to stomach yet another slice of ham stuffed into a tiny
croissant?) or perk up the palate at Thanksgiving for that big,
beautiful bird waiting in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may argue that a dessert cart is more enticing,'' Michele
Scicolone writes in her cookbook ``The Antipasto Table,'' ``but I
find an antipasto table harder to resist. Tender seafood, stuffed
vegetables, moist mozzarella and colorful salads spangled with
herbs and glistening with golden-green olive oil are far more
tempting to me than any sweets.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of a great antipasto is ``to stimulate the appetite but
not fill the stomach completely,'' says Elviana DeZan, who for six
years with her husband, Armando, has owned and operated Atlanta's
AREL Group, which supplies olive oil, pesto and other Italian food
products to grocers. ``Think of it as a start to something _ not
the end to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional antipasto is frequently finger food divided into
five basic groups: toasted bread (bruschetta and crostini topped
with various cooked meats or vegetables); sliced cold meats (like
prosciutto, mortadella and salami); cooked or raw vegetables (like
marinated eggplant, stuffed sweet peppers, winter squashes and
mushrooms); cheese and eggs (especially buffalo mozzarella in
little morsels and slow-cooked, round and flat frittatas); and
seafood (like anchovies, oysters, clams, scallops, shrimp and
lobster).
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, sometimes 20 different dishes are prepared for the
antipasto buffet. But DeZan says you can also pull off a successful
start to a dinner party with two or three kinds of antipasto.
Portions are colorful, often bite-size, made with the freshest
ingredients available and encompass a broad spectrum of textures,
flavors and temperature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is to be creative,'' DeZan says. ``Work
with ingredients that look good together and stimulate the
appetite. You want your guests to enjoy themselves without feeling
very full.''
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Lorenza De'Medici says there is no better way to
welcome guests than to start things off with a really tasty dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can anything be more unappetizing than being offered some of
those miserable little packaged things that are often served?'' she
writes in her new book ``Lorenza's Antipasti.'' ``The meal that
follows could be quite wonderful but, unfortunately, first
impressions last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we entertain,'' she adds, ``we should commence with
our best efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   How else to show how much we've grown?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
