<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This Weekend on TV
 &HT;    By Bob Logino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Mercury 13: Secret Astronauts'' 8 p.m. EDT on The
History Channel _ The story of 13 American women who trained to
become Mercury astronauts during the early days of the country's
space program but were ultimately denied approval to travel into
space.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mystery! Touching Evil'' (PBS-check local listings)_ If you
missed ``Mystery's'' terrific season opener, the six-hour
miniseries in five parts gets another airing starting this night on
WPBA. Robson Green stars as a London special investigator tracking
three separate cases involving murder. The two-hour opener is the
best story.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Love Boat: The Next Wave'' 9 p.m. EDT on UPN _ For a kick,
tune in to this tale of wrestlers, including champ-of-champs Bill
Goldberg (a former Atlanta Falcon and Georgia Bulldog) and Kevin
Nash, out for a spin on the sea.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Triumph of the Nerds: The Rise of Accidental Empires in
Silicon Valley'' (PBS-check local listings)_ Another airing of the
interesting three-part series detailing the rise, fall and
potential future of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Right Stuff'' (1983) Noon EDT on TNT _ With John
Glenn's return to space set for next week, TNT airs this critically
acclaimed astronaut movie, based on Tom Wolfe's book. Sam Shepard
plays test pilot Chuck Yeager as the film traces the lives and
training of America's first astronauts. 270m.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Africans in America: America's Journey Through Slavery''
(PBS-check local listings)_ Angela Bassett narrates Orlando
Bagwell's effective four-part documentary about slavery, from its
beginnings in America through the Civil War. Two parts air this
night; they repeat and the final two installments air on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Cold War'' 8 p.m. EDT on CNN _ Episode 5 looks at Korea
from 1949 to 1953, including North Korea's invasion of South Korea
on June 25, 1950, President Truman's dismissal of Gen. Douglas
MacArthur and the armistice at Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
