<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DVD22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These horror flicks a real scream on disc
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whet your appetite for Halloween with a couple of offbeat horror
flicks. Full of mutations and mutilations, David Cronenberg's
amazing ``Videodrome'' is like ``Network'' on a bad acid trip.
James Woods is the owner of a small cable TV station trying to
track down a mysterious program that's nothing but sex and violence
(remember, this is way before Jerry Springer). Talk about ratings
potential ... Deborah Harry plays one of the show's on-air talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thing,'' John Carpenter's remake of Howard Hawks' sci-fi
classic from the 1950s, offers Kurt Russell and a band of
supporting players enduring several cold days in hell when a
bloodthirsty, shape-shifting alien attacks their Antarctic outpost.
The DVD bonuses include running commentary by Russell and Carpenter
and a behind-the-scenes look at what was then (early '80s) some
pretty fancy special effects work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
