<HEADER>
A9631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL22-COX     10-21 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Some true heavies: Nazis as aging villains
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once World War II was safely won, the Nazi Next Door became a
fairly familiar figure in movies. After all, not all of them made
it to Argentina. ``Apt Pupil,'' opening Friday, casts Ian McKellan
as a death camp commander who has eluded capture for decades. Here
are some other films about old Nazis who, somewhat like MacArthur's
old soldiers, preferred to fade away ... into the woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Marathon Man'' (1976) _ This is the movie that made people
more worried about dentists than about Nazis. Dustin Hoffman is a
grad student at Columbia University _ a marathon runner who runs
afoul of former concentration camp commandant Laurence Olivier. The
script, which was written by William ``Nobody Knows Anything''
Goldman, is pretty convoluted, but all you really need to know is
that Olivier is looking for some diamonds smuggled out of Germany
and that he tries to extract (literally) information from Hoffman
during an after-hours dental session.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Boys From Brazil'' (1978) _ Olivier goes from Nazi to
Nazi hunter (based on Simon Wiesenthal) in this adaptation of Ira
Levin's thriller about aging Nazis still plotting to breed a race
of Aryan supermen. Olivier's portrayal won him his 11th Academy
Award nomination (he lost to Jon Voight in ``Coming Home''). But
the performance most people remember is upstanding, heroic Gregory
Peck _ our Atticus Finch, for goodness' sake _ cast against type as
the nasty Nazi mastermind Josef Mengele.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Music Box'' (1989) _ OK, so the Nazi posing as the
kindly old man across the street who always says hello to your kids
is a scary enough proposition. What if maybe ... just maybe ...
your own father came under suspicion? The great Armin Mueller-Stahl
plays a Hungarian refugee accused of being the leader of an SS
death squad who has managed to disguise his past for almost 40
years. Add one more twist: When Mueller-Stahl goes on trial, his
defense lawyer is his own daughter, played by Jessica Lange. The
atrocities of the Holocaust are a constant echo, but this movie is
less about the father's guilt or innocence than the daughter's
inevitable loss of innocence. After all, what do we ever really
know about our parents' pasts?
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Producers'' (1968) _ For a truly nutty take on Nazis,
you can hardly do better than Mel Brooks' blithely tasteless farce
about an overbearing producer (Zero Mostel) and a meek accountant
(Gene Wilder) who team up on a seemingly foolproof scheme: to sell
25,000 percent of the profits of a show they're sure will be the
biggest flop in Broadway history. The show, they think, will fold
and they'll keep the investors' money. Their author is a deranged
Nazi-in-hiding (Kenneth Mars) who's written something called
``Springtime for Hitler.'' That's also the title of the immortal
opening number, which offers statuesque chorus girls goose-stepping
in swastika-shaped formations that would do Busby Berkeley proud.
The lyrics, if memory serves, go something like this: ``Springtime
for Hitler and Germany / Winter for Poland and France.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Hotel Terminus: The Life and Times of Klaus Barbie'' (1987)
_ Of all the movies listed here, this is the most important. And
the most compelling. Because it's true. Oscar-winning documentarian
Marcel Ophuls uses the postwar exploits of Klaus Barbie, a.k.a.
``the Butcher of Lyons,'' to examine the human response to evil.
Barbie spent his later years in South America, where various
dictators and drug lords welcomed his expertise in torture with
open arms and open wallets. In 1987, Barbie was finally extradited
to France and put on trial for ``crimes against humanity.'' Yet the
facts of his monstrous resume interest Ophuls less than the
reactions of those who knew him _ as friends, bosses or even
victims. The true heart of darkness that he uncovers is their
indifference; we hear ``that was 40 years ago'' or ``not the Jews
again'' time after time. It is a remarkable piece of filmmaking
with implications that stretch far beyond the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
