<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINI VIEWS: Reviews of the latest on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Hope Floats'' (PG-13) _ The Lifetime Channel writ large.
There's nothing wrong with this sweet drama about a former beauty
queen (Sandra Bullock) who gets dumped by her hubby and moves back
home to live with Mom (Gena Rowlands, having to do eccentric,
life-affirming shtick for the zillionth time). There's just not a
lot that's compelling about it. Gee, will Sandra let herself fall
for hunky, sweet, perfect Harry Connick Jr.? The suspense is
killing me. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Big Hit'' (R) _ The big ho-hum. Treading territory that
``Grosse Pointe Blank'' covered better last year, ``Hit'' ponders
the problems of a professional killer trying to maintain a domestic
life. Mark Wahlberg plays Mel, a hit man torn between mowing down
mobsters and romancing a girlfriend (Lela Rochon) and a fiancee
(Christina Applegate).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Species II'' (R) _ Garbage. This sequel casts former Emory
University student Justin Lazard as an astronaut infected with an
alien monster. The result? He has sex with anything that moves,
causing instant pregnancies that make the women explode. Don't say
we didn't warn you. Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Anchoress'' (unrated) _ In this luminous, black-and-white
drama, Natalie Morse plays a medieval woman who agrees to be the
anchoress of a small country church. That means that she allows
herself to be walled up in a tiny room for her entire life, in
honor of the Virgin Mary. The local priest (Christopher Eccleston)
sees her as a great tourist attraction for his parish. But life and
nature prove to be more powerful than doctrine in Chris Newby's
(``Madagascar Skin'') slow but rewarding film. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang'' (G) _ It's chitty, all right.
This 30th-anniversary re-release of the Dick Van Dyke flying-car
flick might help you understand why the movie musical died. But
your (little) kids will probably dig it. Priced to buy, $14.95.
Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
