<HEADER>
A9639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIPASTO-RECIPES-COX     10-21 2484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIPASTO-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In all their glorious variety, appetizers of Italy are an
enticement
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antipasto is singular. Antipasti is plural.
</P>
<P>
   There now. You're on your way to learning about Italy's great
appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   The country's range of antipasto dishes is great, and the
intricacies in regional varieties mind-boggling. But you don't have
to learn it all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Just know that by absorbing the following 10 terms, all adapted
from John Mariani's ``The Dictionary of Italian Food and Drink''
(Broadway Books, $17), you can begin to master antipasto in all its
forms:
</P>
<P>
   -- Affettato (ah-feh-TAH-toh) _ Sliced, cold meats, including
prosciutto and mortadella.
</P>
<P>
   -- Assaggio (ah-SAH-j'yoh) _ A taste of something, a morsel or
little bit.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bocconcini (boh-kohn-CHEE-nee) _ ``Small mouthfuls.'' Also
refers to small balls of mozzarella about 1 inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bruschetta (broo-SKEH-tah) _ Toasted bread, often rubbed with
garlic and drizzled with olive oil and spread with various
toppings.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bufala (BOO-fah-lah) _ As in buffalo mozzarella. Milk from
the water buffalo is the basis for Italy's best cheese.
</P>
<P>
   -- Crostini (kroh-STEE-nee) _ Thinner than bruschetta, they are
slices of toast with toppings. They are a Tuscan specialty.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gnocchi (N'YOH-kee) _ Dumplings, usually cooked in water or
broth, but also baked. They are made with flour (sometimes
semolina), egg and often potatoes, but also Parmesan, ricotta,
spinach, pureed pumpkin and more. For antipasto, they're often
served unsauced as finger food.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mortadella (mohr-tah-DEH-lah) _ Finely ground pork meat and
lard formed into large sausages. Think bologna, but a kind so
superior it could be stamped ``made in heaven.'' Usually flavored
with peppercorns and coriander.
</P>
<P>
   -- Parmigiano (pahr-mee-J'YAH-noh) _ Cow's milk cheese made in
wheels and aged. The best is Parmigiano-Reggiano, made only in the
morning and aged at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   -- Prosciutto (proh-SHOO-toh) _ Superior ham cured in a minimum
of salt for at least 300 days (it is forbidden to use nitrites,
sugar, smoke, water or additives in the curing process). It's
usually served in paper-thin slices.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Bruschetta Alla
</P>
<P>
   Salsiccia (Bruschetta With Sausages)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 6 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This Italian sausage ragu, from Lorenza De'Medici's ``Lorenza's
Antipasti'' (Broadway Books, $40), works well on bruschetta but
also can be used quite successfully as a fettuccine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   10ounces sweet Italian sausages
</P>
<P>
   7ounces lean boneless pork meat
</P>
<P>
   1small carrot
</P>
<P>
   1celery rib
</P>
<P>
   1small onion
</P>
<P>
   4ripe plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   6large slices coarse country bread, 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Peel the sausages and crumble the meat into a bowl. Finely chop
the pork, carrot, celery and onion. Peel and chop the tomatoes.
Heat half the oil in a frying pan. Add the carrot, celery and onion
and cook over medium heat for about 3 minutes, stirring constantly,
or until the onion is translucent. Stir in the sausage meat and
pork and cook for 3 minutes. Add the tomatoes, fennel seeds, wine,
thyme and salt and pepper to taste. Cover the pan, lower the heat
to a minimum and cook for about 1 hour, stirring from time to time
and adding a little water if necessary to keep moist.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover and let the juices evaporate completely.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Place the bread
slices on a baking sheet and toast in the oven for about 5 minutes,
or until barely golden, turning them once. Brush with the rest of
the oil and arrange on individual dishes. Spread with the sausage
ragu and serve immediately while still very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 339 calories, 15 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 25 grams carbohydrates, 41
milligrams cholesterol, 477 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Gnocchi Di Ricotta (Ricotta Dumplings)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 30
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, also from ``Lorenza's Antipasti,'' works well as an
antipasto with drinks because, De'Medici says, the semolina coating
will be crisp enough to allow the gnocchi to become tasty finger
food.
</P>
<P>
   3cups ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1large egg
</P>
<P>
   3ounces freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Pinch grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3cups coarse semolina
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Put the ricotta in a bowl. Add the
flour, egg, cheese, nutmeg, salt and pepper to taste, stirring
until well-blended. Using your hands, shape the mixture into
walnut-sized balls and roll them in the semolina to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pan of water to the boil. Add salt and the ricotta
gnocchi, a few at a time. Remove with a slotted spoon as soon as
they come to the surface. Arrange in an ovenproof dish. Bake in the
oven for about 20 minutes until a light crust forms. Arrange on a
platter and serve hot or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 109 calories, 6 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 36), 11 grams carbohydrates, 25 milligrams
cholesterol, 69 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Spicchi di Peperoni Ripieni
</P>
<P>
   (Stuffed Pepper Wedges)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 45
minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, also from ``The Antipasto Table,'' calls for red
bell peppers, but you can use green and yellow bell peppers to
enhance the color presentation.
</P>
<P>
   3large red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1large ripe tomato, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1large garlic clove, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   12imported black olives, such as kalamata, pitted and thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce can anchovy fillets, drained and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350. Oil a 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish.
Cut the peppers lengthwise into quarters and remove the seeds and
white membranes. Arrange the quarters skin side down in the
prepared dish. In a bowl, combine the tomato, garlic, olives,
anchovies, parsley and pepper to taste. Spoon the mixture into the
pepper wedges. Drizzle with the olive oil. Bake for 45 minutes or
until the peppers are tender when pierced with a fork. Serve warm
or cold.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 194 calories, 9 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 72), 6 grams carbohydrates, 17
milligrams cholesterol, 605 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Frutti di Mare
</P>
<P>
   (Seafood Salad)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't order this succulent dish from Rao's, the popular
10-table Italian restaurant in New York's East Harlem? It comes
from Frank Pellegrino's ``Rao's Cookbook: Over 100 Years of Italian
Home Cooking'' (Random House, $40).
</P>
<P>
   1pound fresh, small squid with tentacles, cleaned (see notes)
</P>
<P>
   2cups lemon juice, divided
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   8large shrimp (see notes)
</P>
<P>
   1cup fine quality olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves, peeled and halved
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2cups jumbo lump crab meat or imitation crab meat (see notes) or
1 cup jumbo lump crab meat or imitation crab meat and 1 pound
cooked fresh lobster meat
</P>
<P>
   6lemon wedges
</P>
<P>
   Rinse squid in a colander under cold running water. Separate
bodies and tentacles, as they must be cooked in different water to
keep the tentacles from coloring the rings. Place about 1 quart
cold water in a medium pot. Add squid bodies, 1/4 cup fresh lemon
juice and 2 tablespoons salt.
</P>
<P>
   Place about 1 quart cold water in another medium pot. Add squid
tentacles, 3/4 cup fresh lemon juice and 2 tablespoons salt. Bring
both pots to a rolling boil. Lower heat to a gentle boil and cook
until squid are very tender, about 5 minutes. Remove from heat and
run cold water directly into each pot until water is cool. Drain
the bodies, pat dry and cut into rings. Holding the tentacles, run
warm water into the pan. Under the running water, gently rub
between the palms of your hands, pushing the black specks and
colored skin from the tentacles. Use a small paring knife to scrape
the skin, if necessary. Drain well and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the rings and tentacles in a colander. Cover with a damp
cloth and set aside to drain for about 20 minutes. Refrigerate if
not using immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Peel, devein, remove tails and butterfly shrimp. Cover with
water and bring to a boil in a small saucepan. Immediately remove
from heat, drain and refresh in cold running water. Gently press in
a clean kitchen towel to dry well. Cut into quarters. If not using
immediately, cover with a damp towel and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   In a nonreactive bowl, whisk together the oil, remaining lemon
juice, garlic, parsley and salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Add shrimp and squid to the oil mixture. Toss to coat. Using a
slotted spoon, remove seafood from oil mixture and place on a
serving plate.
</P>
<P>
   Add crab meat to oil mixture and very gently turn to coat. Using
a slotted spoon, remove crab from oil mixture and gently fold into
the shrimp-squid mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Add lobster to the oil mixture. Gently toss to coat. Using a
slotted spoon, remove lobster from oil mixture and place on top of
salad. Discard garlic from oil mixture. Pour remaining oil mixture
over salad and serve immediately, garnished with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: When purchasing fresh, whole squid, always look for those
that are clear-eyed, smooth-skinned and very fresh smelling. Have
the fishmonger clean and cut the squid to your specifications. Some
fresh squid are sold precut into rings with the tentacles removed;
however, the rings and tentacles are usually sold together. As the
squid cooks, skim off the foam that accumulates at the top.
</P>
<P>
   To butterfly shrimp: Peel and devein, leaving the tail on for
most preparations and removing it only when called for in a
specific recipe. Using a knife, make a shallow cut from head to
tail along the center but not through the shrimp and remove the
dark vein. Lay the shrimp open, deveined side up, and make shallow
cuts diagonally out from the center on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Handle the crab meat carefully so that the lumps remain whole.
But do check for cartilage and shell remnants.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 521 calories, 28 grams protein, 42 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 73), 8 grams carbohydrates, 313
milligrams cholesterol, 582 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Mele Alla Crema di Gorgonzola (Apples With Gorgonzola Cream)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The tartness of apples weds well with pungent Gorgonzola in this
dish from De'Medici's ``Lorenza's Antipasti.'' She cautions that
fresh Gorgonzola is quite white and not too smelly.
</P>
<P>
   6apples, such as Granny Smith
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   7ounces fresh Gorgonzola cheese
</P>
<P>
   6walnuts, shelled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Peel, core and slice apples; arrange them on a platter. Sprinkle
with lemon juice so they do not brown. Put cream and Gorgonzola in
a pan over low heat and heat until it melts, stirring with a wooden
spoon. Leave to cool, then pour on top of the apples. Sprinkle with
the walnuts. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 200 calories, 6 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 61), 16 grams carbohydrates, 43
milligrams cholesterol, 456 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Zucca Rossa all' Agrodolce (Sweet and Sour
</P>
<P>
   Winter Squash)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Michele Scicolone's autumn specialty, from her ``The Antipasto
Table'' (Ecco Press, 1991), is the Sicilian dish called Fegato dei
Sette Cannoli (Liver of the Seven Cannons). The resourceful
Sicilians used inexpensive squash to make it resemble a meat dish.
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1butternut squash, small pumpkin or other winter squash, (about
2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup chopped fresh mint, basil or flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Generously brush two jellyroll pans
with olive oil. Cut the squash in half lengthwise. Scrape out the
seeds and membranes. Peel the squash and cut into 1/4-inch-thick
slices. Arrange the squash in the pans in a single layer. Brush the
slices with additional oil. Bake for 20 minutes. Turn the slices
and bake for 15 to 20 minutes, or until tender and lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, heat the vinegar, sugar and salt and stir
until the sugar and salt are dissolved. Arrange a single layer of
the squash in a shallow dish. Sprinkle with some of the garlic and
mint. Continue layering the remaining squash, sprinkling each layer
with herbs. Pour the vinegar mixture over all.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate for at least 24 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 119 calories, 2 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 36), 21 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 205
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Grande Antipasto All'Italiana (Grand Antipasto
</P>
<P>
   Italian Style)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   12thin slices prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   12thin slices salami of your choice
</P>
<P>
   12thin slices ham, baked or boiled
</P>
<P>
   12thin slices mortadella
</P>
<P>
   12large or 24 small bocconcini mozzarella, about 3 pounds total
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce jar marinated artichokes
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4large hard-boiled eggs, peeled and cut into thin rounds
</P>
<P>
   13 1/4-ounce can rolled anchovies, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound mixed Italian cured black and green olives
</P>
<P>
   Fresh curly parsley for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Alternate the meats, arranging them in a decorative fashion on a
large round platter, leaving space in the center for the bocconcini
and artichokes. If you wish, roll up the slices of meat. This will
save space on the platter.
</P>
<P>
   Pat the mozzarella dry and place in a mixing bowl. Pour the oil
from the jar of artichokes over the mozzarella. Add a grinding of
pepper and toss. Place the dressed mozzarella in the center of the
platter.
</P>
<P>
   If the artichokes are large, cut them into halves or quarters.
Set them around the mozzarella. Place the eggs around the edge of
the platter. Top the eggs with the rolled anchovies. Scatter the
olives over all and garnish with the parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 511 calories, 36 grams protein, 38 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 67), 5 grams carbohydrates, 196
milligrams cholesterol, 1,473 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
