A9640 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE22-COX     10-21 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two Atlanta brewpubs find gold in Denver
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, silvers; this year, golds.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which wasn't on the craft-beer industry's map only a
few years ago, is making a name for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, two Buckhead brewpubs _ John Harvard's and
Rock Bottom _ became the first Atlanta breweries to win gold medals
at the Great American Beer Festival in Denver, the most prestigious
blind competition in the country. John Harvard's beat out 34 other
entrants in the Scottish-Style Ale category, and Rock Bottom was
best among 42 entrants in the American-Style Brown Ale category.
</P>
<P>
   No other Atlanta brewers won a medal _ gold, silver or bronze _
at this year's competition, which drew almost 2,000 entries in more
than 50 styles.
</P>
<P>
   For Kurt Harrison, head brewer at John Harvard's in Buckhead,
winning had a special satisfaction. Last year, judges found nothing
worthy of a gold in the Scottish-Style Ale category, but the entry
Harrison's designed and brewed for John Harvard's
Massachusetts-based chain of restaurants was awarded the silver.
(Sweetwater Ale, brewed in Atlanta, won a silver last year in the
English-Style Bitters category.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Scottish ale was the first recipe I did when I came to
John Harvard's, just after we opened,'' says Harrison, who grew up
in Stone Mountain and trained at the White Horse pub in London and
at Manhattan Brewing Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Scottish ales are on the malty side, with little
hop character but a roastiness to the malt that counters the
natural sweetness of the grain. A few craft brewers, notably Bert
Grant's in Yakima, Wash., have broken with that tradition and given
their Scottish ale a pronounced hop note. Harrison's stays true to
the style, and it's been one of the top sellers at the Buckhead
brewpub.
</P>
<P>
   A gold medal at the GABF speaks for itself and yet there are
those who aren't sure the Scottish Ale is Harrison's best. His
India Pale Ale, following the British rather than the Pacific
Northwest style, was already one of the better beers brewed in
Atlanta and now it's acquiring more hop character.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar way, many beer aficionados would have mentioned the
cask-conditioned IPA or the Iron Horse stout that Clay Gentry brews
for Rock Bottom. The stout, in fact, won a silver medal at the
World Beer Cup competition in August (no gold medal was awarded).
</P>
<P>
   But if the Sweet Magnolia Brown Ale was a sleeper to some, it
wasn't to others. ``It's the personal favorite of the majority of
our staff,'' Gentry says. And, among the half dozen or so styles on
tap at Rock Bottom, the Sweet Magnolia Brown accounts for 20
percent of beer sales.
</P>
<P>
   Light to medium in body, brown ales are somewhere between the
maltier, fuller-bodied Scottish ales and the hoppier pale ales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who actively look for browns,'' Gentry says.
``It's also a good introductory beer for people who aren't
experienced in craft beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry (whose beer was registered as the entry of corporate
partner Big River Brewing Co., based in Chattanooga) sought a more
American flavor profile than the familiar British style _ less
nutty, a little more chocolate malt character, a touch hoppier. In
England you won't find many brown ales brewed with Mount Hood hops,
popular with American microbrewers. ``I'm a particular fan of Mount
Hoods,'' Gentry says. ``They give a spicy aroma that I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainier wins gold
</P>
<P>
   Generic beer _ the kind pitched at ballparks and advertised on
billboards _ also has its category at the GABF. It's called
American-style lager, to distinguish it from real lager, and the
winner among 18 entries was ... Rainier, made in Seattle, a city
more associated with microbeers. Second went to last year's gold
medal winner, Old Milwaukee, brewed by Stroh's. More interesting
was the winner of the bronze _ Schlitz, the Beer That Made
Milwaukee Famous but today as forgotten as Falstaff. Wonder where
the King of Beers ranked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
