<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cornwell serves up feast of recipes, bite of plot
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia Cornwell's fictional medical examiner Kay Scarpetta is
known more for slicing and dicing bodies than for whipping up
holiday recipes. But apparently there's more to the good doctor
than meets the eye. In ``Scarpetta's Winter Table'' (Wyrick &AMP; Co.,
$19.95), Cornwell takes a break from her best-selling whodunits to
show the softer sides of Scarpetta, her niece Lucy and her police
sidekick, Pete Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Written as a novella, ``Scarpetta's Winter Table'' follows
Scarpetta and friends as they gather to celebrate the days between
Christmas and New Year with their favorite foods. And, along the
way, they manage to rescue a delinquent child.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 10 chapters feature a recipe concocted by one of the
principal characters, from Marino's ``cause-of-death eggnog'' to
Scarpetta's famous pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patsy really does make great pizza,'' says Charles Cornwell,
the author's ex-husband and an editor at Wyrick &AMP; Co. in
Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   He says the writer first approached him about a cookbook. ``She
said she keeps getting requests from her readers for recipes, since
she writes about food in her novels. It started out literally as a
book of favorite recipes of the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are woven into the story line and illustrated with
black-and-white photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The book is expected to be the small publisher's biggest seller
since Richard Lederer's ``Anguished English.'' A first printing of
75,000 copies will be shipped this week.
</P>
<P>
   YESTERDAY'S BEST: If you're looking for a first-edition William
Faulkner or Ernest Hemingway, the best place to find it this
weekend is at the Atlanta Antiquarian Book Fair at the Gwinnett
Civic Center. Nearly 100 dealers from the United States and England
will display their wares Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll find books from $5 to $5,000,'' says book fair manager
Giles Hollingsworth. Among the selection are first editions of
``Gulliver's Travels'' for $5,750, ``Life of King Charles'' by Sir
Francis Bacon for $950 and ``Gone With the Wind'' for $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   A new feature of the book fair is the Advanced Book Exchange, an
Internet locating service that allows collectors to connect with
3,400 used and rare book dealers and browse their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Hollingsworth has this advice for beginners: ``Don't collect
books with the idea of making money on them. If it happens, fine,
but don't count on it. And always buy the best-condition book
available. In their haste to build a collection, many collectors
settle for less _ for example, books without dust jackets.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the most collectible Southern books, Hollingsworth cites
``Gone With the Wind,'' ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' ``Uncle Remus,''
``Absalom, Absalom'' and ``The Yearling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gwinnett Civic Center is located off Exit 42 on I-85 north.
Admission to the book fair is $4 for each day or $5 for both. Hours
are 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday and noon-5 p.m. Sunday. Information:
770-518-1393.
</P>
<P>
   WOLFE FOR DINNER: Tickets are still available for a Nov. 18
cocktail and dinner party with Tom Wolfe at the Atlanta History
Center. Before the dinner, Wolfe will discuss his forthcoming book,
``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $28.95, Nov. 10), at 7
p.m. at McElreath Hall, 130 W. Paces Ferry Road N.W. Dinner guests
will receive priority seating for the lecture and signed copies of
``A Man in Full.'' Tickets are $600, with proceeds benefiting the
Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum. Information: 404-249-7012, Ext.
15.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE NEWS: More than 10 years ago, Thomas Harris captivated
readers _ and scared the wits out of them _ with his best-selling
thriller ``The Silence of the Lambs.'' Harris reportedly has been
working on a sequel featuring his famous villain Hannibal Lecter,
but there's no word from Bantam Books on when the manuscript will
be completed. Meanwhile, St. Martin's Press has reissued a
10th-anniversary edition of ``Lambs'' in an oversize paperback for
$13.95. If you haven't read it, it's great for curling up with a
nice glass of chianti and some fava beans.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
