u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-AUTHOR-COX     10-21 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AUTHOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peterson principle: Seize the moment
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody should cook with Jim Peterson once. Not only cook with
him, but accompany him to the market and watch as he stares
intently at a pile of potatoes and ponders the age-old question:
What's for dinner tonight?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Peterson is the only cookbook author who proudly, almost
defiantly, claims that he never cooks the same thing twice. How
does he test recipes? ``I have my assistant take care of that,'' he
answers with a laugh. ``I can't bear it.''
</P>
<P>
   His assistant did a fine job of translating the Peterson
philosophy and the Peterson palate into more than 300 appealingly
simple and reliable recipes in ``Vegetables'' (Morrow, $35). But
the real pleasure of this book is Peterson's cleanly written text
that encourages you to think about every step of the process. If
you're going to cook great vegetables, you have to know how to shop
for them, how to cut them, how to cook them and what seasonings you
should be thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   To see Peterson in action, I took him to the DeKalb Farmers
Market while he was in Atlanta and let him loose. Not impressed by
the sheer vastness of the store, Peterson was disappointed that
little farm-fresh produce was in evidence. The fennel was brown and
scuffed. The leeks were droopy.
</P>
<P>
   Then he caught sight of the fresh field peas in the shell and
visibly brightened. ``These look good, and I've never cooked with
them. Let's start here.''
</P>
<P>
   We loaded our basket with a bulging bag of black-eyes, purple
hulls and zipper peas. We got a couple of ears of corn, and he
marveled at what a good idea it was to shuck it in the store. He
loved the shiny, unblemished poblano peppers, and grabbed one.
</P>
<P>
   After a long tour of the fish/meat side of the store, he settled
on pork tenderloin. He picked up a bunch of concord grapes to make
a sauce, and the menu was set: pork with some kinda grape glaze,
and pea-corn succotash that's almost but not quite Southwestern. It
sounded vague but wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Back in my kitchen, I watched closely, chopped when asked and
noted that there were three important considerations for cooking
the Peterson way:
</P>
<P>
   -- You need to have a sharp knife and know how to use it. That's
how he transformed simple boiled field peas into the succotash of
dreams with additions of chopped roasted pepper, corn kernels,
cooked bacon and basil.
</P>
<P>
   -- You need to know how to saute. Forget every other method.
With a little olive oil and a majorly cheap, formerly Teflon-coated
pan he transformed 2-inch-thick pork pieces into crusty, succulent
medallions. His trick was even, steady heat and a brief trip to a
warm oven as he made the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   -- You need to experiment, but let your palate guide you. He
made a perfectly balanced glaze from concord grapes, sherry vinegar
and some Turkish grape syrup called ``pekmez'' I had on hand. I
doubt these three ingredients have ever been combined before, and I
doubt they ever will again.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking with Jim Peterson is deliciously of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Idea recipes from the book, H5
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
