<HEADER>
A9643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE22-COX     10-21 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall into the season with delicious apple dishes
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure signs of the season are the sumptuous heaps of gleaming
apples overflowing and perfuming supermarket aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists have found evidence that humans have been
enjoying apples since at least 6,500 B.C. As then, most people
today like their apples straight up, crunching into about 18 pounds
per person of the fresh fruit per year. Applesauce, apple juice
and, of course, apple pie and other desserts are regularly enjoyed
as well, but too many people remain unfamiliar with myriad other
delicious manifestations of the apple.
</P>
<P>
   Although we are most familiar with names like Delicious, Granny
Smith, Rome and McIntosh, there are more than 7,500 known varieties
grown throughout the world. A search of the Internet quickly
reveals hundreds of recipes, not only for the more familiar dishes
but also for recipes where apples are used in a more unexpected
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Take a peek at http://www.seanet.com/Users/tberry/recipe.html
for lists of the familiar, with new twists, including 17
mouthwatering versions of apple pie including Apple Ginger Pie With
Cider-Bourbon Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is http://www.grannysmith.com/grannies.html, the
site for fans of the tart, green, juicy Granny Smith. Find out
about the contest to find this year's ``Granny Smith'' and check
out some unusual recipes, like apple and potato soup.
</P>
<P>
   You will find extensive apple recipes divided into breakfast,
side dish, entree, salad and soup categories at
http://www.bestapples.com/Recipes/index.html (detail at right), and
two other good sites for ample recipes are
http://www.motts.com/moms/bake/bake.htm and
http://www.phillipsfruit.com/recipes1.html
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that apples are good for you, but at
http://michiganapples.com/, under ``health benefits'' you will find
out just how good they are. Nutrition research indicates that they
are effective cholesterol reducers. There are lots of other facts
at this site, including what varieties work best and a wide variety
of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Apple Ginger Pie With Cider-Bourbon Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 1 hour Chilling time: 1 hour
Cooking time: 45-50 minutes Cooling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   It is said that bourbon was first distilled in 1789 by a
Virginia minister, and by the 19th century it had become an
important regional industry. It makes a great cocktail, of course,
but we also like it in this rich sauce.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CRUST:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon apple pie spice
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) chilled unsalted butter, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup chilled solid vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   7tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE FILLING:
</P>
<P>
   3pounds Golden Delicious apples, peeled, cored and cut into
1/2-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons minced crystallized ginger
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons bourbon
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon apple pie spice
</P>
<P>
   Milk
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CIDER-BOURBON SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   5cups apple cider
</P>
<P>
   5tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons bourbon
</P>
<P>
   To make the crust: Mix flour, sugar, salt and apple pie spice in
food processor. Add butter and shortening and cut in until mixture
resembles coarse meal. Add sour cream and blend in, using on/off
turns just until dough forms. Turn out dough onto lightly floured
surface. Divide in half. Form each half into a ball; flatten into
disc. Wrap each disc in plastic wrap and refrigerate 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   To make the filling: Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a bowl,
toss together apple slices, sugar, flour, ginger, bourbon and apple
pie spice.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out one dough disc between sheets of plastic wrap to
12-to-13-inch round. Peel off top sheet; invert dough into 9
1/2-inch deep-dish glass pie dish. Peel off plastic. Roll out
remaining dough disc between sheets of plastic wrap to
12-to-13-inch round. Peel off top sheet of plastic. Mound filling
in pie dish. Invert dough over filling. Peel off plastic. Pinch
edges of dough to seal. Trim excess crust. Crimp edges
decoratively. Cut 5 slashes in top of dough to allow steam to
escape. Brush top with milk and sprinkle with sugar. Bake until
golden brown, covering with foil if browning too quickly, about
45-50 minutes. Let pie stand until just slightly warm, about 1
hour. Serve pie with ice cream and Cider-Bourbon Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   To make the Cider-Bourbon Sauce: In a heavy medium-size
saucepan, boil apple cider until reduced to 3/4 cup, about 45
minutes. Add butter and sugar and whisk until butter melts. Boil 3
minutes, whisking occasionally. Remove from heat. Whisk in bourbon.
Cool sauce completely before serving. Makes 1 cup. _ Adapted from
Bon Appetit magazine, November 1992
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 654 calories, 5 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 93 grams carbohydrates, 56
milligrams cholesterol, 312 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Ghttp://www.grannysmith.com/grannies.html
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Apple, Potato
</P>
<P>
   and Cheddar Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour and 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3medium Granny Smith apples, cored and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1potato, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1rib celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   5cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4cups (about 1 pound) grated mild cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Buttered croutons and unpeeled diced apples for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in large saucepan or Dutch oven; add apples, potato,
celery, onion and thyme. Saute 10 minutes. Stir in wine and simmer
2 minutes; add stock and simmer 45 minutes. Puree soup mixture.
Return to saucepan; over very low heat, stir in cheese, cream,
nutmeg and salt and pepper to taste. Cook just until heated through
_ do not allow to boil. Garnish with croutons and diced apples.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-cup serving: 299 calories, 13 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 70), 11 grams carbohydrates, 65
milligrams cholesterol, 312 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   www.bestapples.com/Recipes/index.html GOOD ART
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Crunchy Apple Salsa With Grilled Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: 30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Grilling time: 8-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE SALSA:
</P>
<P>
   2cups chopped, cored Gala apples
</P>
<P>
   1Anaheim chile pepper, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE GRILLED CHICKEN:
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon grated lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2whole boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   To make the salsa: In a medium bowl, combine apples, chile
pepper, onion, lime juice and salt and pepper to taste; cover and
set aside while preparing chicken. (If making several hours or day
ahead, refrigerate salsa.)
</P>
<P>
   To make grilled chicken: In large bowl, combine white wine,
apple juice, lime zest, salt and pepper. Add chicken and turn to
coat with mixture; cover and refrigerate 30 to 40 minutes. Heat
grill. Drain and discard chicken marinade. Grill chicken until
cooked through, turning once, about 8-10 minutes in all; serve with
salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 255 calories, 37 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 19), 12 grams carbohydrates, 119
milligrams cholesterol, 400 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
