<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Readers go nuts over Pina Colada Cake request
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have a taste for the Tropics, your request might match a
simple one from Betty Mullins of Lawrenceville, Ga., who asked for
a Pina Colada Cake.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three recipes were sent in by readers, along with high
praise from coconut lovers, such as, ``This is my favorite cake
recipe. I bake it every month.''
</P>
<P>
   Most began with a cake mix topped with some combination of
nondairy topping, flaked coconut, pineapple and sometimes pecans
and maraschino cherries. Some added a splash of rum or rum
flavoring, while others omitted the namesake spirit.
</P>
<P>
   This one, sent by Shelia Skinner of Decatur, Ga., came with the
high recommendation that it is both easy and very moist, the best
she has found that starts with a cake mix. Our tester approves.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Easy Pina Colada Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 to 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1(18 1/2-ounce) package yellow cake mix (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1(3 3/4-ounce) package instant vanilla pudding and pie filling
mix
</P>
<P>
   1(15-ounce) can Coco Lopez cream of coconut, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup plus 2 tablespoons rum, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1(8-ounce) can crushed pineapple, well-drained
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream, pineapple chunks, maraschino cherries and toasted
coconut for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If using cake mix with pudding in the mix, omit the
additional pudding mix.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine the cake mix, pudding mix, 1/2
cup Coco Lopez, 1/2 cup rum, oil and eggs. Using an electric mixer,
beat on medium speed for 2 minutes. Stir in drained pineapple. Pour
into a well-greased and floured 10-inch tube pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 45 to 50 minutes. Remove from oven and cool slightly,
about 25 minutes. Remove from pan. With a steak knife or skewer,
poke holes in the cake about 1 inch apart almost to the bottom.
Combine the remaining Coco Lopez
</P>
<P>
   and the rum in a small bowl. Pour over the cake. Chill
thoroughly before serving. Garnish as desired. Refrigerate
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 434 calories, 5 grams protein, 25 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 47 grams carbohydrates, 72
milligrams cholesterol, 376 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Tracy Roberts of Atlanta is seeking a recipe for a chiffon
pie like one her family used to buy around Thanksgiving at a
now-closed restaurant near the intersection of Briarcliff and North
Druid Hills. Roberts remembers it had a layer of pumpkin, one of
sweet potato and a third that was either a topping or a
combination.
</P>
<P>
   -- Elaine Dooley (e-mail) is looking for a recipe for Chicken
Pasta Supreme.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689,
Atlanta, GA 30302. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
