<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REM-NEWALBUM-COX     10-21 2652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REM-NEWALBUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    R.E.M. redefined
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_Dressed in an awkwardly undersized black suit, plastic
click pens in his pocket and geeky glasses perched on his nose,
Michael Stipe looks anything but a rock 'n' roll deity. Standing
silently in a production studio in a low-rent area of Astoria, in
Queens, he appears more like a high school kid on his way to a
costume party, the theme being ``Revenge of the Nerds.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing here on the dark set of the music video
``Daysleeper'' that smacks of the glamour world of rock 'n' roll is
the catering _ a table spilling over with tiny spring rolls,
asparagus spears, bright yellow bananas and an espresso machine _
and a small group of foreign journalists plopped down in folding
chairs, waiting with microphones in hand for the moment Stipe will
talk to them. It's not clear when that will happen, but then
nothing ever seems to go predictably with the members of one of the
world's most revered rock bands, R.E.M.
</P>
<P>
   Take the band's much-debated new album, ``Up,'' which arrives in
stores Tuesday. Earlier in the day, Warner Bros. executives
provided a sneak peek to staffers and curious critics, who reacted
as if they had just been jettisoned through some kind of
mushroom-induced musical directed by Ken Russell, guru of '70s film
excess. The closely guarded CD may have the name ``R.E.M.''
scribbled on a homemade label, yet the sound is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things we had been used to doing, the ways we used to
work in the studio, were totally thrown out the window,'' Stipe
says of the new project. ``Typically, we would go into the studio
and do a basic track with a guitar, drum and bass. But this record
was nothing like that. Everything was backwards and sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Band mates Peter Buck and Mike Mills aren't here today; their
video scenes will be shot later. Neither particularly likes the
tedium of making music videos. They've opted to head back into the
studio for one last listen to ``Up.'' Buck and Mills are
preoccupied with final mix of the project, like sculptors running
their hands over a bust before a public unveiling. And their
concerns may be justified.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the albums R.E.M. has produced in its 18-year career,
this one is perhaps being dissected and probed the most. It's the
first without longtime drummer and founding member Bill Berry, who
shocked his musical family in October 1997 by announcing he was
quitting the band. ``Up'' is also the second album recorded under
R.E.M.'s huge financial deal with Warner Bros., a reported $80
million contract Buck, Stipe, Mills and Berry inked with the label
in 1996. The band's previous CD, ``New Adventures in Hi-Fi,'' was
critically acclaimed but flopped commercially, yielding no hit
singles, despite the presence of some lovely ballads and vaulting
rock numbers. This record is being released at a time when
America's musical landscape is changing, the moody sounds of
alternative _ which R.E.M. virtually invented _ being edged out by
the more in-your-face rhythms of rap, hip-hop and bubbly
Hanson-pop.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the greatest pressure for Athens' most famous export
comes from the calendar. Stipe is 38. Buck is 41. And Mills is 39.
Their fan base, the young
</P>
<P>
   end of the baby boomers and the ``whatever'' clump of Gen X'ers,
are now raising families and signing up for 401(k)s. Yet much of
R.E.M.'s mystique and appeal is built squarely on the band's
iconoclasm, an attitude stitched to the members like a Prada label.
With the band and its core of followers squarely into middle age,
and the original lineup reduced to a trio, it is inevitable for the
media and music community to cast R.E.M. in the light of survival
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, boomer rocker John Mellencamp mused to The New York
Times, ``I'm interested in seeing what happens to R.E.M. because
they've entered my world now. The alternative era is over, and it
will be interesting to see how they handle being mature artists
rather than being this year's model.''
</P>
<P>
   It all begs the question: Can a group that has been the essence
of ennui and hipness for an entire generation remain vital well
into its graying, second decade?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question we had to ask ourselves,'' Buck says, relaxing
on a couch in the suite of the posh Hotel Plaza Athenee on the
Upper East Side of Manhattan. He responds to hints of a midlife
crisis this way: ``Rather than get a 22-year-old girlfriend and
drive a sports car, we decided to redefine ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   From the sounds of ``Up,'' R.E.M. certainly has.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with Berry's departure, and a tenacious desire to continue
to be perceived as artists as opposed to a product, the band has
come up with perhaps the most unexpected and avant-garde album of
its career. ``Up'' is a grand experiment, a quirky, somewhat
psychedelic journey into the possibilities of sound and studio
production. The band has virtually thrown its drum/bass/guitar
style out the window, opting for a more electronic and ethereal
mood drenched in alternative percussion (drum machines, xylophone,
bells, Mellotron) and production tricks that remind you of the days
when rock music careened through fat headphones from one ear to the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about this album is it really doesn't sound like
us,'' Buck says. ``Except for Michael's vocals, you couldn't tell
who was playing on it. Structurally, the songs are different than
anything we've ever done. There isn't such a band feel. A lot of it
is done to drum machines, not a lot of guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   All three band members concede the radical shift in style and
direction was, in part, due to Berry's exit from the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole impetus for this record sounding like it does is,
when Bill quit, I didn't feel like going and getting another
drummer and go right on rocking,'' Buck says. ``It's a record where
we're coming to terms with the fact that there's only three guys in
the band. We don't really have a drummer. We just don't approach
playing music the same way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift in R.E.M.'s style apparently began in the final days
of Berry's tenure in 1996. Gathered in Hawaii to talk about where
to go musically, Buck and Mills were already preoccupied with
Buck's extensive collection of circa-1960s studio tricks _ drum
machines, old synthesizers and sound effects gadgets. As they each
hovered over the primitive demo tapes they were making, they
realized they liked the sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going differently even before we found out Bill was
quitting,'' Mills says, nursing a sprained wrist he damaged while
playing pingpong. ``We were already suggesting to him, `Hey, why
don't we on this record do less drums and bass and maybe do some
drum loops and rhythm loops and have some fun with that?' We were
started on that anyway, so when he quit, it just accelerated the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   The band and producer Pat McCarthy began using the studio as a
toy, pushing the envelope on sounds, harmonies and instrumentation.
For example, on the second single ``Lotus,'' there's a barking
chorus with a voice shouting ``HEY HEY HEY!'' It's actually a
snippet of an old reel-to-reel tape Buck discovered after someone
had tossed it on a trash pile in his Seattle neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This album was more experimental than any other R.E.M. album
I've been connected with,'' says John Keane, the Athens-based
producer who helped engineer ``Up.'' ``I'd say when Bill left the
band, it really kind of pulled the rug out from under everybody. It
left them in kind of a quandary as to what direction to go in for
the next record. Peter and Mike had already created a lot of demos
based around drum machines and synthesizers, a lot of distorted
drum loops and things like that, which normally they would have
replaced with real drums. But I think they were sort of influenced
a lot by new groups like Radiohead and Massive Attack, where a lot
of different types of rhythm are going on. A lot of the finished
product is basically the demos they started with, with a lot of
other stuff built up around it, weird sounds that have been twisted
and looped and turned around backward.''
</P>
<P>
   R.E.M. seems delighted with its creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Well, if we can get away with this, then we're
gonna be OK,'' Mills laughs. ``People know we're not a jukebox.
We're the kind of band that's always going to take a left turn, or
try to anyway. Maybe people like to be challenged. Maybe people get
tired of being spoon-fed. Any record is a reflection of what's
going on in your life personally and professionally. We've been
though a lot in the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics and industry insiders who have gotten a preview of
``Up'' say they feel like the band did exactly the right thing by
changing its sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they made a really smart move. It would have been
foolish to do anything else,'' says New York rock critic Anthony
DeCurtis (Rolling Stone), who is writing a biography of the band.
``I don't think this is a commercial record, but artistically, it's
an extraordinary record. It's impressive for a band that's been
together for almost 20 years to now be doing some of their
strongest work.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Fram, program director of Atlanta's modern rock station
99X (WNNX-FM 99.7), got a chance to hear the album and calls it
``very, very different. But that's what R.E.M. fans appreciate,''
she says. ``The true R.E.M. fans relish the fact that the band goes
wherever their hearts take them at the time. The '80s
alternative-radio listener is now moving into a more stable phase
of life. They've got a job, kids and a mortgage payment. But these
people still listen to music, and they want to be turned on by new
music from a band they grew up with. And even though our listeners
are a little bit older, Michael Stipe is still the voice of this
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impressive that Stipe has been able to stay in this kind of
demagogue relationship with his audience. Maybe it's because he's
really the anti-rock star, the guy who made being you start doing
songs that reflect the happiness and secure feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way. Tritt admits that going from the
halls of Sprayberry High School(Ga.) to the fast lanes of the music
business was a ride he wasn't quite prepared to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fame and success, which is what I spent the first part of
my life chasing after, became almost addictive. I didn't know how
to handle it, all the sudden attention. I'm lucky to be alive. I
lived with a devil-may-care attitude, and pretty much didn't take
anything seriously at all. After I started getting recognition for
being this outlaw, I probably started feeding into it. I probably
said, 'well, if that's what they think of me, I'll show 'em what an
outlaw is.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road for most of his early career, Tritt partied hard. He
says he went through women ``like picking apples in an orchard.''
All the while, he wore a gold nugget around his neck _ melted down
wedding rings from two previous marriages _ to remind him never to
do this again. But then came Theresa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was really ready for the other two marriages,
as much a I would like to talk myself into that I was. When I met
Theresa, there was just this feeling that `this is right. This is
really right.' If I look back and am honest with myself, I've never
really felt that way before. I can't explain why it happened when
it did, but it's the most wonderful experience I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics like to write off Tritt as a dumb redneck, a
guitar-slinging rube with Lynyrd Skynyrd hair. But in person, he's
polite, confident, and refreshingly unapologetic about his
middle-class tastes and Southern heritage. When he speaks, he wraps
his thick Georgia accent around references to books (he's reading
``The Man Who Listens to Horses : The Story of a Real-Life Horse
Whisperer''), complex musical analyses and ``buck up'''
philosophical insights straight out of a Scott Peck book.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as living on the edge, I was doing it,'' he says. ``And
I had fun. I'm not really sorry for any of those times except that
I let myself get somewhat out of control for a few years. There
were a lot of different women, a lot of wild and crazy alcohol and
drug-filled encounters. Nobody really ever got hurt. It was
something everybody wanted to take part in. But that's something I
look back on now with mixed emotions. In a way, I'm kind of ashamed
of the fact I let myself get to that point. On the other side of
that coin, I'm kind of glad I had those experiences, because it
taught me an awful lot, and I don't think I could be nearly as
happy now if I hadn't gone through them. But it's not what I'm
looking for anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ed Norman, the head of the Nashville division of Warner
Brothers records, believes Tritt has survived the fickle climate of
today's country music precisely because of his introspection.
``There are phases to each artist's career in this business, and
Travis has transcended most,'' Norman says. ``You can see great
entertainers like George Jones or Waylon Jennings go through the
first phase of a career in which they develop and build their
relationship to the marketplace and their constituent base. Then
there's a transition, where they tend to sit back a bit and look at
themselves in the context of the work they've done and how it makes
a contribution to the world of music. To some extent, that's how I
see Travis and what he's doing, which is making the best music he's
ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tritt has indeed stepped back to look at his life and music,
as those who know him testify, his thoughts have led him back home.
Though he has toured the world, made movies and become a household
name, he has never left Georgia for the chic haunts of Nashville or
Los Angeles. When he wears Armani, it's with cowboy boots. Theresa
laughs when she confesses they love to shop at Wal-Mart: ``Travis
makes fun of me `cause I even make the bus stop there when we're
out on the road.'' Though she could certainly afford designer duds,
Theresa's favorite pastime is taking advantage of sales at mall
stores like Clothestime. One of Tritt's favorite possessions is his
Massey Ferguson tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've realized that the very thing you're running from often
ends up being the very thing you're running to,'' Tritt says,
gazing out his window at the rolling countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like living on this farm, for example. My dad (James Tritt,
who still lives in Marietta) used to have gardens that would feed
third-world countries. He'd plant four rows, 200 yards long of
corn. Four rows, 200 yards long of okra. Six rows, 200 yards long,
of butter beans. I've hoed more beans than anyone could imagine.
We'd spend our summers working, and I absolutely hated it. I said,
'if I ever get away from this I'll never, ever do this again in my
life. ''
</P>
<P>
   Tritt says he ``wrote a song about this not too long ago, but
it's so personal I've never put it on an album: I remember how I
cussed/that old hillside dust/in the hot summer sun/that burned my
back.'' It talks about a young man who says he wants to get away
from everything, to run from all this stuff, and he does. A few
years later, he returns and realizes this is where he belonged all
the time. The thing he would love to do more than anything is pick
up a hoe and plant 200 yards of corn, and snap beans and okra.
That's exactly me.''
</P>
<P>
   Out back of the house, there's proof positive that Tritt isn't
kidding about getting back to his country roots. Eight rows of
painted white gourds hang gracefully in the fall sunshine, awaiting
the comings and goings of the purple martins. ``This is exactly
where I want to be, personally and professionally,'' he says.
``This is home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
