</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `ER' slips on trends as viewers switch to cable
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``ER'' Nielsen numbers tell the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago at the start of the new TV season, the tube's No. 1
show debuted with 31.85 million viewers. The next week, ``ER'' got
30.63 million. Then 29.34 million. And in the latest ratings for
Oct. 12-18, ``ER'' remains No. 1 with 27.87 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, viewership is falling. And not just for ``ER,''
but for the four major networks as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The household share for NBC, ABC, CBS and Fox so far this season
is 56 percent, down 6 percent from last year, according to The
Hollywood Reporter. In 1996, the share was 65 percent. In 1995, it
was 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer people are watching the major networks (CBS is the only
one that can boast a rise _ a 2 percent jump in its target audience
of viewers age 25-54). Last season, ``Seinfeld'' finished No. 1 and
averaged 33.58 million viewers per week. This season, ``ER's''
Nielsen-leading average is 29.92 million.
</P>
<P>
   Just over 13 million people are watching ABC's Wednesday night
``20/20.'' And that's good enough to rank the show in this season's
Top 25. Last season, 13 million viewers would rank the show at No.
35.
</P>
<P>
   So where is everybody going?
</P>
<P>
   They're following their friends to cable. Among viewers 18-49,
for example, ratings for all basic cable networks _ like TNT, AMC
and USA _ are up 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
