<P>
   2. Still into assault, but laying off the battery.
</P>
<P>
   1. He won't fight on `'Will And Grace' Night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson has been told he can box again. Isn't that like
telling Bill Clinton to energize his libido?
</P>
<P>
   The Middle East peace negotiations no doubt have taken a lot out
of Mr. Clinton, but we bet he's liked them more than his summer
vacation talks with Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Former White House spokesman Mike McCurry says Mr. Clinton is a
``richly gifted leader'' but ``exasperatingly stupid in his
personal life.'' We think he meant sexasperatingly stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The list of folks unofficially running for president grows: Gary
Bauer, Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle, John Ashcroft, John Kasich,
Dick Gephardt, Al Gore, Bill Bradley. But the only guy officially
campaigning is Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says his new White House chief of staff, John
Podesta, ``has a tough hide.'' More important now is knowing where
to hide.
</P>
<P>
   The 105th Congress certainly hasn't done much. And we're not
sure if the country is doing well because of _ or despite _ that.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft trial has been interesting so far, but would be
even better if someone could figure out how to blame O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has recovered much of the ground it had lost
since August. But probably it will need to rise a lot more before
some financial analysts recommend small investors get back in.
</P>
<P>
   In a doctoral thesis, Saddam Hussein's son predicts the U.S.
will lose its superpower status. And will Iraq become Kuwait's
closet space?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit is growing due to the Asian financial
crisis. So should we order out more or less Chinese food?
</P>
<P>
