<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOFT-DRINKS-HNS &LR;      10-21 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFT-DRINKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD RESEARCH GROUP ATTACKS HIGH CONSUMPTION OF SOFT DRINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans consume twice as much soda pop as they
did 25 years ago, a habit that can result _ especially for
teen-agers who down two to three 12-ounce cans a day _ in obesity,
tooth decay and loss of bone mass, according to a new report
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are drowning in soda pop _ it's become their main
beverage,'' said Michael Jacobson, executive director the Center
for Science in the Public Interest, a food research organization
that sponsored the study. The center has issued earlier reports
attacking the nutritional value of theater popcorn, many fast foods
and many Chinese, Mexican and Italian dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said at a news conference that ``soda is squeezing more
nutritious foods and beverages out of (youngsters') diets. It's
high time that parents limit their children's soft drink
consumption and demand that local schools get rid of their
soft-drink vending machines, just as they have banished smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Soda consumption has displaced milk, a prime source of calcium,
which is essential for bone growth, the report said. Teen-age boys
and girls drink twice as much soda pop as milk while 20 years ago
they drank twice as much milk as soda, it added.
</P>
<P>
   The study also said that about a quarter of the teens who drink
soda get 25 percent or more of their daily calorie intake from it.
``Those calories, of course, come from sugar, and teens consume two
to three times as much sugar as government guidelines recommend,''
Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's report said that while excessive soda
consumption can lead to obesity, tooth decay and bone-density loss
in teens, it is also linked to such ailments in adults as kidney
stones and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of bone density is a particularly disturbing trend in
girls, said Dr. Bess Dawson-Hughes, a professor of medicine at
Tufts University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see many young women whose bones have fractured, often
during team sports,'' she said at the news conference. ``Almost
routinely, they report diets low in calcium and often high in soft
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Excessive soda consumption ``sets up these teens for
osteoporosis in later life,'' she warned.
</P>
<P>
   The center urged Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala to commission a study on the impact of soda pop on the
nation's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside a wall of 868 cans that the center said
represents the annual consumption for the average soda-drinking
male, Jacobson also called on the soda industry to cease marketing
campaigns aimed at children and adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   The soda pop industry blasted the report. The National Soft
Drink Association said the research group ``yet again ... is
promoting unfounded consumer alarm by attacking a perfectly safe
and enjoyable food or beverage product, in this case soft drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization's ``strained efforts to blame soft drinks for
various health issues simply are not supported by the facts and are
an insult to consumer intelligence,'' the association said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Finkelstein, a spokesman for the association, added that the
industry never claimed that soft drinks provide nutritional value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has always been that there's room for water, milk
fruit juice, soft drinks and other beverages'' in a healthy diet,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Grabowski, a vice president of the Grocery Manufacturers of
America, said the soda study was ``another tiresome tirade against
the food industry. The alarmists should quit attacking food and
beverage companies that provide consumers with the products they
want and instead join us in educating everyone about proper
nutrition,'' Grabowski said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the average 13- to 18 year-old male who
drinks soda consumes more than three 12-ounce cans of it a day. Ten
percent of soda-drinking males consume seven cans a day, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   Girls drink about a third less than boys. The average 13- to
18-year-old female soda-drinker consumes more than two cans a day,
and 10 percent of them drink five or more cans daily.
</P>
<P>
   The group said the statistics were based on consumption data by
the Department of Agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
