<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICAN-REVOLT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SENATE REPUBLICANS REVOLT AND OPPOSE MAMMOTH SPENDING BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A surprising number of Senate Republicans revolted
against their party's leadership Wednesday to vote against the huge
federal spending bill that the Senate passed and sent to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican rebels criticized the 40-pound document as too
pricey, too rushed and so huge that members barely knew what was in
it.
</P>
<P>
   The $520 billion appropriations measure combined eight of the 13
spending bills needed to fund the government for the fiscal year
that began Oct. 1, along with $20 billion earmarked for emergency
spending, and a host of pet projects slipped in at the 11th hour.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost accounted for about one-third of the $1.7
trillion federal budget for the 1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Senate vote of 65-29 for passage included 20
Republicans and nine Democrats in the ``nay'' column.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final vote, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., defensively conceded that the bill ``is too big, and the
process isn't the preferred way'' to complete spending bills. But,
Lott added, ``It is what is needed to keep important government
programs working.''
</P>
<P>
   With Congress headed home to campaign for the Nov. 3 mid-term
elections, the chaotic final days of the session reflected the
harsh reality facing Republicans. Their options were either to
accept the mammoth spending package or face a government shutdown.
The last time that happened _ in 1995 _ the public blamed the
Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators called into question the tenure of the Senate
leadership. Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who voted against the bill,
said Republicans ``are going to have some questions'' about whether
the present GOP leadership should be retained. He called the
spending bill ``the irresponsible product of a dishonest process.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., another ``nay'' vote, faulted
Republican committee chairmen for taking ``feet-in-the-cement
positions'' and failing to compromise on spending issues earlier
this year, forcing Congress to take up the eight spending bills at
the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said Republicans were forced to ``turn the ball over to
the White House'' and agree to extra spending for
Democratic-sponsored programs because Congress failed to get its
job done.
</P>
<P>
   Senate critics of the jumbo package said the annual
appropriations process became bogged down this year. They blamed
the lag on the zeal of some lawmakers to pass anti-tobacco
legislation or overhaul the managed care system or the
time-consuming efforts to investigate the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   In the last vote of his 18-year congressional career, retiring
Sen. Dan Coates, R-Ind., voted against the bill and criticized the
budget process as ``deeply flawed.'' He derided his colleagues for
approving $20 billion for emergency spending on what he deemed
non-emergencies. That emergency spending included money for farm
relief, natural disasters and fixing the year 2000 computer problem
in government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Many members said a major reason for the breakdown was the
absence of a budget resolution. That blueprint for spending
programs and taxes is supposed to be approved in the spring so that
congressional appropriators then will know their spending targets
in time to pass spending bills before August.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional budget negotiators failed to pass the budget
resolution for the first time since the Congressional Budget Act
was enacted in 1974. Negotiators intentionally delayed their work,
hoping to carve out a major tax cut, which eventually failed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., another GOP naysayer, denounced the
bill for being chock full of ``pork-barrel spending projects.''
McCain cited several examples of what he called pork, including $1
million for peanut quality research in Georgia, $250,000 for a
lettuce geneticist in Salinas, Calif., and $2.5 million for the
federal Office of Cosmetics and Color.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism came from both sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.V., an acknowledged expert at sliding
pork into spending bills, denounced the bill as ``a monstrosity''
and voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said it was ``terrible'' for Congress ``to wait until the
last minute and then pass an elephantine monstrosity and call it an
appropriations bill... There's no living person that knows
everything that's in this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Out there in the real world, when you don't do your work, you
are fired,'' Byrd added. ``On the real job site, colleagues, we
would be gone!''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., another ``nay'' vote, said
the breakdown in the budget process, which led to lawmakers voting
on millions of dollars in programs no one even debated, indicates
``Congress is getting ominously careless with its rules and
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats griped that they were left out of the process
while Republican leaders cobbled together the final details of the
jumbo spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to resemble a kind of bastard parliamentary
system'' in which ``the real decisions are made in a closed room by
three or four people,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said he voted against the bill because
it contained ``several hundred pages that are a complete mystery to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey said it was impossible to make decisions about the public
interest because it was impossible to know how that interest jibed
``with a bill whose 3,800 pages were not even published until the
dark of last night.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the Republican leadership for failing to schedule the
Senate's time properly over the course of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said never before in his memory had
the Senate been confronted with such massive appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not support the wretched process which produced this bill
and cannot in good conscience vote for it,'' Levin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
