<SLUG> BC-MORDUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CONFIRMS MORDUE FOR FEDERAL JUDGESHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Wednesday unanimously approved the
nomination of Norman Mordue, a Supreme Court justice in New York,
as a federal judge for the state's northern district.
</P>
<P>
   During his confirmation hearing earlier this month, Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., called Mordue ``a great lawyer, a great judge, a
great citizen, a patriarch of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said, ``You're
an example of what a federal judge ought to be and what a human
being ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mordue, the Senate confirmed 16 of President
Clinton's nominations to federal judgeships Wednesday, bringing the
total for the year to 65.
</P>
<P>
   That is 29 more than last year, but Democrats continue to
grumble over what they see as a politically motivated effort by
Republicans to slow the nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   Mordue, of Syracuse, N.Y., was born on June 26, 1942, and
received an undergraduate degree in 1966 and a law degree in 1971
from Syracuse University. From 1966 to 1968, he served in the U.S.
Army and received the Purple Heart and other awards for his service
in Vietnam before being discharged as a captain.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1982, Mordue served with the district attorney's
office in Onondaga County, first as a clerk, then as an assistant
district attorney. From 1982 to 1985, he was a Onondaga County
court judge. Since 1986, Mordue has served on the state Supreme
Court in that county.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
