<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-SCHOOLS-KAN &LR;      10-21 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Judge gives school board credit, warns against accusations of
racism  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A federal judge Tuesday credited the Kansas
City, Mo., Board of Education for making a decision on
Superintendent Henry Williams _ but not before warning members to
stop making race an issue in district affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if the last superintendent was white, black,
yellow or any color, and I don't care if the next superintendent is
white, black, yellow or any color,'' U.S. District Judge Dean
Whipple said. ``It does nothing but throw gas on the fire when
heated debates take place for board members to defend their
position by calling their opponent a racist. You can't help the
school district by throwing that word out in heated debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple's comments came at the end of a hearing to review a
court-appointed committee's recommendations on ways to move the
district forward.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing comes less than a week after Williams' termination,
a move that caused sharp divisions on the board. At least one black
board member, Lee Barnes Jr., called white board members Connie
Clark and Lance Loewenstein racists after they initially voted to
fire Williams. The board ultimately agreed instead to buy out the
last 8 months of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Whipple ordered the school board to immediately
begin looking for a search firm to help identify a new
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   He also ordered the board to complete a long-range plan by Dec.
31, scheduled a hearing next week to determine whether to allow
Phyllis Chase to continue as interim superintendent and held off on
a recommendation to force the resignation of about 20 top district
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said Whipple was not in the closed meeting at which
Barnes made the comment about Clark and Loewenstein and had no idea
of the context. He said the board's private discussion should have
remained private.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to control ourselves in public,'' said Barnes, one
of three board members to attend Tuesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple also expressed his strong support for the work of the
Desegregation Monitoring Committee, the three-member panel of
educators that Whipple appointed in October 1997 to oversee
district operations.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Whipple reinforced his desire that the committee be
intimately involved in district decision-making and that the
relationship not be adversarial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I selected what I thought were three of the top experts I
could find,'' Whipple said. ``I think one of the problems we had
making any progress was Dr. Williams' refusal to work with the
DMC.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple ordered the school board to work with the DMC to
identify a search firm to help locate the next superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Delaney, an attorney for the district, said school board
members hoped to begin soliciting applicants about Jan. 1 and
complete contract negotiations by the end of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Benson II, lawyer for the plaintiff schoolchildren,
questioned whether any candidate could succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there's a superintendent out there who can run
this district in the atmosphere that exists,'' Benson said. ``I
think you could name the number of good superintendents in the
United States on the fingers of one hand, and none of them want to
come to Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   John Murphy, DMC chairman, agreed that Kansas City would be a
tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has to happen systemwide and communitywide to make this
an attractive position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than being just a good leader. It's getting the
community and the school board to focus on the importance of the
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple, meanwhile, scheduled a hearing Oct. 29 to determine
whether Chase should be allowed to continue as interim
superintendent. The school board appointed Chase to the top spot
last week after agreeing to a severance package with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring committee had recommended that two persons,
including Chase, take over the district's leadership during the
search for a new superintendent and that neither person be allowed
to apply for the permanent post.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members say Chase should be allowed to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple noted that the school's board action in appointing only
Chase was in direct violation of an earlier court order that said
disputes between the DMC and the board should be resolved in a
court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Board President John Rios said the board's executive committee
planned to meet with the DMC before next week's hearing to resolve
as many issues as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The school board agreed at Tuesday's hearing with a DMC
recommendation to develop a long-range plan for dealing with
charter schools, decentralizing many administrative office
functions to individual schools and reducing the achievement gap
between black and white students.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the long-range plan should identify problems that
prevent the district from progressing and plans for addressing
those problems. The plan also should include a system that holds
every principal, teacher and student accountable by setting
benchmarks and then measuring for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple ordered the district to work with the DMC and complete
the long-range goals by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Benson argued that long-range goals had been in place since June
1996 for raising achievement, improving teacher training and
implementing a new curriculum, a new accountability plan and new
student assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have goals,'' Benson said. ``What we don't have is
visionary leadership to pull all this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple took no action on a DMC recommendation that the current
top-level administrators submit their resignations effective June
30 and reapply for their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In a report last week to Whipple, the DMC wrote: ``It cannot be
emphasized enough that any superintendent cannot be successful if
changes are not made in key personnel positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaney said such a measure would devastate employee morale and
impair the district's ability to move forward with planning.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Raisher, an attorney for the teachers' union, agreed that
top administrators should not be left hanging until the summer. The
DMC should help identify those who need to be removed immediately
and then do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel putting all the administrators under a cloud...raises
a problem,'' Raisher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
