<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILADELPHIA-MUSIC-RE     10-21 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILADELPHIA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA ORCHESTRA: A STAND-IN AND A SOLOIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Wolfgang Sawallisch, the music director of the
Philadelphia Orchestra, announced that he had to remain in Germany
recently because of the illness of his wife, finding a conductor to
cover the all-Brahms program the orchestra presented in
Philadelphia last week and at Carnegie Hall on Tuesday night was
challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Not many conductors know the two works that constituted the
first half of the program. In addition, Maurizio Pollini, the
exacting and intellectually imposing Italian pianist who performed
the Brahms Piano Concerto No. 1, had to be accommodated. And this
came in the thick of the fall season, when most conductors are busy
with concerts long booked.
</P>
<P>
   But the orchestra was able to hire Andreas Delfs, a 39-year-old
German conductor best known for his work as music director of the
Hannover State Opera and Orchestra and his new post with the
Milwaukee Symphony. Delfs was free because his wife is expecting a
baby and he was beginning a period of paternity leave. Such are the
often circuitous ways that classical musicians reach career
milestones.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to estimate the depth of Delfs' capacity from this
single save-the-day debut. He is a dynamic, technically gifted
conductor, and he clearly knew the Brahms choral works, because he
conducted them from memory.
</P>
<P>
   Brahms wrote a lot of music for amateur chorus, but ``Naenie,''
a setting of a Schiller poem about the ephemerality of beauty, and
``Schicksalslied,'' a Hoelderlin ode to immortality, are
contemplative, compositionally sophisticated works. Delfs, his
players, and the fine Philadelphia Singers Chorale gave beautiful,
luminous accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Pollini's performance of the Brahms D Minor Concerto abounded
with the musical insight and pianistic elegance that place him
among the most admired of today's senior pianists. This is a
rhapsodic, ruminative, youthful score, a work Brahms struggled
with. Textural and structural clarity are not its strong points.
</P>
<P>
   But the music has seldom sounded so lucid as it did in Pollini's
account, which revealed intertwining contrapuntal lines, startling
asymmetries of phrase structure, and complex chromatic harmony
where so many other performances are clouded over with thick
pianistic mists. And of course he had the requisite pianistic power
and stamina for the double octave outbursts and the thick, leaping
chords.
</P>
<P>
   Those who respond to his restrained approach find Pollini's
playing aristocratic. Those who don't find him cool, as I sometimes
do.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while he let go with what seemed, for him, real
abandon, as in the finale of the first movement, which he played
with demonic fervor, and the climax of the Adagio movement, in
which he could be heard singing along with the surging melody. I
wish he would let this side of himself out more often.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was a distinguished performance, and the audience
responded rapturously.
</P>
<P>
   Delfs did his best to keep Brahms' thickly scored orchestra part
from swamping the soloist, but sometimes it did anyway. Yet, given
the constraints of the occasion, Delfs did solid work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9694 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAYOFF-PICTURE-KAN &LR;      10-21 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYOFF-PICTURE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Employment outlook better than layoff figures suggest, analysts
say  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ A new wave of layoffs is lapping at the American
work force. Among sizable downsizing announcements so far this
month:
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. will trim 4,300 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co. will let 3,100 workers go.
</P>
<P>
   Shell Oil Co. will cut 20 percent of its exploration and
production staff.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. will ax 14,000 defense sector jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Cuts are seeping even into Kansas City's bedrock-strong economy.
Among them: Western Auto Supply Co., Dickinson Theatres, the J.C.
Nichols Co., Sun Publications, Hallmark Cards Inc. All are taking
payroll nips here, cost tucks there in efforts to operate more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it looks as if American business has begun
fighting an economic undertow that formed on foreign shores and
this summer rippled through American financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But most authorities say don't fly the red storm-warning flags
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The employment outlook is mostly optimistic, according to a
study made public today by the American Management Association. The
report says U.S. firms are scaling back their hiring plans somewhat
but still are expecting overall job growth through June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses, disappointed with lower quarterly earnings and
slower growth projections, are cutting staff, speeding retirements
and encouraging other forms of staff attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate mergers also promise to add to the layoff numbers,
employment experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put Bank of America and NationsBank together and not
have duplication of resources,'' said Michael D. Gunter, a
Winston-Salem, N.C., lawyer whose firm specializes in employment
issues related to downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   But this new job-cut ripple, at least at its outset, is sending
different signals from the downsizing tsunami that hit in the late
1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies learned that earlier staff slashings weren't the
cure-all for financial ills. They still needed people, though
perhaps in different positions from the ones cut, to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   Among all companies reporting job cuts to the American
Management Association, there was nearly a one-for-one exchange of
job cuts and job creations in the 12 months that ended in June
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Also, overall U.S. employment growth continues. Most layoff
victims are finding re-employment quickly. Thus, if it's possible
to speak of job loss in kinder, gentler terms, the layoffs of 1998
_ so far _ may qualify.  &LR; brk:Net growth  &LR; tx:According to the
American Management Association staffing report released today, net
job growth should continue through June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slightly fewer companies planned new hiring, and slightly more
projected new job cuts, but the real change is in the average
projected net work force growth, down to \P4.6 percent from \P6.9
percent a year ago,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   But last year's projected net work-force increase of 6.9 percent
was exceeded. Surveyed companies actually reported a 7.7 percent
net work-force growth for the 12 months ending in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The association surveyed 1,231 member organizations this summer.
About 44 percent of the respondents said they planned to add jobs
in the 12-month period beginning in June 1998. Only about 17
percent said they planned job cuts in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that, based on previous survey results, those
percentages would change as the year goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The share that actually cuts jobs is often double the share
(that has) cuts planned at the outset of the period, while the
share that creates new jobs is more than 50 percent higher than
planned,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate hiring managers expressed some caution about the
future job environment because of the ongoing ``correction'' in the
U.S. stock market; political uncertainties in Washington; and
economic turmoil in Southeast Asia, Japan, Russia and Latin
America.  &LR; brk:Gentler downsizing  &LR; tx:When Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan said last month that ``it is just not credible that
the U.S. can remain an oasis of prosperity'' among strained world
economies, American industry listened _ but didn't panic.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment this year hit a 28-year low. Economic expansion has
been undergoing one of its longest sustained runs in history.
Generally, both private and public balance sheets are solvent. And
consumers continue to spend their earnings, which have stayed ahead
of the nearly invisible inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent stock market gyrations, sick foreign markets and
U.S. business realignments _ especially mergers _ are causing many
industries to project lower short-term profits. When that happens,
layoffs often follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merger-related layoffs, in particular, are going to happen
because of cost-cutting reasons,'' said Gerald L. Miller, professor
of economics at Rockhurst College. ``And desperation layoffs are
going to happen when some execs search for quarterly profit
increases and preservation of their bonuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Miller said, ``As our economic expansion continues,
companies are going to be less and less capable of keeping up with
the double-digit growth rates they set at the beginning of the
expansion. There will be shakeouts _ especially in the auto,
aerospace, and oil and gas industries. And there will be mergers
across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of downsizing, while painful to the workers let go,
may be occurring under a more humane umbrella, observed Gunter, the
North Carolina lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Gunter said there was an evolution of thinking among many
employers. Five or 10 years ago, downsizing companies often asked
their corporate attorneys, ``What's the minimum we can do?'' when
letting staff go, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I see a little more of the employers' thinking as
`Let's do what we can that's fair and hopefully leave these folks
with a good taste in their mouths,' '' Gunter said.
</P>
<P>
   This gentler downsizing has at least three characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   More generous severance pay for rank-and-file workers. Severance
typically amounts to one month's pay for each year of service, up
to a maximum of 24 months, Gunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies seem to be paying the agreed-upon severance even
if the laid-off worker gets a new job within the severance-pay
period, he added.
</P>
<P>
   An extended period of health insurance coverage beyond the
severance date.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, companies are continuing to fund their employer
contribution for about six months, he said. More rarely, employers
will pick up the costs of their former employees' COBRA premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Access to outplacement services.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file workers are getting employer-financed help in
finding new jobs through the resources offered by outplacement
firms, a perquisite previously limited to executives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staffing authorities say payroll size always will be scrutinized
when profit pictures change. Thus, even if the domestic economy
avoids recession, no one expects a layoff-free climate.
</P>
<P>
   Given current economic signals, the consensus calls for net job
growth. That means a layoff slip is not a ticket to long-term
unemployment, though some job retraining may be required to fit
current hiring needs.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, the downsizing wave is swimmable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
