<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-CASES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Missouri Supreme Court overturns man's conviction for child sex
abuse  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Supreme Court ruled Tuesday that
it was unconstitutional for prosecutors to tell juries in child
sexual-assault cases about other abuse allegations and convictions
against defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in a Jackson County case could result in the
overturning of convictions of dozens of people, prosecutors and
defense attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court overturned the 1997 conviction of Robert L.
Burns, 21. Burns was sentenced to 15 years in prison for sodomy
involving a 7-year-old boy behind a Kansas City church in 1995.
Prosecutors called on witnesses in an alleged assault of another
boy to bolster their case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Claire McCaskill said Tuesday that Burns would be
retried as quickly as possible. McCaskill said she would seek high
bonds to keep Burns, as well as others to be retried because of the
ruling, behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated that Jackson County would have to retry about a
half-dozen or more cases. A spokesman for state Attorney General
Jay Nixon said that his office did not know how many cases would
have to be retried.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors statewide have used the law since it was enacted in
1995, McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to introduce all the evidence you legally can,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Fry, assistant county prosecutor and chief trial
assistant, said Burns would not face an easy retrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a free man,'' Fry said. ``He's just back for another
dose of due process.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Denzel, the Columbia assistant public defender who
represented Burns, praised the court's ruling and predicted:
``There will be a lot of ripples.'' Public defenders are
re-examining cases and will make use of the new ruling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missouri has historically recognized the right to be tried
only for the crime charged,'' he said. ``It's too easy to think if
they (defendants) did it before, they did it this time.''
</P>
<P>
   A round of sex-crime retrials or releases followed a similar
ruling in 1993, when the state Supreme Court severely limited the
use of prior crimes as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly responded by passing the 1995 law allowing
such ``propensity'' evidence. High courts in some other states had
found such laws constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Supreme Court on Tuesday stood by its 1993 ruling
that such evidence of prior sexual misconduct was allowed only if
crimes were so bizarre, unique and distinctive as to create ``a
signature'' for a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson County also had to retry or take pleas on about
a half-dozen cases after the 1993 ruling, McCaskill said that ``by
and large, we were able to get about the same results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
