u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-TECH-VISAS-HNS &LR;      10-21 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-VISAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING BILL WOULD ALLOW COMPANIES TO HIRE MORE FOREIGN WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Labor-hungry technology companies will be able to
hire more skilled foreign workers under a provision lumped into the
mammoth spending bill that cleared Congress Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Technology and computer companies in California's Silicon Valley
have lobbied for the measure, which would double the number of
employment visas for foreign computer programmers and others with
high-tech skills.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say there is a scarcity of skilled Americans, but
organized labor says the provision is a sellout of American
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, spearheaded by Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.,
would increase the number of so-called H1-B work visas from 65,000
to 115,000 in 1999 and 2000, and 107,500 a year later. President
Clinton supports the change.
</P>
<P>
   The visas have been used in recent years to recruit computer
programmers, many of them from India, Taiwan and Europe. Holders of
H1-B visas are allowed to remain in the United States for up to six
years, but many settle here permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers-USA, which
represents 218,000 engineers and computer scientists, said the
measure didn't include enough protections for Americans who may be
displaced by an influx of skilled foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the economy grows at a substantial rate, there may not be a
detrimental effect,'' said Vin O'Neill, a policy analyst at the
institute. ``But if it turns down, we are concerned _ especially
about older workers over age 45.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said he wasn't surprised that the measure cleared
Congress because ``it was clear that the (Clinton) administration,
the Republican congressional leadership, and the high-tech industry
wanted it pretty badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Golodner, president of the Department for Professional
Employees of the AFL-CIO, which represents 4 million union members,
said the legislation would hurt college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will retard the increases in their salaries and benefits,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was lumped into the legislation that included $520
billion to round out the government's $1.7 trillion federal budget.
The spending package was approved by the House Tuesday and the
Senate Wednesday and is expected to be signed into law by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said the labor provision would
``allow dynamic American companies and research labs to hire more
skilled foreign professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he was confident the measure included adequate
safeguards ``to protect American workers and provide substantial
funding to educate and train Americans to fill the lucrative
high-tech jobs that are available across our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure appeared in jeopardy earlier this month when Sen.
Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, threatened to block it, questioning the claims
of a worker shortage. But the measure sailed through Wednesday,
attached to the spending bill that many members of Congress were
anxious to dispense with so they could return home to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said he would challenge the need for importing foreign
high-tech workers when Congress reconvenes next year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, if 15 percent or more of a company's
employees hold H1-B visas, the company must attest that the workers
have not replaced qualified Americans.
</P>
<P>
   However, companies hiring H1-B workers with at least a master's
degree or at salaries of $60,000 or more would be exempt from
having to provide the information. Small businesses and start-up
companies also would get exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also requests that the Labor Department look
into any reported abuses of the program, and places a $500 filing
fee on visa applications and renewals, which would raise more than
$75 million for scholarship and training programs for U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, pushed for a similar
bill that originally would have provided broader safeguards for
American workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
