<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9708 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HN     10-21 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE MOVES TOWARD ONLY REFERENDUM THIS YEAR ON
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a closely watched replay of pitched battles in
California and Houston over government preferences for women and
minorities, Washington state is moving toward the nation's only
referendum this year on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   A measure on the Nov. 3 ballot, known as Initiative 200, would
bar the state and local governments from granting ``preferential
treatment'' to women or minorities in hiring, education or awarding
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in California, the nation's most populous state, approved
a similar proposal two years ago. But Houston voters last fall
defeated an attempt to dismantle the municipal affirmative action
program, although a state judge has ordered a second election.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, opponents of affirmative action are looking to the
outcome in Washington state to determine how _ or perhaps even
whether _ to take their campaign to other states and localities.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the preferences hope a campaign pitched strongly at
women will help defeat the measure here and provide a guide if
other electoral fights on the emotionally charged issue are in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
   Women are the critical element in Washington because the state
is 86 percent white. Preferential treatment for blacks and
Hispanics, so at play in the California and Houston campaigns, is a
subsidiary point in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pull back the curtain and expose the Trojan horse.
Women and their families are targeted by this,'' said Sue Tupper, a
Democratic political consultant advising the Stop!200 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action backers contend the measure represents an
assault on equal rights for women, and have aimed at the
pocketbooks as well as the hearts and minds of female voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will roll back the progress women have made in getting
equal pay for equal work,'' Democratic Gov. Gary Locke contended in
Stop!200's first TV commercial opposing the initiative. Another ad,
citing the League of Women Voters' opposition to the measure, says:
``200 will cut the training women need to get family-wage jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of affirmative action dispute the contention that the
measure harbors any adverse economic prospects for women.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Connerly, the Sacramento businessman who sponsored the
California initiative and bankrolled the Washington measure, said
the same ``scare tactics'' were used in his state and raised in
legal challenges, which finally failed at the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea that (the initiative) sets women back to the era
when they were kept barefoot and pregnant is just absolute
nonsense,'' said Connerly as he left Sacramento for several days of
campaigning in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Given the small numbers of minority voters in Washington, the
opponents' focus on women in the final weeks before the election is
not unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning we knew they would have to appeal to a
significant portion of the population and so would be aiming at
women,'' said Brett Bader, a Republican political consultant
working with the initiative's advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly told the Seattle Times: ``In order to win, they have to
scare the crap out of white women.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates argue the initiative ``means that affirmative action
could reach out with opportunity but not keep out with quotas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing us together,'' concludes one television ad touting
Initiative 200.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot question asks: ``Shall government be prohibited from
discriminating or granting preferential treatment based on race,
sex, color, ethnicity or national origin in public employment,
education and contracting?''
</P>
<P>
   Locke, in his television ad, conceded that the measure ``is
written to sound good,'' but he added, ``It's full of hidden
consequences.'' Opponents contend it would gut a dozen or more
affirmative action programs. The measure would also, he warned, set
off a round of ``expensive lawsuits that waste our tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent interview Locke said the initiative looks to a
world that does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we were in a period where affirmative action was no
longer needed, but we're not there,'' said Locke, a
Chinese-American who said he was helped into Yale Law School by
programs seeking public school graduates and applicants from
outside the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action supporters have their work cut out for them.
A statewide poll taken two weeks ago for the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer and KOMO-TV showed likely voters favored the
initiative 55 percent to 35 percent. But when the same respondents
were told the measure would virtually wipe out affirmative action
programs, the margin of approval dropped to 46 percent to 40
percent, giving opponents hope that their ads are properly focused
and may yet help defeat the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the initiative are far better financed. The most
recent reports showed the campaign in favor of the initiative had
raised almost $240,000 and had about $136,000 on hand. The No!200
campaign had raised almost $1 million and had almost $350,000 for
the final pre-election push.
</P>
<P>
   Bader conceded the ads aimed at women will ``have an effect,''
but Connerly said: ``I just believe we have enough steam in the
engine to counter it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote in Washington comes after California voters in 1996
adopted Proposition 209, which outlawed racial, gender and ethnic
preferences in state affairs, including college admissions. The
measure was sponsored by Connerly, a University of California
regent who is black.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Houston voters defeated a measure aimed at
dismantling the affirmative action program that set goals for the
percentages of construction, purchasing and personal service
contracts with the city that should be taken by woman and
minorities. A state court judge in June, however, threw out the
result, ruling that the ballot language adopted by City Council did
not reflect the intent of the proposal's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   As originally submitted by a group led by Houston investment
adviser Edward Blum, the proposal said the city ``shall not
discriminate'' in hiring or contracting on the basis of race,
gender or minority status. Under pressure from Mayor Bob Lanier, a
proponent of affirmative action, Council rewrote the ballot
language to say the city shall ``end the use of affirmative
action'' for women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   A new election in Houston is not expected until a potentially
lengthy appeals process is completed. In a related case, which
could make a new Houston election moot, a federal judge is
considering a separate constitutional challenge to the city's
affirmative action program. A federal judge has already struck down
a similar program of the Metropolitan Transit Authority, a decision
that is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is unquestionably moving in this direction,'' said
John Carlson, chairman of the Washington State Civil Rights
Initiative. ``It doesn't matter if there's a bump in the road or an
adverse court decision here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Connerly had said earlier in the campaign that a defeat
in Washington state might stunt his effort nationally, he said
Tuesday that ``win or lose'' in Washington state, ``obviously the
movement continues for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said the next initiative effort might be in Nebraska or
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly _ and his checkbook _ were called in when the signature
drive to get the measure on the ballot was sagging. Connerly's
American Civil Rights Institute put up more than half of the almost
$400,000 spent on gathering the required petitions. Connerly's
group is also paying for a separate television and radio ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Initiative opponents have called Connerly and his proposal
``carpetbaggers'' from California, but Connerly replied: ``The day
they keep Al Gore, Jesse Jackson and the NAACP out of here is the
day that I, too, will say that I, as a federal taxpayer, have no
right to be here.'' Vice President Gore was featured speaker at a
No!200 fund-raising event earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Locke called on _ ``strong armed,'' said proponent
Bader _ Washington state businesses to oppose the initiative, and
several major firms have.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the state's largest private employer, donated $50,000
and Microsoft and Costco each gave $25,000. Starbucks chief
executive and his wife gave $10,000. Corporate contributions are
permitted in initiative campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the dam had broken,'' Carlson said, but after about
a quarter of the state's major corporations lined up against the
initiative, the endorsements ``just stopped cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Most major banks and the state's leading retailer, Nordstrom's
department store, have stayed on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents have impugned Boeing's motives, suggesting the
aerospace giant is attempting to buy goodwill as it faces several
employment discrimination lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives have expressed concern about being seen to
oppose affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to take the grief that disclosure would
bring,'' Bader said. Opponents of the initiative wrote major donors
backing the measure to say: ``We intend to publicize, in various
ways, the support or the opposition of businesses on this vitally
import issue confronting our community.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
