<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His name will not appear on a single ballot, but
President Clinton has become the wild card in the Nov. 3
congressional elections, and no one knows how he will play with
voters. By RON HUTCHESON. Story will move in ``w'' Washington
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE MEDICINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Afraid and confused, the elderly woman
walked into the Fort Worth library seeking information about a
recently diagnosed disease. She had just left her doctor, who told
her she had neuropathy and sent her to a specialist. Kathy Malone,
senior librarian and Internet guru at the central library, said she
remembers the relief on the woman's face when her research found
treatments for the condition, which affects nerves in the feet and
other extremities. The knowledge came courtesy of the information
superhighway, technology that is changing the way that the newly
diagnosed, chronically worried or sporadically curious learn about
medicine. By CHARLOTTE HUFF. Story has moved in ``a'' national news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-SEMINARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Board members of Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary have changed a bylaw to require faculty
members to sign the updated version of the denomination's statement
of faith that includes a passage stating that women must ``submit
graciously'' to their husbands. By TARA DOOLEY. Story has moved in
``a'' national news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL DROPOUTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ No matter what their age, race or gender,
most high school dropouts regret the single decision that shapes
much of their adult lives _ their jobs, their lifestyles, their
self-esteem. Three people who didn't finish high school tell why
and how they dropped out _ and what it took for them to get their
educations. By LARRY BINGHAM. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRAZZLED PARENT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ I guess I always knew that, someday, everything I
learned in the pursuit of my liberal arts degree would become
completely useless when it came to helping my kids with their
academic development. I suspected that this would happen during
their high school years as they delved into logarithmic equations
and beyond-DOS computer programming. But now I see I was wrong. Now
I know that it's all over by second grade. By CATHERINE NEWTON.
Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
