<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RED-OUTLAWED-HNS &LR;      10-21 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED-OUTLAWED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCIPAL SEES RED, BANS THE COLOR AT SCHOOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Fearful that a gang called the Bloods would
terrorize the town and her students, too, the principal of Round
Rock High School decided one day to ban the color red.
</P>
<P>
   Red was the gang's color, said Sherry Blackett, the new
principal of the town's largest high school. Red was the color of
violence. Red was a color she connected with the town's first
drive-by shooting late last month, the vandalism of a school art
project one week later and frequent fights among students. Red
could endanger your life, just by wearing it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to create an environment that will not allow gangs
to flourish, so I banned the color red,'' she said. The principal,
who spent most of her career in Corpus Christi, Texas, added that
she knew of kids killed for wearing gang colors.
</P>
<P>
   So for three weeks this month, students who showed up in scarlet
were asked to change clothes or were sent to in-school suspension.
Some shrugged. Others rolled their eyes. One girl, whose wardrobe
was dominated by red, cried. A group of vocal parents grew irate.
</P>
<P>
   Now Blackett is reversing the ban and asking all of her students
to wear red on Friday as a kick-off to the national ``Red Ribbon
Week.'' Students will cut red ribbons in memory of lives lost to
drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be bringing the red back. I feel like the
lesson has been learned and the point made,'' Blackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The principal insists that the point is school safety, an issue
that strikes a receptive chord with parents concerned about school
shootings around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Blackett's ban has raised anew questions about gangs, the
right to self expression and whether dress codes or even uniforms
have any affect on conduct. And several Round Rock students
question whether banning red makes common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like red. Red's a good color,'' said Andrea Miller, a
sophomore. ``For somebody like me to have a color banned from my
wardrobe is really kind of silly. It's really kind of pointless.''
</P>
<P>
   Student Brandon Bennight said he doesn't care about the ban, but
``I think it's stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, James Payton, said if it makes the principal
feel better or makes the school safer, he's all for it. He added,
however, ``Red is not one of my colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin Henry, donning a bright red Mickey Mouse sweatshirt two
days before the ban's formal lifting, said she didn't understand
why Blackett banned red for the Bloods but not blue for the rival
Crips or yellow for a third gang called the Latin Kings. Indeed,
local police have identified at least six colors associated with
gangs, including the color maroon, which is one of the school
colors of Round Rock High.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes down to wearing khaki and white, they're going to
find some other way to identify themselves,'' said Deirdre Feehan
at the American Civil Liberties Union of Texas, which plans to send
the principal a letter outlining their concerns. ``We are
questioning whether this policy falls within the bounds of
constitutionality under freedom of expression, free speech and
freedom of association.''
</P>
<P>
   Round Rock police Officer Rod Hampton, who is assigned to the
school, said the town's gangs are so new that their colors and
symbols are not firmly established.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the reds, you've got the blues, you've got the
greens, you've got the maroons. You can go down the rainbow,''
Hampton said. ``They just go to another color.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said the vandalism at the school, the defacing of
artwork, did not appear gang-related, in spite of the fact that it
was carried out with red spray paint.
</P>
<P>
   To a mural of Darth Vader of Star Wars fame, for example,
vandals added a red smiley face over his mask. Two figures included
in the mural had what appear to be red bullet wounds as did a
separate mural of Superman. A painting of a car had the letters MHS
imposed over it, with the S in the form of a dollar sign. One
parent said she thinks the letters stand for a rival high school in
the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say this is not a case of gang graffiti,'' said Sgt.
Jack Abbott, gang specialist for the Round Rock police force. ``It
was more just an attack on the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said the drive-by shooting occurred in the wee hours of a
Sunday morning in late September and did not take place near the
school. Of the five suspects arrested, two different gangs were
represented in the car, he said. Members of one of the gangs wear
red, he said, and one of the two young women wounded in the attack
was a student at the high school. Neither of the women was wearing
red, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the purpose of the shooting, because of the color
red,'' he said. ``As far as a connection between the drive-by and
the criminal mischief at the high school, I haven't found that.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said Blackett didn't consult with police before
connecting either incident to a gang that wears red or connecting
the separate crimes to each other, a point that annoys Debbie
Weaver, a parent whose son was sent home from school for wearing
red in protest of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he ought to be able to wear whatever color he wants
and I agree,'' she said. ``You shouldn't punish the kids for
something that may or may not happen, and banning a color is silly.
Are we advertising gang colors by flying our flags outside the
school?''
</P>
<P>
   Other parents are troubled as well.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Ross said she was upset that her son, who is black, was
asked to remove his red shirt earlier in the year before the ban
went into effect. What bothers her most, she said, is it appeared
to be a selective color ban aimed at minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be some other way to deal with this because I
can't personally sacrifice the self-esteem of my children,'' said
Ross who has been assigned to a task force to recommend dress code
policies. ``You're taking the shirt off his back and that destroys
all I've worked for.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
