<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9716 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIN-EURO-TRADE-LATI     10-21 2561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-EURO-TRADE-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIES THAT BIND
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By SERGIO R. BUSTOS, with BARBARA BELEJACK in Mexico City, LAURA
COVILL in Frankfurt and JIM RUSSO in Madrid 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The scene in Mexico City was a familiar one. A banquet room full
of businessmen wanting to hear about investment opportunities in
Mexico. On hand were plenty of Mexican government officials touting
the benefits of the country. But the businessmen mingling with the
Mexicans earlier this year weren't from the United States. They
were Europeans, mostly British, thirsty for information about the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and other business
opportunities in Mexico.
 &HT;    As the global economy expands, European companies and investors
are flocking to the region to make up for lost ground and tap what
has become one of the world's most attractive emerging markets.
 &HT;    ``The importance of Mexico wasn't always evident in Europe,''
says Jacques Lecompte, currently the head of the EU delegation in
Mexico. ``NAFTA brought a new conception of Mexico.''
 &HT;    With its long-standing ties, its proximity and its historical
relationship _ both good and bad _ the United States has long
dominated much of the rest of the world in terms of trade with
Latin America and the Caribbean. Within the last few years, the
domination has increased, mainly because of NAFTA.
 &HT;    However, with the improved European economies, many companies
there are increasingly looking to Latin America for new business.
 &HT;    Trade among the eight largest Latin American economies and their
five top European partners reached a total of US$61.3 billion last
year, an increase of 10.2 percent over 1996, according to IMF data
compiled by Latin Trade.
 &HT;    Germany remains the undisputed top trading partner, followed by
Italy, France, Spain and the United Kingdom, in that order. (see
chart).
 &HT;    Brazil. In terms of Latin American partners, Brazil tops the
list, followed by Mexico and Argentina. But while Argentina saw
modest growth in trade with Europe and Brazil a respectable 10.8
percent increase, it was Mexico that saw the strongest growth last
year _ a whopping 24.2 percent, largely spurred by strong trade
growth with Italy and the UK.
 &HT;    Still, European companies remain a far cry from their U.S.
counterparts as far as foreign direct investment is concerned,
according to a recent report by the United Nations Economic
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (ECLAC). It found
the United States well ahead of the European Union as the biggest
source of foreign direct investment. It also found that Spain,
Germany and the United Kingdom were among the leading countries
with investment interest in the region.
 &HT;    ECLAC's Michael Mortimore, who authored the report, says most
European investment is destined for the Southern Cone because of
Mercosur. But, he says, European companies have yet to develop a
true investment strategy in Latin America.
 &HT;    ``I don't find much to call a European strategy,'' says
Mortimore, who says each European country seems to have a different
plan. Spanish firms appear bent on concentrating on electricity,
banks, telecommunications and airlines, while German firms seem
focused on automotive and chemicals. The British firms, he says,
seem particularly keen on targeting oil, banks, telecommunications
and gas distribution.
 &HT;    The strategy of the Spanish firms seems to be related to their
inability to compete within Europe on the one hand and the cultural
affinity with Latin America and the Caribbean on the other, he
says. Germany's interest seems to be based on firms with a
long-standing presence in the region _ Volkswagen, Bayer, BASF and
Hoescht. The British expansion is closely related to sales of
assets and new concession for natural resources.
 &HT;    Mexico. The European Union is Mexico's second most important
trading partner and is the second largest source of foreign direct
investment. But it's far behind that of the United States. Last
year, trade between Mexico and the European Union was $12 billion
compared with $176 billion between Mexico and the United States. On
the other hand, Mexican exports to Europe are showing signs of
growth. Last year, Mexican exports exceeded $43 billion, up 14
percent from 1996.
 &HT;    Britain's ambassador to Mexico, Adrian Beamish, blames NAFTA. He
says the European share of the Mexican market ``has plummeted since
NAFTA became effective.'' Indeed, the share has been cut roughly in
half from what it was in 1990.
 &HT;    Yet, despite such figures, Mexican trade and commerce officials,
including Undersecretary of Commerce Jaime Zabludovsky, continue to
pitch Mexico as the bridge between North and South America, and
between East and West. Mexico, says Zabludovsky, is intent on
diversifying its markets, especially since trade figures show 80
percent of all Mexican goods and services are traded with the
United States.
 &HT;    One step toward diversification was taken this year when the
European Union and Mexico embarked on negotiating a trade
agreement. Mexico sees talks with the EU as a way to lessen its
dependence on the United States as a trade partner. But any sort of
agreement may be a long way off because several EU members,
including France, would rather see the EU develop trade ties
through the World Trade Organization and not through individual
countries. France also balked at a similar agreement with Mercosur.
 &HT;    In the meantime, European countries with existing ties to Latin
America are expanding and new European companies are trying to
figure out where best to invest. Mexico, thanks to NAFTA, is a
favorite country for investment for Europeans who see it as a
convenient gateway to the lucrative U.S. market. They also are well
aware of the benefits of Mexico in terms of its natural resources
and its infrastructure needs.
 &HT;    For example, the Mexico subsidiary of France's Suez Lyonnaise
des Eaux currently operates water service contracts for about
one-quarter of Mexico City's residents. The parent company also has
business interests in Argentina, Brazil and Chile. British Oxygen
Co. (BOC) plans a $1 billion investment in Mexico's state oil
company Pemex, the largest British investment in Mexico.
 &HT;    Along with its Mexican-U.S. partner ICA Fluor Daniel, BOC plans
to construct the world's largest nitrogen complex to inject
nitrogen into the wells at the Cantarell crude oil field off the
coast of Campeche.
 &HT;    Among those most keen to enter Mexico is British Airports Group,
created by Britain's Ministry of Commerce to pursue opportunities
overseas. England was the first country to privatize all its
airports. During the Mexico City meeting, sponsored by London-based
Canning House, an organization that promotes ties between the
United Kingdom and Latin America, BAG officials spent time talking
up the company's track record and the potential commercialization
and tourism boom that airport privatization might bring to Mexico.
 &HT;    Few European companies are as deeply entrenched in Latin America
as Germany's automaker Volkswagen. The company, which will
manufacture more than 125,000 Beetles in its Puebla, Mexico
factory, is among the region's top European investors in Latin
America. Much of the production of cars in Mexico will be exported
to the United States. Volkswagen ranked first among the top 20
foreign enterprises in Latin America, according to an ECLAC report.
Eight other European countries made the list, including Italy's
carmaker Fiat, U.K./Holland-based oil giant Royal Dutch/Shell,
France's retail chain Carrefour and Switzerland's food processor
Nestle.
 &HT;    Long-term. Shell is a prime example of the kind of European
company that has had longstanding ties to the region. It first sank
money into the region during the early part of the century and
company officials remain as bullish about Latin America's long-term
prospects as they did at that time.
 &HT;    ``The Shell Group has ambitious growth aspirations for the
region,'' says Phil Watts, who is in charge of the company's
operations in Latin America. ``Latin America offers us the ability
to use a well-established presence to develop businesses in rapidly
growing and deregulating markets.''
 &HT;    The company has $5 billion worth of investments in oil and gas
exploration, production, distribution, marketing, oil refining,
petrochemicals, liquefied natural gas, coal and forestry in Latin
America. Most of its investment is tied up in oil refining,
distribution and marketing.
 &HT;    Despite Shell's huge investment, the region accounts for less
than 10 percent of all company revenues. Watts is not discouraged.
``As the region matures _ politically, economically and socially _
we want to be part of [it's] growth, and for Latin America to be a
growing part of our business,'' he says.
 &HT;    Shell's long history and commitment to the region are unusual
for European companies, according to European trade experts, who
say that the signing of recent trade pacts _ especially NAFTA and
Mercosur _ have suddenly drawn the curiosity and interest of
European companies.
 &HT;    Some European firms see Latin America as a manufacturing site,
while others, especially Spain, view the region as a growing
consumer market for its products.
 &HT;    ``The Spanish market is small, so I think that it is more likely
that most companies will look to Latin America as a consumer market
as a first step,'' says Rafael Dominguez, a spokesman for the
Spanish government's Ministry of Economy and Trade. ``Manufacturing
would come later, once a market is established. ''
 &HT;    ``Right now, the general feeling is that the region's economies
have turned around and there's a strong feeling of confidence in
Spain concerning Latin America,'' he says. ``The Latin American
market has a solid future.''
 &HT;    The fallout from the Asian crisis, says Dominguez, is benefiting
Latin America in the eyes of Spanish investors.
 &HT;    One of the most aggressive Spanish companies to invest in Latin
America is Banco Santander. The bank was founded in 1857 as a small
provincial bank in the port of Santander, where most trade
originated with Latin America. It opened its first offices abroad
in the 1950s in Havana and Mexico City.
 &HT;    Until a few years ago, Spanish companies were not as prepared to
invest in the region as companies from other parts of Europe. That
is no longer the case, says Keith Grant, a spokesman for Santander.
``Spanish companies are more lean and efficient than before and are
strong in areas [such as] banking, energy and telecommunications,
where the possibility for growth is greatest in Latin America.''
 &HT;    Privatization. The ongoing trend toward privatization in Latin
America is especially appealing to Spanish companies, according to
Grant.
 &HT;    ``Spain is a small market, so the privatization going on in
these sectors coincides with those areas in which Spanish companies
are ready for expansion,'' he says. ``It's natural that Spanish
companies look to expand in a market that lacks the kind of
services and infrastructure these companies can provide.''
 &HT;    Wolfgang Handtke, who heads the North America and Latin America
division of the German Economics Ministry, hopes more German
companies will follow in Spain's footsteps to take advantage of the
current opportunities now available in Latin America.
 &HT;    ``We wish companies would take a greater interest in Latin
America than they have done in the past,'' says Handtke.
 &HT;    The privatization of telecommunications, energy, airports and
ports are prime opportunities for German companies with the ability
to sell plant machinery and provide know-how. But, because of lack
of experience, German companies are reluctant to invest in
state-owned companies now being privatized, according to Handtke.
 &HT;    Germany remains bullish on improving trade relationships with
the region. In the first quarter of this year, for example,
Germany's exports to Latin America reached $3.4 billion _ almost 20
percent higher than during the same period last year.
 &HT;    The trade relationship has changed over the years, says Handtke.
Latin American companies are now exporting products the Germans
used to export to Latin America, including electrical machinery and
precision tools.
 &HT;    Latin American interest in Germany remains very strong, says
Handtke, noting that more than 220 Brazilian firms recently
attended the annual German-Brazil trade fair in Munich.
 &HT;    ``The Brazilians were interested in contacts with German
companies that could supply sophisticated equipment to help improve
the efficiency of Brazilian manufacturing plants,'' he says.
 &HT;    Still, despite the increased trade, it is Germany's huge
multinational companies that remain the dominant players in the
region. Smaller companies are not so active because of the distance
and cost of transport, the credit risk and the language barrier.
 &HT;    Being closer to the market is precisely why Mercedes Benz AG
chose to move its Latin American headquarters to Miami. The trip to
visit dealers in the region was so long and tiring that company
officials often made only one trip per year, says Mercedes-Benz
Latina Inc. President Matthias Luehrs. Now, with flights available
to every major city in the region and with the distance trimmed
from two to five hours to most markets, company officials will be
visiting as much as six and seven times per year.
 &HT;    Success. There are perhaps few companies that have taken as much
advantage of the increasing trade between Europe and Latin America
as Netherlands-based TNT, the international package and mail
express company. It is enjoying enormous success in Latin America,
with sales having doubled since 1995, according to James
Hartenstein, a TNT vice president who is regional manager for Latin
America and the Caribbean.
 &HT;    With more and more flights to the region, the growing amount of
trade and the improvement of airports, Latin America and the
Caribbean are filled with opportunities to expand the reach of TNT,
says Hartenstein.
 &HT;    TNT has taken an approach to doing business in the region that
is growing more and more common. Instead of setting up its own
facilities in some of the smaller markets, it is teaming up with
local partners who already know the pitfalls and profits of the
market.
 &HT;    ``We have done phenomenally well in the region,'' he says.
 &HT;    More European companies would surely like to be able to say the
same.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
