<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-PRYOR-NYT &LR;      10-21 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PRYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUGHS MIX WITH PATHOS AT RICHARD PRYOR TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A laughing group of comedians and actors who have
been inspired in their work by Richard Pryor gathered on Tuesday
night at the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts to pay tribute
to him. Robin Williams brought all the loose ends together when he
recalled the Mark Twain observation that sorrow is a greater source
of humor than happiness.
</P>
<P>
   But the laughter far outweighed the sorrow. The performers' acts
served to remind the audience that Pryor, whose health problems
include multiple sclerosis, was a pioneer among comics in creating
characters who spoke in the true voice of the streets, obscenities
and all.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the words heard during the tribute were probably coming
from a Kennedy Center stage for the first time, and many cannot be
repeated here. But the Comedy Central cable channel taped the event
for showing on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The event was to honor Pryor as the first recipient of the
Kennedy Center's award for humor, the Mark Twain Prize. Pryor sat
in a box, but he was so weak that he could not rise to acknowledge
the loud applause from the audience in the center's concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see you up there,'' said one of the entertainers,
Morgan Freeman, who echoed another hallowed Twain remark by adding,
``Reports of your death were greatly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   At a party after the show, Pryor, 58, was unable to rise from
his wheelchair and was barely able to say, in a low moan, ``Thank
you,'' when James Johnson, the chairman of the Kennedy Center, gave
him the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Mark Twain, you made us laugh and also think,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said at the party that Pryor had been alert to the
tributes paid him. ``He lights up,'' Williams said. ``You can see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own appearance at the concert hall, Williams came
onstage, saying he was scalping tickets to the hugely popular van
Gogh show at the National Gallery of Art. ``I've got two tickets to
van Gogh,'' he said. ``Check it out. Two tickets. Two hundred bucks
and you'll see `The Potato Eaters.' '' He refused to take a check.
</P>
<P>
   When his turn came, Freeman recalled yet another Twain
observation, that he would rather see a taxidermist coming toward
him than a tax collector. ``The taxidermist isn't going to take
more than your skin,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian Damon Wayans said in his routine that he had drawn
inspiration from Pryor, to a point. ``I wanted to be just like
him,'' Wayans said, ``except for the drug habit, the failed
marriages and the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoopi Goldberg also cited Twain in her remarks, saying:
``Suppose you were an idiot, and suppose you were a member of
Congress. Oops, I repeat myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedian Chris Rock said that Pryor had come on the scene
``between the two great plagues, disco and AIDS.'' Another comic,
Richard Belzer, recalled one of his worst stage experiences, having
to follow Pryor's act at the Improv in Manhattan. ``It's like
having to paint a picture next to one by da Vinci,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian and social activist Dick Gregory was on hand, not
as a performer, but as a friend of Pryor's. ``It must have thrilled
him to be there and look down on it,'' Gregory said. ``It had to do
a lot for him, to see that, to feel that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      10-21 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LAWYER CLAIMS JUDICIARY COMMITTEE ADOPTING UNFAIR
PROCEDURES FOR TAKING TESTIMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee has adopted unfair
procedures for taking testimony during its upcoming impeachment
inquiry, President Clinton's lawyer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Gregory Craig, emerging from a 90-minute meeting with a
House panel investigator, said the Republican-run committee is
forcing Clinton to play ``a game with the rules being made by one
side.''
</P>
<P>
   A committee spokesman derided the attack as an effort to obscure
Clinton's allegedly impeachable attempts to cover up his
extramarital affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, the president's special counsel, accused the panel of
violating Clinton's rights to ``fundamental fairness'' and ``due
process'' by failing to state clearly the specific charges it will
level against the president regarding his efforts to keep secret
his escapades with Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Kenneth Starr, in a report to Congress last
month, alleged that Clinton committed 11 impeachable offenses. The
committee's chief Republican investigator, David Schippers,
expanded that list to 15, but panel Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
has reportedly winnowed that number to the three offenses of
perjury, obstruction of justice and witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said the committee has failed to disclose which of the
three lists it will pursue, making it extremely difficult for
Clinton's attorneys to present a strong defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has a right to know what the charges are,''
Craig said. ``We will have no fair chance to represent our client,
the president of the United States, adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig met with Schippers to express the president's concerns
regarding his ability to present witnesses and testimony during the
as yet unscheduled impeachment hearings. Unfortunately, Craig said,
the committee has shown no willingness to alter its controversial
procedures, which require panel approval before the president can
present witnesses and evidence on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the committee's planned procedure will permit
Clinton's attorneys to present evidence and testimony only after
they submit to the panel a written request containing ``precise
summaries'' of what items they plan to show or state ``precisely
and in detail'' what the witness will tell the panel. The
committee, after considering the lawyers' requests and summaries,
will decide if the proposed evidence and testimony is, again in the
words of the panel, ``necessary or desirable to a full and fair
record'' in the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial procedure places due process on its head,
Craig said. ``You (on the committee) are gathering facts and then
looking for an offense to charge him with,'' the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig also derided Republican accusations that the president is
trying to delay the process, saying his client wants hearings to
begin as early as Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a fast proceeding; we want to have a fair
proceeding; we want to have a just proceeding,'' Craig said. ``We
are still hopeful we can improve the process and make it fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But committee spokesman Paul McNulty defended the panel's
planned process and said Craig's effort is part of the president's
move to ensure the American people ``never get to the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's defenders have got to get away from these
partisan attacks,'' McNulty said. ``It won't work. We're going to
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee will proceed in a fair and efficient manner,
consulting with legal scholars on what constitutes the ``high
crimes and misdemeanors'' the Constitution states are grounds for
impeachment, McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said that the committee's controversial procedure
was modeled on the process the panel used in investigating whether
President Nixon committed impeachable offenses. The panel, then
chaired by Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., concluded in 1974 that the
president should be impeached. But Nixon resigned on Aug. 9, 1974,
before further action. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SCENE-1022-CO     10-21 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SCENE-1022-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDDLE EAST SUMMIT SHOWS HOW ART OF DIPLOMACY CAN GET A LITTLE
MESSY
 &HT;    With COX-MIDEAST-TALKS-1022.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As high stakes Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
slouched through their seventh contentious and inconclusive day in
an isolated compound in rural Maryland, a profound question
emerged: what ARE they doing out there?
</P>
<P>
   For seven days and nights, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and scores of their top aides have been
closeted at the Wye River conference center trying to strike a deal
that would advance a five-year-old peace process.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton has journeyed to the Eastern Shore
retreat five times since talks began last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he brought in ailing Jordanian King Hussein to try
to spirit the talks along.
</P>
<P>
   There have been formal dinners winding late into the evening,
relaxed luncheons and walks through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat even took an hour-long bicycle ride the other day to
clear his head and, presumably, contemplate the prospects for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all glamour.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart described the atmosphere at a
two-hour dinner Clinton hosted for the parties on Monday night as
''cordial.''
</P>
<P>
   He later confirmed, however, that Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon snubbed Arafat at the soiree, refusing to shake the former
commando leader's hand.
</P>
<P>
   And the hours these guys keep.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who's own late-night work habits are legend, met for
three hours Tuesday night with Netanyahu, wrapping up at 1:25 a.m.
Wednesday before boarding the presidential helicopter for the
flight back to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Albright stayed up and called Netanyahu right
after Clinton left to wish the Israeli leader a happy birthday,
before launching into a discussion centered on land and peace.
</P>
<P>
   What the talks are designed to do is to create an atmosphere
conducive to tough decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, after all, is being asked to turn over land to
Palestinians. They, in turn, are being asked to crack down on their
own people -- if they pose a threat to Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   There are arguments over maps, tiffs over history and squabbles
about the meaning of words.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes there is a dispute on what constitutes an
agreement,'' Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, told reporters at
Wye on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The issues, to be sure, are difficult, the compromises required
to get a deal are painful and the risks both sides are being asked
to take for peace are incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   When push comes to shove, doubts inevitably creep in.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat wonders whether Netanyahu is negotiating in good faith.
Netanyahu ask whether Arafat will, or can, make good on his
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Both deal with anxiety about their place in history. Would an
agreement under the terms available be judged by future generations
as a triumph or a sell-out?
</P>
<P>
   Threats and counter-threats are exchanged. One side or another
packs its bags and swears it's ready to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, the mediators, in this case Clinton and
his battery of Middle East diplomats, must work to assuage fears,
dispel doubts and, when all else fails, even point out that a
failure to reach an agreement can also carry risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The art is knowing what's conceivable, to start with, what's
possible, in the second instance, and what's doable in the third,
and knowing how to convey the results of that analysis in some
persuasive way, to get the parties to take the next step, or steps,
forward,'' said former U.S. diplomat Harry Barnes, director of the
conflict resolution program at the Carter Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''But,'' said Barnes, who's been closely involved in
negotiations over peace in Bosnia, Sudan and North Korea, ''there's
always the problem that sometimes neither side can face up to
making that agreement on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Resolving such an impasse often requires a delicate mix of
empathy and pressure, a mix that, by Wednesday, U.S. officials were
searching hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ''Secretary Albright has now been here for seven days and seven
nights. The president has spent an enormous amount of time here.
The vice president has been here. Other key players have been
here,'' said Rubin. ''We are trying to provide all the assistance,
the creativity, the persuasive powers that we can so that we can
advance the security and the prospect for peace for the peoples of
the region. But we can't make decisions for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SCENE-1022-CO     10-21 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SCENE-1022-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDDLE EAST SUMMIT SHOWS HOW ART OF DIPLOMACY CAN GET A LITTLE
MESSY
