<P>
   Netanyahu, after all, is being asked to turn over land to
Palestinians. They, in turn, are being asked to crack down on their
own people -- if they pose a threat to Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   There are arguments over maps, tiffs over history and squabbles
about the meaning of words.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes there is a dispute on what constitutes an
agreement,'' Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, told reporters at
Wye on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The issues, to be sure, are difficult, the compromises required
to get a deal are painful and the risks both sides are being asked
to take for peace are incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   When push comes to shove, doubts inevitably creep in.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat wonders whether Netanyahu is negotiating in good faith.
Netanyahu ask whether Arafat will, or can, make good on his
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Both deal with anxiety about their place in history. Would an
agreement under the terms available be judged by future generations
as a triumph or a sell-out?
</P>
<P>
   Threats and counter-threats are exchanged. One side or another
packs its bags and swears it's ready to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, the mediators, in this case Clinton and
his battery of Middle East diplomats, must work to assuage fears,
dispel doubts and, when all else fails, even point out that a
failure to reach an agreement can also carry risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The art is knowing what's conceivable, to start with, what's
possible, in the second instance, and what's doable in the third,
and knowing how to convey the results of that analysis in some
persuasive way, to get the parties to take the next step, or steps,
forward,'' said former U.S. diplomat Harry Barnes, director of the
conflict resolution program at the Carter Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''But,'' said Barnes, who's been closely involved in
negotiations over peace in Bosnia, Sudan and North Korea, ''there's
always the problem that sometimes neither side can face up to
making that agreement on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Resolving such an impasse often requires a delicate mix of
empathy and pressure, a mix that, by Wednesday, U.S. officials were
searching hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ''Secretary Albright has now been here for seven days and seven
nights. The president has spent an enormous amount of time here.
The vice president has been here. Other key players have been
here,'' said Rubin. ''We are trying to provide all the assistance,
the creativity, the persuasive powers that we can so that we can
advance the security and the prospect for peace for the peoples of
the region. But we can't make decisions for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
