<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPLIFE-NYT &LR;      10-21 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: LOSSES RECALLED IN `ELECTRO-SHOCK BLUES'; A MUSIC
FESTIVAL WITH LITTLE MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Fla.)  (lb) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ There are two things that listening to
``Electro-Shock Blues,'' the second album by the Eels, makes one
want to say when talking to E (formerly Mark Oliver Everett), the
band's singer, songwriter and guitarist. The first is ``I'm
sorry''; the second is ``Congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The first response is out of sympathy for the recent tragedies
that inspired the album: the suicide of his sister, the diagnosis
of terminal cancer for his mother, the deaths of several friends
and, years earlier, the heart attack of his father, whom E
discovered dead.
</P>
<P>
   The second response is out of admiration that E, on the verge of
becoming the only surviving member of his immediate family, managed
to create such a beautiful, profound and moving album out of these
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ```I'm sorry, congratulations, is the card I'd like to get from
people,'' E said in an interview on Tuesday. ``That's why I called
it `Electro-Shock Blues.' The electro-shock part is based on the
experiences my sister had in the mental hospital, and the blues
part is because _ though it's not blues music per se _ it's what
blues singers do. They take seemingly negative situations and turn
them into something positive by processing them and telling people
the story.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Congratulations' is also the right response,'' he continued,
``because when you have tragedy in your life, you have two choices.
You can get weighted down by it and give up, whether by killing
yourself or numbing yourself. Or you can let it make you stronger.
It's a thin line. I've accepted that I'm an inch away from going
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The harrowing result, ``Electro-Shock Blues'' (released this
week on Dreamworks), is a concept album in the best sense of the
word, a testament not to self-pity but to self-awareness. It is a
grim journey that begins in the mind of E's sister as she loses
consciousness for the last time on her bathroom floor.
</P>
<P>
   As the album moves through birthday parties and funerals,
hospitals and sanitariums, E spares no details about chemotherapy,
hospital food and coffins. But E arrives at a happy ending,
affirming, ``Maybe it's time to live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That part's really genuine,'' E said. ``I really have a lust
for life that keeps me going _ just barely. When you have all these
tragedies happen, you figure out what's really important. That's
why I made a record like this rather than what people would have
wanted me to make, which is something that didn't have the word
`cancer' in it so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles trio's previous album, ``Beautiful Freak'' from
1996, was a slightly more upbeat affair, spawning the hit
``Novocaine for the Soul.'' A much more revealing and unsettling
project, ``Electro-Shock Blues'' is filled with strings, brass,
turntable scratching, samples of past Eels songs, meditations on
everything from the meaning of life to the meanness of life and,
most disturbing, the process of a human being coming to terms with
the death of a loved one and arriving at important realizations too
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``The songs about my sister are the truest tributes I can do
because they're not some `Candle in the Wind' thing,'' E said.
``I'm doing songs from her point of view because I think I
understand. We grew up together. We have a lot of the same problems
in common. I wanted to see how difficult it was for her, and I
don't blame her. I think that's an amazing tribute.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eels are to perform at Mercury Lounge in New York on Sunday
and Monday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Deleting the Music
</P>
<P>
   In contemporary rock, the presence of political-activist
organizations amid the concession stands, notably on Lollapalooza
tours, has become a staple at festivals. More recently, the
political sideline of Lollapalooza has become the driving concept
of festivals like the Beastie Boys' Tibet Freedom Concert and Sarah
McLachlan's Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of California's Berkeley campus on Sunday, the
idea was taken to its extreme by the Spitfire Tour, which drew
1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other festivals, the Spitfire Tour was conceived by a
musician, Zack de la Rocha of Rage Against the Machine. The
difference is that Spitfire is a music festival with hardly any
music.
</P>
<P>
   The performers _ Amy Ray of the Indigo Girls, Michael Franti of
Spearhead, Exene Cervenka of X and the former Nirvana bassist Krist
Novoselic _ perform few or no songs. They mainly speak about
political issues that mean something to them _ race, sexuality,
environment, personal responsibility and political representation _
hoping to spark a social consciousness in their fans.
</P>
<P>
   Besides musicians, other speakers include the actor Woody
Harrelson, the MTV personality Kennedy, the medical-marijuana
advocate Todd McCormick and the environmental activist Julia
``Butterfly'' Hill, who has been living in an endangered redwood
tree for 10 months, a real-life equivalent of the protagonist in
the Italo Calvino novel ``The Baron in the Trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Lilith Fair, which tested its concept with smaller
concerts before planning a big tour, Spitfire is experimenting.
Berkeley was one of just four dates at colleges this month (the
final stops will be in Nashville, Tenn., on Monday and Gainesville,
Fla., on Tuesday) as a trial run for a 30-to-40-date tour in the
spring. Will students and fans show up for speeches without an
entertaining concert to help the medicine go down?
</P>
<P>
   So far, said Sarah Haynes, one of the tour's organizers, the
results have been encouraging. At the tour's first stop at Clemson
University in South Carolina, protesters accused tour organizers of
holding the event to proselytize for homosexuality, but 3,000
people showed up. Tickets range from free to $3. After the
addresses, the speakers have in-depth discussions with interested
members of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of creating the tour is to educate and entertain
at the same time, to make learning fun, and to speak about topics
that aren't necessarily brought up in college,'' Ms. Haynes said.
``We want to make an impact, to instigate action, and to show
people what they can do without fame and money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
