<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-POLL-HNS &LR;      10-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOV. BUSH'S POPULARITY ISN'T CARRYING OVER TO OTHER GOP
CANDIDATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A new statewide poll released Tuesday shows that
despite the likelihood that Gov. George W. Bush's would score a
major re-election victory, his popularity is not carrying over to
other Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is leading Democratic challenger Garry Mauro 66 percent to
21 percent in the latest Texas Poll, with 12 percent undecided or
refusing to answer.
</P>
<P>
   But 38 percent of those voters who say they are backing Bush
also say they will be casting ballots for Democratic attorney
general candidate Jim Mattox. Mattox is leading Republican John
Cornyn 47 percent to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in two other major contests, a quarter of the Bush voters
say they will cast ballots for Democrat John Sharp for lieutenant
governor and Democrat Paul Hobby for state comptroller. Sharp and
Hobby are running even with their Republican opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker noted that Bush was campaigning in
Dallas on Wednesday with Cornyn and Republican lieutenant governor
candidate Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is working hard to make sure good people like
Rick Perry and John Cornyn get elected,'' Tucker said. ``The final
determination of how successful this campaign is going to be will
be seen on Nov. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 764 likely voters was conducted Oct. 5-18 by the
Office of Survey Research at the University of Texas for Scripps
Howard and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.6 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox's political comeback has continued to be one of the
surprises of this election season.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox was attorney general from 1983 to 1990, but then lost
races for governor and U.S. Senate. Mattox was expected to fade
quickly this year against Cornyn, a former Supreme Court justice.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattox has remained strong since summer, and Cornyn has
gained only slightly in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're very pleased. They (the voters) know who I am
and they're glad to have me back,'' Mattox said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the race will tighten up but added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they understand the contrast between Cornyn and me.
He's for the big folks, and I'm for the little guys. I've had a
strong record to run on.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn spokeswoman Michele Kay said the Texas Poll was conducted
before Cornyn made his heaviest television advertising purchases.
She said Mattox's lead is based on people remembering his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week that we run TV, we do a lot better,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Bush's coattails will show up when voters understand
which candidates he is supporting in this election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and Election Day people will understand that the
person George Bush is supporting is John Cornyn and not Jim
Mattox,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for Texas lieutenant governor is heading into the
final weeks with Sharp tied with Perry. Each enjoyed 37 percent
support from likely voters, with Libertarian Anthony Garcia holding
5 percent support and 18 percent still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer Texas Poll, Perry led Sharp 36 percent to 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp spokesman Kelly Fero said the poll demonstrates that the
election is moving in Sharp's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a choice between John Sharp's independent leadership
and Rick Perry's partisan followership,'' Fero said. ``The
independents are clearly breaking for the candidate with his proven
record of independent leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry spokesman Ray Sullivan said Republican polls show their
candidates doing better than the Texas Poll does. But he said the
Texas Poll shows that Sharp's critical television ads about Perry
is not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Sharp will lose because he has no vision, no plans and no
interest in getting out of the gutter,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   The race for state comptroller also has narrowed since summer.
Hobby now is in a statistical dead heat with Republican Carole
Keeton Rylander at 36 percent to 33 percent. But in the summer
Texas Poll, Hobby trailed Rylander 30 percent to 35 percent.
Rylander's summer lead was outside of the poll's margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   In the contest for state land commissioner, Republican David
Dewhurst is leading over Democrat Richard Raymond 34 percent to 29
percent, with more than a third saying they were undecided or not
wanting to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   For state agriculture commissioner, Democrat Pete Patterson had
moved up statistically even with Republican Susan Combs. Combs led
34-31 percent in the summer poll. But now the race is Patterson, 35
percent, Combs, 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Tony Garza is leading over Democrat Joe Henderson 38
percent to 26 percent in the race for a seat on the Railroad
Commission. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
