<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      10-21 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: REFLECTED GLORY; SECOND SIGHT; IN TRANSIT;
STAR-STUDDED SIDEWALK; STARTING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: England, N.Y.) 
 (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthur Miller leads a list of playwrights named by more than 800
authors, actors, directors, theater professionals and arts
journalists in a poll by Britain's Royal National Theater to select
significant 20th-century plays. Among 188 playwrights nominated for
377 plays, Miller was followed by Harold Pinter and Samuel Beckett
in the balloting, which is aimed at guiding the National in
celebrating the century. The plays that received the most
nominations were Beckett's ``Waiting for Godot,'' Miller's ``Death
of a Salesman,'' Tennessee Williams' ``A Streetcar Named Desire,''
John Osborne's ``Look Back in Anger'' and Eugene O'Neill's ``Long
Day's Journey Into Night.'' Throughout next year, in a program
called NT2000, the National will stage 45-minute presentations from
100 plays to reflect the range of drama and illustrate the
development of English-language theater in the last 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Second Sight
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In conjunction with a retrospective devoted to Mary
Cassatt (1844-1926) at the Art Institute of Chicago, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art opened an exhibition from its extensive
collection of light-sensitive Cassatt drawings and prints
Wednesday. ``Mary Cassatt: Drawings and Prints in the Metropolitan
Museum of Art'' reflects the theme that became her signature,
mothers or nurses tending children. The exhibition runs through
Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   In Transit
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1935, under the patronage of the Museum of the
City of New York, the photographer Bernice Abbott (1898-1991) got
help from the Federal Arts Project to spend four years documenting
the transformation of the city from its 19th-century trappings.
Thursday through Jan. 19, in an exhibition organized by the Museum
of the City of New York and titled ``Changing New York,'' the
National Museum of the Women in Arts in Washington will display 126
of Abbott's 305 prints, many for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Star-studded Sidewalk
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hollywood has its Walk of Fame. Now Greenwich Village
is going to get a Playwrights' Sidewalk. Roughly 50 feet long, the
walk will be filled with bronze stars inscribed with the names of
43 playwrights, from Edward Albee to Paul Zindel, whose work has
been performed off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The Playwrights' Sidewalk will be unveiled and dedicated by
Lucille Lortel at 6:45 p.m. on Monday in a ceremony directed by the
Tony Award-winning choreographer Donald Saddler in front of the
Lucille Lortel Theater, 121 Christopher St. Ms. Lortel, a producer
and theater owner, has been a driving force in off-Broadway since
1957.
</P>
<P>
   Among the playwrights expected to attend are Carter Beane,
Horton Foote, William Hoffman, Larry Kramer, Marsha Norman, Murray
Schisgal, Paul Vogel, Michael Weller, Lanford Wilson and Zindel.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Out
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a student of piano and composition was
summoned on a few hours' notice to substitute for an ailing
conductor. No, this is not the Leonard Bernstein story. It's the
story of the event that won acclaim for Simone Young when, at age
24 in 1985, she made her debut at the Sydney Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young went on to become an assistant to James Conlon in
Cologne and Daniel Barenboim in Paris and Bayreuth, and to conduct
in many of the world's foremost opera houses. Next year she will
become music director of the Bergen Philharmonic in Norway, and in
2001, music and artistic director of the Australian Opera. Thursday
and Friday at 8 p.m., her story converges with Bernstein's when Ms.
Young will lead the New York Philharmonic in works by John
Harbison, Copland and Respighi in concerts that begin the
orchestra's seventh annual Conductor Debut Week and its third
annual American Classics Initiative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1853EDT &QL; 
