<SLUG> BC-GLENN-EXPERIMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN DISQUALIFIED FROM PORTIONS OF KEY MEDICAL EXPERIMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Glenn has been disqualified from portions of a key medical
experiment to be conducted aboard the shuttle Discovery next week,
but NASA characterized the impact of the move as minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 77, was quietly dropped in August when he failed to meet
the criteria established by the experiment's principal
investigator, Dr. Charles Czeisler of the Brigham and Women's
University in Boston. The decision was not disclosed until this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, which has flown earlier this year, is designed
to study why astronauts in space, like many elderly on Earth, do
not sleep well and to what degree it impairs their performance of
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was disqualified from the portion of the experiment that
would have required him to take small doses of melatonin, a hormone
produced in the brain that some researchers believe enhances sleep
and could serve as a countermeasure for weariness among astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   The use of melatonin constitutes about one-third of the sleep
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored and excited that Senator Glenn has volunteered for
(other portions) of the sleep experiment,'' said Czeisler. ``This
is a very special opportunity to study the sleep patterns of older
astronauts.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn still plans to don a sensor-laden sleep helmet and swallow
a cold capsule-sized thermometer/transmitter every two to three
days as part of the research project.
</P>
<P>
   The high tech sleep cap and other gear will furnish Czeisler's
team with data on Glenn's pulse, respiration, eye and muscle
movements as well as readings on the levels of melatonin his body
secretes naturally as he rests. The ingestible transmitter will
send core body temperature readings to an electronic recorder on
Glenn's waist.
</P>
<P>
   Czeisler said federal medical privacy requirements and his
institution's own medical ethics prevented him from disclosing the
reasons for Glenn's disqualification from portions of the
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dave Williams, the physician-astronaut who serves as the
director of NASA's life sciences research, would say only that
either the health of the astronaut or the experiment's criteria
would serve as a basis of disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to protect the non-coercive manner of
that decision-making,'' said Williams. He added the policy extended
to NASA's decision not to voluntarily disclose a decision made
months ago until it was uncovered by a New York Times medical
correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese physician-astronaut Chiaki Mukai will participate in
all phases of the sleep experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, meanwhile, remains a full participant in the mission's
second major medical experiment _ an assessment of how the body
metabolizes the proteins that contribute to muscle development in
weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   That experiment will require more than a dozen blood draws and
regular urine specimens. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
