<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-MICROSOFT     10-21 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT: NETSCAPE MEMO UNDERCUTS ANTITRUST CASE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON A Microsoft lawyer sought on Wednesday to rip apart
the government's antitrust case against the software giant by
accusing Netscape Communications Corp., its chief rival in the Web
browser wars, of once having secretly wooed Microsoft's hand in a
technological marriage of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   As the landmark trial entered its third day, Microsoft attorney
John Warden cited an e-mail message that Jim Clark, Netscape's
co-founder and current chairman, sent Microsoft executives seeking
``a financial investment.'' In return, Clark suggested Netscape
would allow Microsoft to extend its Windows monopoly to the then
fledgling Internet without any interference.
</P>
<P>
   In that message, dated Dec. 29, 1994, at 3:01 a.m., Clark wrote:
``We'd like to work with you. Working together could be in your
self-interest as well as ours. Depending on the interest level, you
might take an equity position in Netscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark went on to note that ``Microsoft is the de facto standard
'client' software company and we have never planned to compete with
you, so we have never considered a 'client' as being our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in my organization knows about this message,'' Clark
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice contends that Microsoft sought to use
its powerful Windows hold over the world's 100 million personal
computers to undermine Netscape as an effective competitor by
giving away its browser, which was beginning to become a lucrative
cash cow for Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, Warden sought to discredit James Barksdale,
the government's key witness, who had submitted 127 pages of
written direct testimony, alleging that in a June 1995 meeting
Microsoft tried to divide the Internet market between the two firms
in return for taking a stake in Netscape, which was still more than
a year away from selling its shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But Barksdale, who became Netscape's president and chief
executive officer a few weeks after Clark wrote his 1994 memo to
Microsoft, disavowed the document and minimized its weight.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale told the court the memo had played no role in the
crucial June 1995 meeting, a session which if the testimony is to
be believed government lawyers view as a violation of the 1890
Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Clark has described this (memo) as a moment of weakness,''
Barksdale said on the witness stand in his flat Mississippi twang.
``Netscape was burning through money and not making much cash and I
think Mr. Clark was looking to get Microsoft to make an
investment,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the trial, Netscape attorney Christine Varney
said Clark had written the memo in a moment of desperation. ``It
was the end of the year, they were out of money and at 3:00 a.m.,''
she said. ``Microsoft rebuffed him the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Also outside the courtroom, David Boies, the government's lead
counsel, called Warden's move ``another attempt by Microsoft to
change the subject because that is a subject that Microsoft doesn't
like.''
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand Barksdale, asked if he regarded Clark as
``a truthful man,'' replied: ``I regard him as a salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to touch that one, Mr. Barksdale,'' Warden said
to the witness, whose 5 million shares in Netscape are currently
worth about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
