<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NUCLEAR DUMP APPEARS TO BE IN DANGER OF REJECTION  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas environmental regulators take a final vote
Thursday on an embattled and politically charged proposal to build
a low-level radioactive waste disposal facility in the West Texas
desert community of Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the site less than 20 miles from Mexico would serve
as a permanent graveyard for contaminated items from nuclear power
plants in Texas, Vermont and Maine, as well as waste from hospitals
and universities in Houston and other Texas cities.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of the vote, the proposal appeared to be in
danger of rejection, due to the site's geological instability and
proximity to Mexico. And political implications hung over the issue
as well.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, political operatives have said that approval of
the Sierra Blanca site could hurt Gov. George W. Bush's
gubernatorial re-election bid and might harm his presidential
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   The three members of the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission are Bush appointees, and the governor is being pressured
by Mexican officials to lean on the panel to reject the Sierra
Blanca site.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said the decision is in the hands of appointed
regulators, who should make their decision based on science, not
political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   To dramatize their fervent opposition to the Sierra Blanca site,
anti-nuclear protesters from Mexico and the United States held a
vigil outside the commission offices on Wednesday, as well as at
the Texas Capitol and Governor's Mansion. One protester, dressed as
the grim reaper, carried around a black barrel marked radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   Similar events are expected Thursday when protesters,
politicians and reporters from Mexico fill the normally sedate
commission meeting room for the morning meeting. The panel will
only hear final legal arguments from the state, public counsel,
proponents and opponents. Commission members would not discuss the
case publicly before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Houston operators of an existing storage site 200
miles to the northeast are mobilizing to offer their dump as an
alternative. Operated by Waste Control Specialists of Houston, the
Andrews County site is ``the answer to all the drawbacks that the
Hudspeth County site has,'' said Lloyd Eisenrich, one of the
proponents. He said it could accommodate the radioactive waste in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities, hospitals and other groups supporting the Sierra
Blanca site on Wednesday were steadfast in their backing of the
proposal, which calls for digging deep trenches and lining them
with concrete to store huge concrete canisters of waste.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Selig, manager of Advocates for Responsible Disposal in
Texas, said his group of waste-producing entities, including
Houston Lighting &AMP; Power, remained hopeful the commission would
grant the license for Sierra Blanca. The commission will be
considering its own staff's conclusion, after four years of study,
that the site is safe, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They agreed that scientifically, geologically and
hydrologically, it will be a safe facility,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   But even with approval, ``there are still some significant
challenges that lie ahead,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have threatened to file suit if the license is
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's major political parties decided this week to prepare a
complaint against the United States to be filed in the World Court
in The Hague. The complaint would allege violations of the North
American Free Trade Agreement and an international pact on
environmental controls known as the La Paz agreement.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sierra Blanca site is rejected, the 17-year-old debate
over where to safely store hazardous waste would be tossed back to
the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
