<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COMMUNIST SWORN IN AS ITALY'S PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Massimo D'Alema was sworn in Wednesday as Italy's prime
minister and appointed an eclectic Cabinet that has something for
everyone: Communists, conservatives, and six women _ twice the
number who served under the departing prime minister, Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, 49, who will head Italy's 56th government since the end
of World War II, is the first former Communist selected to become
prime minister of Italy. If in the coming days Parliament approves
his Cabinet, he will be the only former Communist to head a major
Western European country.
</P>
<P>
   But his is not a solidly leftist government by any means. Among
other compromises, D'Alema was forced to name to such key
ministries as Defense and Communications supporters of Francesco
Cossiga, a former Christian Democrat who now leads a small
center-right party.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 17 parties in Parliament. Seven are
represented in the new government, eight if Prodi's Olive Tree
coalition is included.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema's effort to forge across-the-board allegiances to secure
a majority signals a classic Italian paradox: a government whose
stated goal is the introduction of a two-party system is itself a
mirror of the patchwork quilt of small, constantly mutating parties
that is the source of Italy's chronic political instability.
D'Alema, who tried and failed to pass reforms in Parliament this
year, has already pledged to make electoral reform a top priority.
Many Italians wonder how he will manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe that so heterogeneous a coalition
will be prepared to reform the electoral system,'' said Sergio
Romano, a former diplomat and political expert. ``Too many people
behind this government, like Cossiga, thrive on the very system of
proportionality that the reform is supposed to change.''
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible Cossiga, 70, is distrusted by both left and
right in Italy. Having survived the collapse of the old political
system dominated by the Christian Democrats, of which he was a
leader, he created the Union of Democrats for the Republic six
months ago and is now a key power broker.
</P>
<P>
   Cossiga navigates noisily from one political side to another.
While Cossiga was president of Italy in 1991, D'Alema's party
sought to have him impeached. Cossiga's new bond with D'Alema has
infuriated his former allies in the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall see how men who only yesterday insulted and attacked
each other can stay clasped together in a grab for power,'' said
Silvio Berlusconi, a media tycoon and former conservative prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, Italians are waiting to see how the Communists
and Cossiga's men will clash at Cabinet meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Some government priorities, like passing a 1999 budget that
allows Italy to meet the requirements for joining a single European
currency in January, seem widely shared and well within reach.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema reappointed the two top economic ministers who are
credited with helping Prodi trim Italy's bloated economy and
qualify for membership in the euro last spring: Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi will stay on as treasury and budget minister, and Vincenzo
Visco will continue as finance minister. Italy's respected foreign
minister, Lamberto Dini, was also reappointed.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema has already said he will present the same budget to
Parliament that caused Prodi's center-left government to collapse
two weeks ago. Fausto Bertinotti, general secretary of the Marxist
Communist Refounding party, withdrew his support from Prodi over
budget disputes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Bertinotti's intransigence quickly split his own party. A
more moderate faction led by Armando Cossutta, unwilling to be
blamed for sabotaging the first center-left government in 50 years,
split off, forming yet another small leftist party, the Italian
Communists' Party. A week ago, Cossutta vowed that he could never
join forces with Cossiga. He relented, and his party was rewarded
with the Justice Ministry and the Ministry of Regional Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   There are new faces, like Giovanna Melandri, 36, a member of
D'Alema's Democratic Party of the Left, who was named minister of
culture and sports, and Enrico Letta, 32, a member of the Popular
Party, who will take over European Affairs and is the youngest
member of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   But D'Alema also brought back Giuliano Amato, 60, a former prime
minister and one of the few Socialist leaders who escaped unscathed
from the scandals that toppled former Prime Minister Bettino Craxi,
who is now living in exile in Tunisia. Amato was awarded a newly
revived post, minister of institutional reform, which includes
drafting new electoral laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have found a balance between the need for political
representation that exists in a coalition government and personal
competence and quality,'' D'Alema said of his Cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
