<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-WRAPUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES FINAL SPENDING BILL, BRINGS 105TH CONGRESS TO AN
END 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved a final spending bill for
fiscal 1998 Wednesday, bringing the 105th Congress to an end and
sending members home to face the voters.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of 65-29 brought the bill worth nearly $600 billion to
President Clinton, who signed it before a fifth stopgap funding
measure was set to expire at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the measure that included eight of the 13
major appropriations bills Tuesday night on a 333-95 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Although members on both sides of the aisle squawked about the
massive size of the bill, in the end it proved too much for most of
them to resist because of the political pork that could help in
their re-election bids.
</P>
<P>
   From roadways to historic preservation projects, nearly every
incumbent, regardless of party, was able to claim something for the
folks back home or the special interests who help finance
campaigns. The spending ranged from the vital to the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   The vital included a $1.9 billion increase in funding for the
National Institutes of Health. A lot of that money will end up
going to Houston medical facilities, where research on cancer and
other diseases will be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The absurd included a provision added at the last minute by
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that would lengthen the
duck-hunting season in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The special interest items in the budget angered a lot of new
members, especially conservative Republicans who said they ran for
Congress hoping to change the traditional way of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from they call that pig-picking. Forty pounds of
pork and everybody trying to pull off a piece,'' is the way Rep.
Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., described the final bill which weighed in
at nearly 45 pounds and stacked up at almost 2 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   A number of senators opposed the measure because it was hammered
together at the last minute by Clinton, Lott and House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., for example, said the
process resembled a ``bastard parliamentary system'' with the final
decisions being made ``in a closed room by three or four people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most legislators were cut out of the last-minute negotiations,
which began after the House and Senate passed only two of the 13
major appropriations bills needed to fund government by the Oct. 1
start of the new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Some members, including Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas,
complained about the $20 billion in so-called emergency spending
for defense projects, the peacekeeping mission in Bosnia and aid to
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was certainly disappointed in both the process and the
product,'' said Gramm spokesman Larry Neal, noting the oddity of
placing the Bosnia peacekeeping mission, which Congress has funded
for the last three years, in the category of emergency spending.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kevin Brady, R-The Woodlands, Texas, joined Gramm and four
other Texas House members in voting against the bill because he
said it would ``consume one-third of the expected (budget)
surplus'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money should have gone first to preserving Social Security
and, with what's left over, providing tax relief to help families
make ends meet,'' Brady added.
</P>
<P>
   The measure includes nearly $1.2 billion in additional education
money for hiring new public school teachers, $18 billion for the
International Monetary Fund, $10 billion for building a missile
defense system, nearly $6 billion in drought and flood relief for
farmers. The bill covers just about every government department.
</P>
<P>
   Being one of the largest states, Texas won big in the budget
negotiations. For example, the state will reap about $97.2 million
this fiscal year for hiring new teachers and reducing class sizes.
Only California and New York will receive more.
</P>
<P>
   A big chunk of the $7.2 billion earmarked for border patrol,
immigration and drug enforcement efforts will also end up in Texas
and the other Mexico border states.
</P>
<P>
   Texas youth will benefit from the $871 million summer jobs
program included in the budget. The money will help employ about
41,000 of the state's most disadvantaged young people next summer,
including about 5,000 from the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   The failure pass spending bills by by Oct. 1 was due primarily
to a loose work schedule and disagreements among conservative and
moderate GOP members over legislative priorities and policies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's threatened vetoes of some bills and Democratic
delaying tactics complicated matters even more. But some GOP
members said it was the pressure from the Republican conservative
and Christian right elements that helped tie Congress up by knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent time fighting battles we had already lost on
abortion, school prayer and other conservative issues ... (that)
could have been spent on things we had a chance (of passing),''
said one disgruntled GOP member.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that many elements of the so-called ``family values
agenda'' went down to defeat was not lost on leaders of the
religious right.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after the Senate vote, Christian
broadcaster Dr. James Dobson, blasted the Republican leadership for
failing to deliver on the promises they made conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson chastised Lott by name for having what he called a
``stunning lack of commitment to families.'' He also criticized
Gingrich for not working hard enough to eliminate funding for
Planned Parenthood and other family-planning programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there just aren't enough true conservatives in
Washington,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
