<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL DISTRESS TAKES TOLL ON CITIGROUP RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PETER TRUELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Citigroup Inc., the world's largest financial
services company, Wednesday reported a 65 percent drop in
third-quarter earnings, reflecting the impact of trading losses in
volatile global markets this summer that offset strength in its
domestic consumer businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The results of $729 million, or 30 cents a diluted share, for
the three months ended Sept. 30 was close to analysts' expectations
of 29 cents a share. Comparable earnings from the year earlier were
$2.1 billion, or 96 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 8, Citigroup estimated that it would report earnings of
$700 million for the quarter after it suffered hundreds of millions
of dollars of trading losses from the slump in financial markets,
particularly in Russia and developing counties.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup was created by the merger of Citicorp and Travelers
Inc., announced in April this year and completed at the end of last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real message here is the global consumer business seems to
be doing quite well,'' even as the firm ``absorbs the body blows on
the capital markets side of the business,'' said Judah Kraushaar, a
banking analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like putting all this Russia, emerging markets aside,
the underlying businesses are either OK or have yet to
deteriorate,'' said John Keefe, president of Keefe Worldwide, a
financial services consulting firm in New York. ``Behind some of
these dramatic losses _ these events of biblical proportions _ are
some strong businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Citigroup tried to take the third-quarter
earnings slump in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're disappointed with the results,'' Sanford
Weill, co-chairman and co-chief executive of Citigroup, said in an
interview Wednesday. But, Weill added, he and his colleagues are
encouraged by the continuing strong performance in their consumer
businesses and by the helpful steps taken by governments in recent
weeks to stabilize international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Weill cited congressional agreement to provide further funding
to the International Monetary Fund, the Federal Reserve's second
interest rate cut, which he said showed clear understanding of the
liquidity problems in markets, and Japan's plan to inject more than
$500 billion to help to revive its troubled banking system.
</P>
<P>
   But Weill cautioned that the fourth quarter was not proving to
be easy. ``I think we're still going to have lingering problems in
the fourth quarter, but they won't be of the same kind of degree as
the third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the turmoil has necessarily been bad for the company,
Weill added, saying that it had caused some depositors to turn to
larger institutions, like Citibank, the company's bank subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Weill also said that the combined company was well positioned to
take advantage of more difficult markets. The combined firm's
equity strength, he said, would ``prove very useful'' as Citigroup
came across opportunities to expand its own businesses or acquire
other firms in markets that have been hard hit by the recent
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with analysts Wednesday, Weill and his co-chairman
and co-chief executive, John Reed, set out how they were cutting
costs to reposition the firm for the changes in financial markets,
according to some who attended.
</P>
<P>
   In reply to analysts' questions, the two financial leaders
played up the potential for revenue growth and the benefits from
cross-marketing insurance, banking and brokerage products at the
newly combined firm.
</P>
<P>
   The two men also told analysts that results for 1999 should look
good compared with those for 1997, according to Joan Solotar, a
banking analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, who said that the
leaders had projected a 15 percent average growth rate for the next
five years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
