<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9808 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNABOMBER-TAXES-HNS &LR;      10-21 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNABOMBER-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHER BLOCKS UNABOMBER'S BROTHER FROM DISTRIBUTING CASH TO VICTIMS
TAX FREE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, Wednesday blocked an
effort on Capitol Hill to enable the brother of Unabomber Theodore
Kaczynski to distribute a cash reward to his brother's victims
without Uncle Sam taking a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate unanimously approved a measure Wednesday that would
have granted a special exemption to allow David Kaczynski to hand
over $750,000 in reward money tax free.
</P>
<P>
   But Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee and
the most powerful tax writer in the House, refused to allow a
measure to go to the floor for a vote without a hearing. That
effectively killed the proposal for this year.
</P>
<P>
   David Kaczynski, who had alerted authorities after realizing his
reclusive, older brother was responsible for a 17-year-long mail
bombing spree that left three dead and another 29 injured, had
originally been awarded $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   David Kaczynski used $250,000 of the award to pay his brother's
lawyer, who had saved the Unabomber from a possible death sentence
by negotiating a plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped to turn over the rest of the reward to the victims and
their families. But that plan didn't take the tax laws into
account, which Congressional staffers estimate would have required
David Kaczynski to pay about $335,000 to the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   David Kaczynski traveled to Capitol Hill to lobby lawmakers for
an exemption and picked up the support of New York Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Finance
Committee, the Senate's tax-writing body. Kaczynski could not be
reached for immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats raised the issue with Archer's office on Oct. 2, when
lawmakers were battling over a Republican-backed tax-cut plan.
Archer refused to allow Kaczynski's request to be added to the tax
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Archer supports this proposal, at least in principle, but
he's unwilling to use his authority as chairman to give a special
exemption to this particular provision when everyone else's special
case doesn't get the same treatment,'' said Sean Rushton, Archer's
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Archer was ``very clear in telling the tax staff `We can't
insert any special provisions in this or this whole thing is going
to turn into a free-for-all for all,' '' Rushton said.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, however, Archer did agree to insert a
provision to give a tax break for students working at Texas' state
universities. That provision would enable Texas, Pennsylvania and
New Jersey to exempt full-time students who work at their
state-supported universities from paying Social Security taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Rushton said that provision was a different case, since it was
not granting anyone special privileges but merely granting students
in these three states an opportunity to take advantage of a tax
break enjoyed by students in all other states.
</P>
<P>
   Archer has agreed to have the Ways and Means Committee take up
the matter when lawmakers return to Washington for the new Congress
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rushton noted, however, that commitment did not mean Archer _
who is concerned about the precedent the issue would set _ would
necessarily vote for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Archer has not always been so loathe to provide special tax
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he offered to intervene himself when IRS
officials indicated they might try to assess sports fans gift taxes
if they turned over baseball slugger Mark McGuire's record-breaking
home run baseballs to the player rather than keep the highly prized
balls themselves. Rushton said Archer would have held a hearing on
that issue as well, if the IRS had not backed down.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, Archer was the target of Democratic
criticism when he refused during negotiations on an IRS overhaul
bill to correct what administration officials described as a
technical error discovered in last year's tax bill. The result was
a $200,000 tax break to people inheriting estates worth $17.2
million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the philosophical debate, the Kaczynski provision also
had become embroiled in a turf battle between the Ways and Means
Committee and the House Appropriations staff over who had
jurisdiction on such an issue. The tax writers had suggested
Congress allow David Kaczynski to pay the tax and then make a
special authorization to the victims and their families of an equal
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the floor of the House Tuesday, Rep. David Obey,
D-Wis., argued Ways and Means officials had blocked the measure
``because of dumb, Hill considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a more disgraceful action on the part of
anyone in this Congress than that action denying those funds to the
victims of the Unabomber,'' Obey said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Maffei, press secretary for Democrats on the Ways and Means
Committee, said, ``It's so very frustrating for us that we can't do
this for this guy, who is simply trying to help the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw this as addressing a situation that the Internal
Revenue Code could not have possibly anticipated,'' Maffei said.
``And that's, frankly, why actual people come to Congress and meet
and discuss these issues.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 1932EDT &QL; 
