<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-GYM-MOCEANU     10-21 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GYM-MOCEANU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic gymnast suing her parents
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu's parents knew from the day she was born that
she would become a gymnast. That was the promise the Romanian
immigrants made to each other before the birth of their first
child.
</P>
<P>
   Now Moceanu, who turned 17 on Sept. 30, has sued for
independence from her parents, Dumitru and Camelia. She claims they
have squandered the fortune she has earned since becoming a
professional at age 10 and, in the process of making her a
champion, robbed her of her childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, a member of the United States' ``Magnificent Seven''
gold-medal winning team at the '96 Olympic Games in Atlanta, told
the Houston Chronicle her relationship with her parents ``always
had to be about the gym. I would think, `Don't you guys know
anything besides gymnastics? Can't we go out for ice cream? Can't
you be my mom and dad instead of me being your business?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu also said her father has hit her ``a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   The gymnast ran away from home on Sunday and has been staying
with friends ``like a fugitive'' so her parents can't find her.
After her lawsuit was filed Monday in state district court in
Houston, a judge signed a temporary restraining order saying the
parents must stay away from the gymnast until a Nov. 11 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Her father held a press conference Wednesday to plead for his
daughter's return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love her very much,'' Dumitru Moceanu said. ``And I hope
she change her mind and come home, start training again. She's just
a child, she's just a minor. I don't believe this comes from her.
It comes from other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu told the Houston newspaper that ``things have been
getting rough for a while ... . We've been trying to keep things
hidden.'' But the last straw came Saturday, when her father
threatened to fire her coach, Luminita Miscenco, and have her
deported to Romania. Miscenco, 26, arrived in January, and Moceanu
credits her with revitalizing her career and her interest in the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   When she won the Goodwill Games' all-around title in July,
Moceanu said, ``I could have never done it without (Miscenco).
She's so close to me, she's like my sister, like my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The gymnast said Miscenco helped her with her ``outlook in
life,'' which apparently included advising her to look into where
her money was going.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu spent $4 million building a gym in Houston that
opened June 1997 and bills itself as ``the largest gymnastics
facility in the United States,'' with 70,000 square feet and room
for 10,000 spectators. Other ventures under Moceanu Gymnastics Inc.
include a clothing outlet that specializes in leotards.
</P>
<P>
   Other gym owners in the Houston area say the facility is too
big. Said James Holmes, who runs Acrofit Gymnastics in Bela
Karolyi's old gym, ``Whoever built that gym parked it between the
two most successful recreational gyms in the city. The parking
lot's empty half the time.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, no one answered calls at the gym, but the chirpy
voice on the answering machine said, ``Hi. This is Dominique. You
have reached Moceanu's Gymnastics.'' Then she lists the hours it is
supposed to be open.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, born in 1981 in Hollywood, has spent countless hours in
the gym since age 3, when her father first called Karolyi, the
legendary coach who tutored Mary Lou Retton and Nadia Comaneci, and
asked to enroll his daughter in his program. Karolyi told him to
wait a few years.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 10, Moceanu drove his daughter to Houston where
she, Camelia and sister Christina have remained. Dumitru, who
always regretted giving up his own gymnastics career as a
teen-ager, continued working at a used-car lot in Florida before
joining the family in Houston several years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a childhood,'' said Moceanu, who was the youngest
member of the 1996 gymnastics team at age 14 and hopes to compete
in the 2000 Games in Sydney. ``When I went to compete when I was
young, I always was in fear because I would get yelled at by my
father, and I would say to myself, 'I'm 13 years old; come on,' ``
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of talking to me, they're always yelling with me,
fighting with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu and her lawyer, Roy W. Moore, did not reveal how much
money she has made or how much they think is gone. Her lawsuit said
a trust that had been established for her is all but empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kill myself training and going to school, and what is he
doing with my money?'' she asked. ``They haven't been working since
1996. Where does their income come from? Me.''
</P>
<P>
   To receive adult status, Moore said, Moceanu must prove that she
is living away from her parents and can support herself. Once she
has the status, Moore said, Moceanu will be able to demand through
legal channels to see an accounting of her money, and would be
entitled to proceeds from the businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ziert, publisher of International Gymnastics magazine who
works closely with Olympians Bart Conner and Nadia Comaneci, said
the gymnastics community knew there was friction in the Moceanu
household.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underlying the whole thing is the kid has had some problems,''
Ziert said. ``She has always wanted to be a star, and she learned
that gymanstics was her way to be a star. Then she decided she
wanted to be a star without having the gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   He called Moceanu ``a cash cow'' for the family. As she wavered
in her interest in gymnastics, she moved from gym to gym, including
Kurt Thomas's gym in Plano, Texas, a gym in Boston and finally her
family's facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spark wasn't there,'' Moceanu said last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tours dried up, and so did endorsement money for Moceanu, still
the most popular gymnast in the U.S. Her website hasn't been
updated in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all those Mag 7 girls, {from the Olympic team). the money
went away real fast,'' Ziert said. ``If you're earning a lot of
money and it continues, you don't look over your shoulder so much.
Because there seems to be a lot there. When it goes away ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle is Moceanu's mother, of whom Ziert says,
``Thereis no sweeter woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The really tragic thing is she's in a terrible position,'' he
said. ``She loves her kid so much, but she's also in a marriage. I
felt really bad that her mom is grouped in with that; she's not a
stage mother at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sybil Maiers of Atlanta, whose daughter Tanya trained with
Moceanu in Houston, agreed. She was friendly with Camelia Moceanu
and expressed shock at the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how surprising it is to hear this,'' Maiers
said. ``The mom was always particularly warm and soft. Although the
father wasn't my favorite person _ I thought he was a bit cold _ I
never saw any unkindness toward his child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't have been smiling all the time if she was so
unhappy, she was such a cute bubbly thing. Things must have changed
after we left.''
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't think Dumitru ``made a lot of smart
decisions,'' Ziert pointed out that ``all of her money is visible.
It isn't like he went to Las Vegas and gambled it away.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the parents do work, by running the club, and that
Dominique has enjoyed some of the fruits of her success by driving
a Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu started taking more of an interest in her finances last
year, but got no answers from her parents. The senior at the
private Northland Christian School also wants independence in other
areas of her life. She says she has to hide from her father when
she calls friends and has had only one date, which was chaperoned.
</P>
<P>
   She stressed she is doing this on her own, partly to protect her
9-year-old sister, also a gymnast, from the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my parents,'' Moceanu said. ``I hope that after all
this is over, we'll be closer than ever. That would be my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who coached Moceanu when she was a junior, remembered
her good nature and her smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants her money; that's going to be her future,'' he said.
``More than anything, she wants Dominique back, the fun, to be
happy with no pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
