<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9818 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SEASON-SFCHRON &LR;      10-21 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, SO BAD: NETWORKS BEGIN HACKING AWAY TO SALVAGE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two shows are axed. Several have been sent off to the
regenerative waters of ``Hiatus.'' A few are hits, or close enough
to pass. We've identified this year's good show that hardly anyone
is watching.
</P>
<P>
   So it must be official. We have a television season in progress,
even if the network bunting grows more threadbare by the year.
</P>
<P>
   The public appears to have corroborated the critical impression
of the 1998-99 season. Which is to say, the airwaves are skunked up
to the max, so turn off the set and break out the Parcheesi board.
Or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   No one can gaze clearly at the programming array until the World
Series ends and postseason baseball is no longer affecting the
regular-series matchups.
</P>
<P>
   But perfect vision wasn't required to gauge as failures Fox's
``Costello'' and CBS' ``The Brian Benben Show.'' They're gone. And
``Costello'' won the parting gift of a case of Turtle Wax, as the
season's first canceled show.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shows that seem destined to join them, soon:
``Conrad Bloom,'' ``Encore! Encore!'' _ on second thought, skip the
curtain call _ ``Living in Captivity'' (pulled from the air but not
yet pronounced dead), ``Holding the Baby'' (also in limbo), ``The
Army Show,'' ``To Have and to Hold'' (just can't get a grip),
``Wind on Water.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything labeled UPN can be added to the list. ``Mercy Point''
has already been sent packing to Hiatus, which is believed to be in
the Cape Cod area. It's unlikely to return. Last season, UPN shows
were posting ratings, albeit slim, between 1 and 2. This season,
closer to a bare 1.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Fantasy Island'' and ``Cupid'' are suffocating on
Saturday night. You'd need a metal detector to find ``Vengeance
Unlimited'' on Thursday. NBC's ``Trinity'' needs time, like maybe
20 years, to build an audience.
</P>
<P>
   And, alas, a couple of million households leave CBS when ``Buddy
Faro'' begins on Friday nights. Half of them come back for ``Nash
Bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes no sense to me; ``Buddy Faro,'' with Dennis Farina,
isn't castor oil. It's breezy entertainment. Why it is so deeply
offensive to ``Candid Camera'' viewers, who are bailing out en
masse after their show ends, is a mystery. Geez, you'd think it was
``Nothing Sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN is gagging on its paltry ratings, but Fox is hemorrhaging.
October baseball is the main thing propping up the network; the
numbers for series programming are off dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Fox expects improvement when ``The X-Files'' begins its season
next month. But the network is slapping bandages on its wounds for
the November sweeps. That means more of its comically shocking
specials, led by ``When Good Pets Go Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd point at Fox and giggle some more, but from NBC comes news
that a version of Shakespeare's ``The Tempest'' has been yanked
from the sweeps and repositioned for mid-December. That's after
``Crime and Punishment'' tanked. And in November, NBC's prime-time
programming will include a special called ``Exposed: Pro
Wrestling's Greatest Secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Good Wrestlers Go Bad'' sounds like a natural for
February.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is being heavily criticized for its supremely bad decision
to break up its perfectly fine Sunday lineup, moving ``King of the
Hill'' to Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Fox might take some convincing, though. This week, a Fox press
release raved about how ``King of the Hill'' has goosed the
network's Tuesday ratings compared with a year ago. But ``King of
the Hill'' is averaging a 4.3 rating in the key 18-to-49-year-old
demographic bracket, which is barely half its 18-to-49 average last
season on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' is Fox's only success among new shows. The
Sunday comedy has been green-lighted for the entire season, but its
ratings are only moderately encouraging and it isn't meeting its
creative potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity,'' on the WB, is the tidy little hit it was expected
to be. But in ratings it's being eclipsed on its own network by
Shannen Doherty's new series, ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   All of TV is in a funk, it seems, except the WB. At least it has
``The Army Show'' and the static ``Hyperion Bay'' to enforce its
humility.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that ``Maggie Winters'' is improving on its
``Nanny'' lead-in? That ``Two of a Kind'' will keep the Olsen twins
in clover in their dotage? That ``The Hughleys,'' bolstered by
``Home Improvement,'' is succeeding on ABC? That ``L.A. Doctors''
is hanging in with little CBS support on Mondays? That somehow
``The King of Queens'' is doing fine?
</P>
<P>
   It matters to the respective networks, but that's all. The more
significant success in the early season is ``Will &AMP; Grace'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   First, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is a polished little comedy, so its
apparent health is good to see purely on an aesthetic basis.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Will &AMP; Grace'' also tests whether a gay lead, Eric
McCormack as Will, will poison the ratings. What, exactly, had
``Ellen'' wrought?
</P>
<P>
   Lots of good, it appears, and perhaps no lasting damage.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' are being excruciatingly
cautious, though. What if Will ever discovers that he has a sex
organ? He does have a sex organ, doesn't he?
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, that sounds like a ``Dateline NBC'' story
to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
