<HEADLINE>
SAY IT AGAIN, SAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A panel of critics gathered on behalf of the Guinness Book of
Film created a top 10 list of the most memorable lines in movies,
as reported by the BBC and gleaned by  &UR; Jerry Matters &LR; . The winners:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Bond. James Bond,'' said by  &UR; Sean Connery &LR;  in ``Dr. No.''
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Of all the gin joints in all the towns in all the world,
she walks into mine,'' said by  &UR; Humphrey Bogart &LR;  in ``Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   3. ``It's not the men in your life that counts, it's the life in
your men,'' said by  &UR; Mae West  &LR; in ``I'm No Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   4. ``I'll be back,'' said by  &UR; Arnold Schwarzenegger &LR;  in ``The
Terminator.''
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Would you be shocked if I changed into something more
comfortable?'' asked by  &UR; Jean Harlow  &LR; in ``Hell's Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Life is like a box of chocolates; you never know what
you're gonna get,'' said by  &UR; Tom Hanks &LR;  in ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   7. ``I could dance with you until the cows come home. On second
thought, I'd rather dance with the cows until you come home,'' said
by  &UR; Groucho Marx &LR;  in ``Duck Soup.''
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Frankly, my dear, I don't give a damn,'' said by  &UR; Clark &LR; 
 &UR; Gable &LR;  in ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   9. ``You talkin' to me?'' asked by  &UR; Robert De Niro &LR;  in ``Taxi
Driver.''
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Gimme a whiskey with ginger ale on the side _ and don't be
stingy, baby,'' said by  &UR; Greta Garbo &LR;  in ``Anna Christie.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DUKE'S GIFT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Soon after she entered Congress, former Rep.  &UR; Pat Schroeder &LR;  was
visited by  &UR; John Wayne &LR; , who ``wanted to warn me about Commies,''
she writes in ``24 Years of House Work ... and the Place Is Still a
Mess'' (Andrews McMeel; $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sworn to uphold the Constitution,'' she says she told
him. ``Do you think I'm the weak link here?''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne tried to present her with a silver lighter engraved ``F_
(written out) communism _ John Wayne,'' but ``I was appalled and
declined the gift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband was furious, imagining its memorabilia value at a
flea market,'' she writes. ``He reminds me of this incident about
once a week.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The reason manhole covers are round, writes  &UR; Scott Madison &LR; ,
is ``because the manholes are round.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Carly Simon &LR;  sang ``Happy Birthday'' to Sinn Fein leader
 &UR; Gerry Adams &LR;  _ who was 50 _ at the nightclub Webster Hall in New
York on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jay Leno &LR;  and his wife,  &UR; Mavis &LR; , have donated $100,000 to the
Feminist Majority Foundation for a campaign against the ruling
Taliban in Afghanistan. Leno and his wife are holding news
conferences about the regime _ which denies women education and
bans them from working _ in New York and Los Angeles this week.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR;  received a foil-wrapped packet covered with
smiley faces and reading, ``Great Days Begin With Great Mail.''
Inside were coupons for an assortment of businesses, asking and
recommending: ``What would you choose ... cremation? mausoleum
entombment? ground burial?''; ``You Can Sell Your Life Insurance
Policy for CASH Now, while you are alive (and) in need of money'';
``How Much Does a Scooter or a Power Wheelchair Cost?''; ``Think
You'll Never Need Long-Term Care?''; ``Why you can't count on
Medicare or Medigap''; ``Pre-Planning for Those You Love; A Simple
Cremation''; and Justice Viatical Group, in which ``investors
receive death benefit proceeds directly from insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``High-level intervention'' was required, said the Washington
Post, to admit  &UR; Sarah Netanyahu &LR; 's hairdresser to the grounds of
the Middle East peace summit in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday's full-page ad in California newspapers, urging women
to vote, was sponsored by Women Count, which is sponsored by a
nonpartisan group of Bay Area women that includes  &UR; Bill &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR;  stalwart  &UR; Susie Tompkins Buell &LR; . The ad was placed in
response to pollsters predicting apathy from female voters _ 52
percent of the electorate _ in next month's election.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken has not taken one weekend off in the four years he has
worked on this case.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alice Starr, wife of special prosecutor Kenneth Starr, telling
Mirabella magazine that the country is getting its $40 million
worth in her man.
</P>
