 BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR  
   
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Oct. 22. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
KPTY-RADIO (Undated) - A Phoenix area radio station, struggling in
the ratings, turns to drugs and sex as a way of building an
audience. By MICHAEL CLANCY. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TRIPLE5-MALL (Undated) - The developer behind the two largest and
most flamboyant malls in the world is making a move into Arizona.
Triple Five Corp., a Canadian conglomerate that built the Mall of
America in Minnesota and the West Edmonton Mall in Canada, is
quietly moving forward with a lush $200 million urban village in
Mesa, Ariz.,
</P>
<P>
   that would include high-end botiques, outdoor cafes and
galleries topped by condominiums. The company is also eyeing sites
in Gilbert and Peoria for future projects, and plans to set up a
satellite office in the Phoenix area. By LISA GONDERRINGER. Story
will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CANON (Undated) - In the imbecilic culture wars that currently
ravage the intellectual countryside, the lines are drawn between
ignorant armies. On one side, you find right-wing reactionary
fossils fighting to maintain the canon of mainly European classics.
On the other side, there is a cadre of victimization that wants to
eliminate anything written by dead white males. A pox on both their
houses. With
</P>
<P>
   CANON-SIDE. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in the ``E'' and
``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CANON-SIDE (Undated) - Here's a list of those things we ``should
have read.'' This is not a list of the ``best,'' but of the most
influential, the things without which you cannot understand what
followed. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in the ``E`` and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WELLES-MOVIES (Undated) - He's a man who had it all. Admiration.
Respect. Looks. Professional success. And downfall.
</P>
<P>
   So, what happened? What quirk of personality led him down from
such heights? Don't worry. This story is not about President
Clinton. It's about the director of what's long been considered the
finest movie ever made, Orson Welles. By DON RENFROE. Story moved
in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MRSCASTANEDA (Undated) - They were improbable lovers. For decades,
he denied she even existed. She was a tall Southern belle with
Cleopatra bangs and a seductive patter; he, short and serious,
recently immigrated from Peru in hopes of becoming a successful
artist in America. Yet, their paths crossed in Los Angeles during
the mid-'50s, and in 1960 Margaret Evelyn Runyan married Carlos
Castaneda, the man who would become the most famous literary
sorcerer in the world. By THOMAS ROPP. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
