<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, Oct. 22 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   TOO-MUCH-SODA (Los Angeles) _ Super size. Big Gulp. These are
the sales pitches for America's addiction to soda, an addiction
that particularly jeopardizes the health of teen-agers, according
to a new study. ``The average American is drinking twice as much
soda pop as in 1974,'' said Michael Jacobson, head of The Center
for Science in the Public Interest. By David Baker and Melissa
Schmitt. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-DEVELOPER (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum Commission voted Wednesday to put its hopes of winning a
National Football League team into the hands of developer Edward
Roski Jr. and his New Coliseum Ventures Inc. The commission, in a
rare unanimous 8-0 vote, approved a two-year contract with Roski
and NCV to negotiate with the NFL to get an expansion team or have
an existing team relocate to Los Angeles. By Rick Orlov. (Will move
in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SCHOOLS (Los Angeles) _ In the Northeast San Fernando
Valley where there are some of the worst-performing schools in Los
Angeles, Cristina Moran says her two daughters are farther ahead
than many students their age. And the reason is simple, she
asserts: They attend Fenton Avenue Charter School in Lake View
Terrace, one of three charter schools in the region and nine in the
Los Angeles Unified School District. By Sherry Joe Crosby. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-POLITICS (Los Angeles) _ Charter schools in Los Angeles
Unified have boosted test scores and student attendance rates but
they aren't a panacea for school reform, critics say. Sherry Joe
Crosby. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SUCCESS (Los Angeles) _ Health education teacher Larry
Marshall has worked at Palisades Charter High School for 33 years,
yet he barely recognizes the place. For the first time in decades,
the West Los Angeles school has doubled its enrollment, reaching
its maximum capacity of 2,500 students. Marshall and others credit
Palisades' metamorphosis to a host of reforms, including adoption
of a charter in 1993. By Sherry Joe Crosby. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SIART (Los Angeles) _ When Bill Siart failed to get the
nod as the new superintendent of the Los Angeles Unified School
District, he didn't stop his plans to reform the nation's
second-largest district. Instead, the former First Interstate CEO
formed a private company that is helping charter schools take the
next step of independence from the LAUSD by becoming financially
independent. By Terri Hardy. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
