<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Despite U.S. efforts to keep the
Israelis and Palestinians talking at an isolated resort in
Maryland, efforts to resolve security issues and revive the peace
process remain uncertain. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICAN-REVOLT (Washington) _ A surprising number of
Republicans rebel against their party's leadership to oppose the
colossal $520 billion spending package approved by the Senate and
signed by President Clinton. The renegades complain that the
40-pound document represents a failure of Congress to follow its
own rules. Most senators, they say, knew little about the budget's
contents when they voted. By JUDY HOLLAND. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee has
adopted unfair procedures for taking testimony during its upcoming
impeachment inquiry, President Clinton's lawyer says. Attorney
Gregory Craig says the Republican-run committee is forcing the
president to play ``a game with the rules being made by one side.''
By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-VISAS (Washington) _ The $520 billion spending bill
approved by Congress includes a big bonus for Silicon Valley _ a
provision that would almost double the number of employment visas
for foreign computer programmers and others with high-tech skills.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-DRINKS (Washington) _ Americans consume twice as much soda
pop as they did 25 years ago, says a new study by the Center for
Science in the Public Interest. The result _ especially for
teen-agers, who typically down two to three 12-ounce cans a day _
is more medical problems including obesity and tooth decay. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER-TAXES (Washington) _ Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
blocked an effort on Capitol Hill to enable the brother of
Unabomber Theodore Kaczynski to distribute a cash reward to his
brother's victims without Uncle Sam claiming a share in taxes. By
DAVID IVANOVICH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MORDUE (Washington) _ The Senate unanimously approves the
nomination of Norman Mordue, a Supreme Court justice in New York,
as a federal judge for the state's northern district. (Already
filed.)
</P>
