pitched battles in California and Houston over government
preferences for women and minorities, Washington state is moving
toward the nation's only referendum this year on affirmative
action. By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-EXPERIMENT (Undated) _ Sen. John Glenn has been
disqualified from portions of a key medical experiment to be
conducted aboard the shuttle Discovery, but NASA says the impact of
the move is minimal. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RED-OUTLAWED (Round Rock, Texas) _ Fearful that a gang called
the Bloods would terrorize the town and her students, too, the
principal of Round Rock High School decided to ban the color red.
Red was the gang's color, said Sherry Blackett, the new principal
of the town's largest high school. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-DUMP (Sierra Blanca, Texas) _ On the eve of Thursday's
decisive vote on whether to allow a radioactive waste storage
facility near Sierra Blanca, Mexican officials opposed to the site
stepped up high-level political pressure. The dump would handle
nuclear waste from Texas as well as Vermont and Maine. By JOHN W.
GONZALEZ. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-POLL (Austin, Texas) _ A statewide poll shows that despite
the likelihood Gov. George W. Bush would score a major re-election
victory, his popularity is not carrying over the other Republican
candidates. By R.G. RATCLIFFE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIAN-SUIT (Houston) _ The parents of Olympic gymnast
Dominique Moceanu agree to discuss their side of allegations that
they mismanaged the young athlete's finances. Their attorney says
they plan to fight the lawsuit filed by their daughter, 17, and
they deny the allegations of squandering money. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   TX-FLOOD-VICTORIA (Victoria, Texas) _ Floodwaters from the
swollen Guadalupe River are subsiding, but the authorities have
declared the estimated 850 homes that were evacuated off-limits for
several days. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
