<HEADER>
A9868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1022-CO     10-21 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1022-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALKS AT MIDDLE EAST SUMMIT BOG DOWN, ISRAELIS THREATEN TO LEAVE
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-SCENE-1022.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Working to push the parties to an
Israeli-Palestinian negotiating marathon the final steps toward the
finish line, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright challenged
both sides Wednesday to embrace a U.S.-authored land-for-peace
plan.
</P>
<P>
   In a tense seventh day of negotiations, however, Israelis
threatened to walk out of the talks, Palestinians accused them of
rejecting the American formula and U.S. officials suggested the
summit was oscillating almost hour by hour between failure and
success.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a roller-coaster,'' State Department spokesman James
Rubin told reporters gathered at the Wye River conference center in
rural Maryland. ''We can't answer the question of which way this
will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat have been meeting since last Thursday at Wye, under
the auspices of Albright, who has been on hand night and day to try
to shepherd the talks toward a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton, who made five trips to the secluded
retreat on Maryland's Eastern Shore during the first six days of
talks, pointedly stayed away Wednesday for the first time since
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent nearly 60 hours talking with, listening to and --
figuratively, if not literally -- holding the hands of the two
leaders, Clinton was sending a signal to Netanyahu and Arafat that
there were limits to the time he was willing to invest in the
talks, unless they were advancing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president has been very closely and personally engaged in
trying to build an atmosphere where the parties can make the tough
choices they need to make to move
</P>
<P>
   forward,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ''The
parties need to work through the issues that remain.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House left open the possibility that Clinton might
return to Wye on Thursday, if that's what it takes to close a deal
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Albright presented Arafat and Netanyahu with a
text of what the United States regards as points of agreement, and
remaining issues of contention, in efforts to move the two parties
beyond a 19-month stalemate in the peace process set in motion by
the 1993 Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart described the text as a ''working document,'' and said
it was meant to lay out a set of road maps toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will codify some agreements that have been reached and
focus attention on the
</P>
<P>
   significant gaps that remain,'' Lockhart told reporters at a
White House briefing. ''I think that's where the proper focus is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. text, which was not made public, centered around the
core issue in an Israeli-Palestinian dispute that spans half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for Israeli troops to withdraw, in phases, from an
additional 13 percent of the occupied West Bank, and hand over
control of the territory to Palestinians, in a deal that would
eventually leave the Palestinians with authority over 40 percent of
the West Bank lands c aptured during the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the Palestinians, aided by the U.S. intelligence
community, would launch an aggressive campaign against terrorists
who target Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that Israeli negotiators had rejected the U.S. plan,
Palestinian spokesman Ahmed Tibi broke with a U.S.-imposed news
blackout to talk with reporters at Wye.
</P>
<P>
   Tibi appealed to the Israelis to accept the plan and not to walk
out on the talks, as Israelis threatened to do several times
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there will be substantial progress, we will stay,''
Netanyahu said in a statement, the Associasted Press reported. ``If
not, we will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Tibi said, however, that it was the Israelis who were bogging
down the talks by rejecting the U.S. plan. ''We said 'Yes' to the
American initiative,'' Tibi told CNN television network. For
Israelis to back out of the summit without an agreement, Tibi
added, ''would be a dangerous step, very unjustified.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has said that he would unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state by May 4 unless a permanent Palestinian-Israeli agreement is
reached by then, as called for in the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   With the Oslo deadline looming, U.S. officials have cast the Wye
talks as a last-ditch effort to get the peace process moving toward
permanent status talks in time to head off a showdown next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're worried about is that the peace process is off
track, that the interests of the people are suffering,'' Rubin
said. ''In the absence of tough choices on the part of their
leaders, we can't put the process back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rubin, ''We've been here for seven days and seven nights.
The president has spent tens of hours working the issues. We want
to do all we reasonably can do to provide
</P>
<P>
   constructive solutions to real problems. But we can't hold
people here against their will, and we can't make them make the
tough choices.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
