<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CIA-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BUDGET INCREASE FOR INTELLIGENCE OPERATIONS IS APPROVED
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CONGRESS-SPEND, CONGRESS-ASSESS) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Heeding warnings from the director of central
intelligence that the CIA ``will no longer be relevant'' without an
infusion of money and talent, Congress and the White House on
Wednesday approved the largest spending increase for intelligence
in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The director, George Tenet, has been telling members of Congress
that the machine of U.S. intelligence might rust and falter in the
coming decade without an injection of billions of dollars. He
received secret ``emergency assistance'' from Congress in April,
and on Wednesday, officials said, he received a supplemental
appropriation of about $1.8 billion. In budget requests for coming
years he will seek billions more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not allow the CIA to become a second-rate
organization,'' he told its employees recently.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, American intelligence has failed to foresee
India's nuclear tests, to quickly and accurately assess a North
Korean missile launch, to come up with a workable plan to undermine
the Iraqi leader, Saddam Hussein, and to provide sharp analysis of
global financial crises. The CIA's evidence to justify a cruise
missile attack on the Sudan in August has been questioned by
administration officials and within the agency itself.
</P>
<P>
   These problems illustrate shortcomings in the intelligence
agencies' abilities to analyze world events and to undertake secret
operations, say supporters and critics alike.
</P>
<P>
   But intelligence officials and congressional overseers caution
that some of those abilities will take years to build and cannot be
created by money alone. They say _ and CIA officials acknowledge _
that the agency must attract a new generation of talented people:
not just spies, but computer wizards, scientists, engineers,
economists, and experts in foreign languages, cultures and other
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet has warned his employees and members of Congress that the
agency, which celebrated its 50th anniversary last year, would not
see its 60th year without the money to become smarter, faster and
sharper. This year he undertook a campaign to restore the agency to
its cold-war strength.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 5 speech at the agency, which has not previously been
made public, he said the CIA had to ``rebuild our field strength''
in order ``to stay in the espionage business.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledged ``to mount increasingly complex and expensive
operations'' to steal secrets. He vowed to build up the agency's
clandestine service of spies, open more overseas stations,
undertake more covert operations, hire more in-house experts, buy
faster and better computers, and bring in a new generation of
recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, moving ahead without more money would be
difficult,'' he said in the speech, which became a basis for his
requests for the billions he says are needed to create a skilled
and agile intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are we going to pay for it all?'' he asked. ``I will work
with the administration and Congress to obtain more funding.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Tenet has done just that, buttonholing
President Clinton, House Speaker Newt Gingrich and key lawmakers.
He convinced them that American intelligence was ``seriously
eroding'' and needed rebuilding, said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla.,
chairman of the House Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intelligence isn't just something for the cold war,'' Goss, a
former CIA operations officer, said in an interview. ``When you
think back to Pearl Harbor, you can understand why. Unpleasant
surprises are out there, like embassies being blown up. We finally
have a very clear manifestation of a commitment that we are going
to invest in intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The retirement of several thousand employees since 1991 has cost
the CIA a great deal of talent and experience. Past and present
agency officials say those people left because the cold war ended
and lesser missions did not interest them, because they did not
like the Clinton administration, because morale sagged as five
different directors led the CIA over six years, and because of a
lack of spirit, which Tenet is trying to revive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the agency have enough people on board to deal with the
challenges it's facing? Not enough,'' said Fred Hitz, who retired
after a long CIA career, including eight years as inspector
general. ``Our stocks have been severely depleted. Trying to
replace these individuals, the knowledge they took out the door,
the elan and the sense of mission that they had is a very difficult
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   An intelligence official outside the agency said that ``the
brain drain can be remedied,'' but ``it's going to take five, six,
seven years of steady rebuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   Several intelligence officials said that money was not the sole
solution, but that the CIA and the other intelligence services were
assured of more in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to throw money at them,'' one said. ``But this
is not a binge. This is not a one-time huge shot of money. This is
an upward glide'' that Congress intends to continue for years.
</P>
<P>
   The overall budget for intelligence will rise by about 7
percent, to about $29 billion, close to the figure at which it
peaked during the cold war, without accounting for inflation. The
money finances the CIA and a dozen other intelligence services; the
CIA spends about a tenth of the sum.
</P>
<P>
   The spending figures have traditionally been kept secret. But
the increase approved on Wednesday appears to be the largest since
1984, the last of four years when President Reagan's director of
central intelligence, William Casey, presided over
multibillion-dollar annual spending increases, undertook scores of
covert operations and hired several thousand new CIA officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
