<HEADER>
A9920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-21 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Blair's Peacekeeping Plan
</P>
<P>
   Dropping Britain's objection to giving the European Union a
defense mission, Prime Minister Tony Blair proposed a force that
would draw on European armies for peacekeeping in areas like
Bosnia. The proposal, to be raised at a weekend meeting in Austria,
demonstrates Britain's eagerness to play a leadership role in
Europe, even though it will not participate in the single currency
that begins in January.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Bid to Move Pinochet Trial
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Reflecting public concern, British legislators from the
all-party Human Rights Group pressed Wednesday for Gen. Augusto
Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator, to be tried here on torture
charges if efforts fail to extradite him to Spain. Pinochet, 82,
was detained Friday under a warrant issued by a Spanish judge,
accusing him of genocide and other crimes. He is under police guard
at a private clinic in London.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: 3 Sentenced in Belfast Prison Murder
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the renegade Irish National Liberation Army
have been sentenced to life in prison for killing Billy Wright, a
Protestant paramilitary leader, in December in the Maze prison
outside Belfast. The murder set off a wave of revenge killings
against Roman Catholics across Northern Ireland that threatened to
derail the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Exam for Yeltsin
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin, who cut short a visit to
Central Asia this month, had an X-ray and a physical exam at the
exclusive Central Clinical Hospital in Moscow. As Yeltsin was
recovering at his dacha from what aides said was bronchitis,
visiting officials from the International Monetary Fund began a
crucial examination of Russian fiscal policy to determine whether
the government receives further allotments of a $22.6 billion loan
package. The IMF has already delayed releasing $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Treason Trial
</P>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ A retired Russian navy captain is on trial in
St. Petersburg on charges of treason, accused of disclosing nuclear
secrets under a statute so secret that it has not been published.
Prosecutors say the former officer, Alexander Nikitin, harmed
national security by reporting on Russian submarine accidents and
the potential for nuclear contamination. Nikitin, now an
environmental advocate, insists that his report on nuclear
pollution in northwestern Russia relied entirely on published or
unclassified material.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Protests Over Community Center
</P>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ A plan to build an ultra-Orthodox community center in
the heart of an affluent area of Tel Aviv has worsened tensions
between secular and religious Jews. The Ramat Aviv Gimel
neighborhood has had regular protests against the city's decision
to let the center be built.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Questioning in Salinas Case
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office plans to question wealthy
executives who said they had donated millions of dollars to an
investment fund led by Raul Salinas, brother of the former
president. Salinas has said $90 million found in his Swiss bank
account in 1995 belonged to the fund. But Swiss authorities
confiscated the money this week, saying that it was derived from
narcotics trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
