<HEADLINE>
AUTO CLUB RESUMES TRACKING GAS PRICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Gasoline supplies are plentiful. Adjusted for
inflation, prices are near historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   But the Automobile Club of Southern California is reviving a
relic of the Arab oil embargo when consumers were stuck in long
lines at service stations and purchases were restricted to odd and
even days, depending on license plate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The auto club's monthly ``Fuel Gauge Report'' is back for the
first time in about a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   So residents in the Southern California suburb of Burbank can
find out whether they're getting a good deal on the three grades of
gasoline and diesel fuel compared to someone living 20 miles west
across the San Fernando Valley in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   And if a traveler is planning a road trip to Inyo or Tulare
counties he or she can figure out how much to budget for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this month the average price of a gallon of regular
gasoline cost $1.1678 a gallon in Burbank, or about three-tenths of
a cent cheaper than in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   If a traveler is headed to California's Mammoth Lakes and
stopped in Bishop it would cost $1.3035 a gallon, the most
expensive price in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are supplied to the organization by Oil Price Information
Service of Lakewood, N.J., which also does the organization's
national survey.
</P>
<P>
   California still is the high-price leader when it comes to fuel.
The average price for a gallon of regular in Southern California
this month was $1.183; the average was $1.195 across the state and
$1.066 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Auto club spokeswoman Carol Thorp said the organization is just
responding to consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept getting calls for it, particularly around the
holidays,'' she said. ``But we also got calls whenever prices
shifted up or down. There was a need out there and we are in a
position to fill it.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
