<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ UP SHARPLY, PACED BY MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(JT) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology shares led the Nasdaq stock market sharply
higher Wednesday, while blue-chip companies saw a far more mild
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by Microsoft, which rose 6 3/16, to 106 7/16, the Nasdaq
composite index climbed 2.17 percent, or 35.56 points, to 1,674.75.
The Nasdaq index has surged 18 percent in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 13.38 points, to 8,519.23,
posting its sixth consecutive advance. More of the 30 stocks that
make up the Dow were down than up and the average, which spent much
of the day in negative territory, would have ended lower without
the contribution of IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Big Blue rose 4 13/16 a share, to 142 11/16, after reporting a
10 percent increase in third-quarter profits late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 5.98 points, to
1,069.92.
</P>
<P>
   Several multibillion-dollar mergers announced recently _ the
latest being the Newell Co.'s $5.8 billion deal for Rubbermaid _
have helped improve the climate on Wall Street lately, as has the
re-emergence of credit for some borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to see some thawing out,'' said Peter Canelo,
a domestic investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``I
think we've turned the corner on the panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Canelo added that the options volatility index has registered
distress in 23 of the latest 34 sessions, but none in the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ackerman, chief strategist at Fahnestock, said that ``mood,
momentum and money-flow seem to be coming together'' in the
markets, particularly for Nasdaq stocks. In many cases, he said,
those still sell for ``a pittance'' relative to earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suggested that the traditional year-end selling of
battered stocks to establish losses for tax purposes seems to be
occurring early this year, with bargain hunters already moving in
to scoop up shares at their lowest prices.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks are also getting a lift from generally favorable
third-quarter corporate earnings, which have slightly surpassed
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some pretty good numbers coming in,'' said Mary
Farrell, senior strategist at Paine Webber. ``The important thing
is that the market continues in positive territory _ it's
holding.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices, which have been highly volatile for months
as many investors sought a safe haven from equities, were little
changed Wednesday though issues of two years or less sagged enough
to bump rates up by several basis points.
</P>
<P>
   Bond analysts said the market is anticipating further
interest-rate cuts by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which dominate the Nasdaq index, were once
again the standout performers among equities. Dell Computer rose
3|, to 56 15/16, Cisco Systems climbed 3{, to 57 5/8, and Intel
jumped 2 1/2, to 87 1/16. PeopleSoft, though, dropped 6, to 19 3/4,
following the company's projection of slower sales next year.
</P>
<P>
   Among blue chips, drug stocks were strong, with shares of Merck,
Eli Lilly, Schering-Plough, Warner-Lambert, American Home Products
gaining more than 2 points each.
</P>
<P>
   But airline shares, prominently those in United Airlines, were
lower. UAL, the parent of United, fell 3 7/16, to 62 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
