<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PANEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS ACCUSE PANEL OF UNFAIRNESS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's defense team, meeting for the
first time with lawyers for the House Judiciary Committee,
Wednesday accused the panel of designing an impeachment process
that is ``like attacking a man who is blindfolded and handcuffed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stymied in their effort to limit the scope and length of the
impeachment inquiry, Clinton's lawyers harshly disputed claims by
the Judiciary Committee's Republican majority that the
investigation into the president's sex scandal is being run as
fairly and expeditiously as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not fair procedures,'' said Greg Craig, one of
Clinton's lawyers, immediately after the closed-door meeting on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's GOP staff returned the fire, as both sides scrambled
for the high ground in the final weeks before the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point the president's defenders have got to get away
from this partisan attack on process and fairness,'' said Paul
McNulty, the committee's communications chief. ``I think they
believe if they say `unfair' 5,000 times, eventually you just
believe it. ... We have gone out of our way to be fair. But the
strategy is clear: attack the process, attack the process, and that
way you never get to the facts. Well, let me tell you, sooner or
later you've got to get to the facts, and that's what the committee
will do.''
</P>
<P>
   With both sides sensitive to public concern that undue
partisanship could undermine the historic proceedings, lawyers from
each camp described their opening meeting as cordial and
professional. But they agreed on little else, from what charges
Clinton should face, to the standards for impeachment, to the pace
of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is weighing possible impeachment charges against
Clinton stemming from his sexual affair with former White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky. The independent counsel, Kenneth W.
Starr, alleged in a report to Congress that ``substantial and
credible'' evidence existed that Clinton may have committed 11
impeachable offenses, including perjury, obstruction of justice,
and witness tampering in Starr's investigation of the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's chief investigator, David P. Schippers, has
recommended considering 15 possibly impeachable allegations against
Clinton. And Judiciary Chairman Henry J. Hyde, Republican of
Illinois, has suggested he may support consolidating the charges
into two or three major categories, such as perjury and obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without fair notice of what these charges are,'' Craig said,
``we will have no fair chance to represent our client, the
president of the United States, adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment hearings tentatively scheduled to begin in
mid-November, aides to Hyde informed Clinton's lawyers they will be
granted the same rights to participate in the proceedings as
President Nixon's defense team received during the Watergate
inquiry in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Watergate guidelines, Clinton's legal team will be
permitted to participate in hearings and cross-examine witnesses.
But they would be prohibited from attending prehearing interviews
with prospective witnesses, a ban that Craig said Clinton's lawyers
will try to convince Hyde to lift.
</P>
<P>
   Craig attended the meeting with Charles Ruff, the White House
counsel, and David E. Kendall, Clinton's private attorney.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to say afterward whether Clinton is willing to
testify before the committee, calling the issue ``premature.'' Nor
would they say whether the White House will fully cooperate with
the panel's subpoenas for witnesses and documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hypothetical,'' Craig said. ``We're not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the standards for a presidential impeachment, Clinton's
lawyers criticized a Judiciary subcommittee for postponing a
hearing that had been scheduled for today on the issue. McNulty
said the hearing was postponed due to scheduling conflicts and a
new date could be set ``in the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House sent Hyde a letter Wednesday asking him to hold
the hearing on impeachment standards before the full committee by
the week of Nov. 9. ``You cannot investigate conduct without
standards,'' Craig said. ``That's like a game being played with the
rules being made by one side as the game goes along. You can't
investigate charges without telling who is charged what it is that
they're being charged with. It's like attacking a man who is
blindfolded and handcuffed. These are not fair procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the postponed hearing in accusing the committee of
failing to keep its pledge to move swiftly. Hyde has said he hopes
to complete the inquiry before New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority has mastered the `talk' of speed,'' Craig said,
``but it is not conducting the `walk' of speed.''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty noted that only two weeks have passed since the House
approved a resolution to launch the inquiry. And he said Clinton
had plenty of time to resolve the matter since it became public
last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president had eight months to tell the truth,'' McNulty
said. ``It's very important for the American people to remember
that the committee is moving as expeditiously as possible and that
requires cooperation from the White House to get done by our goal
of the end of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
