<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TERRORIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRENADE-THROWING SUSPECT, ISRAELI SECURITY REPORTEDLY CONFERRED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Palestinian suspect captured minutes after he
allegedly tossed two grenades into a crowded bus station reportedly
met three times with Israeli secret service officials during the
weeks in which he carried out other attacks against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's leading newspaper, Ha'aretz, Wednesday quoted sources
from Israel's secret service, Shin Bet, and top Palestinian
security officials saying that Israeli agents had tried to recruit
the suspect, Salam Rajab Sarsour, in a meeting in August and two
meetings last month.
</P>
<P>
   The report added that Sarsour, 29, confessed to Israeli
authorities that he had also carried out other attacks in the
Hebron area, including the August murder of a rabbi from a Jewish
settlement and throwing grenades at Israeli soldiers earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   This would mean that while Israeli Shin Bet agents were meeting
with Sarsour, and even reportedly providing him with the money for
a mobile phone, he was planning and perhaps even carrying out the
wave of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The unnamed sources said they were unaware of his terrorist
activities until he was apprehended after Tuesday's attack, which
wounded 64 people, including Israeli civilians and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Authority Preventive Security Chief Jibril Rajoub
says Sarsour was a ``double agent'' who foiled the Israeli agents
who had recruited him while simultaneously being inducted into the
armed wing of the militant Islamist group Hamas.
</P>
<P>
   Rajoub maintained that these revelations prove the Israelis
could have stopped the attack. It is bitterly ironic, he added, in
light of the way Israel _ within minutes after the attack _ blamed
Palestinian officials for doing too little to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mideast peace summit in Maryland, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu seized on the Tuesday attack by immediately
limiting talks to Israeli security and using the attack as an
example of how the Palestinian Authority needs to step up its fight
against extremists from Hamas.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Israeli Government Press Office, Moshe
Fogel, refused to confirm or deny the Ha'aretz report.
</P>
<P>
   For Palestinian negotiators in Maryland, the news reports
underscore their claim that no nation in the world can completely
stop terrorism. They point out that 20 Hamas activists have been
detained for questioning in their efforts to help the Israelis
prosecute the suspect in the attack. They maintain that the
Israelis are ratcheting up security demands as a way to derail a
process that has been deadlocked for 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   Fogel dismissed that claim, saying, ``We are not asking them to
do anything less than to help stop terrorism. We want them to do
what we would do. They have 35,000 people in their police force and
have every reason to be more effective in breaking the
infrastructure of terrorism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
