<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU THREATENS TO LEAVE PEACE TALKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ A troubled peace summit neared a humiliating
collapse Wednesday night as Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu denounced Palestinian leaders, packed his bags and
threatened to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu gave an ultimatum to Yasser Arafat, saying the
Palestinian leader had to agree to extradite terrorists to Israel
and repeal a charter calling for the destruction of Israel. If that
didn't happen by late night, Netanyahu said, the Israelis would fly
home.
</P>
<P>
   The brinksmanship put extraordinary pressure on President
Clinton, who has spent 57 hours at the peace talks on Maryland's
Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they refused to side with Netanyahu but had
urged him to stay. ``It would be very unfortunate if one side
decided to leave when we are ready, willing and able to provide for
the security of their people,'' State Department spokesman James P.
Rubin said last night. ``We're trying to work on the substance
(but) we don't expect anybody to stay here against their will.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the ultimatum and a late-night deadline
that Netanyahu's spokesman announced in public had been ``more
stark'' than Netanyahu's words to Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright during a private meeting the two held at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   While Israeli officials had rebuffed American pressure and
openly suggested cutting off the negotiations several times since
the talks started a week ago, US officials took this latest threat
seriously. Netanyahu even went as far as ordering most of his
delegation to pack their suitcases and send their baggage to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis came on the seventh day of what was supposed to be a
four-day summit. Netanyahu made the threat just before US officials
gave Israelis and Palestinians the draft of an extensive proposal
laying out steps for the next Israeli pullout from the West Bank.
In exchange for the withdrawal of Israeli troops over several
months, Palestinians would have to work with the CIA to identify
and turn over terrorists to Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   While Netanyahu had not seen the exact wording in the document,
US and Israeli officials said it contained no surprises. Indeed, it
was not much different from the accord suggested when Israelis and
Palestinians arrived in Washington to kick off the talks last
Thursday, Americans said.
</P>
<P>
   A news blackout imposed by the White House fell apart as
spokesmen for Netanyahu and Arafat left the seclusion of the Wye
River conference center to speak to reporters confined to a nearby
community college. Accusations ricocheted across a courtyard of the
college and the two spokesmen even got engaged in an impromptu
debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis complained that Palestinians had agreed to several
demands, then backed out when the time came to discuss details.
Specifically, the Israelis said, Palestinians had agreed to hand
over 36 people who have been identified as terrorists and repeal
their national charter, which has nearly 30 separate sections that
seek the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Besides seeking extradition of terrorists, the Palestinians
refused to collect illegal arms and reduce the ranks of police by
several thousand, Israeli spokesman Aviv Bushinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to release some prisoners, some that raped
young children,'' he continued. ``But I wonder what kind of entity
is the Palestinian Authority that it wants rapists and murders in
its territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Ahmed Tibi, a doctor who serves as a close
adviser to Arafat, appeared before reporters to denounce the
Israelis. ``We understand that these new decisions are a pretext in
order to make these negotiations a failure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The day started with ominous signs. Unable to get the
concessions he wanted, Clinton stayed at the 1,000-acre Wye estate
until almost 1:30 am before taking the Marine One helicopter back
to the White House. At 2:15 am, Albright was on the phone with
Netanyahu, pressing for an agreement, when she remembered to wish
him a happy 49th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who has denounced Netanyahu for years, sent flowers for
the Israeli leader's birthday, but the two did not talk face to
face. After Netanyahu said he was considering leaving, Arafat
called him and appealed to keep the talks going and reach an
agreement, Palestinian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   US officials, who had spoken for days of the ``constructive,''
``productive'' and ``workmanlike'' atmosphere, acknowledged that an
agreement was far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the intensity of today and the intensity of Wednesday,
it is not at all clear that the tough choices necessary to reach an
agreement can and will be made,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said that the Israeli posturing could have been
just that _ tough talk designed to shake up the Palestinians and
Americans. Just as important, Americans familiar with the talks
said, Netanyahu has to play to a small group of hard-liners back
home who demand that he snub Clinton and hold on to the remaining
portions of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The most defiant Israeli statements were made in the early
afternoon, in Hebrew before television cameras _ just in time for
the evening news shows back in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found the Palestinians not only unwilling to fulfill their
obligations, most of them old ones ... but they also went backwards
and there's a deterioration of the situation,'' Bushinsky, the
Israeli spokesman, said. ``We have very simple demands.''
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with Albright, Netanyahu awaited concessions
from Arafat. ``If there is progress we'll stay; if there isn't
we'll leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Netanyahu was talking about leaving so suddently,
Tibi, the Palestinian spokesman, responded: ``I don't know. I'm a
gynocologist, not a psychologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's declaration followed a flurry of calls to Israeli
officials from American Jewish groups, sources said. Many
mainstream groups urged Netanyahu to keep talking, though several
said he should not give up land.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Cohen, vice chairman of the Center for Middle East
Peace and Economic Cooperation, said the pressure had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president's ... hours of involvement is not enough to
keep Netanyahu negotiating, then no American Jewish organization is
going to matter,'' he said. ``It's reached the level of an
international peace and security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
