<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONOCO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CONOCO SHARE SALE IS BIGGEST EVER
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Institutional and small investors snapped up more
than 190 million shares of Conoco on Wednesday, raising $4.4
billion for its parent, DuPont, in the largest initial public
offering in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The offering was priced at $23 a share, toward the high end of
the range of $20 to $24 a share that had been anticipated by Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, the lead underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   The demand was so strong that instead of selling 150 million
shares, or 25 percent of DuPont's stake, the underwriters were able
to sell 191.456 million shares, or 30 percent. Smaller investors
bought more than 80 percent of the shares sold.
</P>
<P>
   The results meant the sale far surpassed the previous record
public offering, by Lucent Technologies Inc., for $3.03 billion in
April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from its record size, what made the deal notable was
its timing. Initial public offerings have almost dried up since
global market turmoil ravaged stocks in August and September.
Earnings declines at many major companies have made investors
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Conoco, the nation's eighth-largest oil company,
the sale also coincided with weak crude oil prices, which have
battered the major oil companies. Some reported double-digit drops
in earnings Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it does not look like the most opportune time to
go to the stock market to sell an oil company. But that is not
necessarily so for companies like Conoco, which have long track
records of financial stability.
</P>
<P>
   Conoco offered investors a chance to buy into an established
company that expects to grow even though its earnings have declined
because of lower crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers good dividend income of 76 cents a share, for a
yield of 3.3 percent based on its $23-a-share price.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is the firt major step in a strategy announced by
DuPont last spring to divest itself of Conoco and use the money to
expand into the fast-growing field of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of DuPont fell $2.1875, to $62, but the decline did not
necessarily reflect the Conoco sale. The company reported weaker
quarterly earnings Wednesday, partly due to declining demand abroad
and the effects of the strong dollar.
</P>
<P>
   For Conoco, the offering represents the first step toward
independence from a parent that kept a tight rein on the company's
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good move for both companies,'' said Jay Wilson, an
oil analyst for J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the deal's huge size, it is expected to have little
effect on the languishing market for public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Only six initial offerings have been brought to market in
October and September, compared with 332 for the year. Those
companies that sold stock to the public have seen their shares
decline by an average of 22 percent. There were 628 public
offerings last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will do nothing,'' said John Fitzgibbon, editor of IPO
Reporter, a newsletter. He said only established, financially
strong companies like Conoco, which can sell shares ahead of time
to institutional investors, can now make their debuts.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most recent stock offerings, used by fledgling start-up
companies to raise cash, Conoco has large amounts of cash already.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont bought Conoco in 1981 for $7.6 billion, in what was then
considered a huge acquisition. The chemical company was worried at
that time about oil prices soaring, and it wanted a reliable source
of crude oil _ a basic raw material for its huge chemical business.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices in recent years have been fairly stable, and
this year they have fallen, diminishing the need for DuPnt to keep
an in-house supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Under Charles Holliday Jr., president and chief executive of
DuPont, the company is shifting toward growing its life sciences
business through major acquisitions. It has spent more than $3
billion to buy Ralston Purina Co.'s Protein Technologies
International, a soya products company, and 20 percent of Pioneer
Hi-Bred International Inc., a seed corn company.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont plans to divest itself of the rest of Conoco in a
tax-free stock distribution to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and shareholders have reacted favorably to the strategy
and DuPont's stock has risen each time it spelled out more of how
it planned to dispose of Conoco.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds of the sale are expected to be used to make further
large acquisitions. That is a major shift for Dupont, since Conoco
contributed close to half of DuPont's $45.1 billion in revenue last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
