<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-1st </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT KEEPS HEAT ON CHIEF ACCUSER AT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Fixes attrtibution in graph 8)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Netscape Chief Executive James Barksdale has felt
the heat of Microsoft's wrath in the marketplace for years, and now
he is feeling it in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   During a tense second day of painstaking cross-examination, a
Microsoft lawyer attempted to take apart each complaint and
allegation made by Microsoft's arch competitor in the market for
Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale, whose company's revenues and market share have
plummeted since Microsoft started giving away its own Internet
browser for free, stuck to his guns, insisting that Microsoft has
acted unfairly and illegally in its effort to defeat Netscape in
the so-called browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   But using Barksdale as a foil, Microsoft did manage to introduce
several pieces of evidence potentially damaging to the sweeping
antitrust case brought against Microsoft by the federal government,
20 states and the District of Columbia:
</P>
<P>
   _Netscape's co-founder, Jim Clark, said in a deposition that
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates told him in October 1994 that he
planned to offer the Microsoft browser for free. Microsoft said
that conversation undermines the notion that Microsoft decided to
make its browser free only in 1995 as a tactic to crush Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the Gates statement _ if it was really made
_ doesn't matter because it was made as a threat to Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   _Unbeknown to his colleagues at Netscape, Clark sent a Microsoft
executive an e-mail in December 1994 asking Microsoft to consider
investing in Netscape. Microsoft said that e-mail negates the
government's claim that Microsoft introduced the notion of
investing in Netscape in 1995 as an enticement for Netscape to
agree to an illegal division of the browser market.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the 1994 proposal is irrelevant because it
was rejected the next day by Microsoft. Clark sent it at 3 a.m. on
one of his last days as chief executive when he was anxious to
recoup his personal $5 million investment in the company, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   _Tens of millions of copies of Netscape's browser are downloaded
from the Internet each year. Microsoft says that shows that
Microsoft has not foreclosed Netscape's access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale insisted that many copies are simply downloaded as
upgrades by current Netscape users, and that Microsoft's
integration of the browser into its operating system and
Microsoft's deals with America Online and various Internet service
providers have limited Netscape's access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The third day of the trial _ Barksdale's second day on the stand
_ brought an escalation in the level of anger in the courtroom.
Barksdale and Microsoft's lawyer, John Warden, could barely contain
their contempt for one another, sneering, snapping, interrupting
and raising their voices as they jousted.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony made it clear that Netscape and Microsoft flirted with
a collaborative relationship for about a year before all-out war
broke out between the companies. Barksdale testified that Microsoft
offered to buy Netscape in November 1994, but Netscape rejected the
offer. The next month Clark made his secret request for Microsoft
to invest in the company, but Microsoft rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, in an incident that is at the heart of the
government's case, Microsoft allegedly offered to invest in
Netscape if Netscape would abandon the market for Internet browsers
compatible with Windows 95. Barksdale said Microsoft executives
promised there would be a ``Bill effect'' from a Microsoft
investment in Netscape, in which the potential stock price of
Netscape when it went public would rise because investors would be
impressed by a Gates vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the proposals worked out, and since mid-1995 the
companies have been wrestling over the market for Internet
browsers. Microsoft made its browser free, and included it with the
operating system used by most consumers; in response, Netscape also
made its browser free. Microsoft's market share has risen steadily,
and the two companies each have about half the market now.
</P>
<P>
   Warden suggested that Microsoft's growing market share for
Internet browsers is attributable to the superior quality of the
product. He displayed 19 news articles favoring Internet Explorer,
including one that described the Microsoft product as ``a white-hot
(Netscape) Navigator killer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barksdale attributed the decline of Netscape's market share
to Microsoft's illegally anti-competitive actions _ forcing
computer makers to include Internet Explorer on every computer and
bullying other key industry players into promoting the Microsoft
product.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale testified that he had been told by Gil Amelio, the
former chief executive of Apple Computer, that Microsoft had
threatened to stop manufacturing a key software product for Apple
unless Apple agreed to promote Microsoft's browser at the expense
of Netscape's.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale complained that ``Microsoft took away half my
distribution,'' but Warden sneeringly referred to Barksdale's
notion of ``your God-given right to 95 percent of the market.''
Attempting to show that competition is a part of corporate life,
Warden asked rhetorically, ``what was GM's market share before the
Japanese started selling automobiles?''
</P>
<P>
   Citing statements made by other Netscape executives to book
authors and in depositions, Warden repeatedly tried to get
Barksdale to say that Netscape had planned to give away its own
browser for free, even before Microsoft decided to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Barksdale, who owns 5 million shares of Netscape currently
valued at about $115 million, said ``you can go flat broke doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having difficulty showing a profit,'' he said of his
company's plight since it started offering its own browser free, in
response to Microsoft's action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
