<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9970 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-AIR-POLLUTI     10-21 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-AIR-POLLUTION-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE PENALTY LIKELY AGAINST DIESEL-ENGINE MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency is expected to
impose its biggest civil penalty ever in a likely settlement with
manufacturers of heavy-duty diesel-truck engines for violating
clean-air standards, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several days, lawyers for the EPA and the Justice
Department have been wrapping up a deal with several engine makers
that would force the companies to pay large fines and speed up the
introduction of cleaner engines.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers are also expected to take other steps to
offset the excess emissions produced by as many as a million trucks
with engines that the government says were designed to evade
pollution standards of the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   One manufacturer, Cummins Engine Co., said Wednesday that the
negotiations ``appear to be concluding'' and government officials
said they expected a settlement as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working to conclude discussions as soon as possible so
that we can reach an agreement that protects public health and the
environment,'' said Loretta Ucelli, the EPA spokeswoman. She said
it would be inappropriate to discuss the details until the deal was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the settlement could cost the companies close to $1
billion dollars before taxes and significantly reduce future
pollution from diesel trucks, a major source of smog and acid rain,
especially in the Northeast and California, where officials have
been closely involved.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and government officials say diesel engines
were passed over in emission standards until the 1990s because they
caused much less smog than did cars and smokestack industries. But
since car emissions of hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxide began to be
regulated in 1970, diesel engines have increasingly emerged as a
greater problem.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been briefed on the settlement said it did not
require that the trucks be immediately recalled and modified.
Instead, the EPA wants to use some of the money from the settlement
to pay for changes to the engines when they wear out and have to be
rebuilt, typically after several years or a few hundred thousand
miles of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials decided that truck owners would be unlikely to
comply with a recall, since fixing the pollution problem would cut
fuel efficiency and significantly increase the costs of driving the
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   As many as a million trucks are involved, some of them giving
off as much as twice the allowable amount of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   They were built in the last 10 years by several companies,
including Cummins, Detroit Diesel Corp., Mack Trucks, Navistar
International Transportation Co., Caterpillar, Renault and Volvo.
It is not known which companies will be covered by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The government believes that the companies used computerized
controls built into the diesel engines to ensure that the engines
run as cleanly as possible in the laboratory during emissions tests
required by the federal law. But when the trucks are actually
cruising on the highways, the controls are programmed to adjust how
the engines operate, saving fuel but letting pollution rise.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the computer controls alter the timing of fuel
injection in the engine after monitoring the engine's operating
speed over a period of time, effectively deactivating the main
control that limits emissions, the agency has claimed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, pollution experts say, these trucks are giving off
as much smog-forming chemicals as about 50 million automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers have disputed the assertion that they evaded
the pollution laws, saying that the engine tests designed by the
EPA simulate urban driving patterns and that the engine designs do
indeed control pollution during stop-and-go driving on congested
roads.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its third-quarter earnings Wednesday, Cummins said
that ``resolution of this matter could have a material effect on
Cummins financial results.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil penalties are not tax deductible, but some of the steps
the companies would have to take, like introducing clean engines
sooner than planned, will be a normal cost of doing business and
will lessen the companies' tax liabilities, cushioning the
financial impact.
</P>
<P>
   The companies would also spend some of the settlement money to
provide vehicles with clean-burning engines that they produce
themselves for demonstration projects, like urban mass-transit
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has been under negotiation and in litigation
since early this year, is being watched by state officials and
environmental advocates. Truck operators and members of Congress
have also been putting pressure on the agency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some state officials, including New York and New Jersey
authorities, were involved in the talks, and environmental
advocates have filed a related lawsuit in California.
</P>
<P>
   The American Trucking Association wrote President Clinton on
Tuesday to protest the impending deal, saying it would ``require
significant changes in new engines and trucks in overly short and
unreasonable time periods.''
</P>
<P>
   But Al Meyerhoff, a lawyer representing the Sierra Club and the
Environmental Law Foundation, said the groups would challenge the
deal in court because the agency was not demanding an instant
recall of the trucks. ``Every year of delay is more cancer and more
illness,'' Meyerhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the final details were hammered out, with some
manufacturers still holding out, the outlines of the deal were
described by several people involved.
</P>
<P>
   They said the civil penalty alone, expected to be about $100
million, would make the settlement as big as any ever reached by
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything less would be absurd,'' said Jason Grumet, executive
director of Northeast States for Coordinated Air Use Management, a
regional organization of pollution-control authorities. ``This is
far and away the biggest violation of air-quality standards under
the Clean Air Act.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has estimated that hundreds of thousands of trucks may
emit up to twice the permitted level of nitrogen oxides, chemicals
that contribute to smog and to acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast, heavy-duty truck engines account for about
one-third of all emissions of nitrogen oxides. Rough calculations
by state officials indicate that the faulty trucks may be emitting
a million tons of nitrogen oxides a year. And the trucks that are
already on the road are likely to remain in use for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists objected to the lack of a recall. Others
said they would wait to see how much of the pollution would be
eliminated, and on what timetable, before making comments on any
settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
