<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9972 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPRAH-SHOW-TV-$ADV25-     10-21 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-SHOW-TV-$ADV25-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNER PEACE, EMPOWERMENT AND HOST WORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Oct. 25) 
(af) 
Jeff MacGregor worked in the television industry for 20 years, as a
writer, producer and network correspondent. 
 By JEFF MACGREGOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What little I know of the human heart and the human mind I
learned long ago from television. Programming back then was
black-and-white, as seemed the world it purported to represent.
These were the early '60s, before there was much educational
television per se, and grade-school squirts like me were left to
sort things out for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials of that era were particularly helpful in this
regard, rendering the best and worst of our mutual experience in
schematic diagrams that even children could understand. Hence my
ardent lifetime conviction that the brain is shaped like a tiny
anvil.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden headache pain was then characterized as an equally teensy
hammer, banging away inside a tortured silhouette skull, lightning
bolts radiating from the sickly cranium until soothed by the
advertiser's brand of fast-acting analgesic. The convolute
architecture of our very intellect, I thought, was no more
complicated than a cave painting.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious workings of the modern heart were animated, too,
except that Joe Torso bore a throbbing cartoon valentine in his
mighty breast. Aglow with the fires of unutterable longing,
perhaps? Nope. Too much stress, too much pastrami. Fast, fast, fast
heartburn relief was only an antacid tablet away.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the actual mechanisms of mind and body are far more
complicated than we were led then to believe. Evidence of which is
to be found on this fall's newly revamped ``Oprah'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 13th national season, the show has, like its host,
undergone yet another makeover. A psychospiritual Reformation
really, in which any attempt to entertain has been abandoned in
favor of a search for Truth, Wellness and Reduced-Fat Snacks That
Still Satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   Gamely (if immodestly) titled ``Change Your Life TV,'' the show
is now solely devoted to the mind-numbing cliches of personal
improvement. It is a self-help anthology, presented with the
missionary zeal of someone who's already got hers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it is about nothing so much as Ms. Winfrey herself, and her
televised pilgrimage toward a more rewarding state of Oprahness.
Given our nation's endless search for the short cut to our better
selves, it is the shrewdest programming move she could have made.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Oprah's quest for human betterment is
insincere, but rather that she has once again anticipated the next
pang of her audience's appetite. Oprah was, remember, among the
first to book the sort of pathological sideshows that daytime is so
roundly criticized for today.
</P>
<P>
   She was also among the first to abandon them. Her regular
appearances in the financial monthlies as one of the highest
paid/most powerful people in entertainment is based on more than
her performance as television's most beloved ubiquitous empath. She
is a shrewd businesswoman too.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, like many gurus and circuit riders before her, Oprah has
found a way to shamelessly market the history of her own misery and
confusion as a form of worship.
</P>
<P>
   She is helped in this enterprise by a stable of experts, each
appearing in rotation to explain for us the metaphysics of joy and
sorrow and 401-K plans. First among equals is John Gray, author of
``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus.'' Gray, a PhD, has been
appearing on consecutive Wednesdays to help us feel better about
ourselves by, well, feeling better about ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   To this end the stage is dressed with a number of large blocks
on which are written the emotional states that alternately imprison
us or set us free. One can only break through to selfhood by
exchanging a red ``anxiety'' block for a yellow ``fear'' block,
which leads inexorably to a green ``love'' block. None of which is
any easier to follow than it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise the advice of Suze Ormon, the show's money maven, who
ladles out chicken soup for the portfolio; murky investment tips
laced with the sort of generic uplift found in fortune cookies.
Fear and loathing, it seems, also turn away money.
</P>
<P>
   There are other experts as well this season, but they, too, are
largely superfluous, because the instructor for this course in
miracles is Oprah herself. No longer content to mediate a
discussion between the audience and a guest, Oprah cuts out the
middleman and dispenses advice like a vending machine (the experts
all have a tough time getting a word in edgewise).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the entire show has become completely self-referential.
Witness this year's theme song, sung by Ms. Winfrey. A vague sort
of Up With People nod to an old Negro spiritual, it sounds as
though Oprah's voice was run through more filters than the Newark
water supply. There is a video that accompanies the song.
</P>
<P>
   On the opening show, viewers not only saw the video itself
(which now serves as the show's opening title sequence) but were
treated to a ``making of'' video of the video and a taped package
that chronicled Ms. Winfrey's desultory singing lessons. All
starring guess who?
</P>
<P>
   But this is trifling. Oprah's a good sport about poking fun at
her own voice, and major celebrities often indulge their fantasies
to sing or dance or do comedy.
</P>
<P>
   What's worrisome about the '99-model Oprah is this: like
Lonesome Rhodes in ``A Face in the Crowd,'' she's begun to take
herself seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Self-reference is one thing; self-reverence is another.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The show has more in common these days with an Al-Anon meeting
or a weekend franchise seminar at the airport Hilton than it does
with any recognizable form of television talk show. Rather it is an
hourlong interpretation of the Gospel According to Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   Shot through with the usual platitudes of New Age unmeaning,
there is talk of ``empowerment'' and ``gratitude'' and ``getting to
a better place.'' Homage is paid and prayers are offered to the
``greater spirit.'' Mantras are chanted in service of healing or
better relationships or making more money. Parables are told and
conversions witnessed and the liturgy of ritualized victimization
is pronounced, i.e. ``The only answer to the question `Were you
sexually abused as a child?' is yes or I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Even celebrity interviews are now conducted mainly in
rehabilitative terms. Roseanne's appearance on Oprah's first show
was a three-hankie knee-slapper dealing with all the personal
challenges one confronts on the way to the top. (They're much worse
than those faced on the way to the middle, we're assured.)
</P>
<P>
   A lonely, if lucrative, place, the top, and the necessity of
rigorous self-examination, a better haircut and a competent plastic
surgeon cannot be overstated in its attainment. Luck was not spoken
of. Levels of enlightenment were cataloged and clips rolled and the
truth of things rooted out. Left unexpressed, oddly, was the fact
that Roseanne's show is produced and distributed by the same
company behind Oprah's, an omission that took the nickel-bright
shine off some of the truth telling.
</P>
<P>
   Whether fluffing a colleague's new show, selling more tickets to
her movie or co-opting the literary gravitas of yet another
soon-to-be-best-selling author, Oprah's shows conclude with a
segment called Remembering Your Spirit. These generally find Ms.
Winfrey in a state of soft-focus suburban satori; all rub-a-dub in
a really big tub surrounded by candles and affirmation literature,
or trailing a finger through the cool, still waters of a pond on
her farm.
</P>
<P>
   We are encouraged to relax like Oprah, to be good to ourselves
like Oprah, to ``journal our gratitude'' like Oprah. Photographed
through what looks like a field hospital battle dressing, these
moments seem to argue that our highest philosophical achievements
as a species lie somewhere between the flocked greeting card and
the closing remarks at a high school sports banquet.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the current pop-psych organ-grinders on the
best-seller list, Oprah's solipsistic approach to self-betterment
borrows liberally from the world's great religions, and from every
philosopher who lies between the age of Anaxagoras and the age of
Anna Nicole Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The synthesis of all this is a cryptoreligion of self, a
systematized fixation on personal entitlement. Conveniently ignored
is the fact that Oprah's self-examination is the product of her
success, not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, this kind of navel-gazing seems to result in a
myopic national selfishness wherein we trade our commonly agreed
upon moral imperatives for the short-term comforts of our now
incontestable individual emotions. (I feel, therefore I am.)
</P>
<P>
   We want to feel good about ourselves, or at least better,
sometimes at the cost of our best collective interests. We've
enslaved ourselves to sensitivity. Paradoxically we find the
country mired in the Clinton-Starr mudhole because we sought a
president who promised, Oprah-like, to feel our pain, and little
else. We wanted a touchy-feely presidency, and that's exactly what
we got.
</P>
<P>
   Is Oprah then the cause of the current global decline into
ethical relativism? Hardly, but she's not the cure for it either.
We shouldn't mistake the ersatz deification of celebrity for
enlightenment. She is, remember, a talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   A savvy one, certainly, who's manifested more public
incarnations than Vishnu and Madonna combined. Therein lies the
secret of her great success. Like Elmer Gantry, she was and is and
will be what we want her to be: a sly avatar of the holy
possibilities of personal re-invention.
</P>
<P>
   Me? I'll take the hammer, the anvil and the unutterable longings
of the cartoon heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
