<SLUG> BC-TALIBAN-BINLADEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALIBAN AIDE CASTS DOUBT ON GIVING UP BIN LADEN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A senior official of the Taliban, the militant
Muslim group that controls Afghanistan, says that his government
has no intention of extraditing Osama bin Laden, the man the United
States has accused of planning the bombings of American embassies
in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Abdelhakim Mujahid, the Taliban ambassador to
Pakistan, said in an interview here on Tuesday that the Taliban
continued to allow the Saudi-born millionaire to live in the
country. He said, however, that the Taliban was willing to
entertain any charges that Washington presented against bin Laden
``if they are backed by credible proof'' of complicity in any
terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Mujahid left no room for extraditing bin Laden. He
said if evidence was submitted, the Taliban would examine its
``veracity'' and then convene a committee of Muslim religious
authorities to evaluate what should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osama bin Laden has lived in Afghanistan for more than 15
years, where he is considered a hero for his fight against the
Soviets,'' Mujahid said. ``It would be very difficult for us to
make a case to our people and our public opinion for pushing him
outside now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mujahid, here to argue the case for admitting the Taliban as the
legitimate representatives of Afghanistan to the United Nations, is
the Taliban's candidate for the position. Under present U.N. rules,
Afghanistan is represented by envoys appointed by the previous
government, which has largely collapsed. On Tuesday, the
credentials committee of the General Assembly recommended that a
decision be deferred, leaving the current envoys in place.
</P>
<P>
   Mujahid said the Taliban was not under any pressure from the two
countries that recognize them, Saudi Arabia and Pakistan, to
deliver bin Laden to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the most cordial relations with Saudi Arabia and very
good relations with Pakistan,'' he said. ``As far as bin Laden is
concerned, it must be remembered that these two countries and the
United States supported him for a long time when he played a major
role in fighting the Soviets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden also has a history of backing militant Islamic actions
and has made an open declaration of his intention to make Americans
a target of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mujahid said bin Laden was forbidden to engage in activities
against other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cannot contact foreigners for that purpose,'' he said. ``He
cannot use publications or other means of information to launch any
actions, and he cannot send hostile messages about other countries
or governments.'' He could not, for instance, promote violence in
Egypt, which has accused bin Laden of supporting Muslim
fundamentalist organizations waging a campaign of terrorism against
the government.
</P>
<P>
   Mujahid strongly hinted that relations between the Taliban and
the United States were not as bad as the American press suggests.
``The American attitude is positive,'' he said. ``We are talking.
On Osama bin Laden we have told the United States: If there is
evidence bring it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
