<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COULTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA's Coulter May Have Never Seen It Coming  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
David Coulter may have been the last one to see the barreling
freight train that just ran him over.
<P>
   Until nearly the end, the San Francisco executive who said
Tuesday he will quit the No. 2 job at the new BankAmerica Corp.,
clung to the delusion that he would run the bank within a few
years, people close to him said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a view that virtually no one else in the banking
industry shared.
</P>
<P>
   When NationsBank Corp. agreed to buy the old BofA six months
ago, bank watchers predicted that NationsBank's take-no-prisoners
chief executive Hugh McColl would do what he had done in dozens of
previous takeovers: make short work of the institution's top
managers.
</P>
<P>
   McColl's declaration that it was his ``present intention'' that
Coulter succeed him was widely seen as hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the old BofA's recent huge losses in trading and
investing _ especially its $372 million write-off of its loan to
New York investment firm D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co. _ handed McColl the blunt
instrument he needed to rid himself of Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that problems surfaced at Shaw became very
convenient,'' said Dick Bove, a St. Petersburg, Fla., analyst with
Raymond James &AMP; Associates. ``It allowed the NationsBank people to
do what they wanted to do anyway _ consolidate control of
management in the hands of NationsBank people.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Coulter out of the way, there's little to stop
NationsBank from obliterating the old BofA, an institution integral
to San Francisco since its founding by A.P. Giannini in 1904 as a
bank catering to Italian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank has devoured 37 banks and financial services
companies in the 1990s, establishing itself as the second-largest
bank in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, McColl, 63, an ex-Marine with a tough-guy
reputation, has made himself arguably the most powerful banker in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   McColl's modus operandi is to pour on the charm while he's
negotiating a deal and dump his target's top managers after a
transaction is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to Dave Coulter is something we've seen before
at other companies NationsBank has acquired,'' said Thomas Brown,
an analyst with Tiger Management, a New York investment
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Take Barnett Banks Inc., the big Florida bank that NationsBank
bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   When NationsBank announced its purchase of the Jacksonville,
Fla., bank, it said Barnett President Allen Lastinger would be its
top executive in the Sunshine State. Less than a month after the
transaction was completed last January, Lastinger stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``NationsBank has a very fixed idea about how they want to do
business,'' Lastinger said in an interview. ``It's a fact that not
many senior officers of Barnett remained.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NationsBank's record, Coulter, 51, seems to have taken
seriously the claim that his transaction was a ``merger of equals''
and that he was McColl's heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   In briefings after the merger was announced, Coulter said he
ceded control to NationsBank because BofA wasn't large enough to
remain competitive as banks with nationwide operations begin to
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the merger announcement, evidence began to
accumulate that NationsBank was seizing control, awarding, for
example, plumb jobs to its own people. Several months ago, when top
consumer-banking jobs went disproportionately to executives of the
North Carolina bank, Coulter called McColl in a fruitless protest,
bank insiders said.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, meanwhile, was still telling confidantes that all he
needed to do was ``behave'' himself until McColl retired.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's chief put out word that he was shopping for a house in
Charlotte. And after BofA disclosed that he had a golden parachute
agreement giving him some $50 million to $100 million if he left
following the merger, he sent a voice mail message to bank
employees that he intended to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, who started out as a financial analyst, is cerebral and
personable with little patience for political infighting,
colleagues said. He was no match for McColl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the smartest guys I ever met, but he has no street
smarts,'' said one executive who worked for him recently.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who have talked with Coulter, it became
apparent by the end of September that NationsBank was setting him
up to take the fall for Shaw and other losses.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank channeled all financial information through
Charlotte and put a gag on the BofA people who had managed trading
and investments, bank insiders said. Then after losses were
announced, McColl immediately sent an emissary to demand Coulter's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said that even though Coulter realized NationsBank
was blaming him for losses, he still was stunned when McColl moved
swiftly to force him out. Still, with a severance package worth
tens of millions of dollars on the line, he quickly agreed to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the day his resignation was made public, Coulter sent
another voice mail message to employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the merger has affected the lives of many of you
in personal and profound ways,'' Coulter said. ``I feel responsible
for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
