<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Feinstein No. 2 on List of `Least Net-Friendly'
Congressional  Members  By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The first national ranking of the Internet's political friends and
foes is in, and Yahoo Internet Life magazine has rated Senator
Dianne Feinstein No.2 on its list of ``least Net-friendly''
congressional members.
<P>
   Feinstein's support of government export controls on
data-scrambling technology, which are deeply opposed in Silicon
Valley, makes her ``one of the most anti-Net people in Congress,''
according to one high-tech lobbyist quoted in the magazine's
November issue.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said her pro-law-enforcement stance on encrypted
software is designed to protect national security interests without
compromising the competitiveness of high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Internet to flourish,'' Feinstein said in an
interview. ``It's just there are some places where the public
welfare demands attention, be it protecting kids from online
pornography or banning people from learning to make bombs on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's choice of 10 best and five worst cyberpoliticians
_ based on voting records over the past few years _ paints an
eclectic mix of liberal Democrats and conservative Republicans on
each side.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Feinstein and Senator Dan Coats, the Indiana
Republican who has led the fight against online pornography, top
the ``least Net-friendly'' list.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Senator Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., and two of his
ideological foes, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and Senator
Conrad Burns, R-Mont., are on the ``Net-friendly'' list.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who has presided over three Senate
Judiciary hearings excoriating Microsoft, was the only politician
to make both lists. Although he earned points as a techie, he was
dinged for holding what some have called a high-tech kangaroo
court. Many suggest that Hatch merely was representing the
interests of Microsoft rival Novell, which is based in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lens is clearly one of Net interest, regardless of
political affiliation or ideology,'' said Barry Golson,
editor-in-chief of Yahoo Internet Life in New York. ``We decided to
do this because of the staggering number of Internet-related bills
and because it is an election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy, one of the few politicians to oppose the Communications
Decency Act that barred online pornography in 1996, was singled out
as the most ardent defender of civil liberties on the Internet. The
CDA was ruled unconstitutional by the U.S. Supreme Court last year
but has been revived in a weaker form as part of a $500 billion
spending package that is expected to be signed into law by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cybersavvy is coming along in Congress,'' Leahy said in a
statement. ``The days when some here regarded the PC in their
offices as a television that doesn't get CNN are passing away.''
</P>
<P>
   Close on Leahy's heels was Representative Christopher Cox,
R-Newport Beach,  &LR; Calif.,  &LR; author of the Internet Tax Freedom Act,
which places a three-year moratorium on new state and local taxes
on the Internet. The bill also is part of the pending omnibus
appropriations package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased to be on the Net-friendly list. I believe that
encryption is the key privacy issue in the information age,'' said
Representative Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., who also made the top-10 list.
``Financial transactions, personal information, medical records and
tax returns must all be protected from criminals, spies, hackers
and snoopy government bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, those deemed enemies of the Internet downplayed the
rankings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
