<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Microsoft Unleashes a Barrage of Snippets Against Sun Micro  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Call it the war of the snippets. That's how Microsoft Corp. has
characterized the Justice Department's antitrust case. At every
turn, Microsoft's PR machine has dismissed the government for
taking remarks out of context and calling that evidence of bully
tactics. Prosecution, maybe persecution, by snippet.
<P>
   Well, that didn't prevent Microsoft from launching its own
snippet offense yesterday. The direct target of Microsoft's
quotations barrage was Sun Microsystems, which has filed a breach
of contract suit against Microsoft for allegedly ``polluting''
Sun's Java programming language.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's civil action bears on the government's antitrust case,
currently under way in a federal court in Washington, D.C. In the
next few days, the government will ask Sun Vice President James
Gosling, who created Java, to testify about Microsoft's alleged
attempts to stop Java from becoming a universal programming
language to rival Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The government hopes Gosling's testimony will show that
Microsoft has unfairly muscled not just Netscape, but Sun.
</P>
<P>
   So Microsoft was trying to kill two birds with one snippet
yesterday when it e-mailed reporters some juicy quotes from
previously sealed court documents in its contract dispute with Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft was smarter than us when we did the contract,'' said
one snippet attributed to David Spenhoff, a Java marketing officer.
``What I find most annoying is that no one at Sun saw this coming.
I don't think our folks who negotiated and agreed to these terms
understood at the time what they meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said the remark bolsters his
company's case _ that it hasn't broken any contracts or
``polluted'' Java. It just negotiated a deal that gave it the
leeway to make a version of Java customized to Windows. And if that
confounds Sun's plans to use Java to undermine Windows, there's
nothing unfair about it.
</P>
<P>
   As for the snippet issue, Cullinan said: ``We are not proponents
of trial by snippet. We are just using some points that support our
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft excerpted Spenhoff's comment from a mass of documents
unsealed yesterday by San Jose federal Judge Ronald Whyte, who is
presiding over the Sun-Microsoft dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Sun chose not to highlight excerpts from the court papers it
faxed to reporters. ``Our lawyers really don't think it's ethical
to go through a legal document looking for a few points,'' said Sun
spokeswoman Lisa Poulson.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, when I said ``pretty please,'' she helped me find
a few quotes in the 48 pages of legalese that supported Sun's
contention: Microsoft feared a single version of Java, running on
all sorts of computers, would undermine the predominance of
Windows. And, knowing this, Microsoft sought to fragment Java.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there's chief executive Bill Gates' September 1996
remark: ``This scares the hell out of me.'' And a subsequent e-mail
from a Microsoft manager telling Gates how Microsoft will ``wrest
control of Java away from Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's an e-mail from an unidentified Microsoft vice
president suggesting that the company ``be explicitly different _
just to be different ... to pollute Java.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But I didn't see the smoking snippet that suggested Microsoft
knowingly violated its contract. There is a hint of the strong arm
in one excerpt from a contract in which Microsoft seems to require
that two independent software developers _ Aimtech and Fujitsu _
distribute only the Microsoft version of Java and not competing
flavors of the language.
</P>
<P>
   It's anyone's guess how yesterday's snippets will flow together
with all the excerpts previously released by the government and its
allies in their battle with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems disingenuous for Microsoft to base its PR defense
on demeaning snippets when it knows full well that the news is
nothing more than a snippet here and a snippet there, fairly
balanced if we do our jobs well. Does Microsoft propose we ignore
the most important antitrust trial of the century unless we can
report each and every word?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. That's why Microsoft helped predigest the
relatively minor Sun documents released yesterday _ lest the media
overlook the words most favorable to Microsoft's case.
</P>
<P>
   So thanks for the help, yesterday, Microsoft. But puh-leese.
Stop beating a dead snippet to death!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
