<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE5-MALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEGAMALL VISIONARIES FOCUS ON MESA, ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GONDERINGER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The developer behind the two largest and most flamboyant malls
in the world is making a move into Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Triple Five Corp., a huge Canadian conglomerate that built the
Mall of America in Minnesota and the West Edmonton Mall in Canada,
this week got city approval for a $200 million urban village in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The project, which would be equal in square footage and cost to
the Arizona Mills Mall in Tempe and a major coup for Mesa, would
include an open-air mix of high-end boutiques, chic restaurants,
outdoor cafes and galleries topped by offices and condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also eyeing sites in Gilbert and Peoria for
projects, and plans to set up a satellite office in the Phoenix
area to look at other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really like Phoenix and see lots of possibilities here,''
an exuberant Stacy Rush, executive vice president for Triple Five,
said from the company's North American headquarters in Las Vegas.
``We've been looking at the area for some time now but hadn't come
across the right opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa project, called Village Square at Dana Ranch, will sit
on 66 acres on the northwest corner of Val Vista and Baseline
roads. It is based on a concept Triple Five launched in Las Vegas
and hopes to take into markets around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to create a community-building urban setting where
people can live, work and recreate, all within walking distance of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen this urban village concept pop up in other cities
around the country, and the synergy of retail, homes and jobs has
been very successful,'' Mesa City Councilman Dennis Kavanagh said.
``It's quite a coup for Mesa to have the first project like this in
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The design will include an upscale, open-air feel, with wide,
palm-tree-lined streets, European fountains, flowers, trees,
brooks, and walking paths that encourage people to get out of their
cars and walk around.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like it in the Valley (the greater Phoenix
area),'' said Rush, who has spent 13 years with Triple Five while
living in Phoenix. The closest comparison, he said, is that there
might be some of the same feel as the Biltmore Fashion Park, the
Borgata in Scottsdale, or areas like California's Santa Barbara and
Old Town Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   After months of discussions, Village Square at Dana Ranch won
approval from the City Council and nearby neighbors, whose vocal
opposition has killed past projects proposed for the site.
</P>
<P>
   Rush said Triple Five now must line up financing and sign
tenants, but he is confident both will happen and construction will
begin within the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of went about this the opposite way that most
developers do,'' he said. ``We have tenants who are very
interested, but we didn't want to proceed with anything until we
got the blessing and input of the city and neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Triple Five, based in Edmonton, Alberta, is a privately held
company run by four brothers who grew up in Iran. It has divisions
involved in banking, technology, mining, and hotel, home, apartment
and urban entertainment developments.
</P>
<P>
   But it is perhaps most famous for its two megamalls, which boast
more visitors than Disneyland, Walt Disney World and Euro Disney
combined with their mix of tourism, retail and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Ghermezian brothers' grandiose visions have been scoffed at
when proposed and have seen many struggles, but family members are
widely considered visionaries in combining entertainment and retail
on a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
   The $700 million West Edmonton mall, for instance, is 5 million
square feet, more than twice the size of the Arizona Mills mall. It
has 800 stores, a live dolphin show, several roller coasters, an
enormous water park, an ice rink, a replica of Christopher
Columbus' ship Santa Maria, aquariums and a submarine voyage
through what is billed as the world's largest indoor lake.
</P>
<P>
   At the size of 90 football fields, it is the largest mall in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The $650 million Mall of America, which opened in 1992, is the
largest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa officials are giddy about the Village Square project, which
many see as a major boost to Mesa's image, sales tax coffers and
nearby property values.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same type of development we're trying to stimulate in
our downtown,'' said Kavanagh, also a Mesa lawyer. ``When you bring
clients in to town and take them out to dinner, it's usually not in
Mesa. You go to places like Mill Avenue, downtown Scottsdale, the
Arizona Center. This can become one of those places.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush said Triple Five is looking at sites like Mesa, Gilbert and
Peoria because they are rapidly growing areas that are drastically
underserved. That means the company's projects can have a bigger
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we went to somewhere like downtown Scottsdale, we'd be a
spit in the ocean,'' Rush said. ``In Mesa, we can be a whale in a
pond.'' &QL; 
Lisa Gonderinger can be reached at 444-7967 or at
lisa.gonderinger(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
