<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LICHTENSTEIN-BAM-MEMO     10-21 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LICHTENSTEIN-BAM-MEMOIRS-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLORIOUS ADVENTURE, MADE IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Oct. 25) 
(Eds: See related article LICHTENSTEIN-BAM) 
(af) 
Harvey Lichtenstein, who has announced his retirement as of June
30, is president and executive producer of the Brooklyn Academy of
Music. 
 By HARVEY LICHTENSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORk _ I had no master plan when I came to the Brooklyn
Academy of Music in 1967, nor any objective other than to make BAM
a successful operation. It was far from that then.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, I was inexperienced in programming and running
a theater. On the other, I was prepared to allow myself to be a
sponge, to be available to the dance, music, theater and opera that
was being generated at the time. And then there was Brooklyn. Was
it a cross to bear, as almost everyone said it was?
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the BAM Opera House has 2,100 seats, not exactly an
``off-Broadway'' theater. And the BAM Music Hall, later
rechristened the Carey Playhouse and now reconstructed as the Bam
Rose Cinemas, was a 1,000-seat theater. In addition, there was a
400-seat lecture hall, which is now a studio used mostly for
lectures and rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   To fill out the picture, what is now the Cafe was chopped up
into classrooms and rented out as a private prep school, and the
sixth-floor attic was a rented-out judo school. BAM needed the
income.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be possible to make all of this into an active
performing arts center and, as everyone said, in Brooklyn, no less?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever life is, it is most definitely a work in progress. How
did I know that my past life as a dancer, my exposure to Martha
Graham, Merce Cunningham, George Balanchine, Jerry Robbins and many
others, like Sophie Maslow, Pearl Lang, Jose Limon, Doris Humphrey,
Katie Litz and Sybil Shearer, would prepare me for BAM? That Black
Mountain and Bennington; Jack Tworkov, the abstract expressionist
painter and a cousin by marriage, and other abstract expressionists
in the late 1940s and 50s would prepare me for BAM? That my
father's love of music (he was an amateur fiddler) would prepare me
for BAM? And that my interest in English literature in college,
particularly the contemporary poetry of T.S. Eliot and Robert
Lowell, would prepare me for BAM?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever preparation I had, it was my first five years on my
return to Brooklyn, having been born and bred there, that shaped
and sharpened my view of BAM's place in the New York performing
arts scene and led eventually to the Next Wave Festival and the BAM
opera and theater activity that now defines the Brooklyn Academy of
Music. Those first five years also provided a comprehensive
education in the intricacies of running a performing arts center.
</P>
<P>
   My first full season (1967-68) began with a bang and a rousing
cheer. The season opened with Sarah Caldwell's touring opera
company from Boston doing Berg's ``Lulu,'' Verdi's ``Falstaff'' and
Puccini's ``Tosca'' on a Friday and Saturday, with ``Falstaff'' the
Saturday matinee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a carefully agreed-upon schedule to set up and prepare
the stage, Sarah would not stop. She was indefatigable and
determined. I was a novice, the BAM crew was exhausted, and the
costs were mounting. Finally we turned out the stage lights during
the prep (this was on Thursday evening) and Sarah promptly bedded
down at the rear of the stage. We began again early the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lulu'' was a deserved success, but by Saturday the changeover
from ``Falstaff'' to ``Tosca'' caused the evening curtain to be
held for well over an hour. When Marie Collier as Tosca finally
leaped from the parapet, sometime after midnight, it was cause for
a rousing cheer from the audience, as much for having finally
finished the performance as for the performance itself.
Nevertheless, it was clear that Sarah's work was right for BAM, and
that ``Lulu'' was right for BAM.
</P>
<P>
   When in the spring of 1968 we presented a Merce Cunningham
season of eight performances in the Opera House, I was astonished
by the impact on me of the Cunningham work in such a concentrated
dose. I could only compare it to my first seeing Graham in the late
1940s and Balanchine in the mid-60s, when I worked for the New York
City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   I was stunned by the daring and speed of the Cunningham dancers,
the unexpected twists and turns, the beauty of the formal
arrangements that suddenly appeared and just as suddenly dissolved.
It was a season of work that prepared me for so much more to come,
and it included such artists as John Cage, Jasper Johns, La Monte
Young, David Tudor, Robert Rauschenberg, Andy Warhol, Gordon Mumma,
Frank Stella and David Behrman.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in the fall of 1968, came the Living Theater, back
after five years of exile in Europe, in four plays about as
different as they could be: ``Frankenstein,'' Euripides'
``Antigone,'' ``Mysteries and Smaller Pieces'' and the infamous
``Paradise Now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tumultuous time, rebellious and chaotic, and the
productions were provocations as much as artistic statements. But
Julian Beck and Judith Malina were artists, and their use of the
stage, most particularly in ``Frankenstein,'' was masterly. I will
never forget the pipe grid that filled the stage space, with cells
on various levels. It was a precursor to the extraordinary
spaceship set in ``Einstein on the Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   A great lady, Ninon Tallon Karlweiss, who was a mentor to me
during this time, tipped me off to Jerzy Grotowski and the Polish
Laboratory Theater. Grotowski's book, ``Towards a Poor Theater,''
with an introduction by Peter Brook, had been published in 1968,
and the word was out. Grotowski was at the opposite end of the
spectrum from the Becks, employing extensive training exercises and
an extremely disciplined approach to theater.
</P>
<P>
   His first concern was the theater space: it had to be intimate,
since the audience capacities for the three productions we would
present ranged from about 40 to 100. It also had to have the right
feel, and at Grotowski's suggestion we concentrated on looking at
churches.
</P>
<P>
   After looking at several in Brooklyn, we finally settled on the
Washington Square Methodist Church in Manhattan. This was a ``peace
church'' in 1969 during the Vietnam War, and the basement was being
used to counsel draft-eligible young men.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the limitations on audience size prescribed by
Grotowski, we tried to maximize the audience number. But Grotowski
was adamant. At the opening night of ``The Constant Prince,'' the
first of three productions, Grotowski would not allow the
performance to start until I left the church, since there were no
seats left.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true of the theater producer Oliver Rea, who was
giving the opening night party at his loft. The running times of
the productions were around 60 minutes, and since there were no
intermissions, Grotowski barred latecomers by bolting the large
wooden entrance doors. It was hard for the latecomers, some of whom
banged furiously at the doors, and it was hard on me and the BAM
staff, feeling the wrath of the disappointed public.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
