<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-FUTURE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR TALE THAT'S YET TO BE TOLD  
 2008 SEASON COMES DOWN TO BATTLE AT PIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVONDALE, Ariz. - (Nov. 16, 2008)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone always hoped it would come down to the final race and,
perhaps, the final lap of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sport's former stars, retired drivers such as Dale
Earnhardt, Rusty Wallace and Bill Elliott, clamored for a duel in
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Secretly, the legendary Richard Petty also was telling friends
he wouldn't mind a front-row seat on pit road if it ever came down
to one race to decide the NASCAR Winston Cup championship between
the sport's two greatest drivers.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of anticipation for nearly 10 years now,
ever since Jeff Gordon began collecting checkered flags faster than
you can say, ``A.J. Foyt,'' and Dale Earnhardt Jr. began proving he
was so much more than a chip off the old man's block.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Earnhardt Jr. What a pair. What a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, racetrack promoters and some members of the media
attempted to prod a similar adversarial relationship between Gordon
and Jeff Burton, who was agreeaable to such a proposition.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't work. Couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon-Burton lacked something. Panache, maybe. Or pizazz.
Something.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon vs. Earnhardt Jr.? Oh, man, now you're talking
something to sink your teeth into.
</P>
<P>
   With Gordon, you get the constant champion. Never a hair out of
place. Hollywood handsome. Beautiful wife. Transplanted California
golden boy.
</P>
<P>
   With Earnhardt Jr., well, you get a nice kid with the Earnhardt
name.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter to anyone Earnhardt Jr., was about as ``yes
sir, no sir'' polite a young man as there was in the entire great
state of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Just the mere thought of an Earnhardt challenging Gordon brought
goose bumps the size of a used car lot up and down your spine.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Earnhardt and Gordon never did develop a serious
rivalry, mostly because Earnhardt, now 57, was nearing the end of a
mostly blessed career at about the same time Gordon was beginning
to blow the doors off the competition.
</P>
<P>
   So the stock-car world waited.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the year 2000, the younger Earnhardt was shown the
green light to NASCAR's highest plateau.
</P>
<P>
   It took a season or two before the Gordon-Earnhardt Jr. rivalry
began to mushroom. But when it did, oh, my, what fever it created,
more than Petty vs. Allison or Waltrip vs. Yarborough ever could
hope to spark.
</P>
<P>
   It's not to say Gordon, now 37, and Earnhardt, now 34, are the
sport's only stars. No way.
</P>
<P>
   Not with highly talented hot shots such as Buckshot Jones,
Elliott Sadler, Matt Kenseth, Boston Reed, an Indiana product, and
Adam Petty, the fourth generation Petty to reach the NASCAR summit,
pounding the asphalt week after week.
</P>
<P>
   But no two drivers produce the kind of 200 mph blurry magic as
Gordon and Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident at the season opening Daytona 500, when the
younger Earnhardt sped past a shocked Gordon with only three laps
remaining and went on to grab a second trophy from the sport's
grandest race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying nothing would happen that last lap,'' Earnhardt
Jr. said. ``I remember how my Daddy lost the Daytona 500 one year
when he ran over something and cut a tire. Stuff like that always
seemed to happen in that race. That's why I was so worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that checkered flag, I let out a real whoop.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of season for Earnhardt and Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   One week it's Earnhardt. The next week it's Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth. Ebb and flow.
</P>
<P>
   On one particularly fine April Sunday afternoon at Texas Motor
Speedway, which had finally received its coveted second race date
seven years ago, Gordon absolutely blistered the field.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. was swept up in someone's mess early on and limped
home with a crushed right-side quarterpanel and a deflated spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had him, I had Jeff,'' Earnhardt Jr. droned afterwards. ``I
really had a great race car. Then, someone's oil line broke and
there I went.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Gordon went, no one could follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, people probably won't believe this, but I really
enjoy these battles with Dale,'' Gordon said. ``They're more like
wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Wars. Patton style. Ask no quarter, give no quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It's been like that all season, a season for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, Gordon entered Sunday's final race of the season
with 11 wins, the same as Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Each had the same amount of points in the driver's standings.
</P>
<P>
   And all that remained was the race at Phoenix International
Raceway, which three years earlier had become NASCAR's pick as the
final race.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon always said he wished the title would come to the final
race of the year. He had been criticized for soft-pedaling it over
the final few weeks of the season in prior years, and he admitted
he did so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have been a mistake, but there was a lead in the
standings to protect,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Now there was no lead. Only Gordon and Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The green flag.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who was starting from the pole position, led early and
often. He lost the lead once to an aging Mark Martin, an unsung
star if ever there was one, but by Lap 149 of the 312-lap race, he
again had his rainbow-colored machine up front at the point.
</P>
<P>
   On Lap 260, Gordon survived a near disastrous crash involving
lapped traffic. But as has been his reputation, he somehow steered
cleared of the smoky catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he looked in the mirror, and guess who he saw?
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh. Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Each driver pitted under caution on Lap 262 and each driver
emerged 1-2, Gordon in front.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was getting his wish, a last race tango with his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt Jr. also had secretly pined for such a final race
confrontation. Except Earnhardt took it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted Gordon, and he wanted him on the final corner of the
final lap in the final race.
</P>
<P>
   And he got what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Lap 311. Gordon crossed the start-finish line a half-car length
ahead of Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   They banged fenders diving into Turn 1. By the exit of Turn 2,
they nearly were even.
</P>
<P>
   As they reached the dogleg section of the 1-mile oval along the
back-straightaway, you couldn't have fit a paper clip between the
two roaring machines.
</P>
<P>
   Turn 3: Even.
</P>
<P>
   Turn 4: Even.
</P>
<P>
   The final 100 feet would decide the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras flashed, and fans stood and screamed as the two cars
came flying through the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as Earnhardt Jr., stood at the winner's podium hoisting a
trophy high above his head, he cast a glance toward Gordon, who
stood a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   They eyed each other, then smiled.
</P>
<P>
   And back in their respective motorhomes, 9-year-old Jeff Gordon
II and 6-year-old Dale Earnhardt II were watching television. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9984 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LICHTENSTEIN-BAM-MEMO     10-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LICHTENSTEIN-BAM-MEMOIRS-$ADV25-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: disappointed public.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But there was no denying the brilliance of the work and the
amazing virtuosity of the actors, particularly the extraordinarily
toned Richard Cieslak. Grotowski achieved such an intense union of
actor and audience that it obliterated all the seeming
arbitrariness of the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   To my experiences of the Living Theater and Grotowski were soon
added Robert Wilson and Peter Brook. Wilson had done a piece called
``The King of Spain'' with a company of essentially
nonprofessionals at the Anderson Theater on Second Avenue. This
production (mostly the same) was done at BAM that same year,
renamed ``The Life and Times of Sigmund Freud.'' (It reappeared
again at BAM in 1973 as part of the 12-hour ``Life and Times of
Joseph Stalin.'') Here was a slow-moving, imagistic theater,
nonlinear, disconnected, meditative, surrealistic, achingly
beautiful, seemingly going nowhere and yet of a piece. It was as
singular a vision of theater as that of Grotowski and the Becks.
</P>
<P>
   And then, perhaps the piece de resistance of my early BAM
education, there was Peter Brook's ``Midsummer Night's Dream'' at
BAM in 1971. Brook is more of a mainstream artist than Grotowski.
Wilson and the Becks. His work has been filtered through the Royal
Shakespeare Company, the West End and Broadway, Covent Garden and
the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also an adventurer and an explorer, and he has always
been driven to push beyond the conventional, to explore different
ways of doing theater and of approaching an audience, using
non-Western forms and imagery, different milieus and settings and
more intimate and concentrated stagings of opera. His ``Dream'' was
a coming together of Peter Brook, the consummate theater director,
and Peter Brook, the insatiable explorer, in a joyous burst of
creative inspiration. At the end, ``Give me your hands if we be
friends, and Robin will restore amends'' released tears of pure
joy.
</P>
<P>
   What we had in those first five seasons was the basis for what
BAM has become. First and foremost was a focus on contemporary
work, which could mean an up-and-coming artist like Twyla Tharp or
an innovative staging like ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' What was
important was that the stage work have an inherent energy that
communicated to an audience. It is true that audiences often want
to be comforted by what they know, but since there was plenty of
``what they know'' in Manhattan theaters, concert halls and opera
houses, it became BAM's mission to present new work and adventurous
and/or experimental productions and to explore repertory they did
not know.
</P>
<P>
   It is not ideology that drives BAM but rather an openness to
artists and to challenging work that create anticipation and
excitement. We are also committed internationalists, and have
presented a mixture of American and international work, which again
was pioneered during those early years. Even the more recent term
``multicultural'' would have applied to BAM then.
</P>
<P>
   And where is Brooklyn in all of this? I remember that
unforgettable statement from someone across the East River, ``I'll
wait until it gets to London.'' When I first went to BAM, Morton
Baum, my boss at the City Center of Music and Drama, which then
incorporated the New York City Ballet and New York City Opera, said
that according to the culture barons of Manhattan, the Brooklyn
Academy of Music was simply not viable, an impossible venue.
</P>
<P>
   He was, of course, both right and wrong. It was a risky
business, and we often landed in the soup. For all the excitement,
audiences and money were hard to come by, and we were always
pinched and often depressed by the size of audiences that were
painfully small given the powerful work on stage. Recognition came
first; audiences only later.
</P>
<P>
   But the value of BAM was that it is in Brooklyn. Brooklyn
allowed a free-wheeling operation. It conferred an outsider status
on BAM, and we took advantage of it. Innovative work was a way to
put BAM on the map, and the work itself was exhilarating. We could
give Merce Cunningham his first major New York season in a large
theater; we could present The Living Theater, Grotowski, Twyla
Tharp, Steve Reich, Eliot Feld and Alvin Ailey and Afro-Asian
Festivals with the Royal Khmer Ballet of Cambodia and the Ritual
Acrobats of Persia. We could house the Chelsea Theater Center for
10 extraordinary years. We were learning as we went along, and it
was glorious. It still is.
</P>
</TEXT>
