<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-MOCEANU-LAWSUIT-N     10-21 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-MOCEANU-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCEANU SAYS PARENTS SQUANDERED HER MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raising serious questions about the protection of young athletes
who make large sums of money, 17-year-old Dominique Moceanu has
filed suit seeking independence from her parents and alleging that
they squandered her earnings from a career as a gold-medal-winning
Olympic gymnast.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, who is a high school senior in Houston, has asked a
Texas District Court to declare her an adult so that she can handle
her own affairs and determine what has happened to the
approximately $1 million she has made from a professional career
that began at age 10 and bloomed into gold-medal success as the
American women won the gymnastics team competition at the 1996
Summer Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and advisers of the teen-ager said in interviews that
her father, Dumitru Moceanu, controlled and pressured his daughter,
appeared to be living his life through her and had no apparent
outside source of income.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is diametrically opposed to what her parents think is good
for them and her,'' said Roy Moore, Moceanu's Houston-based lawyer.
``As much money as she's made since age 10, to have little or
nothing doesn't seem right to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father and his lawyer, Katherine Scardino, said Wednesday
that he had acted with his daughter's approval and best interests
in financial matters, including the opening of a $2 million gym in
north Harris County, Texas, using money borrowed from a bank and
from a trust fund set up in Dominique Moceanu's name.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu said at a news conference in Houston that he
provided his daughter with expensive cars and a huge room of her
own at home and did not dictate her life to her.
</P>
<P>
   He said his daughter became influenced this year by a new coach
from Romania named Luminita Miscenco _ Dumitru and his wife,
Camelia, are Romanian natives _ and said the coach badgered the
family for money, a house and a car.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu has also established a friendship with an
unidentified 32-year-old man, said Scardino, the lawyer who
represents Dumitru and Camelia Moceanu. Scardino suggested that the
root of the lawsuit was money being sought by Dominique's
acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw in these allegations, it's not her,'' Dumitru
Moceanu said of his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview that appeared in Wednesday's Houston Chronicle,
which first reported the story, Dominique Moceanu said that she
``never had a childhood,'' that she lived in fear because her
parents often screamed at her and that her father had hit her ``a
couple of times.'' Dominique told the newspaper that she sometimes
thought of her parents, ``Can't you be my mom and dad instead of me
being your business?''
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu said Wednesday that he did not remember if he
hit his daughter, but added, ``We never fight together.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu left her parents' home on Sunday, filed suit
on Monday and secured a temporary restraining order that requires
her parents to stay away from her, pending a hearing on Nov. 11 on
her request to be declared an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Dominique Moceanu said that she had become concerned
about her financial situation more than a year ago and had left
home for a time to train in the Dallas suburb of Plano with the
former Olympian Kurt Thomas, only to be forcibly returned home by
her father.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Feig, a San Francisco-based agent who represented Moceanu
during and after the 1996 Summer Olympics, said he dropped her as a
client last year because he was ``concerned about what was
happening with her money and where it was being invested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there did not appear to be any other income coming
into the family,'' Feig said. Referring to Dumitru Moceanu, Feig
said: ``He felt he could build an empire off of her and go into
management. It was silly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, Feig said, he tried to send a check
directly to Dominique in Plano, but her father drove up from
Houston and ``threw her in the car along with the check.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu ``generally was not a happy camper,'' Feig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaycie Phelps, a 1996 Olympic teammate of Moceanu's, said that
Moceanu mentioned a couple of times that ``she knew she had a lot
of money coming in and she never saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Colarossi, president of the U.S. gymnastics federation, said
the organization had no program to educate gymnasts on protecting
their finances because the money comes largely from outside
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Burg, an agent who represents athletes such as the Olympic
figure-skating champion Tara Lipinski, said that financial
protection was ``the biggest fear I have for every kid athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu told The Houston Chronicle that she loved her
parents and hoped that they could eventually be reunited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if she tried to get anything out of her
parents except control of her life,'' said Moore, her lawyer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
