<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9986 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-ARIZ.-HIST     10-21 1937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ARIZ.-HIST.-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG NASCAR RACED IN ARIZONA  
 1-MILE CIRCUIT AT FAIRGROUNDS HAD 1ST RACE HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He was testing an Indy car on the day he died.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Teague, a truly wonderful driver, was at Daytona
International Speedway on Feb. 11, 1959 and something happened.
Something awful.
</P>
<P>
   There was a crash. Then, there was the stirring news.
</P>
<P>
   Teague, only 36, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the best,'' recalled Cotton Owens, a former
NASCAR driver and team owner.
</P>
<P>
   He truly was.
</P>
<P>
   Teague not only twice drove well enough to qualify for the famed
Indianapolis 500, where he finished seventh in 1957 and 18th in
1953, he had the distinct versatility to also race stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   And Teague did that very well.
</P>
<P>
   Although Teague competed in only 23 NASCAR Grand National races
from 1949-52 _ Teague actually finished runner-up to Robert ``Red''
Byron in the first race sanctioned by NASCAR, which was a modified
event held on the beach-road course Feb. 15, 1948 at Daytona Beach,
Fla. _ he was a frequent visitor to victory lane. He won seven
races, five in the 1951 season alone in only 15 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Teague, however, in an apparent dispute with NASCAR founder Bill
France Sr., left the series in 1953 and began racing stock cars in
the American Automobile Association and U.S. Auto Club circuits.
</P>
<P>
   But before Teague waved bye-bye, he became one of its earliest
top drivers, capturing NASCAR's first ever race west of the
Mississippi River on April 8, 1951, the prestigious event at
defunct Carrell Speedway, a half-mile dirt track located in
Gardena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Teague won only the west's second NASCAR race,
this time on a 1-mile dirt track located near 19th Avenue and
McDowell Road in Phoenix, the first of five NASCAR races to be held
in Phoenix (four) and Tucson (one) between 1951-60.
</P>
<P>
   The stock-car circuit didn't return until 1988, when the first
of 10 such races to date have been held at Phoenix International
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   But it all began at the Arizona State Fairgrounds, which was
Arizona's first NASCAR Grand National (now called NASCAR Winston
Cup) venture and also was the site of NASCAR's sixth race of the
'51 season and 33rd in the history of the sanctioning body.
</P>
<P>
   Teague made the grueling trip from his home in Daytona Beach,
Fla., and according to one account of the 150-mile race, took the
lead in a 1951 Fabulous Hudson Hornet on Lap 81 from Fonty Flock
and led the remainder of the 150-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty drivers started the race and only 17 finished, according
to ``The'' ``Arizona Republic'' recap of the race in the following
morning's newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, 2 hours, 21 minutes and 16 seconds later, a
crowd of 12,000 watched Teague cross the finish line almost a
quarter-mile ahead of runner-up Erick Erickson of Hawthorne, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Teague pocketed $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   The Flock brothers, Tim of Atlanta and Fonty of Hopeville, Ga.,
finished third and fourth, followed by Dick Meyer of Porterville,
Calif., and Danny Weinberg of Bell, Calif. &QL; 
Different accounts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty Years of Stock Car Racing,'' a book chronicling every
NASCAR race, and ``The Republic'' and defunct ``Phoenix Gazette''
agree on the race's top six finishers. But throughout the remainder
of the finishing, including some details of the actual race itself,
there are discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
   Both newspapers list Ed Camrud of Phoenix as finishing seventh,
but the reference book compiled by author Greg Fielden, an author
of several racing histories, lists Walt Sprague of Wellsville,
N.Y., as finishing seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stock Car Racing Encyclopedia,'' which lists every driver
to make at least one NASCAR start, shows Camrud with one career
start in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, who died six months later in a accident at Monroe
County Fairgrounds in Rochester, N.Y., is credited with seven
starts in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Camrud, 71, who raced micro-midgets at Canyon Raceway until his
mid-60s, suffers from Alzheimer's disease and is living in a
Scottsdale nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't married to Ed back in the 1950s,'' said Camrud's
wife, Nancy, who lives in Prescott. ``But he told me he raced in
NASCAR once. He said he raced against Lee Petty and was thrilled to
meet him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Petty, whose son, Richard, holds the record for most career
NASCAR wins (200) and is tied with Dale Earnhardt for most driving
titles (seven), indeed drove in the race and finished a paltry 26th
in a Lee Petty Special 1950 Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Fielden's book shows Bill Holland of Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
Leland Colvin of Darlington, S.C., Bill Stammer of Pasadena,
Calif., and Fred Steinbroner of Inglewood finishing eighth through
11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' and ``Gazette'' list of eighth through 11th
finishers shows Holland, George Seeger of Los Angeles, Bill Skimmer
of Long Beach and Steinbroner. But that's as far back as the
newspapers show the finishing order.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Forty Years of'' ``Stock Car Racing,'' Seeger
finished 24th. And according to ``The Stock'' ``Car Racing
Encyclopedia,'' there is no Bill Skimmer. But there is a Bill
Stammer.
</P>
<P>
   As for what occurred during the race, Fielden's account depicts
Fonty Flock leading the first 14 laps from a pole position start.
</P>
<P>
   Flock, however, was passed by Teague on Lap 15, who led until
hooking bumpers with Al King of Prescott on Lap 72. According to
``The Republic,'' King's 1949 Ford went through a wooden railing
and flipped onto its hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that crash because it happened right in front of
me,'' said 12th-place finisher Lloyd Dane, a Missouri driver now
living in Concord, N.C. ``That was an old horse racing track and
all they had was wooden rails. One of those splintered rails went
right through windshield and came out the back of the trunk lid. I
didn't think he could still be alive. It was a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no mention of King suffering any injuries,
Teague was so discombobulated, he stopped his car on the racetrack,
climbed out and checked on the driver's condition.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, Teague was scurrying to get back inside his
machine. And nine laps later, he caught Fonty Flock and roared on
to victory, posting an average winning speed of 60.153 mph.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Republic's'' account, however, ``The Flock brothers
started off as though they were to make it a runaway. Tim dogged
Fonty by a narrow margin for 54 miles when Fonty took a recess with
a flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, the Georgians were a good three-quarters of a
mile ahead of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the newspaper recounted Tim Flock taking a commanding
lead, but the driver suffered a flat tire on Lap 92 and was forced
into the pits to make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Flock's misfortune put Teague into the lead, but Erickson
soon challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth they battled, each suffering punctured tires.
Teague, however, managed to surge past Erickson on Lap 127 and
built a substantial lead over the final 23 laps.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to know exactly which race version is correct,
however, because many of the drivers are now deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson died nearly two decades ago and Fonty Flock died in
1972. Tim Flock died earlier this year of cancer and Meyer was
killed in a 1953 highway crash en route from a race in Detroit to
be with his pregnant wife. &QL; 
There were more &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along with Camrud and King, there were four other Arizonans in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Englishman Dudley Froy, a former flagman at Tucson Speedway,
finished 13th; Bill Flatcher of Phoenix was 15th; Ernie Dietzman of
Phoenix finished 17th; and Frank Oviedo of Phoenix was 18th. King
finished 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dudley was a real entertainer,'' said Phoenix resident Rick
Trimmer, who knew Froy. I was a little kid at the time and he used
to do funny things with his face. Somehow, he'd tuck his ears
inside his ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time he stuck a needle through his tongue. It
would freak us all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo is listed Oviado in the stock-car encyclopedia, but Turf
Paradise horse trainer Phil Oviedo, Frank Oviedo's nephew,
confirmed his uncle competed in the 1951 race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew him as Pancho,'' Phil Oviedo said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Auckley, 76, now retired and living in Payson, might
have made it seven Arizonans in the race, but he crashed in a
V8-powered Studebaker during qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming down to take the green flag and the steering
wheel broke,'' Auckley said. ``I did about four end over end flips.
I was mad because I thought I had a hot car that could run with the
Oldsmobiles and Hudsons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had a hot engine it, but some guy who fancied himself to be
a race car driver borrowed it the day before the race and was
hot-rodding it around a vacant subdivision. He broke the steering
wheel and I wasn't aware of it when I tried to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rathmann, who switched first names with his brother, Jim,
when they were teenagers, had no trouble qualifying in a 1950 Ford.
But he had a worse time in the race, finishing 28th, two positions
behind Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember too much about that race, but I remember
another time when I knocked the (expletive) out of myself driving a
roadster on that track for A.J. Watson,'' said Rathmann, 74, who
lives in Melbourne, Fla. ``I busted my leg up pretty good. Had a
compound fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That track was real dusty and it had all those wooden guard
rails.'' &QL; 
Switched names &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rathmann, whose real first name is Jim, switched names so
no one would question his brother's age when they were racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just gave him my driver's license,'' Dick said. ``I still
call him Jim, but I myself sign everything James.''
</P>
<P>
   Herb Thomas of Sanford, N.C., had one of his poorer finishes
that 1951 season, sputtering home 22nd in a Sanford Motors 1950
Plymouth. Thomas, however, wound up winning seen races and won the
NASCAR championship by 146.20 points over runner-up Fonty Flock.
Thomas, selected one of ``NASCAR's 50 Greatest Drivers'' also won
the 1953 crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hurt racing in (1957) and they didn't know if I was
going to live for several weeks,'' said Thomas, 75. ``I was
paralyzed on my right side for about a year. I didn't race for
about five years. I came back (for one race), but I didn't think I
could do it. So I quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I hadn't got hurt, there's no telling what I could have
(accomplished).'' &QL; 
Never be disputed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Teague accomplished that memorable April day 47 years ago,
however, will never be disputed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Marshall was he looked like the most unlikely
race car driver you'd ever seen,'' said friend Hershel McGriff of
Green Valley. McGriff, who at age 71 still competes in NASCAR
Winston West races, first met Teague in 1950 at a Mexican road
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a little pot belly, skinny legs and skinny arms,''
McGriff said. ``He looked like the guy watching from the
grandstands. I remember we had a boat together in Florida and I
tried to teach him how to water ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was only a 10 horsepower motor on it and I couldn't
get the boat to go fast enough and Marshall would end up sinking in
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good racer, though. And a real family man. He was
very technical with the car. He could build things from scratch. I
remember he wanted to build me a modified to run on the sand at
Daytona because he thought my driving style would fit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we never got around to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teague, however, did get around to making a cross-country trip
to Phoenix in 1951, making certain when he left, he was not
forgotten. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
