<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9988 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NASCAR-50-YEARS-A     10-21 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NASCAR-50-YEARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING MON STER TOOK 50 YEARS  
 GROWING BY THE SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - NASCAR has been down this road before. Fifty years
now, right?
</P>
<P>
   But in its infancy, when it still was nothing more than
someone's imagination, who would have dared fathom such a monstrous
metamorphosis? Who in the name of Richard Petty could harbor such
dreams of growth and appeal?
</P>
<P>
   Who? Who? Who?
</P>
<P>
   ``Big'' Bill France, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the country needed a national stock-car racing
organization, France on Dec. 14, 1947, gathered a group of friends
in a Daytona Beach, Fla., hotel lounge. When the men emerged
sometime later, they unwrapped a Christmas gift for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Stock Car Auto Racing was born and
race fans forever are eternally grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably didn't ever think it would come to this because he
was too busy looking at the trees to see the forest,'' said NASCAR
President Bill France Jr., who replaced his father as head of the
sanctioning body in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   France Sr. may have been looking at trees, but he came strapped
with a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may not have been an unwritten rule in the
beginning, NASCAR prides itself in its attempt to make parity a
series byword.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it hasn't always succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Richard Petty was seemingly unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was Dale Earnhardt, who in 1994, tied Petty with a
seventh driving championship.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget someone named Jeff Gordon, who may one day
surpass both Petty and Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NASCAR mostly has remained a competitive series over the
past five decades, which, in turn, also has made it the most
opulent.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is the sport inundated with highly-skilled rumrunners,
whose daring exploits hauling moonshine around mountain curves made
them ideal stock-car racers.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers now command huge annual salaries, some in the
seven-figure range, and corporate sponsors are likely to write $5
million-$7 million checks just to have their logos plastered on the
car hoods and driving suits of such megastars as Gordon, Earnhardt,
Mark Martin and Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Cha-ching, cha-ching.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, according to The Sponsors Report, television
broadcasts of Winston Cup events generated more than $1 billion in
exposure for the sport's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always considered ourselves a fan friendly sport,'' NASCAR
spokesman Tim Sullivan said. ``And we consider our drivers to be
the most accessible as any athlete out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``So as long as we stay within the boundaries, keep sight of our
goals and don't overextend ourselves too greatly, we can continue
that double digit growth every year.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's growth is unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR-licensed merchandise sales in 1990 were $80 million. It
reached $800 million last year and is expected to be $1 billion by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance also has skyrocketed, up 65 percent to 6.1 million
encompassing 32 races last season.
</P>
<P>
   Network and cable television ratings? Zoom, boom, to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   While NBA network television ratings have risen 8.9 percent
since 1993, Winston Cup races have increased 20.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On cable television, NASCAR's events are up 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hello. Anyone listening?
</P>
<P>
   ``We love our association with NASCAR,'' said David Hall,
president of The Nashville Network, whose company televises nine
Winston Cup races each season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC for the first time next year also will televise a Winston
Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR is the fastest-growing sport in America, and our
affiliates have continued to express deep-seated interest in airing
NASCAR races,'' said Ken Schanzer, president of NBC Sports. ``When
we made our decision not to be involved in football, we looked in
earnest at other properties. And NASCAR was first on our list.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of NBC, NASCAR now has six broadcast outlets,
including ABC and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to remain rigid or mum in regards to marketing its
product, NASCAR is constantly scoping different avenues in an
effort to spur continued future growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like everybody else,'' France Jr. said. ``We need to be
concerned with growth. We've got some things were working on, but
we're not at liberty to talk about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR already has gotten into children's television with a
syndicated program shown on the Fox network on Saturday mornings.
Driver Kyle Petty is NASCAR's representative.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR also is keenly aware of the importance of cyberspace,
where it is working on developing an interactive NASCAR Racing
League via the internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, you can buy a NASCAR computer game and set your car
up the way you want,'' France Jr. said. ``But you're racing against
a canned program, against a machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is have two people in different parts of
the country be able to call up a given number, plug their computers
in and race against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's reasoning for catering to the younger set makes
terrific economic sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we can't get to kids until most of them get their
driver's license,'' France Jr. said. ``The stick and ball sports
have a leg up on us in that respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we can get this computer idea going, we can get kids to
go racing when they're 7 years old. We can build fans a lot
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows, these same kids may be our future sports editors.
Of course, we're talking 20-25 years down the road, but look what
it could do for us as we go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   As prepared as NASCAR might seem as it proceeds forward, not
everyone is pleased with what's occurring during the present.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports Inc. President Bruton Smith, whose company
owns several racetracks, including beautiful facilities such as
Charlotte Motor Speedway and Texas Motor Speedway, believes the
sport is hurting itself by having Gordon and Martin dominate week
after week.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the Dura Lube/Kmart 500 on Sunday at Phoenix
International Raceway, Gordon has won 11 races, finished runner-up
six times and rung up an astounding 24 top-five finishes in 30
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has seven wins, five runner-up finishes and 19 top-fives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of strange every week to see the same thing,'' Smith
said. ``It's either car 24 (Gordon) or car 6 (Martin). You can kind
of bet on that the last 100 miles of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the fans tired of that? I think they are. I think they'd
like to see somebody else out there beating and banging at the
front. I think it's getting a little monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in the (grandstands) at Las Vegas (Motor
Speedway) and it took me about 100 miles into the race to figure
out something was wrong here. I saw someone pass someone in the
fourth turn, but they were 30 feet apart. Thirty feet apart? Who
gives a hoot?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans want to see some rubbing. They want some competition.
That's what we built racing on, leaning on somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Both France and Charlotte Motor Speedway President Humpy Wheeler
believe the NASCAR schedule needs to start leaning toward taking
the series to new markets such as Chicago, Denver and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're a sport in small markets and is in transition to
moving to major markets, which is the complete reverse of the NBA,
which started in big markets and is moving to small markets, our
weakness is we haven't been regarded as a top-10 market sport,
particularly with the advertisers in New York and Chicago,''
Wheeler said. ``So the thrust needs to obviously be in trying to
get this sport in more major markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty of the situation is that we're in about our
fourth or fifth year of a major growth spurt and a sport has to go
10 to 12 years in a strong growth curve to really become well fixed
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make sure we keep this growth going and to me you
assure this growth by TV ratings, attendance increases, and as much
as anything, increased media intensity. And to get that media
intensity, you need to go to the major markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Wheeler have a major market in the Dallas-Forth Worth
area, site of the $130 million Texas racetrack Smith built two
years ago. The problem for them, which also becomes a problem for
single-race venues such as California Speedway and Phoenix
International Raceway, is with so many cities clamoring for Winston
Cup dates, it appears unlikely NASCAR soon will reward those
promoters with a second race.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, PIR, Texas and California could receive coveted
second race dates if NASCAR were to start slicing second races from
some of its Winston Cup racetracks in the Southeast, where several
facilities lay within about a 100-mile radius of each other. It's
either that or stretch an already seemingly maxed out schedule that
will encompass 34 race weekends in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about Chicago and Denver, and (International
Speedway Corp., which owns PIR and several other racetracks) is
looking at a facility in Kansas City,'' France Jr. said. ``The
Northwest would be nice if it didn't rain so much. We probably have
room for a couple more races, but we don't want to put too much
food on the table that you're going to choke. We have to be
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   And being careful means carefully choosing new venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for whatever reason we had to make out our 2000 schedule
today, (PIR, Texas and the California racetracks) wouldn't be on
it,'' France said recently. ``But who knows what will happen when
we have to make out the schedule next year. I'm not going to
speculate at what changes might happen. But as of today, that's our
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that's NASCAR's only problem, what a nice predicament to
be in, don't you think? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
