<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-AZ-ROBBINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBBINS KNEW WAY AROUND TRACK  
 COUNTRY STAR MORE THAN HELD OWN BEHIND WHEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Marty Robbins could belt out a teary ballad about as
well as Picasso could paint.
</P>
<P>
   The late country-western singer, who died Dec. 8, 1982 at age 57
after suffering a heart attack six days earlier at his Nashville,
Tenn., home, often would return home after a long day of rehearsing
and still have enough voice left in him to deliver a private
concert to his wife, Marizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my fondest recollections of Marty,'' Marizona
said. ``He'd come into the bedroom with his guitar and start
singing until I got drowsy. He sang beautiful songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins sang beautifully and drove a stock car almost as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although country music and NASCAR have been an intertwining act
throughout most of the stock-car circuit's 50-year history, no one
bridged the gap more than Marty Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   While such country music stars as Patsy Cline, Tex Ritter and
Brenda Lee often entertained before NASCAR events in the late
1950s, much like current entertainers such as Martina McBride,
Lorrie Morgan, Alabama, and Brooks and Dunn do today, it was
Robbins who did both.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, born Martin David Robinson on Sept. 26, 1925 in
Glendale, not only was talented enough to reach the top of the
country and pop music charts 18 times during a 30-year singing
career, he had the ability to qualify for 35 NASCAR Winston Cup
races between 1966 and 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robbins never reached victory lane, he was no pushover
on the racetrack. Robbins had a career-high fifth-place finish in
1974 at Michigan Speedway, finished seventh at Darlington (S.C.)
Raceway in 1971 and eighth at defunct Ontario (Calif.) Speedway in
1972. Robbins finished with six top-10 finishes and $49,701 in
winnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought of Marty Robbins as a country western
singer,'' said Buddy Baker, selected by a panel of experts one of
NASCAR's 50 Greatest Drivers. ``I thought of him as a driver. I'm
telling you, he had talent. If he had gone into (full-time) racing
and not sang, he would have been one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Robbins became a fairly decent driver in a limited
career and generally is regarded as Arizona's greatest contribution
to the NASCAR circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, however, apparently never began displaying strong
interests in singing or racing until serving a four-year stint in
the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to play the guitar and he taught himself to play it
when he was in the service,'' said 49-year-old son Ronny Robbins, a
Nashville music publisher. ``He learned how to sing Hawaiian songs
and somebody asked him to fill in one night on the guitar. He wound
up getting the guy's job.''
</P>
<P>
   When Robbins was honorably discharged from the service, he
returned to Glendale and worked as a ditch digger and tombstone
carver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he used to drive an ice truck, but he was only
about 130 pounds and decided early on that he didn't like that,''
Ronny said.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins soon met Marizona, who also attended Glendale High
School, and they were married two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty would sneak off at night and go sing at night clubs, but
he had to change his name so his mother wouldn't find about it,''
said Marizona, 68, who lives in Brentwood, Tenn. ``I remember he
was Jack Robinson for awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Robbins began attending auto races in the
Valley and the late Jimmy Bryan became one of his heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember going to Manzanita Speedway and seeing Hank
Arnold race,'' Ronny said. ``Dad used to take me to the (Arizona
State Fairgrounds) and I think that's where we saw (Bryan).''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins moved his family to Nashville in 1953 and it wasn't long
before he became a fixture at Nashville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started racing micro-midgets in 1959, then got into stock
cars,'' Ronny said. ``Preacher Hamilton, who was Bobby Hamilton's
grandfather, built his first stock car. It was a 1934 Ford Coupe
and he called it the `Devil Woman' car.''
</P>
<P>
   But a desire to seek greater challenges soon led Robbins to the
Winston Cup circuit, then still known as NASCAR Grand National.
Legendary Bobby Allison built one of Robbins' first competitive
stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty wanted to get a better car pretty badly,'' Allison said.
``I was building cars at the time, so he offered me a late-model
sportsman car, a trailer, a pick-up truck, a Black Angus bull and a
Lincoln Continental with a lizard skin roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounded like a pretty even trade to me, so we put the
deal together.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins drove the No. 42 Dodge in the National 500 at Charlotte
(N.C.) Motor Speedway in 1968, starting 32nd and finishing 12th in
a 45-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins never made more than five starts in any one season and,
thus, never posed a serious threat to the championship. But when
Robbins did make appearances, they often were memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty was one of the finest men you ever wanted to be with,''
said Winston Cup car owner Junie Donlavey. ``I remember one time we
were at College Station, Texas, for a race and we were staying at a
Holiday Inn. That evening we wandered down to the pool and Marty
gave us a private concert that was out of this world. He must have
sang until 2 o'clock in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   One infamous on-track incident occurred in 1972 at Talladega
(Ala.) Superspeedway. As the story goes, Robbins rigged the
carburetor so that he could race much faster than he had qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just playing around,'' said Cotton Owens, a former
Robbins mechanic. ``Marty really loved racing, but he always felt
guilty about taking money from somebody who was trying to make a
living at racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have finished fourth at that Michigan race, but he
let a guy pass him on the last lap. That's the kind of guy he
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronny Robbins said his father's reasoning for tinkering with the
carburetor was an effort to challenge the great Richard Petty,
NASCAR's all-time leader in wins with 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to be able to get up next to Richard and wave
to him,'' Ronny said. ``After the race, he told the NASCAR people
what he had done. He was just having some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all of Robbins' races were fun and games. Ronny Robbins
remembers three hard crashes involving his father in successive
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running sixth at Talladega one year in the (1970s) and
Ramo Stott blew an engine,'' Ronny said. ``Daddy hit his oil and
got sideways. (James) Hylton T-boned him and rung daddy's bell
pretty good. He retired for about a year after that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Marizona, whose name is derived from Maricopa and Arizona, said
her late husband retired several times during his driving career.
</P>
<P>
   ``And every time he'd talk himself back into racing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because racing relaxed him so much,'' Ronny said.
``I think if he had done it for a living, it might not have been as
much fun for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins' final race occurred a month before he died, at Atlanta
Motor Speedway, where he qualified 33rd and finished 36th after
falling victim to a blown engine on Lap 89 of the 328-lap race.
Robbins, who had surrendered his familiar No. 42 three years
earlier to Kyle Petty, drove a car formerly owned by the famed
Junior Johnson, ``Sports'' ``Illustrated's'' pick as the greatest
driver in NASCAR history.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a driver, he was better than 80 or 90 percent of the guys
out there,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, no one knew the Atlanta race would be his final
NASCAR appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty called me about 5 o'clock that night and he said called
just to see how he was doing,'' Owens recalled. ``Undoubtedly, he
had some kind of feeling something wasn't right because he was on
his way to the hospital six hours later.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins had undergone what Marizona said was the country's first
triple bypass heart surgery in 1970. Robbins suffered another heart
attack on New Year's Day in 1981 and a final one nearly two years
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we took him to the hospital, he had a quadruple bypass
surgery,'' Marizona said. ``But he never regained consciousness and
died six days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty's first love was always music. But I think if he hadn't
been a great musician, he would have loved to have taken racing
more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is he never wanted to take any chances out there
because he didn't want to be responsible for somebody getting hurt.
He tried to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins was careful all right. He also was good. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
