<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TNN-TV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TNN WORKS RACING TO HILT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an ear-piercing, teeth-rattling and
so-noisy-that-you-can't-hear-what-the-guy-next-to-you-is-saying
song. One person's loony tunes is another's symphony.
</P>
<P>
   For David Hall, the president of The Nashville Network,
beautiful music comes from more places than the stage of the Grand
Ole Opry or a midtown honky-tonk. He led the movement to bring the
network to the forefront of auto racing coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly knew back in 1990 when we made the decision to go
into NASCAR racing that there was a direct correlation between
country music fans and racing fans,`` Hall said. ``The rest is
history.''
</P>
<P>
   TNN will broadcast Sunday's Dura Lube-Kmart 500 from Phoenix
International Raceway. It will have a half-hour show prior to the
race, which begins at noon.
</P>
<P>
   The network has televised racing since its debut it 1983, and
the response was overwhelming from the outset, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the American Cavalcade of Sports, which was racing and
some wacky types of racing,'' Hall said. ``It did well for us
through the years. And then as our access and resources got bigger
and bigger, we took the big leap in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response, ratings and advertisers have been positive since
Day One. Motorsports has been a positive part of TNN over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, 49, began as an engineer, but it didn't take him long to
bolt to the top.
</P>
<P>
   His bullish attitude, as reflected in the way he handled the
transition into more sports coverage by TNN, has proved to be one
of his strongest allies.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1990, Hall was the senior vice president and general
manager at TNN, and he knew that a full-fledged move onto the auto
racing scene would prove nothing but beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leading the charge. I was the man with the sword going
after it,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville Network, which negotiates rights deals with
individual tracks, televises about 100 racing events a year,
including nine NASCAR races.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether TNN should be thought of as one of the
leaders in televised racing, he took it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be recognized as the leader in motorsports,'' Hall
said. ``I think we've been a big part of the success of auto
racing. We brought a new audience and commitment to motorsports
that nobody else had at that time, or has today.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR and Busch racing are our big events. We don't have
football, baseball or soccer. We put a lot of effort and energy
into auto racing. That's the top of the sports heap for us. I see
nothing ahead that will reduce our commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   TNN still retains its strong roots to music and entertainment,
and Monday through Friday programming usually revolves around that.
But Hall is not one to be content with today's success.
</P>
<P>
   One of the staple TV sports of another era is returning. TNN
will begin televising the roller derby on Jan. 15. Hall looks at
the new venture with the same enthusiasm that he tackled the auto
racing challenge, calling it ``the sport of the next millenium.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who has won numerous industry, environmental and public
service awards, has an engineering degree from Vanderbilt. He was
the chief engineer of the Opryland Theme Park and oversaw
construction of the new Grand Ole Opry.
</P>
<P>
   He became president of TNN, the eighth-largest cable network in
America, in September 1997. He also serves as president of the
Country Music Network. &QL; 
Jim Gintonio can be reached at 602-444-8380 or at
jim.gintonio(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
