   STARR-HUBBELL (Washington) _ Responding to the repeated
criticism that he has overreached, Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel investigating the president, asks a federal appeals panel
here to reinstate the criminal tax case against Webster Hubbell,
arguing that it is closely related to the initial fraud
investigation involving Hubbell. By Stephen Labaton. (The story has
moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ New details of treasures hidden in
the $500 billion federal budget deal emerge as the Senate passes
the bill and President Clinton signs it into law. These elements
are tucked into the 40-pound, 4,000-word, pork-laden spending bill
that Congress sent to the president. As in the House, the
Republicans in the Senate are unhappy with the final package. By
Katharine Q. Seelye. (The story has moved in ``w'' news file.) With
photo. See also: CONGRESS-ASSESS, CONGRESS-CIA-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL-PIPELINE (IstanbuL, Turkey) _ The Clinton
administration, increasing the pressure on oil companies to build a
pipeline for Caspian Sea oil that suits U.S. interests, says it
will give Turkey $823,000 to help plan its part of the line. By
Stephen Kinzer. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) With map.
</P>
