<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      10-21 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROFITS STRONG AT 3 AIRLINES, BUT TWA REPORTS A LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Three of the country's largest airlines reported record
third-quarter earnings from strong passenger traffic, the low cost
of fuel and a strike at Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at American Airlines and US Airways surpassed the
expectations of Wall Street analysts, while earnings at United
Airlines were slightly weaker than expected. Trans World Airlines,
however, posted a surprising loss.
</P>
<P>
   THREE OIL COMPANIES REPORT LOSSES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Texaco, the third-largest oil company, fell $2.75, or
4.48 percent, to $58.625, after it announced that earnings dropped
58 percent. Exxon, the nation's biggest oil company, said its
profits declined 23 percent, and Amoco, the fifth-largest, reported
its fourth consecutive quarterly loss, a reflection of the slump in
oil prices that began a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   WALL STREET CONTINUES ITS RALLY
</P>
<P>
   A strong earnings report from Microsoft fueled a rally on the
Nasdaq stock market, which climbed 2.17 percent, or 35.56 points,
to 1,674.75. The Dow Jones industrial average edged up 13.38
points, to 8,519.23, and the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index rose 5.98 points, to 1,069.92.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL GRAPPLES WITH CASH SQUEEZE
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis in Sao Paulo, the industrial nerve center of
Brazil, has caused companies to consider paying workers the
mandated extra month's pay in products, not cash.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE TO RULE NOV. 4 IN AMP SUIT
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge said he would settle the main legal dispute in
Allied Signal's $9.7 billion takeover bid for AMP Inc. on Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANS FORGET THE OIL EMBARGO
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after an oil embargo proved that fuel supplies
were neither reliable nor endlessly cheap, the United States has
relinquished most gains made in conserving energy. Americans have
returned to consuming nearly as much energy as ever.
</P>
<P>
   SEVERAL SURPRISES IN FEDERAL BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   New details of surprises hidden in the $500 billion federal
budget deal emerged as the Senate passed the bill and President
Clinton signed it into law. These included $750,000 for grasshopper
research in Alaska, $250,000 for a lettuce geneticist in Salinas,
Calif., and $1.1 million for manure handling and disposal in
Starkville, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP DISAPPOINTED WITH PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Weill, co-chairman and co-chief executive of Citigroup,
admitted that he was disappointed with the 65 percent drop in
third-quarter earnings. The decline was attributed to trading
losses in global markets that offset strength in the financial
services giant's domestic consumer businesses. Citigroup was
created by the merger of Citicorp and Travelers, completed last
month.
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION PENALTY EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is expected to impose its
biggest civil penalty ever in a likely settlement with
manufacturers of heavy-duty diesel truck engines for violating
clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS INCREASED 13 PERCENT AT ELI LILLY
</P>
<P>
   Steadily rising sales of the anti-depressant Prozac and the
anti-schizophrenia drug Zyprexa created a 13 percent increase in
profits at Eli Lilly in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   NEW HOME CONSTRUCTION FELL 2.5 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Construction of new homes and apartments slipped 2.5 percent in
September as the brisk pace of building cooled.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA BUYING 6 BOTTLERS
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises agreed to buy six domestic bottlers that
had 1997 revenue of $365 million. The deals are worth a total of
$770 million, including assumption of debt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
