<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-2ND     10-21 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WYE MILLS, Md.: the Israelis.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netanyahu called the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations and asked them for support and ``political
cover'' with American Jews and the Clinton White House if he had to
leave, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Any rupture of the talks would cause a serious dispute between
Washington and Jerusalem just a few weeks before President Clinton
faces mid-term elections in the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In public, State Department spokesman James Rubin urged
Netanyahu and his delegation not to leave, saying that it would be
``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is a sufficient basis on which to proceed,''
Rubin said, including on security issues, ``to bring peace and
security to the region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us feel we are at a crucial period and we want
to advance the cause of peace, and we can't do it alone,'' Rubin
said, all but blaming Netanyahu for causing this crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One knowledgable official said that ``the Americans believe that
in each of the key elements that constitute a systemic approach to
fighting terrorism, the Palestinians have provided serious and
effective responses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans ``have the bulk of what is needed on the security
front,'' the official added. ``They are asking whether the Israelis
want an agreement or an argument?''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli threat had been brewing all day, as it became clear
that Netanyahu still had difficulties with a security package,
worked out over weeks between Palestinians and the Americans. But
what was not clear, even to American officials, was whether the
Israeli difficulties were the two issues _ the charter and
extradition _ stated over and over again by Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibi always has his eye on his domestic constituency and the
state of his coalition,'' one official said. ``He's either trying
to prove he's getting the best deal possible, or he's decided that
the deal on offer will break his government apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, for their part, were following their usual
strategy of siding with the Americans whenever possible. Ahmad
Tibi, a senior adviser to Arafat, said that the Palestinian leader
had telephoned Netanyahu to urge him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are satisfied with the Palestinian working
plan,'' Tibi said. ``We are very sorry that we are hearing that the
Israelis are once again raising new demands. But after we heard
that the American administration is satisfied with the Palestinian
working plan, after the long discussions over weeks, any new demand
will not be accepted, and we believe these new demands are a
pretext to bring the negotiations to failure.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Israeli ambassador to the United
Nations, Dore Gold, said the Palestinian ``work plan'' on security
``simply isn't detailed enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without security the peace process won't work,'' Gold said.
``We did our end of the bargain. We came through with a territorial
package for redeployment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gold and Israeli officials said that Netanyahu, having made
such a major political issue out of a public charter change by the
Palestinians and getting justice for Israelis killed by terrorism,
needed firm assurances on these two points.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's spokesman, Aviv Bushinsky, was unusually blunt on
Wednesday afternoon. ``It's simple and sad,'' he said, ``because we
came here to reach an agreement, and we applaud the effort of the
Americans. But we find that the Palestinians are not willing to
fulfill their obligations, old and new, and there is a
deterioration in the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He went through the Israeli difficulties, then said: ``There are
36 terrorists, and we have all kinds of versions of the arrest of
these people. But we see unwillingness of the Palestinians to go
along with these matters. We are ready to release some prisoners
they want, including some who raped children. But what kind of
entity is the Palestinian Authority that wants rapists and
murderers on their territory?''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, American officials described their work on the
text, which is a revision of the long-standing American proposal
for this interim accord, as ``a grand bargain'' designed to get
over the last difficult obstacles of both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The text,'' Rubin said on Wednesday, ``is designed to get the
peace process back on track. Despite the intensity of the work, it
is not at all clear that the tough choices needed to reach peace
can or will be made. It's an open question.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after another late night of negotiating with Netanyahu
and Arafat, decided he would wait for a briefing from Albright
before returning here. But the call for him to return never came on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already devoted nearly 57 hours of his time to the
search for a settlement here. Jordan's King Hussein also did not
come to the talks on Wednesday morning, which was spent in
telephone calls, with no formal meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
