<HEADLINE>
FLOODING IN VICTORIA, TEXAS, CALLED WORST IN 60 YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, Texas _ While city and county officials planned
emergency measures early Wednesday morning, Janie Robles, 48, ran a
garden hose through a pair of muddy cowboy boots fished out of her
flooded home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, by the time I got dressed and washed up it was already
out to here,'' said Robles, pointing a dripping boot toward her
porch. ``I had to get out with no shoes on and get in my car as
fast as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many in her west Victoria neighborhood, Robles refused to
believe the water flowing over the banks of the Guadalupe River
Tuesday would reach her home. Robles and her neighbors barely
escaped with little more than a change of clothing before
floodwaters inundated their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday they returned to salvage whatever was spared by
the worst flood in Victoria in more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 850 homes were evacuated beginning Sunday from
historic townsite neighborhoods and in the outlying county where
the Guadalupe skirts the western edge of Victoria, about 125
southwest of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Though water had receded by as much as two feet Wednesday
morning, most homes remained as much as 10 feet under water. The
Guadalupe Basin River Authority estimated that the river crested at
33.84 feet at 1:30 p.m. Tuesday. City survey crews reported the
river reached 34.26 feet later in the afternoon, eclipsing the
record 31.3 foot level by three feet.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Mayor Gary Middleton said officials will not know the
extent of the flood's toll for two or three days, but estimated the
damage will be in the hundreds of millions of dollars. Victoria
County was among 20 counties listed by Gov. George W. Bush for
federal disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   City officials lifted a 7 p.m. citywide curfew, but imposed a
24-hour curfew in the flooded area and within 500 feet of it,
banning residents from returning to their flooded homes until
damage can be assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of residents like Robles managed to retrieve some
of their belongings before the new curfew was put into effect at 11
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need people going back into their homes that don't
need to go,'' Middleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria County Judge Helen Walker said rescue efforts continued
throughout Wednesday for the 25 to 30 people still believed to be
in homes in the flooded area. She said those residents were asked
to drape white sheets over their roofs if they needed help getting
out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Because the river is expected to recede slowly, she said those
residents who chose to wait out the flood may have ``bought
themselves into their homes for five to seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the river was not expected to rise unless significant
amounts of rain fell in the area or upriver. Until then, she said
city and county officials will continue rescue operations if
needed. She said damage assessment will start once water levels
drop to a safe level for crews to examine the flooded area.
</P>
<P>
   She said the main concern is keeping health and public safety
problems from occurring as residents become anxious to return to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't lost anybody, yet,'' she said. ``We don't want to
lose anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Hewlett, 51, was more fortunate than some, even though his
home received more than a foot of water, ruining furniture and a
new carpet he had recently installed. Hewlett's home was just at
the edge of the flood area in one of Victoria's historic
neighborhoods north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Water had receded from his home, and he spent most of the day
Wednesday removing items left untouched by the water. He also had
not expected the water to rise as far as it had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our lawn chairs out here (in the front lawn) and sat
out here drinking coffee and watched the water as it came up and up
and up,'' he said. ``It was coming real quick that was the scary
thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett and his wife left their home early Tuesday and spent the
night with friends. Though he estimated his personal loss at about
$15,000, Hewlett took the situation in stride Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to get ourselves together and get on with
things,'' he said. ``We'll just tighten up the belt and have a
leaner Christmas this year.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
