<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS THREATEN TO LEAVE PEACE TALKS THURSDAY AS U.S. RUSHES TO
SALVAGE SUMMIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israelis threatened to walk away from peace talks
Thursday as the United States rushed to craft ideas for salvaging
the summit and the Palestinians suggested a negotiating ploy was
afoot.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh day of negotiations at the Wye Plantation in
Maryland fell into turmoil as Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
demanded that Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat meet
Israel's security demands before proceeding further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli government has packed its bags, including the
prime minister. Take off is scheduled for 10 p.m.,'' said a
statement issued by Netanyahu. ``The prime minister says: `If there
is substantial progress, we will stay. If not, we will go,' '' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis' threatened to leave several times Wednesday but
then decided to stay another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without implementation of Palestinian obligations, without a
solution to the issues of extradition of terrorists and amendment
of the (Palestine National) Charter by the Palestinian National
Council, there will not be an agreement,'' the statement said.
Israelis want the charter amended to exclude language calling for
Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation, attempting to save the talks, began
preparing a draft of the peace proposals that it had offered
individually to the Israeli and Palestinian delegations in recent
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope and expect during the course of the day to be able to
provide a text of what we think will help the two sides reach the
agreements necessary to put the peace process back on track,'' said
James Rubin, the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, there had been no meetings between the delegations.
President Clinton, who has shuttled between the White House and the
Wye River conference center for five days, remained in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright shuttled between the
delegations in an attempt to keep the talks alive.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton would fly to the rural retreat only if it
appeared his influence could be of use between the two parties.
Clinton already has vested more than 50 hours into securing an
agreement between Israel and the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be very clear, it is not at all clear that the tough
choices necessary to reach an agreement can or will be made,''
Rubin said. ``That is an open question, and there are significant,
significant gaps remaining.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has attempted to impose a news blackout to
reduce the posturing between the two sides but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort by President Clinton is enormous and I think
continuous intervention of the American administration is crucial.
We are all waiting for the reaction of Mr. Netanyahu to the
American proposal. We said yes to the American initiatives and we
are hearing that Mr. Netanyahu not only saying no but is willing to
leave the Wye Plantation,'' said Ahmed Tibi, an adviser to Arafat,
during a CNN interview.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in these sessions is whether Israel will withdraw from
another 13 percent of the West Bank and cede control to the
Palestinian Authority in exchange for security guarantees to combat
the terrorist attacks on Israel by Palestinian militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel has gone that extra mile to make this process work. We
were told 13 percent is what you have to redeploy from in the West
Bank. That is a concrete concession by the state of Israel. We said
it would be difficult for our security but in the end we came
through and the prime minister took that risk for peace,'' said
Dore Gold, the Israeli ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coming to the Wye Plantation, it was our hope that the
Palestinians would also take an equal risk for peace and come up
with a detailed security plan that would make this redeployment
safe for the security of Israel. We're still waiting to get that
kind of a detailed plan,'' Gold said during a CNN interview.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN also quoted an anonymous U.S. official as saying the
Palestinians had responded ``in all areas seriously and effectively
and in all relevant avenues on security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted a senior Israeli official as saying
the delegation's preparations for departure were not a threat. ``We
are considering it and we've made all the preparations,'' the
official told AP.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Tibi told Agency France Press that Israel was resorting
to blackmail and attempting to force the Palestinians to accept
only a partial accord that would limit land transfers.
</P>
<P>
   He also told AFP that Arafat called Netanyahu to wish him a
happy 49th birthday and sent him flowers. He said Arafat told
Netanyahu he hoped they could reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On CNN, Tibi said if Israel left the peace process, ``it would
be a dangerous step, very unjustified. I don't know what the
implication in the area would be but I am appealing to Mr.
Netanyahu to remain here, to continue discussions and to sign the
treaty as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to provide all the assistance, the creativity
and the persuasive powers that we can but we can't make decisions
for them. We are not holding people here against their will,''
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters reported the Israelis also were blaming the
administration for the faltering talks. ``The Americans have
retreated from previous understandings with the Israelis and the
Palestinians are not willing to give clear answers about their
commitments on different issues,'' an unnamed Israeli official told
Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is attempting to mediate an interim agreement
that will allow Israel and the Palestinian Authority to move toward
so-called final status talks. Those negotiations involve even more
sensitive issues such as a Palestinian state and the status of
Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0022 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENERGY-USE-ART-2NDTAK     10-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-USE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ARVADA, Colo.: tax incentives. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 25 years ago this month, and again in late 1978, that
vengeful Middle Eastern oil exporters squeezed their supplies to
the United States and raised prices worldwide. A nation that was
virtually self-sufficient into the 1950s had become a petroleum
captive. Gasoline prices soared, lines at the pump stretched beyond
frustration and the economy fell into repeated recessions.
</P>
<P>
   Americans turned down their thermostats and bought
fuel-efficient Hondas, Datsuns and Toyotas. At work, they replaced
millions of inefficient motors, lighting fixtures and generators.
Nixon called for a national effort on the scale of the making of
the atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us set as our national goal,'' he said, ``with the
determination of the Manhattan Project, that by the end of this
decade we will have developed the potential to meet our own energy
needs without depending on any foreign energy source.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, wearing a sweater in a televised speech to drive home
his point, termed energy conservation the equivalent of fighting a
war.
</P>
<P>
   But traumatic memories of oil shocks have long been soothed by
plentiful, low-cost supplies. At about $1 a gallon _ compared with
$1.10, adjusting for inflation, in 1973 _ fuel is as cheap as ever.
U.S. gasoline prices remain less than half those in Western Europe
and Japan, where energy is heavily taxed to discourage overuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Information Administration predicts that, in the
absence of efforts to curb growing energy use, carbon emissions
from burning fuel will rise 34 percent from 1990 to 2010, while the
president has pledged to lower them by 7 percent. The agency's
experts scoff at the prospects of meeting Clinton's goal unless
energy prices rise significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our actions rather than words, it's evident we
don't care,'' said Dwight French, a specialist on consumption
trends. ``Only the next crisis will again make conservation a
priority. End of discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Arvada, in the subdivisions carved into the sagebrush
hills of Denver's suburbs, the McCrackens' new home will have far
more efficient heating, air-conditioning and major appliances than
the homes of 25 years ago. Modern weatherstripping and vinyl-sealed
windows will help keep the Colorado cold out and the heat in. In
energy consumption per square foot, the home of the late 1990s is
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   But not the overall champion. Since the early 1970s, the average
size of a new home has risen to 2,100 square feet from 1,600, even
as the average household has shrunk to three people from 3.6.
``It's almost like the trend to sport utility vehicles,'' said Donn
Eley, chief financial officer of Village Homes, the McCrackens'
builder. ``They can't build them big enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Home builders are also bringing to tract homes the expansive
features once reserved for mansions. ``Wow factors,'' they are
called in the trade. In the $150,000-to-$300,000 range, the
confined quarters of yesteryear just won't do.
</P>
<P>
   Larger homes with fewer people but more things to plug in have
pushed home energy consumption back to the levels of the 1970s.
Residential energy consumption per person fell by a tenth from 1973
to 1983 but has since risen about as much.
</P>
<P>
   Tighter federal standards for homes and major appliances promise
to save enough energy over the coming years to offset what goes to
heat and cool larger homes. But then come the computers,
videocassette recorders, dishwashers, clothes washers and dryers
that have been using about 5 percent more energy a year since 1990.
Early in the next decade, the Energy Department predicts, such
appliances will consume even more energy than heating.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these devices are always on, ready at the push of a
button. Razors and electric toothbrushes have chargers, fax
machines are poised to send and receive, televisions and
videocassette recorders merely go dormant, not off.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these items use more power than a refrigerator.
``They're called vampires,'' said Arthur Rosenfeld, a senior
adviser for efficiency at the Energy Department. ``They suck
electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   Central air-conditioning, in less than 40 percent of new homes
in 1971, is now in more than 80 percent. Dishwashers have gone from
luxuries, found in 19 percent of households in 1970, toward
necessities, found in 57 percent as of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The standard ceiling height has risen to nine feet from eight,
meaning more space to heat and cool. ``Even though the efficiency
of larger homes has improved,'' said Gopal Ahluwalia, research
director for the National Association of Home Builders, ``the total
volume, the use of glass, the fireplaces and the appliances lead to
higher energy consumption. They will not buy a home without these
energy-inefficient features.''
</P>
<P>
   As Coloradans who believe weekends were made for hiking and
cross-country skiing, the McCrackens, trim 31-year-olds, say they
would like to live greener. To save water and energy, they plan to
pay about $300 extra for a high-efficiency washer and dryer.
McCracken has even joined the declining 5 percent of Americans who
ride mass transit _ for him a bus _ to his job as a consultant and
programmer for IBM.
</P>
<P>
   But their new house, like many today, is another story. Join the
McCrackens in the Wyndham Park subdivision as they open the door to
a 2,600-square-foot model home like the one they are buying nearby
for $270,000. A towering entryway and its clerestory windows tilt
their gazes upward. The two-story, 21-foot spaces continue on into
the living room and the family room, with nine-foot elevations
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about this is the high ceilings,'' Mrs. McCracken
volunteered. ``I know they are terribly inefficient. But it does
make it seem so spacious.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
