<SLUG> BC-BOEING-OUTLOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA CRISIS MAY BE WORSE NEWS FOR BOEING THAN PREVIOUSLY THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. is expected to wrap up in a couple of
weeks a new review of the impact of the Asian economic situation.
It is expected to be bleaker than the company has previously
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Once the review is completed, Boeing executives will take
another couple of weeks to study the results before deciding the
impact on production rates as Asian airlines continue to cancel or
delay orders and deliveries, said one person familiar with the
on-going review.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be more negative than what we have previously
put out,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts expect Boeing's flagship 747 jumbo jet, which
is built in Everett, Wash., to continue to take the brunt of the
Asian fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Asian customers account for about half of Boeing's 747 backlog.
The 420-seat jumbo jet, the largest commercial aircraft in
production, becomes harder to sell elsewhere if Asian airlines
don't want them.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing previously announced that it will trim production of the
747 from 5 per month to 3.5 early next year. Given the worsening
situation in Asia, those rates could fall even further, perhaps as
low as 2.5 per month, by the end of next year, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, after its last review of the situation in
Asia, Boeing estimated that the economic crisis would result in
about 150 fewer airplanes being delivered by all manufacturers over
the next three years. That translated to about 90 planes for
Boeing, given its 60 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   The company will announce its third quarter results Thursday,
and Chairman Phil Condit is almost certain to be asked about Asia
during conference calls with reporters and industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking out there right now, the production outlook for the
747 in 1999 appears okay,'' said Peter Jacobs of Seattle's Ragen
MacKenzie firm. ``But what we don't know is what kinds of
cancelations or deferrals we will see. Naturally, Boeing will be
talking to those customers ....
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look to the year 2000 it gets pretty gray,'' he
added. ``That's so far ahead that even though right now it does not
appear Boeing has a lot of orders for the 747 for delivery in 2000,
it's really too soon to even talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said it expects to deliver 550 airplanes this year
and 620 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But some planes intended for Asian airlines this year are being
sent to the desert for storage because those customers can't get
financing to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 30, the end of the third quarter, Boeing had 36
undelivered planes in desert storage, which was up from 20 in
storage at the end of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Boeing needs to deliver most of those planes if it
hopes to meet its 550-plane forecast for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the Asian crisis, Boeing's overall production rates
are expected to fall after next year. That's because 1999 is
considered the peak of the current boom cycle that has seen
airlines order planes in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not whether rates will be lower. It's how much
lower,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   He believes Boeing deliveries will fall to about 550 planes in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing will be hard pressed to deliver 620 planes next year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be difficult to achieve, given the world economic
environment. The question is, how much might deliveries decline.''
And with them, production rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
