<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT &LR;      10-21 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER FIRES COUNTERATTACK AT D'AMATO ON HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Invoking relatives he had lost in the Holocaust, Rep.
Charles Schumer on Wednesday assailed Sen. Alfonse D'Amato for
gathering Holocaust survivors to attack Schumer's record on Jewish
issues. He also berated D'Amato for disparaging him with a Yiddish
vulgarism at a meeting with Jewish leaders earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest indication of the attention that both candidates
are paying to Jewish voters, Schumer chastised his opponent both
for staging the news conference at a Holocaust memorial Sunday
morning, and then for insulting him with the Yiddishism. His
vehement response comes at a time when D'Amato's attacks on
Schumer's congressional attendance record have largely dominated
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost family in the Holocaust, and my wife lost family in the
Holocaust,'' Schumer said in grim tones, fairly leaping at the
question after it was raised at the end of a news conference about
gun control. Aides said Schumer's great-grandmother and seven of
her nine children were killed by Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Al D'Amato used a cheap slur against me, and then,
when asked, lied about it,'' the congressman, a Brooklyn Democrat,
continued. ``Al D'Amato and I are meeting in debate Saturday. I
challenge you, Al D'Amato, to say to my face that I am not
committed to victims of the Holocaust. I challenge you at the
debate Saturday to use that cheap slur.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato at first said he did not recall using the vulgarism,
which was first reported in the latest issue of Jewish Week, dated
Oct. 23. ``I have absolutely no knowledge of ever having made that
statement,'' D'Amato said. ``I have no knowledge of it. Certainly
never in a public domain.''
</P>
<P>
   But a number of participants at the private meeting on Tuesday,
including former Mayor Ed Koch, who is D'Amato's most prominent
Jewish supporter, confirmed that the senator had in fact called
Schumer ``a putzhead.'' At the same meeting, they said, D'Amato
referred to Rep. Jerrold Nadler, a Manhattan Democrat, as ``Jerry
Waddler,'' a presumed reference to Nadler's substantial weight.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, D'Amato sent a letter to Schumer in which he
implicitly admitted using the Yiddishism _ but remained on the
attack, asserting that it was Schumer who was trying to ``inject
religious differences'' into the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Making no mention of his earlier denials, D'Amato wrote: ``The
Yiddish word I used to describe you at a private meeting means
`fool.' Again, you are trying to twist that into a religious slur.
And again, I stand by my remark 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Joys of Yiddish,'' by Leo Rosten (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1968), the word ``putz'' is defined as ``vulgar slang for
`penis,''' which is used as ``a term of contempt for a fool'' or
``a jerk.'' Rosten adds a cautionary note: ``Putz is not to be used
lightly or when women or children are around.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's exchange was another example of Schumer using
against D'Amato a weapon that the senator had employed against one
of his own opponents. The congressman's injured tone recalled the
way D'Amato reacted six years ago, almost to the day, after his
Democratic challenger, Robert Abrams, called D'Amato a ``fascist.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato presented himself as a sympathetic figure under attack,
and forced Abrams, then the state attorney general, to defend
himself against allegations of anti-Italian bias.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's impolitic description of two of New York City's
best-known Democratic members of Congress was not entirely out of
character for the senator, who once used a fake Japanese accent to
mock Lance Ito, the Japanese-American judge in the O.J. Simpson
murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   But D'Amato, a disciplined politician, normally keeps a tight
rein on his public utterances in the middle of a campaign. And some
of his advisers expressed concern Wednesday night that his remarks,
coupled with criticism over D'Amato's Holocaust news conference,
could pose a problem for the senator.
</P>
<P>
   There clearly was an element of calculation in Schumer's attack.
Although he and Nadler had accused D'Amato of politicizing the
Holocaust after the Sunday news conference at the Holocaust
Memorial Wall across from the United Nations, Schumer did not
mention his lost relatives until Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NY     10-21 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS: DEMOCRAT IS GAINING IN RACE  
 WASHINGTON STATE: MONEY AND MESSAGE  
 ALASKA: REPUBLICAN CANDIDATE IS ADRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats don't always win in Massachusetts. But mostly they do.
So with less than two weeks to go to Election Day, can the
Democratic candidate for governor, Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger, overtake his Republican opponent, Acting Gov. Paul
Cellucci?
</P>
<P>
   He is closing in.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Harshbarger was down 10 points or so in the polls.
But now, according to the latest Boston Herald poll, he has cut
that deficit in half.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger has been hammering Cellucci hard recently, asserting
in campaign advertising that the acting governor has yet to
adequately explain how he could be some $700,000 in personal debt.
Independent voters in particular appear to have responded favorably
to the advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger still has a steep hill to climb. His voter base
is shaky, with many Democrats lukewarm about his candidacy because
they remember that he once politically challenged a Kennedy, and on
another occasion aggressively investigated possible wrongdoing by
some party members.
</P>
<P>
   Equally difficult for Harshbarger, he must overcome the built-in
advantage that Cellucci has as an incumbent running in economic
good times. That advantage is enhanced considerably by the fact
that the acting governor is a liberal Republican, and thus not all
that ideologically different from Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Money and Message in Washington State
</P>
<P>
   Going into this year's Washington state race for a U.S. Senate
seat, many state and national Republican leaders insisted that
their candidate, Rep. Linda Smith of Vancouver, had a real shot at
unseating the Democratic incumbent, Patty Murray. But would they
put their money where their mouth is?
</P>
<P>
   Not wholeheartedly, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith has good conservative credentials _ strong enough,
political analysts say, to guarantee her a hefty Republican vote.
She also has a strong populist streak, which analysts believe will
stand her well with independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Smith is having trouble getting her message out.
</P>
<P>
   Her outspoken support for campaign-finance reform has come back
to haunt her. Because she refuses to take many types of campaign
contributions, she is running low on money and is unable to match
her opponent's big television advertising campaign. The latest
polls have Ms. Smith trailing by nearly 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals for money to the Republican Senate Campaign Committee,
run by Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, an outspoken opponent of
campaign-finance reform, have mostly been ignored. The committee
could legally give Ms. Smith up to $540,000 but has sent only
$17,500, without explaining why.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated Washington state party officials last week sent word
to the national party and to McConnell that if they were not going
to help the Smith campaign, they should stop all money
solicitations in the state.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Ms. Smith announced that she had just been sent
$100,000 by the Republican National Committee, a gift that she
gladly accepted. The national committee can accept gifts from
sources that Ms. Smith will not accept gifts from. How, then, could
she accept such money?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said it was not an issue for her, because she did not
know who gave the money to the committee, and thus there could be
no quid pro quo on her part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate hypocrisy,'' Sen. Murray shot back.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Candidate Is Adrift in Alaska
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska governor's race has taken another topsy-turvy turn,
one that very well might doom whatever slim chance the Republican
nominee, John Lindauer, had.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Republican leaders in the state questioned whether
the party should continue to support Lindauer, given that there
were so many confusing and unanswered questions about the source of
his $2 million in campaign funds. He insisted that everything was
aboveboard, and the party leaders backed off.
</P>
<P>
   But questions continued to arise, with a least one Alaskan
filing suit in an effort to get a more detailed answer _ or, in the
absence of one, to have Lindauer thrown off the ballot. Was there
or wasn't there a secret financial source, something not permitted
under Alaska law?
</P>
<P>
   Lindauer, a retired newspaper publisher, insisted initially that
he was spending his own money. Then he said it was his wealthy
wife's money. Then he said he was broke. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Republican leaders announced that the party was
withdrawing its support of Lindauer because of all the confusion
and contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   The party chairman, Tom McKay, said Lindauer would, of course,
remain on the ballot, pending any court action on the citizen's
suit. But he added that the party would ``rally around in a big
way'' should a prominent Alaska Republican step forward to start a
write-in campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something we're having fun doing,'' McKay said.
``But it's necessary to preserve the Republican Party as a viable
institution in Alaska politics.''
</P>
<P>
   If past results in Alaskan elections for governor are any
indication, there is not much viability to preserve. The last time
a Republican won the office was 20 years ago, and political
analysts say this year's Democratic incumbent, Tony Knowles, a
moderate, has few re-election concerns, particularly in light of
Tuesday's decision by Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Lindauer, a conservative, vowed to push on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't lie about the source of my income,'' he said. ``The
party lied that I lied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
