A0046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASTRO-COX     10-21 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTRO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers seek punishment for Castro
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Many Cuban-Americans say they want Fidel Castro to
suffer the same fate that befell former Chilean dictator Augusto
Pinochet, who is in British custody in connection with the deaths
of several Spaniards during his 17-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by Pinochet's arrest Friday on a Spanish warrant,
eight members of the House of Representatives have sent a letter to
President Clinton asking him to bring Castro to justice for the
deaths of four Cuban-American aviators two years ago. In addition,
the Cuban American National Foundation, the largest anti-Castro
lobbying group in the United States, said Wednesday it is putting
together a team of American and international lawyers to try to
have the Cuban dictator arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that Pinochet is responsible for applies to Fidel
Castro,'' said Ninoska Perez, a spokeswoman for the Miami-based
lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish judge has ordered Pinochet extradited from London,
where he underwent back surgery, to face trial on charges of
genocide, torture and terrorism. The Spanish National Court is
expected to rule on the case soon.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, who assumed power in 1973 during a U.S.-backed coup
that toppled democratically elected Socialist President Salvador
Allende, cannot be prosecuted in Chile for the deaths and torture
of nearly 3,000 people because he has immunity as a
senator-for-life. He relinquished power to a civilian regime in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cuban exiles see a parallel to Castro, who has ruled the
island nation since 1959. Castro's foes say he should be held
responsible for the downing of two Brothers to the Rescue airplanes
in international airspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without minimizing the immensity of Castro's crimes
perpetrated throughout the last 40 years,'' the eight lawmakers
said in their letter to Clinton, ``the killing of Americans in the
Florida Straits on Feb. 24, 1996, clearly provides the basis for
immediate legal action by the Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers urged U.S. authorities to examine the Pinochet
case and to take similar steps against Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the lawmakers' attempt to nab Castro is
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not underestimate the importance of such a move,''
said Robert Pastor, who served on President Carter's National
Security Council and is a visiting professor at Harvard. ``What
they're saying is, `If it applies to one, it can apply to the
other.' No tyrant can feel he can travel with immunity anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers' attempt, he said, is ``symbolic but not
insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, dated Monday, was signed by Republican Reps. Lincoln
Diaz-Balart and Ileana Ros-Lehtinen of Florida; Dana Rohrabacher
and William Thomas of California; Michael Forbes, Gerald Solomon
and Peter King of New York; and Democratic Rep. Robert Menendez of
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
