<HEADER>
A0050 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDREWS22-COX     10-21 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDREWS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andres County awaiting TNRCC vote on radioactive waste site
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If a state commission shoots down a plan to
build a radioactive waste disposal facility near Sierra Blanca,
Andrews County, an oil-patch West Texas community on the New Mexico
border, has laid out the welcome mat for the site.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission is scheduled
to cast a long-awaited vote this morning on whether to grant the
Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal Authority a license to
operate a site near Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   As critics from both sides of the border attack the Sierra
Blanca site, Lloyd Eisenrich, president of the Andrews Industrial
Foundation, continues to sell his county's amenities: low rainfall,
an existing private site with permits to dispose of dangerous
waste, a deep water table below hundreds of feet of clay, and
perhaps most importantly, a population that has made its living
from the oil fields and isn't alarmed by the idea of radioactive
waste nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews County made an unsuccessful pitch for the site in the
late 1980s, and ``We've just been kind of sitting in the wings for
10 years,'' said Eisenrich.
</P>
<P>
   The business that Eisenrich would like to see run Texas' site is
Waste Control Specialists, which in 1997 opened a 1,300-acre
facility straddling the Texas-New Mexico border. Located 30 miles
west of Andrews, the county seat, the site disposes of hazardous
and toxic waste in a lined landfill and already stores some types
of radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Hance, chairman of the company's board, said the facility
opened in 1997 and has submitted a 5,000-page application to the
U.S. Department of Energy for a license to accept federal waste.
</P>
<P>
   Hance, a well-connected former state and federal lawmaker who
has contributed at least $15,000 to Gov. George W. Bush this
election cycle, said the company could move quickly to accommodate
a disposal site because it already has done exhaustive enviromental
impact studies.
</P>
<P>
   Even if regulators refused a license for the Sierra Blanca site
and favored Andrews, lawmakers _ which originally mandated that the
state run a facility in Hudspeth County _ would still have to enact
new legislation to move the site and allow it to be run by a
private company.
</P>
<P>
   Hance said his company is willing to discuss deeding land to the
state and letting the state run the site. ``All that could be
worked out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state would also have to settle questions about the site's
proximity to an important aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Diamond, spokeswoman for the Texas Low-Level Radioactive
Waste Disposal Authority, said they excluded Andrews County as a
potential site a decade ago because the county is within the
recharge area for the Ogallala Aquifer _ which extends from the
Dakotas to northern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have never considered that area, not for a moment,''
Diamond said. ``The map that we used (from the Texas Department of
Water Resources) back then clearly shows the recharge area for a
major aquifer over the entire Andrews County area.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Tom Rainwater, an associate professor of civil
engineering at Texas Tech University who was hired as a consultant
by the Andrews Industrial Foundation, said core samples drilled by
Waste Control Specialists shows that the state maps were wrong.
``The reality is that part of Andrews County doesn't really connect
at all to the Ogallala Aquifer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
