<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-BLANCA1022-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decision due on Sierra Blanca
 &HT;    By Ralph Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The worst possible decision the state's top
environmental regulators could make regarding the proposed nuclear
waste site in Sierra Blanca is no decision.
</P>
<P>
   The three members of the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission no doubt feel as if they are under a microscope today as
they decide whether to allow a permit for the waste site. And they
unquestionably are under a microscope with state, national and
international lenses.
</P>
<P>
   The waste site, to be located near the U.S.-Mexico border in
Hudspeth County, has sparked debate that is both scientific and
emotional. Gov. George W. Bush, who inherited the situation from
predecessor Ann Richards, says that if the site is safe for a
nuclear disposal facility, it should be built. If it's not safe, it
shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   Local, state and congressional officials of the Mexican
government also express opposition, while members of the Zedillo
administration are either neutral or cautiously support the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, experts argue both sides of the safety issue while
industry officials argue for its need.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition on this page to using Hudspeth County land to
dump nuclear waste has been consistent and we reiterate that
opposition today.
</P>
<P>
   After all the rhetoric, the dueling analyses and the political
considerations are weighed, however, the three members of the
commission today bear the responsibility of reaching a decision. To
postpone would make an already bad situation worse for two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   The decision won't be the final word on the matter. Too much
time, money and emotion have been invested in the site for either
side to let go. Hudspeth County Attorney Tom Chellis has threatened
to sue to keep the site out of the county. There is no reason not
to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, proponents of the site can't be expected to just go
away quietly if the decision goes against them.
</P>
<P>
   A decision today would set events in motion that would
ultimately lead to resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Hudspeth County residents have lived in this political limbo
long enough. Although it will be years before the matter is
ultimately resolved, at least an end will be brought to the initial
skirmishing. And the people of Hudspeth County will be in a
position to decide whether they want to live there any more.
</P>
<P>
   A decision today would be most welcome in another way. A
decision should spark the incoming Legislature to take a look at
the process, and we urge that the incoming administration and
legislative leadership work with the U.S. Congress to streamline
the selection process and make it as understandable as possible to
the communities that are asked to host the site.
</P>
<P>
   The decision today will not please everyone. Most decisions
don't. But deciding will at least let the various parties involved
know what they need to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
