A0053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-RACISM-HIGHER-ED-C     10-21 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-RACISM-HIGHER-ED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT observing National Days of Action on Wednesday
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Despite wanting him to shut up and go away,
supporters of restoring affirmative action at the University of
Texas said Wednesday their efforts are less focused this year
without a Lino Graglia to mobilize the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Graglia, a UT law professor and longtime foe of affirmative
action, galvanized the campus last fall when he said blacks and
Mexican Americans were not competitive with whites in selective
schools like UT because their cultures did not look on failure in
disgrace. The remarks captured national attention and sparked a
series of protests at UT that culminated in a huge rally led by
two-time presidential candidate Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no Lino Graglia to sort of spark the passion, but that
doesn't mean it's not there,'' said Bob Jensen, who teaches
journalism and who helped organize two panel discussions Wednesday
to put a spotlight back on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The events continue today with a West Mall protest rally and
news conference by the Anti-Racist Organizing Committee. The
activities are in conjunction with National Days of Action at other
schools where affirmative action has been attacked. Walkouts were
planned at the University of California at Berkeley, where minority
enrollments have dropped significantly because of an affirmative
action ban, and at the University of Michigan, which is being sued
by the Center for Individual Rights for admissions policies the
center called discriminatory against whites.
</P>
<P>
   The center succeeded with a similar suit against UT. The case,
known as Hopwood, effectively dismantled affirmative action
programs at Texas colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think students are concerned, but there's a feeling right
now that there's nothing to focus on,'' said Peter Haney, a
graduate student in anthropology. ``Obviously, we have a
legislative session coming up, and I'm sure that's something we can
mobilize on.''
</P>
<P>
   UT is appealing the Hopwood ruling, but arguments to the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals probably won't be scheduled until
next spring or summer. And if the case goes to the U.S. Supreme
Court, it could be 2000 or 2001 before the issue of racial
considerations in higher education is resolved, said Betty Owens,
an attorney with Vinson &AMP; Elkins, which is representing UT in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Owens appeared at one of two panel discussions Wednesday
afternoon that each drew about 75 students and explored racism,
access to higher education and the fate of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty and students said that while they wished more of
UT's 49,000 students had attended, they did not detect a lack of
interest in the topic. Nor does Graglia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hot topic,'' said Graglia, noting that he has made
five speeches around the country in the last few weeks. Affirmative
action has ``been on the defensive for a few years, and all that
has done is make it hotter.''
</P>
<P>
   Graglia said that even though only eight blacks and 29 Mexican
Americans were admitted to the first-year law school of 465 at UT
this year, it was better for everyone to know they got in without
the help of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-affirmative action panelists disagreed. Because minorities
have less wealth and because society is not colorblind, affirmative
action has meant access to premier universities and subsequent
access to power, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me what this whole debate is about . . .is a
fairly blatant attempt to maintain white privilege,'' said Robin
Kilson, who teaches history at UT.
</P>
<P>
   Her history department colleague Neil Foley agreed it was time
to shift the discussion about affirmative action to the privileges
whites enjoy. ``When we get into victimization (of minorities) ...
it's a no-win situtation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
