A0054 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINIMED-PLUNGE-LADN     10-21 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-PLUNGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGATIVE NEWSLETTER SPURS MINIMED STOCK SLIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- An unfortunately timed, critical newsletter can
cost a profitable company dearly, as MiniMed Inc. learned Wednesday
when its stock price plunged 16 percent even as it reported strong
third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The insulin pump maker reported that net income climbed a steep
71 percent to nearly $3.2 million, or 23 cents per diluted share,
compared with $1.9 million, or 14 cents per diluted share, from the
comparable year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 39 percent to $34.9 million from last year's $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   Far from lapping up more shares, however, investors unloaded
their stock en masse, pushing the price down $9.50 to close
Wednesday at $58.625. They apparently were spooked by a newsletter
from the Rockville, Md.-based Center for Financial Research and
Analysis Inc. that questioned the Sylmar, Calif.-based firm's
accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   It said MiniMed's July 31 sale of its costly,
still-in-development implantable insulin pump technology to Medical
Research Group LLC, which was founded by MiniMed Chairman Alfred
Mann, would provide an ``artificial boost'' to the company's bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Related-party activities should generally be viewed with
skepticism because they often fail to constitute arm's-length
transactions,'' the newsletter said. ``In this particular case,
CFRA believes that (MiniMed's) decision to sell the assets of its
implantable pump business to MRG will provide (MiniMed) with an
artificial boost to reported earnings by removing certain expenses
from (MiniMed's) income statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The CFRA stated that the company misclassified $1.5 million
payments under a research and development contract with American
Medical Instruments Inc. as a reduction in operating expenses
rather than revenue, wrongly based those payments on a
discretionary milestone stipulated in the contract rather than on
actual receipt of payment, and said those payments constitute a
one-time boost rather than a recurring revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter also noted an eroding gross margin, cash-flow
deficits and an increase in receivables relative to sales as other
causes for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Its evaluation was based on second-quarter financial reports.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Nalbone, a medical devices analyst for Volpe Brown
Whelan in San Francisco, called Monday's newsletter a ``spurious
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement with Medical Research was the sensible approach
to take and is standard practice for medical products companies,
Nalbone said. In addition, the $1.5 million quarterly milestone
payments are likely to recur through the end of 1999 and are a
legitimate item to book each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was reiterating his ``buy'' recommendation for
MiniMed stock, adding that the depreciated price creates a prime
opportunity for investors to pick up a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very solid company; it's clearly the technological
leader in the diabetes care area,'' Nalbone said. ``We just hate to
see people focused on incorrect issues. This is a really solid
company, and their growth prospects are intact.''
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed President and Chief Operating Officer Terrance Gregg
said investment bankers and analysts are calling ``to tell them
what a great buy (our stock) is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a company, we're not going to respond to (the
criticisms),'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
