<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CHANDLER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler still sore, likely will miss Jets game
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler did not
practice Wednesday and will have to make a strong improvement to
have any chance of playing Sunday against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler jogged and threw passes of 12-to-15 yards to trainer
Ron Medlin, but his left arm, held tightly against his side,
obviously was bothering him. He's listed as questionable on the
injury report, which translates to a 50-50 situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chris does not practice (today), I would say he'll be
doubtful,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. ``He didn't make as much
progress from yesterday to today as we hoped. He's had trouble
sleeping. And when you don't sleep, a lot of times that's where
healing takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the decision would be Chandler's and could be made
as late as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, 33, left Sunday's game against the Saints with a
strained left, non-throwing shoulder and with bruised tissue around
the ribs beneath the left shoulder blade after being sacked by New
Orleans linebacker Mark Fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can move it around a little bit, but it's very sore,''
Chandler said after practice Wednesday. ``If I can go, I can. If I
can't, I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Medlin said Chandler has no broken bones, torn tendons, muscles
or cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't feel as good today as he has the last two
days,'' Medlin said. ``It's really right under the shoulder blade.
His motion is getting better, but sometimes when he moves it, it's
very sore. The rhomboids, trapezoids and all those muscles come
together in the shoulder, and with a compression blow they get
stretched. We're not discouraged; we're cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chandler can't play, backup Steve DeBerg, 44, will make his
first start since Dec. 13, 1993. He will be trying to lead the team
to its first 6-1 start in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 season, Chandler missed two complete games and parts
of four others, with two concussions, a bruised sternum and a
sprained ankle. Atlanta lost all six.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the offense under DeBerg would be more conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of Steve's strengths are in the play-action area; we'll
probably do more play action,'' Reeves said. ``To say we're going
to be exactly the same would be ridiculous. If Chris doesn't play
... the running game will be that much more important.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
