<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COUCH-CARTER-COX     10-21 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUCH-CARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couch, Carter take different paths to stardom
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three years ago, Quincy Carter and Tim Couch were
considered the nation's top high school quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was a Parade All-American at Southwest DeKalb High,
leading the Panthers to the Class AAAA state title as a senior in
1995. Only Couch, who shattered national passing records for career
completions, yardage and touchdowns at Leslie County High in tiny
Hyden, Ky., was rated higher.
</P>
<P>
   The pair exchanged telephone calls during their senior seasons,
then met in person in the summer at Disney World at an All-America
team gathering. They hit it off immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really got to know Tim in those two days,'' Carter said.
``We were both quarterbacks and had both signed with schools that
weren't doing so well at the time. There were some obvious
similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll meet again Saturday, when No. 11 Georgia faces improved
Kentucky in Lexington in a SEC East showdown. The Wildcats enter
the game 5-2 and are ranked second nationally in passing with
Couch, a Heisman Trophy candidate. And the Bulldogs, 5-1 overall,
haven't missed a beat under Carter, perhaps the nation's top
freshman quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a matchup of the two best quarterbacks in the
country,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``I haven't seen (UCLA's
Cade) McNown play much, so I don't know about the rest of them. But
(Carter) is having a great year, and Couch is too.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players enter the game ranked among the nation's leading
passers _ Couch is 12th nationally in passing efficiency; Carter is
14th. But they took strikingly different paths in getting there.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a 6-foot-3, 220-pounder, never enrolled at Georgia Tech
after signing a letter of intent with the Yellow Jackets in
February 1996. Instead, he signed a minor league baseball contract
with the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised because he was so good coming out of
high school,'' Couch said. ``I thought he'd follow his aspirations
in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch shocked the college football world as well, choosing to
play for Kentucky, which did not have a winning record the previous
six seasons under former coach Bill Curry. Couch turned down
several established programs, including Florida, Notre Dame and
Tennessee, to remain loyal to the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, his marriage with the conservative Curry turned
sour. Curry refused to promote the freshman over returning starter
Billy Jack Haskins in 1996 and later had the strong-armed Couch
running the option in a 65-0 loss to top-ranked Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Couch's life changed as a sophomore, however, when Curry was
fired and Kentucky hired pass-happy coach Hal Mumme, formerly of
Valdosta State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a dream come true to be in an offense that's
geared toward me,'' Couch said. ``I never had any idea that it
would be this much fun. I'm having the greatest time of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than two seasons under Mumme, Couch has rewritten the
Kentucky and SEC record books. He has thrown for at least 300 yards
and one touchdown in every game this season, and leads the nation
in pass completions. Last week, Couch completed 37 of 50 attempts
for 391 yards and three touchdowns in the Wildcats' 39-36 upset of
LSU, earning him SEC player of the week honors for the first time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to take Tim for granted,'' Mumme said, ``and I think
it's something our conference is doing a little bit, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is taking nothing for granted after a lonely two-year
layoff from football. When he decided to return to the sport,
Carter called several friends for advice. He contacted former
Georgia coach Ray Goff. ``He told me to go to North Carolina,''
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   And Carter called Couch, who already had become established as
one of the nation's best in only a few starts a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just asked me what I thought about him playing college
football,'' Couch said. ``I told him that I thought he'd be great
for college football and that he'd be very successful. Obviously,
he's got a great career ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
