<SLUG> BC-FBC-MARTIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves warns against distractions
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves met with the team
Wednesday morning and told players not to be bothered by the report
that receiver Tony Martin is under federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves acknowledged that the news that Martin is suspected
of laundering drug profits for longtime friend and convicted
narcotics trafficker Rickey Brownlee would be a distraction to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. I talked to our football team,'' Reeves said. ``And when
you should be talking about (Sunday's game against) the Jets, you
got to talk about something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said he reminded players, ``You're not guilty by being
investigated.'' Several Falcons said the situation would not cause
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 33, had no comment. But defensive end Chuck Smith turned
his apparent frustrations toward more than 15 journalists and four
or five TV cameras on hand, about three times the usual number of
media representatives. Smith raised his voice and chastised
reporters. He said later, ``I have no problem with the story; it
has to be reported. But it's vulture journalism when all these
people show up who aren't usually here. Where were they when
(Martin) was tearing everybody up (playing football)?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who leads the team with 27 receptions and 492 receiving
yards, practiced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A distraction is anything that you allow to take your focus
off what you're doing,'' fullback Bob Christian said. ``To me, it's
not a distraction. I saw Tony this morning, and he looked like
business as usual. We're there for Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety Devin Bush agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of your own, and you want to support him because
that's what a team is all about,'' Bush said. ``They're just
allegations; they're not true. It might be more of a distraction
for him, but how can we let that happen? We're not little kids.
We're professionals. We've got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony and his lawyers have assured me that they have nothing to
worry about,'' Reeves said. ``Hopefully, that's what comes out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
