</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banged-up Falcons prepare for more of the same Sunday
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons practiced in helmets, shoulder
pads, and shorts Wednesday eschewing the usual full dress because
they're so banged up after last Sunday's 31-23 win over the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   That was by far the most physical game of the season, and this
Sunday's road game against the Jets (3-3) promises to be more of
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler did not practice (see story, page 1),
DT Travis Hall also sat out with a sprained ankle, and, most
importantly, bruised tendon above his knee, and DE Chuck Smith
rested a strained thigh muscle.
</P>
<P>
   All three are questionable (50-50) for Sunday, but count on
Smith playing. Chandler and Hall are another story, although Hall's
chances appear better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it funny on the turf (at the Georgia Dome),'' said Hall,
who is fourth on the team with 39 tackles, has two sacks, 19
quarterback pressures, two tackles for losses, four batted passes,
one fumble forced, two recovered, and two PATs blocked. ``If the
game was today, I couldn't play, but we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall's absence would be huge. He's the team's biggest defender
at 6-feet-5, and 300 pounds, and one of the top tackles in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't go, Esera Tuaolo (6-2, 281) would probably start,
and first-year DT Shawn Swayda (6-5, 290) would probably dress for
the second time. Also, starting left DE Lester Archambeau would
play some at DT, and reserve DE John Burrough would play a little
more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient one
</P>
<P>
   If Chandler can't play, backup Steve DeBerg, 44, would become
the oldest player in NFL history to start a game. The record is
held by Seattle QB Warren Moon, who will turn 42 next month. Former
Oakland QB/K George Blanda at 47 was the oldest to play in the NFL,
but his last start came when he was 41 years, two months old.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg's last start was Dec. 13, 1993, when he completed 27 of
44 passes for 344 yards and a TD for Miami in a 21-20 loss to
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   He was 2-2 as a starter for the Dolphins, including a 16-14 win
at eventual Super Bowl champion Dallas. That was the Thanksgiving
day game on a snow-covered field. Cowboys DT Leon Lett gave the
Dolphins another shot at victory when he mistakenly touched a
rolling ball after a blocked field goal. Miami recovered to get
another field-goal try.
</P>
<P>
   If DeBerg and second-year man Tony Graziani were hurt against
the Jets, and Chandler couldn't take over, it's not clear how
Atlanta would react. Punter Dan Stryzinski has in years past been
emergency QB, but Reeves didn't verify that would happen Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd probably just go to the shotgun, and snap it to (RB)
Jamal (Anderson),'' he said. ``We'll come up with something.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the rest of the Falcons' injury report: Out _
LB Henri Crockett (wrist); questionable _ CB Ronnie Bradford
(abdomen/back muscle); probable _ CB Randy Fuller (hamstring), DT
Shane Dronett (knee), LB Craig Sauer (knee). Jets: Out _ TE Fred
Baxter (knee); questionable _ LB Chad Cascadden (hamstring), S
Chris Hayes (leg).
</P>
<P>
   The last word
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated's soon-to-be-released list of its 10 dirtiest
players includes Falcon C/G Dave Widell _ again. SI says Widell
will hit a defender late, or away from the ball. Seattle G Brian
Habib said of Widell, ``At the end of a play, he'll come up behind
a guy and give him a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Widell, who hasn't dressed the last four games, was Habib's
teammate in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian only says that because he's on the other side of the
country,'' Widell said, laughing. ``He's probably out there having
a good time, working on the '65 GTO he spent $5,000 to buy and
another $25,000 to get running.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   In winning 11 of 14 games, the Falcons last Sunday for the first
time beat a team with a winning record, although the Saints are now
3-3. The combined record of the teams Atlanta has beaten this
season: 7-25. ... The Falcons are tied with Green Bay for second in
the NFL against the run, allowing an average of 85.3 yards per
game. They trail San Diego (72.0). ... The Jets are 3-0 in games
started by quarterback Vinny Testaverde (AFC player of the week
after completing 22-of-32 passes for 294 yards and three TDs in
Monday's 24-14 win at New England). ... Jets RB Curtis Martin has
rushed for more than 100 yards in each New York victory. ... No
running back has had 100 yards against the Falcons in 14 games,
second-longest streak in the NFL (Jacksonville, 18). ... Jets coach
Bill Parcells said Wednesday of Chandler's status: ``He'll play.''
... Atlanta has scored a defensive TD in three straight games for
the first time since 1981. ... CB Ray Buchanan was not fined for
his roughing-the-passer penalty against the Saints. S Devin Bush's
appeal of his fine for a late hit in the Oct. 4 game against
Carolina has not been heard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
