<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-LINE22-CO     10-21 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-LINE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offensive line's unsteadiness vs. blitz still Falcons' Achilles'
heel
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons are 5-1, and there are a few very
good reasons.
</P>
<P>
   They lead the NFL in average time of possession (33:06), they're
second with a plus-eight turnover ratio, and they've scored on 15
of 16 red zone possessions, the only exception being a kneel-down
in the waning seconds of Sunday's 31-23 win over New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But the offensive live remains a concern.
</P>
<P>
   The same unit chiefly responsible for paving the way for running
back Jamal Anderson to lead the NFC in rushing with 644 yards has
allowed 25 sacks _ more than all but five teams, two that have
played one more game.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons say a lot of the problem comes down to a lack of
familiarity with each other, and a resulting lack of trust.
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Bob Whitfield is in his seventh NFL year, and right
guard Gene Williams is in his eighth. But left guard Calvin Collins
is a second-year player who was at center last year. Tobeck was at
left guard, and right tackle Ephraim Salaam is a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are blitzing the Falcons like mad because they see that
Atlanta is having problems picking them up.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the Saints came up with one Atlanta had not seen,
and quarterback Chris Chandler might not play Sunday against the
Jets (3-3) because of it. When New Orleans linebacker Mark Fields
slammed him to the turf on a sack, injuries to the quarterback's
shoulder forced him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy was asking me last week, `Don't you just block the guy
that's over you? But that's not always the case,'' said center
Robbie Tobeck. ``Sometimes teams overload one side, and you have to
slide over.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Saints) criss-crossed all three linebackers, and I should
have kept sliding out (and trusted someone else to pick up the
first blitzer), but instead I picked up the first guy, who wasn't
my man. I should have gone for the second (Fields). The coaches
want us to stay with assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Bob Christian, a key in blitz pickup, said, ``when you
have three guys trying to switch (assignments), they're going to
get you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Saints, the Jets run a vast variety of blitzes,
although they have just 11 sacks, tied for next-to-last in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, meanwhile, is running like never before. The line is
blocking better in the run game than in two years, Christian is
picking off stragglers, and Anderson is running quicker to the
hole, and hard as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest improvement seems to be communication,'' said
Anderson. ``When a play doesn't work, we're talking immediately
about what we can we do to make it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rhythm you get into. You just hit (the hole) and
believe in it. I have a lot of confidence in the guys ... and that
Bobby's going to take care of whoever is (unblocked).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
