A0062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD22-COX     10-21 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flood waters rage through Victoria
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell and Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the Guadalupe River spreading into a flood
six miles wide in spots, emergency crews in Victoria used
helicopters, airboats and a small armada of rowboats to rescue
stranded residents Wednesday, navigating by the tops of street
signs through the record-high water.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was less intense but no less worrisome in Wharton,
where the Colorado River had already flooded 300 homes by Wednesday
afternoon _ and the flood isn't expected to crest until this
evening.
</P>
<P>
   While coastal cities scrambled to cope, upstream counties began
totaling the damage from weekend storms that killed 22 and left
five still missing. The preliminary estimate: $400 million, a
figure that will rise as the floodwaters ebb.
</P>
<P>
   The damage prompted President Clinton to declare 20 South and
Central Texas counties disaster areas, offering federal aid to
supplement local recovery efforts. Additional counties may be added
as damage surveys continue, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster decree was the fourth in Texas since May, a state
record. Two were presidential decrees for Tropical Storms Charley
and Frances, and one was an emergency decree for the summer drought
and wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an incredible year, and it's not over yet,'' said
Jack Colley, assistant state emergency coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, the sun is expected to return today, pushing
through the persistent clouds and lifting temperatures into the low
70s. That will be welcome news to the thousands of flood victims
who picked through soggy, mud-caked possessions Wednesday with
temperatures in the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   The nights will be on the chilly side, dipping into the 40s
tonight and Friday night. The next chance of rain appears to be
Sunday or Monday _ ``but it doesn't look like heavy rain,'' said
Bob Rose, meteorologist for the Lower Colorado River Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime in Caldwell County, the search continued for Devin
McCoy, the 6-year-old swept into Brushy Creek near Uhland on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Devin's mother had tried to cross the creek when her Suburban
was carried downstream. She and another child survived. On Tuesday,
divers found the Suburban in 27 feet of water and recovered the
body of Heather Cottle, 11, a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   A search dog was taken along a small lake downstream of where
the Suburban was found. A game warden and a Caldwell County
sheriff's deputy also searched the lake by boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty much going to be the routine,'' said Caldwell
County Sheriff Mike Bading. ``We'll go out every day to check. I
assume that in the days to come we will fly the area also.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officers from Bexar and Atascosa counties resumed
searching today for a family of four missing since Saturday.
Richard Hartman, his mother, daughter-in-law and 2-year-old
granddaughter had attended a wedding in eastern Bexar County but
did not return to their suburban San Antonio home.
</P>
<P>
   In hard-hit Victoria 120 miles south of Austin, an overnight
curfew was in effect as emergency workers estimated that one-third
of the city remained underwater. Electricity was slowly being
restored as water receded from the power plant, but gas service
remained out at more than 500 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's water rescues included parents with a 5-month-old
baby and two workers at the Texas Zoo who had to be removed through
a hole in a zoo building roof. The fate of the animals was not
immediately known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the folks were neck-deep in water by the time help
reached them,'' said one dispatch to the State Emergency Management
Center in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, the rescues were mostly over and the
floodwaters had begun to recede. Three shelters remained open and
two National Guard helicopters were ferrying supplies into flooded
areas.
</P>
<P>
   South of Victoria, a DuPont chemical plant near Bloomington was
the scene of ``a made-for-movie drama,'' Colley said.
</P>
<P>
   At about 6:30 a.m., workers began scrambling to move several
chemical-filled barges from a canal before rising water prevented
them from floating under the Texas 35bridge. Left unattended,
officials said, the huge barges could have become battering rams in
the swirling waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got them out _ just in time,'' Colley said.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical plant was quickly shut down, as were three others
father downstream, Colley said. State environmental officials
remained to watch for leaks or other problems, but none were
reported, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Wharton, 120 miles southeast of Austin, more than 60,000
sandbags and 15 military trucks were deployed by midday. Evacuation
sites were moved 12 miles away to El Campo after officials realized
that potential shelters would be flooded. A dusk-to-dawn curfew was
instituted in evacuated areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to inundate probably 40 percent of the city of
Wharton,'' said Wharton County Judge Lawrence E. Naiser. ``It's
just coming up and up.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the flooding will be six to 12 inches deep in homes,
Naiser said. The LCRA predicts the crest could persist through the
weekend in the flatlands around Wharton, the last city expected to
flood before the Colorado River empties its floodwater into the
Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's federal disaster declaration will provide grants for
temporary housing, home and business repairs and other expenses.
The counties listed were Bastrop, Bexar, Burleson, Caldwell,
Calhoun, Colorado, Comal, DeWitt, Fayette, Goliad, Gonzales,
Guadalupe, Hays, Jackson, Karnes, Refugio, Travis, Victoria,
Wharton and Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   With disaster relief offices already open in Houston and Del Rio
to aid victims of earlier storms, state officials said they plan to
open a new disaster field office in San Antonio _ where they will
probably consolidate operations from the other two offices. From
the San Antonio office, federal and state agencies will operate
recovery centers in the hardest-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   Classrooms reopened Wednesday in Comal County, one of the
hardest-hit areas of Central Texas, with counselors available for
students and teachers. School officials were anxious to help
students regain a sense of normalcy, said Don Clark, school
district spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nurses. It's a warm building. We have warm food _ some
of these kids haven't had a decent meal for days,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuero, where the Guadalupe River crested Tuesday 30 feet
above flood stage, hundreds of homes and two-thirds of the town
remained underwater Wednesday. At least 1,600 people were in area
shelters and power was out in many locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the (homes) that were flooded pretty much lost
everything they owned,'' said Nancy O'Neal, an emergency center
volunteer. ``Everybody is anxious to see what the damage is.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 33 shelters remained open Wednesday night, housing
2,200 people, American Red Cross officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental clean-up crews were picking up spilled limestone
and lime products where three Longhorn Railway cars derailed
Tuesday evening in a tributary of Boggy Creek in far East Austin.
Floods washed out some railroad pilings on a bridge, causing the
derailment on the Austin-Northwestern Railroad line, said Don
Cheatham, owner of Longhorn Railway.
</P>
<P>
   If uncontained, the spill's high alkaline content could
contribute to a major fish kill. Capital Metro, which owns the
railroad line, has hired an environmental company to contain the
spill.
</P>
<P>
   In San Marcos, which received 22 1/2 inches of rain since
Saturday, flood victims were told to register for assistance in
person at the San Marcos Activity Center, 501 E. Hopkins. Cleanup
kits with shovels, sponges and water vacuums are also available. At
least 70 homes received at least a foot of water, while 706 homes
had 2 or more inches, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bastrop County raised its damage estimates to 160 homes
destroyed and 240 damaged. Preliminary damage is estimated at $3.5
million, said County Judge Peggy Walicek.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers Andy Alford, Debbie Hiott and
Rebeca Rodriguez contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
