<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-SUPREME-COURT-RACE     10-21 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-SUPREME-COURT-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spector held back by party label
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ November's ballot lists eight candidates for the
Texas Supreme Court, but the Rose Spector-Harriet O'Neill race may
tell the story of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from their campaign contributors, both enjoy wide
respect as judges from lawyers pushing and pulling over how much _
and how _ lawsuits should be restricted in Texas. But regardless of
her qualifications or experience or respect, Spector's party label
alone _ Democrat _ may end her judicial career.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas _ one of only a handful of states that select Supreme
Court justices by partisan election _ the emerging Republican era
forecasts a singular political mindset for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Most Texas voters don't know much about judicial races, and they
respond to that uncertainty by voting Republican on statewide
judicial candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If voters hit an unfamiliar name, they'll lean Republican,''
says political science professor Anthony Champagne of the
University of Texas at Dallas, who studies Texas judicial politics.
``Even though they may call themselves independent voters, they
have voted Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Spector's upset of an incumbent six years
ago, then a San Antonio trial judge backed by personal-injury and
consumer lawyers, every race but one for the court this decade has
ended in a Republican victory. Republicans hold a 7-2 majority.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Raul Gonzalez's retirement at the end of the year would
leave Spector the only Democrat among judges who, ironically,
grapple with legal questions based on complex judicial philosophies
that usually defy partisan considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some friends of mine told me the 'D' behind my name is sort of
like putting a target on it,'' Spector says about her ballot
listing. ``But I'm cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Not flush with campaign money _ O'Neill has a 2-to-1
fund-raising advantage _ Spector drives herself across Texas for
campaign appearances in her 1994 Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, 40, says the race frames philosophical differences
between her and Spector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I would define the differences in our judicial
philosophy that I am a judicial conservative,'' O'Neill says.
</P>
<P>
   That means strictly interpreting state statutes according to the
Legislature's intentions and resisting by court-made common law the
creation of new possibilities for lawsuits. Spector's philosophy
shows inconsistency, she says.
</P>
<P>
   She offers no examples. In constrained judicial campaigning,
candidates don't detail why they fault an opponent's record. That
might venture into telling voters how they would decide a case _
and that's unethical.
</P>
<P>
   So O'Neill and Spector campaign by meeting with lawyers,
newspapers editors, anyone they can. They tout their experience and
call themselves judicial conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't recall,'' Champagne says, ``how many candidates in
recent years have identified themselves as 'judicial conservatives
with proven records.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But this year, with the exception of Spector, the Democrats
running for the court contend the court has been anything but
conservative. They say judicial conservatism means ensuring
consistency in the law by deciding cases according to legal
precedent. These Democrats _ state district Judge Mike Westergren
of Corpus Christi; Austin civil lawyer David Van Os, a onetime
labor union attorney; and Killeen lawyer Jerry Scarbrough , a
former gas station owner who attended Baylor Law School while he
served as Bell County justice of the peace _ argue that the court
has instead changed personal injury and consumer protection law in
ways that benefit business and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awfully funny to me that they come down 8-to-1 or
9-to-nothing time and again and usually on the side of the
defendant,'' says Scarbrough, who is challenging Justice Deborah
Hankinson, the latest of Gov. George W. Bush's three appointments
to the court. ``Law that comes out of a one-sided court is not very
good law and can't stand the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   To see the debate over judicial philosophy and judicial politics
in real terms, consider last year's Supreme Court decision in
Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc. v. Havner. The court overturned a
jury's $3.7 million verdict for a girl born without fingers on one
hand and left her with nothing. Her lawyers had contended a
morning-sickness drug her mother took during pregnancy caused the
birth defect.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Priscilla Owen held for the unanimous court _ Spector
included _ that Texas' method for evaluating a scientific expert's
testimony needed to be changed. Then the court decided on its own
that scientific evidence in the Havner case could not support the
birth-defect claim.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's attorney, Robert Hilliard of Corpus Christi, said
justice and fairness should have allowed him to retry the case
according to the new rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept under our system that they are free as political
judges to change the law,'' Hilliard says. What angered him, he
says, is ``that they changed (the law) and didn't allow me to meet
the new burden.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge who presided over the Havner case, Westergren,
criticizes the court for being too ready to ignore juries in too
many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court has had a total disregard for jury verdicts,''
Westergren says. ``I want restoration of a true balance without an
agenda, either plaintiffs' or defendants'.''
</P>
<P>
   Westergren, who ran once before for the Supreme Court,
emphasizes that the Havner case had no bearing on his decision to
run against Justice Craig Enoch this year. For his part, Enoch says
the Havner opinion's reasoning speaks for itself. His philosophy as
a judge _ judicial conservatism and restraint _ has not changed
since his election to the court in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond each of the Supreme Court races this year are money
questions adding a new dimension to these traditionally staid
campaigns: How much to spend to get name recognition? How much in
contributions comes from lawyers and litigants with cases before
the court?
</P>
<P>
   How much will an impending ``60 Minutes'' report on these how
much questions affect the election?
</P>
<P>
   Of the Democrats, Spector has raised the most money _ close to
$500,000, maybe enough for a small broadcast ad campaign _ but even
she trails far behind O'Neill's $840,000. Westergren, Scarbrough
and Van Os count their money in the thousands of dollars, not
hundreds of thousands or millions.
</P>
<P>
   Van Os has collected just over $100,000 through the latest
reporting period. Scarbrough listed less than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have enough to do anything to get out a statewide
campaign,'' says Champagne, counting Spector among them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Van Os' and Westergren's money has come in relatively
small amounts, the larger amounts from smaller law firms or perhaps
labor committees.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, their opponents _ Justices Greg Abbott and Enoch _
both listed contributions through Sept. 24 totaling more than $1
million, much of it from large defense-oriented law firms or
political committees representing corporate, medical and insurance
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same contributors gave to Hankinson, Spector and
O'Neill, although in smaller amounts. Spector and O'Neill also got
several larger contributions from personal-injury and consumer
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Special-interest money is no stranger to Supreme Court
campaigns. But this year's differs from the past by sometimes loud
barking from two so-called watchdog organizations tied up outside
the court. One _ Court Watch, a spinoff of a consumer-activist
group _ contends from counting winners instead of analyzing
opinions that the court favors business defendants instead of
consumers. The other _ Texans for Public Justice _ tracks the
business, legal and political interests behind the court's campaign
contributions and raises conflict-of-interest questions because of
millions given from lawyers and even litigants with cases on
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne, for one, doubts the noise will have any bearing on
the outcomes. Even the anxiously awaited follow-up ``60 Minutes''
report on the court's campaign contributions should have no effect,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing investigation in 1987, the CBS news program found
contributors actively lobbying justices for decisions from what was
then a decidedly pro-plaintiff court. One fearful scenario has ``60
Minutes'' broadcasting its newest story days before the election,
sending the court's Republican justices searching for work just as
Democrats did after the first report 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne dismisses the ``60 Minutes'' report and its doomsday
prospect for incumbent Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's grossly overestimated,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But few, if any, of this year's court candidates applaud the
high-stakes campaigning or the time spent raising the money.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill wonders why the Legislature won't adopt nonpartisan
election for judges, or set a judicial election date apart from the
cram-it-all-in general election for all statewide offices, or
eliminate straight-ticket voting for judges.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Spector says she's often asked, why take campaign
contributions at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer, unfortunately, is I want to be re-elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
