<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slow fade: Ex-champ Barkley to fight at Roxy
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He won a world middleweight championship 10 years ago
over Thomas Hearns and has headlined shows in Las Vegas, Atlantic
City and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 38, several years and 65 pounds past his prime, Iran
Barkley has arrived where many former marquee boxers seem headed:
Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, having ballooned to a heavyweight in hopes of some day
landing a title shot _ or at least a significant pay day _
headlines tonight's card at the Roxy. Two months ago, Tyrell Biggs
was the main event.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who will fight an obscurity named Caseny(cq) Truesdale,
knows he is a long way from neon and might never make it back. In
recent months, he has fought in North Carolina, Missouri, Illinois,
North Dakota, Virginia, Iowa and Oklahoma. He estimates that 225
pounds hang on his 6-foot-1 frame and admits he was as high as 236
for a recent win over Marcello Aravena. When Barkley knocked out
Hearns in 1988, he weighed 160.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm barnstorming,'' Barkley said with a chuckle. ``I have to
be realistic about this. I've got to fight often and stay active
and take whatever comes my way. I'm not getting offers from (major
promoters). If my situation calls for me to fight in Iowa or the
Roxy, I'll be there. I don't mean to say anything detrimental about
those places, but it's not Caesars Palace.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley makes no secret as to why he still is fighting: ``Money.
People can say what they want, but no athlete fights for any reason
other than money.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``Every day puts me one day closer to retirement.'' But
first, he would like to get a shot at Herbie Hide, who owns the
lesser WBO belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can win that,'' Barkley said, ``then come back here to
Atlanta and knock on that guy's door _ you know, the one who has
two other belts.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Evander Holyfield to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield update
</P>
<P>
   Officials on all sides of negotiations for the Holyfield-Lennox
Lewis fight continue to say that even though there are unresolved
issues, none can be classified as deal-breakers and that the
contracts for the title unification bout should be completed by
early next week. ``There's nothing unusual about this; it's a
complex deal,'' said Milt Chwasky, one of Lewis' attorneys.
Promoter Don King has four different sets of contracts _ with
Holyfield, Lewis, Time Warner and Lewis' promoters, whom King is
buying out for this fight. All issues revolve around money, such as
liability if pay-per-view flops and King's desire to have options
on Lewis if he wins. Lewis promoter Dino Duva says the contract
that King sent him is not the same one that had been agreed to
verbally. There's been in no hurry to complete the agreement during
the World Series, particularly with the Yankees playing. Coverage
in New York newspapers can be key to a promotion's success.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in South Africa, meanwhile, have expressed interest in
hosting the Holyfield-Lewis fight, but commercial demands dictate
the bout likely will be held in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line
</P>
<P>
   Although the Holyfield-Vaughn Bean fight at the Georgia Dome
drew an announced crowd of 41,357 for a ticket value of $3.539
million, the Dome box office recorded sales of 29,286, for a gate
of $2.419 million. King's office confirmed that of the remaining
12,071 tickets, with a value of $1.12 million, King and Holyfield
bought 9,000 to distribute to Atlanta-area youth groups. The rest
were assorted complimentary seats, advertising tradeouts and the
like. The Georgia general treasury took in $203,392 _ $159,000 in
sales tax and $44,392 generated by the Georgia Boxing Commission's
2 percent take of the live gate, pretax. The Georgia Dome received
a flat fee rent of $125,000. ... Roy Jones Jr. has resumed his
pursuit of Holyfield. The problem is that only one guy thinks it
would be a great fight. ... The IBF is arranging a boxoff among
four top-10 contenders _ Frans Botha vs. John Ruiz and Hasim Rahman
vs. David Tua, then winner vs. winner _ to determine an eventual
mandatory challenge to the IBF champion, currently Holyfield. ...
Former Tyson co-manager John Horne is suing new Tyson adviser
Shelly Finkel, seeking 10 percent of the fighter's next five
purses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
