A0069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTES22-C     10-21 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU's strength is defense
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When you think of Florida State, you think Bobby
Bowden, high-octane offense, trick plays and all that jazz. Over
the past 11 years, no high-profile program has lit up the
scoreboard as much.
</P>
<P>
   But in his private moments, Bowden will tell you the real reason
Florida State has finished in the top four 11 seasons in a row has
nothing to do with offense. Florida State's unprecedented string of
10 or more wins every season over that span began not long after
Bowden hired Mickey Andrews as defensive coordinator. It is not a
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '80s, Bowden learned what Florida's Steve Spurrier
would learn in the '90s. All that sizzle on offense is fun and
might sell a bunch of tickets, but you're not going to win a
championship _ any championship _ without a nationally ranked
defense.
</P>
<P>
   In steps, Andrews, who played for Bear Bryant at Alabama,
learned his trade at a number of stops, including North Alabama,
Clemson, Florida and the Arizona Wranglers of the USFL. Andrews was
getting his taste of professional football when Bowden persuaded
him to come to Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best at what he does,'' Bowden said. ``All I do is
just get out of the way and let him coach. I don't stick my nose
into the defensive huddle much any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden also promised Andrews that he would get his fair share of
the great athletes that came to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we've been successful is we've had great players
here,'' Andrews said. ``You can scheme all day long and put them in
the right place to make the play. But they don't have the ability,
you're going to get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews' standing in college football was ratified two years
ago. The Frank Broyles Award goes to the best assistant coach in
the nation. The first one went to Mickey Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   It was Andrews' defense that kept Florida State together when
the offense was bent on self-destruction earlier this season. And
with Georgia Tech averaging 39.8 points, defense again will be the
key for the Seminoles in Saturday's game. The Seminoles, despite
some injuries at linebacker, lead the nation in total defense
(214.1 yards per game).
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking
</P>
<P>
   Orange Bowl site still uncertain
</P>
<P>
   _ Discussions continue between the Bowl Championship Series and
the Orange Bowl over the site of this year's game, set for Jan. 2.
It was originally scheduled for Pro Player Stadium, located north
of Miami, but the NFL playoffs pose a potential conflict. The bowl
series is hoping for an agreement that the NFL will not schedule a
game at Pro Player on that date, if the Dolphins make the playoffs.
If the NFL will not give that assurance, the game could be moved
back to the old Orange Bowl, which could cause some problems. SEC
Commissioner Roy Kramer, the coordinator of the Bowl Championship
Series, hopes to have some kind of resolution by Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   _ The last time Auburn was 1-5 (1952), the Tigers went on to
finish with a 2-8 record in coach Shug Jordan's second season. A
guy named Vince Dooley was the quarterback. The next year Auburn
was 7-3-1 and went to the Gator Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think Notre Dame is looking forward to the next four weeks?
The next four games for the Irish are against Army, Baylor, Boston
College and Navy. Notre Dame's record against those four schools is
104-19-5. Then, it's struggling LSU and underachieving Southern
California to finish out the season. If you're an Irish fan, it
would be smart to book a hotel room in Pasadena right now.
</P>
<P>
   _ This time of year there are a lot of hot coaching rumors, but
here's my favorite: Lou Holtz to Oklahoma to replace John Blake.
The Sooners have fallen on hard times and are averaging about
20,000 empty seats per home game. The athletic department is
drowning in a sea of debt. Holtz is just crazy enough _ and that's
meant as a compliment _ to think he could turn that place around.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's Franklin honored by Ole Miss
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN's Ron Franklin will team with Mike Gottfried and Adrian
Karsten to broadcast Saturday night's game between Georgia Tech and
Florida State at Bobby Dodd Stadium. Franklin will not arrive in
Atlanta until Saturday morning because Friday night he will be
inducted into the Ole Miss Hall of Fame. Congratulations to one of
the really good guys in the business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even the wife of Temple coach Bobby Wallace benefited
fromSaturday's stunning 28-24 upset of Virginia Tech. She received
three dozen roses from entertainer Bill Cosby, Temple's most famous
alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   _ The SEC is in the process of completing a deal to place one of
its teams in the Independence Bowl. The deal is expected to be for
three years and would pit the SEC against a team from the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   _ This from Ohio State's Rob Murphy, who takes the term
``offensive'' lineman literally: ``I'm a dirty player. That's the
attitude you have to have. You do what you have to do to survive.
Sometimes it's breaking those rules.''
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers
</P>
<P>
   375 _ The number of career games coached by Florida State's
Bobby Bowden, second only to Penn State's Joe Paterno (384) among
active coaches. Bowden's won 287 of them.
</P>
<P>
   .723 _ Passing percentage of Central Florida quarterback Daunte
Culpepper, which leads Division I.
</P>
<P>
   5 _ Number of turnovers committed by Florida State in its last
five games, after turning the ball over nine times in the first two
games.
</P>
<P>
   42.8 _ Average number of points scored by Georgia Tech in its
five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
