<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-CAPSULES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama takes on Tennessee Saturday
 &HT;    Tony Barnhart and Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALABAMA at Tennessee, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama has practiced with loud speakers blaring to simulate
crowd noise in an effort to prepare quarterback Andrew Zow for
Saturday night's game at Tennessee. ...Coach Mike DuBose said the
Crimson Tide's best hope against the No. 3 Volunteers is to control
the ball and keep Tennessee's offense off the field. ``If we have
to play 80-plus snaps defensively it's going to be a long afternoon
for us,'' he said. ...Coaches are looking at several players to
replace free safety Kevin Sigler, who is out for the season after
tearing a knee ligament against East Carolina. Sigler underwent
surgery on Monday to repair a torn lateral collateral ligament in
his right knee. Sophomore Tony Dixon will move from strong safety
to free safety and Marcus Spencer will play strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS at Auburn, Oct. 31
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks, who moved to 6-0 after a comeback 41-28 win at
South Carolina, are ranked No. 12 this week by USA Today/ESPN and
15th by the AP and are one of the last eight undefeated teams in
Division I-A. ...Coach Houston Nutt became the first Arkansas coach
to go 6-0 in his first season. His boss and mentor, Frank Broyles,
started out 0-6. ...Arkansas' touted run defense gave up a
season-high 131 yards rushing and 28 points to South Carolina,
which led 21-10 at the half only to surrender 24 unanswered points
in the third quarter. ...After hearing ESPN's Lee Corso predict a
South Carolina upset, DB Zac Painter couldn't wait to issue a
post-game retort: ``Make sure you write this,'' he told the
Arkansas Democrat-Gazette. ``Lee Corso's no rocket scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN vs. La. Tech, Saturday, 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 1-5 record, the defense is second in the SEC, allowing
just 266.5 yards a game. ...Auburn has held five of six opponents
under 200 yards passing. That's important with Louisiana Tech (4-4)
up next. The Bulldogs lead the nation in total offense (593.63 ypg)
and passing offense (434.4 ppg) and, are eighth in scoring offense
(40.1 ppg). Quarterback Tim Rattay has thrown for 3,303 yards and
30 touchdowns. ...Placekicker Robert Bironas has made all six of
his field goal attempts. Three of the kicks have been from 40 yards
or more. ...Wide receiver Karsten Bailey has caught at least one
pass in 23 consecutive games. ...Auburn has won 20 of 21
non-conference regular-season games dating to 1991. The only loss
was to Virginia this season.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA vs. Georgia, Oct. 31
</P>
<P>
   The Gators desperately needed this week off. Florida had a total
of 17 players out with injuries or suspensions for the Auburn game.
...Five of Florida's seven opponents have been held to less than 10
points, the lone exceptions being Tennessee (20) and Kentucky (35).
...Quarterback Chris Stephens, son of line coach Jimmy Ray
Stephens, has given a verbal commitment to Florida. Stephens is
considered the top quarterback prospect in Florida. They also have
a commitment from quarterback Rex Grossman of Bloomington, Ind.
...Free safety Teako Brown needs one interception to move into tie
for first place on the school's career list. Brown, who has 14
career picks, has an interception in four of the five games he has
played.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY vs. Georgia, Saturday, 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The unconventional atmosphere at Kentucky has given Jeff Zurcher
a seemingly unlikely chance to shine. The starting free safety, who
joined the lineup when Willie Gary suffered a season-ending knee
injury against Florida, notched a career-high 12 tackles at LSU on
Saturday, all unassisted, and sacked Herb Tylerin the second half.
He had 11 stops against Arkansas. Zurcher, once a Rhodes Scholar
candidate who already has earned a degree in English, transferred
in 1996 after playing on an NAIA Division II national basketball
championship team at Bethel College (Ind.). ...The win didn't help
the Wildcats crack the rankings, but they are receiving votes in
both polls. ... The Wildcats are last nationally (112th), averaging
2.4 yards a punt return.
</P>
<P>
   LSU vs. Miss. State, Saturday, 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After consecutive losses to Georgia, Florida and Kentucky, LSU
is glad to be playing a running team Mississippi State. ``It should
help us get together and maybe calm the defense down,'' defensive
end Jarvis Green said. ``It will be like starting over, to be
honest.'' LSU gave up an average of 347 yards passing in those
loses. ...LSU's game next week at Mississippi will not be
ontelevision. It will start at 2 p.m., and be shown on Tigervision,
LSU's closed-circuit broadcast. ...LSU's offensive line remains
banged up, not good news against blitz-happy Mississippi State.
Center Todd McClure has missed practice this week recovering from a
staph infection on his right shin. McClure did not play against
Kentucky. . . . Linebacker Jamal Hill has a groin injury but is
expected to play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI vs. Ark. State, Saturday, 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tommy Tuberville used the off week to do a serious
evaluation of his team. Overall, he gave the Rebels a C-plus for
their 4-2 record. Tuberville remains disappointed that his team let
the game against Alabama slip away. The Rebels lost to the Crimson
Tide 20-17 in overtime on Oct. 10. ``It was a game that we were in
position to win and didn't, so I marked us down for that,'' he
said. ``Our offense has gotten better each week, but defensively, I
think we've slipped.'' ...Opposing defenses have really been
concentrating on tight end Rufus French (17 catches, 213 yards). As
a result receivers Grant Heard (26, 352) and Grant Peterson (25,
337) are getting more opportunities. ... French, linebacker Armegis
Spearman and center Matt Luke returned to practice.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI STATE at LSU, Saturday, 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs can do something that's never been done in the
school's history Saturday _ if they win at LSU, they go 4-0 in the
SEC. But given last year's collapse after a 7-2 start _ they
finished 7-4 and did not go to a bowl _ State isn't putting a lot
of stock in such superlatives. ...Still, they need a victory
Saturday to remain in the race in the SEC West. ``I hope we get in
that position in our last two games,'' coach Jackie Sherrill said.
...The Bulldogs have won four of their last six road games ...The
pass defense, giving up an average of 82.1 yards a game, is second
in Division I-A, trailing only Ohio State (77.6). ...Inconsistent
QB Wayne Madkin bounced back with a 194-yard, three-TD performance
against East Tennessee State.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA at Vanderbilt, Saturday, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Brad Scott concedes that his team (1-6) needs any kind of
win it can get, after six consecutive losses. That why he's trying
to keep the Gamecocks focused, even though Vanderbilt is 0-6.
``We're two teams that need a win, no question about that,'' Scott
said. ``Our team is in a position now that we need to win a game,
no matter who it is against.'' After facing the Commodores, the
Gamecocks end the season with three difficult games _ the annual
``Orange Crush'' _ at home against Tennessee, at Florida and at
Clemson. ...Scott has asked his team to ignore speculation about
his job security. Many of those media reports insist that Scott
will be given another year. ...Kickoff for the Oct. 31 South
Carolina-Tennessee game has been moved to 12:30 p.m. It will be
televised by Jefferson-Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE vs. Alabama, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Back up TE Antron Peebles had surgery on his right wrist and is
out for the season. Peebles thinks that he hurt the wrist in the
opener against Syracuse and tried to play through the pain.
...Tackle Jarvis Reado continues to improve from a broken right
foot. Coach Phillip Fulmer said Reado remains questionable but
might be available for Saturday's game with Alabama. ...LB Al
Wilson will have no contact in practice the rest of the season, as
he continues to heal from a shoulder injury suffered against
Houston on Sept. 26. ...With Tennessee No. 3 in the AP poll, Fulmer
was asked on a recent call-in show if he would run up the score in
order to impress the pollsters. ``I'm not going to run it up and
get it into the 70s,'' he said, ``but we're conscientious of what
we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT vs. S. Carolina, Saturday, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodores have their two best chances to avoid their first
winless season starting against South Carolina, which is 1-6 and
0-5. However, they are 0-7 against the Gamecocks. Vandy then hosts
Duke the next weekend. ...For the third time this season, Vandy
will go to a new QB. Redshirt freshman Greg Zolman, who played well
in relief at Georgia, will start over Dave Wallace. Zolman was
13-for-21 and 162 yards and threw for a touchdown, prompting coach
Woody Widenhofer to say he ``played better than I thought he
would.'' ...Vandy had 380 yards against Georgia, but the defense,
young and riddled with injuries, is giving up 30.2 points a game.
The Commodores have been outscored 135-19 in SEC games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
