<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crankbaits drawing fish with fall in the air
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As leaves change color and the seagulls return to the
lake for the winter, striper fever is beginning to set in, with
top-water crankbaits getting plenty of action early and late in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Long A Bombers and other topwater lures such as Zara Spooks,
poppers and chuggers cast toward shore and retrieved slowly are
attracting more attention from stripers, which are chasing shad
toward the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Guide Don Roberson and client Dendy Harmon hooked into several
Monday on Lake Lanier. ``He had a backache before we started,''
Roberson said of Harmon. ``The stripers made it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Working island points and reefs in the main lake on the lower
end has been successful. Typically, the stripers have been rather
small, most coming under 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament trail
</P>
<P>
   It took Kenyon Hill 111 chances to win his first Bass Anglers
Sportsmen Society tournament. The Norman, Okla., pro caught four
days of five-fish limits for 61 pounds, 5 ounces of bass to win the
Kmart BASS Masters Top 150 tournament last weekend on the Louisiana
Delta. Hill won $100,000 and a berth to next summer's BASS Masters
Classic. Jay Yelas of Tyler, Texas, was second with a 52-14 total.
Buford's Mickey Bruce was Georgia's top finisher. Bruce finished
23rd in the pro division with 15 fish weighing 30 pounds, 4 ounces;
only the top 10 anglers from the first three days qualified for the
fourth. Bruce's son, John, finished 17th in the amateur division
with an 18-1 total, including the big fish on Day 1, a 5-pounder.
... Kim Carver of Milledgeville, who won last year's Red Man
All-American, won a Red Man regional last weekend on Kerr Lake,
N.C., boating a two-day total of 35 pounds, 6 ounces to top the
113-angler field. ... Gary Meyer of Woodstock and Windell Lightsey
of Marietta teamed to win the H.D. Marine/Scottish Rite Charity
bass tournament last weekend on Lake Lanier.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife tag sales
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the popular wildlife-conservation license plate have
exceeded 621,000, earning more than $8.7 million for non-game
wildlife conservation in Georgia, according to state Wildlife
Resources Division figures. The tag costs $15 and all but $2.59
goes directly to WRD.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
