<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panoz drivers to battle for Pro Sports Car title
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite heavy rains at Homestead, the Panoz GT1 was in
third place in the FIA GT Championship Series 500-kilometer race
when Eric Bernard collided with a tire barrier, losing the car's
hood, only 10 laps from the end of the 141-lap race. After a pit
stop to replace the hood, the Panoz car got back into the race in
sixth place. David Brabham was co-driver.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Ludwig and Ricardo Zonta drove their Mercedes-Benz CLK-LM
to victory, followed by the factory Porsche driven by Jorg Muller
and Uwe Alzen. Yannick Dalmas, who was involved in the spectacular
crash at Road Atlanta last week, finished third in the other
factory Porsche, co-driven by Allan McNish.
</P>
<P>
   The season finale for the Visteon Panoz Racing Team is
Saturday-Sunday at Laguna Seca. On Saturday, one of the Panoz
drivers _ David Brabham, Andy Wallace or Bernard _ will clinch the
Professional Sports Car Racing Driver's Championship title. On
Sunday, Brabham and Bernard will compete in the final round of the
FIA-GT championship.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycle racer dies
</P>
<P>
   A motorcycle racer was killed Friday at Road Atlanta during a
practice session for the weekend's WERA meet. Rodney Priest, 28, of
Charlottesville, W. Va., lost control of his Suzuki ZSR 750 and
fell. Coming out of Turn 5 and leading the pack at the time, he was
struck by several other bikes and died at the scene, according to
Capt. Ken Grogan of the Hall County Sheriff's Dept.
</P>
<P>
   F1
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Ecclestone has authorized a Formula 1 race in Zhuhai,
China, on March 21. Ecclestone takes the television money and lets
race promoters make what they can on tickets. Meanwhile, Atlanta's
car owners still are waiting for word of a possible F1 race here.
</P>
<P>
   IRL
</P>
<P>
   Pep Boys Indy Racing League standout Jeff Ward plans to make his
NASCAR Winston Cup debut at the Dura-Lube/Kmart 500 Sunday at
Phoenix International Raceway, where he won his first Pep Boys IRL
pole in March. Ward will drive a car owned by Bill Strauser of
Walla Walla, Wash. Ward won the pole for the Dura-Lube 200 Pep Boys
IRL race in March at 172.753, a track record. ``The stock cars and
IRL cars are totally different, and I'm going to have to use my
natural instincts to make the right adjustment for the stock car.''
</P>
<P>
   NHRA
</P>
<P>
   On a bone-chilling night at Heartland Park Topeka, Warren
Johnson of Duluth toasted his fourth career NHRA Winston Pro Stock
championship with a cup of hot coffee. With a wind-chill factor in
the 20s, it was not a night for champagne. Johnson's chassis
wizardry paid off in Topeka as he made four-straight 6-second
passes on the stone-cold track surface. ``If I keep getting
reaction times like that, it could ruin my reputation,'' Johnson
laughed. ``I never claimed to be a driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
