<HEADER>
A0073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-SCOTT-HALLOFFAME-     10-21 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SCOTT-HALLOFFAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wendell Scott enters NASCAR's Hall
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The late Wendell Scott made history as the first
African-American to win a NASCAR race on Dec. 1, 1963, at Speedway
Park in Jacksonville, Fla. Scott took another checkered flag on
Wednesday, when he was selected for induction into the
International Motorsports Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   He joins Louise Smith of Greenville, S.C., the first female
inductee, who won 38 NASCAR Late Model Stock races against the top
male drivers in the 1940s and '50s; Gordon Johncock, two-time
Indianapolis 500 champ; and Alan Prost, four-time Formula One champ
with 51 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who died of cancer in 1990, is the only African-American
to win a Winston Cup race and a pole. The victory originally was
awarded to Buck Baker, but it was changed after Scott correctly
pointed out a scoring error.
</P>
<P>
   It took hours for race officials to unscramble the scoring
mistake that had him third behind Baker and apparent runner-up Jack
Smith. After starting 15th in his own underfinanced Chevrolet,
Scott had come to the front and clearly passed Baker and Smith
several times. He ran two extra laps to make sure he was the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty, who raced against Scott, said he'll never forget
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember him because he didn't have the best
stuff, but he nearly ran us to death on junk,'' Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Brooks, a long-time friend of Scott, remembered when the
two were turned away at the gate in Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to be that way, let 'em,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott raced for most of the 1960s and into the '70s, finally
retiring after suffering injuries in a crash at Talladega in 1973.
He was sixth in season-ending points in 1966, then 10th, ninth and
ninth in his last three years.
</P>
<P>
   His life was the basis of the film ``Greased Lightening,'' which
starred Richard Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
