A0074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWM-UGA-COACH-COX     10-21 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWM-UGA-COACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wins will make Georgia coach top Dog in SEC
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia swimming coach Jack Bauerle is so close to
a milestone that many people _ including himself _ thought was well
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But if his men's and women's teams beat North Carolina today,
Bauerle will become the winningest swim coach in SEC history.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's men, ranked sixth in preseason polls, and the women,
ranked second, are expected to take care of business today. North
Carolina's men are ranked 22nd and the women 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Bauerle, last season's NCAA women's coach of the year, said that
catching Tennessee's Ray Bussard was not on his mind until
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago, I wasn't even thinking about it,''
Bauerle said. ``But we have won a lot of meets in that time. I
wasn't even aware of (the record) until last year. But what it
really means is a tribute to the athletes who have been here
through those years. It's a tribute to the program.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 20 years at Tennessee, from 1968-88, Bussard compiled a
252-20 record. Bauerle, who began as coach of the women's team in
1979 and became overall head coach in '83, has a record of
251-69-1. The only coach close to Bauerle who coached men and women
is Randy Resse, who had a 219-29 record at Florida from 1976-90.
</P>
<P>
   The record seems secondary to what he really wants: a national
title. And it could be that his women might give him one, despite
the team ahead of them _ defending national champion and
traditional power Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia will host the NCAA Women's Championships in March, but
the Lady Bulldogs will get an early look at Sanford when the Lady
Cardinal comes to town for a meet Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that our men are ranked a little higher than we
should be, although we have some good young swimmers,'' he said.
``But our women, well, we are going to work hard, and I can tell
you we will not be satisfied with second place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia women are led by All-American and multi-record
holder Kristy Kowal, who Bauerle said is ``just getting stronger
and faster.'' Kowal, who swims several events, is one of the NCAA's
premier breaststrokers.
</P>
<P>
   Bauerle said he also has some ``exciting freshmen'' swimmers,
including Stefanie Williams, freestyle and backstroker from
Bloomsburg, Pa., and Ashley Roby, a breaststroker from Lithonia.
Among the men, Yoav Gath, a backstroker from Israel, and Nicholas
Kintz, a freestyler from France, are the top swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
