<SLUG> BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOCUM KNOWS THE SCORE AFTER 25 YEARS OF COACHING AT A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If R.C. Slocum ever had a personalized bumper sticker, it could
read like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a native Aggie, but I became one as fast as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has stayed one seemingly forever, or, in the opinion of
some Texas A&AMP;M former students, too long.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard road to travel, that Texas Highway 6.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you would think an unhappy Aggies football fan had to
be nonexistent, Slocum was talking yesterday about his recent mail
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I heard from more than several about how they didn't like
our fourth-quarter defensive strategy,'' Slocum said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the week after the upset of No. 2 Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   As legend has it, there is no place tougher in Texas, or maybe
the nation, to coach football than in College Station. Aggies are
considered, well, crazy when it comes to football and football
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum can testify to that more than anyone who ever tried to
coach in Aggieland. An Orange product with a degree from McNeese
State, Slocum has spent 25 years on the A&AMP;M staff, longer than any
football coach in school history.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, he has been head coach, third only to Dana X.
Bible (11 seasons) and Homer Rice (14 seasons). But those two names
involve ancient history. No head coach in more than 50 years has
survived as long as Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greatest fans and greatest place in the world,'' he said. ``By
and large, the people are good. They've got a life and they've got
jobs, and their entire existence doesn't revolve around a football
game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are disappointed when we lose, and they celebrate when we
win. But the right perspective is there. Then there are a few
others, and those are the ones you hear from, and no matter what,
they aren't going to be pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   In what has been Slocum's strangest season, the critics were
louder than ever until two weeks ago. There was the loss to
then-No. 2 ranked Florida State in the opener, followed by a
struggling offense in wins against so-called lightweights, followed
by a quarterback change, followed by ...
</P>
<P>
   The shocking win against Nebraska. Then last week, the Aggies
showed no victory hangover in disposing of a Baylor team on the
road. Until A&AMP;M, Baylor had played everyone extremely tough.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought that the Aggies would be ranked No. 8 in
the land by late October? Who would have thought the contest at
Kyle Field on Saturday against No. 25 Texas Tech would mean another
big-game atmosphere for College Station?
</P>
<P>
   ``For 99.9 percent of Aggies, the mood changed dramatically
around here after the Nebraska game,'' Slocum said. ``We had won
the game _ the so-called big one _ that many said we couldn't. I
always thought that criticism was way overblown, but it was there,
no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum is fond of reminding about this being the winningest
decade in A&AMP;M history. ``To achieve that, you have to have won some
big games along the way,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   And he also tacks on the zinger that makes the dog bark in
College Station. ``At no time has the NCAA ever felt better about
this football program _ just ask the NCAA,'' Slocum said. ``This is
a university where the entire foundation is supposed to be built
upon honor and upon integrity. And then to have football scandals _
that should not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there was the Jackie Sherrill era. And Slocum was an
assistant on Sherrill's staff, leading some of us to believe more
dirty tricks were coming with his promotion in 1989. But Slocum has
taken the program in exactly the opposite direction. Meaning up.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, there was a scandal under Slocum. The
infamous case of Warren Gilbert, the Dallas booster, in the
mid-1990s. ``It gave us another bad name and it hurt recruiting for
several years, but in the end, it was the best thing that ever
happened,'' Slocum said. ``The NCAA came out and said the school
president is trying to do it the right way and the coach is trying
to do it the right way _ that we had gotten the message. But that
others obviously hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum called it ``a clear line being drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``Some of our fans still thought the old way was
the right way. But what that case did was tell one and all that if
you did it the old way, you wouldn't be involved with us any
longer. The whole process did hurt, but it was also very
beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   For Slocum, this particular season has been the same. The
``99.9'' now love him in Aggieland. And will continue to do so as
long he beats Tech on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
