<HEADLINE>
NHRA TOP FUEL POINTS LEADERS OFFER TOP-NOTCH RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only 11 points separate National Hot Rod Association Top Fuel
championship contenders Cory McClenathan and Gary Scelzi, who after
19 events are giving professional drag racing something sorely
missing from the NASCAR Winston Cup Series.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rivalry worth getting worked up about. And it will make
the 13th annual Revell Nationals at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis
the hottest ticket in motorsports this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   With his final-round victory against Kenny Bernstein in the
rain-delayed Parts America Nationals at Topeka, Kan., early Sunday
morning, McClenathan reclaimed first place over Scelzi by those 11
points. Scelzi began final eliminations with a 44-point advantage,
but his second-round loss against McClenathan helped rearrange the
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that could begin to change with the first four-second
qualifying blast down the Motorplex's all-concrete quarter-mile
tomorrow afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the points standings show that I have the lead, I look
at it as if it were a tie,'' said McClenathan, driver of the
McDonald's Dragster owned by former NFL coach Joe Gibbs. ``When
you're talking 11 points, that's only one round and we have 12
rounds \Rover three remaining events\S to go. This is great for the
fans but nerve-wracking for the drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unlikely collapse by either Cory Mac or Scelzi this
weekend, the Top Fuel chase will leave Ennis, head south to Houston
Raceway Park in Baytown next weekend and continue to the Winston
Finals at Pomona (Calif.) Raceway on Nov. 12-15.
</P>
<P>
   Depending upon how they qualify this weekend, it is conceivable
that Scelzi and the Team Winston Dragster could wind up staging in
the lane opposite McClenathan during Sunday evening's final, live
on The Nashville Network.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that within a recent seven-day stretch, McClenathan and
Scelzi faced each other in the second round at national events,
with each recording a victory. Scelzi beat McClenathan at Memphis
Motorsports Park on Oct. 11, and Cory Mac returned the favor at
Heartland Park on Sunday. Heads-up, McClenathan has a 4-2 advantage
against Scelzi this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a rivalry,'' said McClenathan, the Top Fuel
points runner-up in 1992, 1995 and 1997. ``Jimmy Spencer told me
one time that when those \RWinston Cup\S guys are rubbing fenders,
there's a lot of love there. This is male bonding at its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gary and I could do that \Rrub fenders\S, we'd be doing it.
But it keeps you on your toes knowing that Winston car is going to
be there. That keeps you competitive. Keeps you alive. This is life
at its best for me. To be in the middle of this deal is an
incredible feeling. You don't see guys on a pedestal because this
is a humbling sport.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion has been hammered home this season for Scelzi, who
won the Top Fuel title last year in a storybook rookie campaign of
driving for team owner and tuner Alan Johnson. Scelzi, who replaced
the late Blaine Johnson in his brother's hot rod, dramatically
clinched the 1997 title at the season-ending race at Pomona. This
year, Scelzi did not make a final-round appearance until the
series' ninth event at the new Route 66 Raceway in Joliet, Ill., in
late May. But he since has won four races, including three
consecutive from mid-August to mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   McClenathan has kept in the hunt by matching the class
record-tying six victories he racked up during 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year Cory was on our tail all the way,'' said Scelzi, a
38-year-old resident of Fresno, Calif. ``The competition got
tougher from half-season on. This year, although there hasn't been
that many different winners, there has been a lot of stellar
performances in Top Fuel. There are a lot of good teams out there.
But the ones I consider the best, it brings out the best in me. I
want to race Joe Amato, Cory, Kenny _ I want to race those guys. I
might be throwing up in my helmet before the round, but if you beat
them you've accomplished something.''
</P>
<P>
   Linked as they have been for the past two seasons, McClenathan
and Scelzi have developed a healthy mutual respect for one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I don't have to put in the equation is Cory jacking
around,'' Scelzi said. ``Most of the guys racing this deal, we
don't play \Rmind\S games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down to where every round counts. Cory is a good `leaver'
\Roff the starting line\S and one of the best drivers out there, if
not the best driver out there. But it's crunch time now. You've got
to be on your game without forcing a mistake on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   McClenathan, a 35-year-old resident of Anaheim, Calif., insisted
that even with all that is on the line, he plans to thoroughly
enjoy this weekend at the Plex. Recall that he is the two-time
defending race champion. And that during the finals last October,
McClenathan became the first driver to crack the 320 mph barrier at
321.77 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up wishing that I could be in a position like this. And
now that I'm here, I can't stand it. It's killing me,'' said
McClenathan, who has three races to register a Top Fuel record
seventh victory in a single season. ``Gary and I love this sport
and will do anything to keep on doing it. I'd even love to hate the
kid, but he's too cute.''
THE BUZZ
NHRA
</P>
<P>
   Wet weather has prompted a second change in plans for events
associated with the 13th annual Revell Nationals at the Texas
Motorplex in Ennis. Yesterday's sixth annual Dallas Motorsports
Expo was canceled by the threat of rain. And this afternoon's
scheduled debut of the NHRA's Pro Stock Truck class has been
rescheduled for tomorrow. The latest change was prompted by water
saturation in the unpaved areas of the Motorplex pits, sections
where Sportsman racers generally park their rigs and race cars.
Elon Werner, the track's director of media services, said the Ennis
area has received approximately eight inches of rain since the
weekend. ``Every year we add more asphalt to the pits, and that's
more land the water is running off of,'' Werner said. ``The fringe
areas are wet and rather than get a bunch of Sportsman racers mad
and hinder their competitive edge, we decided to treat everyone
equal.'' For professional drivers in Top Fuel, Funny Car, Pro Stock
and Pro Stock Truck, that has meant a temporary move to the parking
lot of the former supercollider office center on Highway 77, just
north of Waxahachie. Werner said that lot is about a 15-minute
drive from the track. ...
</P>
<P>
   All the pro classes and Competition Eliminator are parked at
that satellite site through tonight. That will open up the paved
Motorplex pits to competitors in Federal Mogul Dragster, Federal
Mogul Funny Car, Super Comp, Super Gas, Super Stock and Stock.
Sportsman racers are scheduled to begin qualifications at noon,
with Federal Mogul Dragster and Federal Mogul Funny Car to run
their first rounds at 7 p.m. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Stock Trucks, originally scheduled to qualify at 3 p.m.
and 6:15 p.m. today, will run tomorrow at 10 a.m., 2 p.m and 6 p.m.
in anticipation of Saturday's final. Early tomorrow morning, all
the pro classes and Competition Eliminator drivers will move into
the Motorplex paved pits. On Saturday morning, all remaining
Sportsman competitors will relocate from the remote lot to the
Motorplex. ...
</P>
<P>
   Advance ticket sales for this weekend are up 20 percent, Werner
said. That, in addition to wet parking lots, has prompted the
addition of two remote lots for spectators this weekend. Remote
parking will be available in Waxahachie today at the intersection
of Highway 287 and Highway 77 at Tractor Supply Co., Kroger and the
HEB Grocery lots. Beginning tomorrow and continuing through Sunday,
Waxahachie remote parking will be at the Waxahachie High School
football stadium. Remote parking in Ennis will be available
tomorrow through Sunday at the Ennis Junior High School football
stadium on Belknap Street. ``We used this system in 1994 and
received a number of compliments,'' Motorplex owner Billy Meyer
said. Remote parking will be free, and the track will provide
continuous shuttle service from 8 a.m. until two hours after
completion of each day's racing.
FAST LAPS
He keeps going and going
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Terry Labonte will make his 600th consecutive
NASCAR Winston Cup start at Phoenix International Raceway this
weekend. Texas Terry will do so in a specially designed ``Iron
Man2'' edition of the No. 5 Kellogg's Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte broke seven-time NASCAR champion Richard Petty's record
of 513 consecutive races started in the spring of 1996. And Labonte
keeps on going and going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with my two championships, breaking Richard Petty's
record and then adding to it as much as I have are the highlights
of my career,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a big weekend for him,'' said Bobby Labonte,
Terry's younger brother. ``It kind of goes back to he's the
`Iceman.' He doesn't get in situations where he gets himself into
trouble.''
Daytona sees the light
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's historic first nighttime edition of the Pepsi 400 at
the Daytona International Speedway has been declared a resounding
success by officials of International Speedway Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million system installed by Musco Lighting, Inc.,
generated not only daylight-like conditions but also rave reviews
from drivers, fans, sponsors and media. That does not mean,
however, that speedway management is planning to move the Daytona
500 _ NASCAR's traditional season-opening Super Bowl _ from Sunday
afternoon into primetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daytona 500 is such a great tradition,'' said John Graham,
the president of DIS. ``I think it's the premier sporting event in
the world. It's documented to be the most watched motorsports event
in the U.S. and in the world. With that kind of tradition and
following, we will probably stay with the tradition of that race at
the time it's run, at noontime on the second or third Sunday in
February.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said the entire stock-car portion of SpeedWeeks 1999 at
Daytona will be run during daylight hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 2000, we are looking at the possibility of one or two of
those events being run in the evening,'' Graham said. ``In the
event there is a weather delay, the lights do give us additional
flexibility. But for 1999, all events for SpeedWeeks will be run in
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said the light bill for Saturday's event ranged between
$25,000 to $30,000, or approximately $5,000 to $6,000 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, you've got to figure that the estimated 170,000 fans
who turned out for the race will help ISC cover that cost of doing
business. Nuts and bolts With his victory in the Pepsi 400, Winston
Cup points leader Jeff Gordon moved into a tie for 13th place on
the all-time NASCAR winner's list. Gordon has 40 career victories,
matching Bill Elliott and the late Tim Flock.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty is the only Winston Cup driver who has run in all 30
races this season and has yet to lead a lap.
</P>
<P>
   Should Dale Earnhardt Jr. win the remaining three NASCAR Busch
Grand National Series races of 1998, the points leader would tie
Sam Ard's single-season record of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Two new teams have announced plans to compete in the Pep Boys
Indy Racing League in 1999. Indianapolis 500 veteran Scott
Harrington will drive for a team formed by his father, Gene. And
rookie Greg Gorden will drive for Truscelli Team Racing.
Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what `pressure' means. It's like `vacation'
_ it's not a word in my vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Johnson, newly crowned four-time NHRA Winston Pro Stock
champion
</P>
</TEXT>
