<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NIEUWENDYK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS BEGIN AGAIN WITH ALL PIECES IN PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The process of building the Stars into a serious contender for
the Stanley Cup begins in earnest tonight. Injured centers Joe
Nieuwendyk and Brian Skrudland are expected to return to the lineup
in a 7:30 game against the Phoenix Coyotes at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as getting Nieuwendyk back gives fans a look at the
three big shooters _ Mike Modano and Brett Hull included _ coach
Ken Hitchcock stresses that trying to view the Stars as a finished
product would be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny business, because the process of being a good
team has to start all over again,'' Hitchcock said. ``The pieces
are there, but as far as the chemistry, we're a ways off.''
</P>
<P>
   That could show tonight as Hitchcock plans to start Nieuwendyk,
last season's team most valuable player, on the ``fourth'' line
with Skrudland and Grant Marshall. Nieuwendyk, 32, has played as a
first- or second-line center his entire career and last season led
the Stars in goal-scoring with 39. The fourth line generally has
the task of checking or banging.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hitchcock has moved fourth-line center Tony Hrkac to
the second line with Jamie Langenbrunner (who moved from center to
left wing) and Pat Verbeek, so Nieuwendyk and Hrkac can be switched
in the middle of the game if Nieuwendyk appears to be playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got two pretty big parts of your team back in the same
game. That's going to be an adjustment,'' Hitchcock said. ``Joe's
going to have a tough time, he knows that. But he wants to get
through it and move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk said he feels comfortable with both knees that
underwent reconstructive surgery in May. His right knee, which was
injured in a collision in the first game of the playoffs with San
Jose Sharks defenseman Bryan Marchment, had a torn anterior
cruciate ligament that was repaired. His left knee had a missing
ACL replaced with a ligament from a cadaver. Nieuwendyk had been
playing for seven seasons without an ACL in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it should be stronger. I can already feel the
difference,'' Nieuwendyk said of having two healthy knees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to leading the team in goal-scoring, Nieuwendyk also
set a franchise record with 11 game-winning goals (second in the
NHL), was the team's top scorer on the power play with 14 goals
(tied for fifth in the NHL) and finished second in the NHL in
faceoff percentage (59.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a complete player who does a lot of things,'' said Hull,
who started his career as a teammate of Nieuwendyk's with the
Calgary Flames. ``I don't think he's lost a step, even with the
knee injuries. He's going to add a lot to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's importance to the Stars was underscored in his
absence from the playoffs. Without him, Modano faced extended
pressure and wasn't as effective as the first-line center. Without
Niuewendyk, linemate Verbeek, who was second on the Stars in
goal-scoring with 31 during the regular season, also wasn't as
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``With both lines last year, other teams had to make a choice,''
Modano said. ``And if they chose to send their checkers at us, then
Joe and Patty took advantage of it. They were the line that picked
us up a lot of times last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the process begins of getting that combination and
chemistry back. Nieuwendyk likely will see some playing time on the
power play, but he hasn't practiced with a regular unit and will
have to work his way onto a power play that has become the most
prolific in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where they play me or what they want to do with
me, I just want to get in,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Nieuwendyk's return also schedules him to be on the
ice Saturday when Marchment, whom Nieuwendyk called a ``dirty
player,'' returns to Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'm looking forward to it,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I
need to get back into the game and playing against a guy like him
is part of the game.''
Severyn rests
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brent Severyn rested his sore neck and back
yesterday and is not expected to play tonight, Hitchcock said. The
move is, in part, designed to give Severyn a better chance to play
Saturday when Marchment is scheduled to return and Severyn's
fighting skills and toughness could be needed.
Modano rests
</P>
<P>
   Modano missed practice yesterday with a sore hip flexor. He said
he expects to practice today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
