<HEADLINE>
STUMPEL HEADS LIST OF INJURED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. - An injury to No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel was the
most noteworthy in an epidemic of afflictions that conspired to
leave Los Angeles Kings coach Larry Robinson with just enough
healthy players for his 20-man lineup against the Florida Panthers
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, held without a point the first four games, is day to
day with a left-hip-flexor strain. Additionally, rookie wing Josh
Green missed the game with a left-shoulder strain suffered in a
scrape with Keith Jones during Sunday's 5-5 tie with Colorado.
Defenseman Steve Duchesne, officially scratched as a coach's
decision, has been bothered by a mild groin strain for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries allowed defenseman Garry Galley and center Roman
Vopat to crack the lineup for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel's injury came to light Tuesday. Robinson, concerned by
the performance of a player who led the Kings with 79 points last
season, wanted to know why Stumpel was struggling. Stumpel told
Robinson he'd been bothered by the hip since the Kings' final
exhibition game Oct. 4 in Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be OK,'' Stumpel said. ``But it
didn't get better, and now it's getting worse. It's hard to move on
the ice. The problem is skating, starting and stopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said, ``Apparently, it's been bothering him more than
we thought, and here we are getting mad at him because he's not
playing as well as he's capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Pete Demers said that if it was late in the season or
during the playoffs, Stumpel probably would be able to play. But
five games into an 82-game season, it's more important for Stumpel
to rest until he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   For Stumpel, who missed most of training camp with an ankle
injury, this means more time on the exercise bike, less time on the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a hockey player,'' Stumpel said. ``You like to play
hockey and skate. If you have to ride the bike, after a few days,
you get sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury updates: As for the other injured players, Duchesne is
day to day, and so is Green. Center Ian Laperreire remains
sidelined indefinitely with a partially torn anterior cruciate
ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Stephane Fiset's groin injury is mild enough that he
might be able to play soon, possibly Friday at Tampa Bay. But
goalie Jamie Storr is sidelined indefinitely with his groin injury,
which is much more serious than Fiset's.
</P>
<P>
   Storr's absence means goalie Manny Legace, Wednesday's starter
against the Panthers, will be around for a while. Even if Fiset
plays against Tampa Bay and makes it through the game without ill
effects, the Kings probably also will keep goalie Alexey Volkov
around until they are certain Fiset's injury is behind him.
</P>
<P>
   __ Cashing in: Not only are Legace and Volkov getting a taste of
life in the NHL, they are getting a taste of NHL finances, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Both players have two-way contracts. Legace's salary is $80,000
when he's in the minors, $400,000 when he's in the NHL. Volkov was
making $47,500 while with Halifax in the Quebec Major Junior Hockey
League, and makes $425,000 in the NHL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
