<HEADLINE>
A SERIES OF TIDBITS FROM WORLD OF BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News, rumors and opinions from the World Series:
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles appear to be leaning toward Florida Marlins
assistant Frank Wren as their next general manager. The other
finalists are White Sox assistant Dan Evans and Braves assistant
Dean Taylor. The Rangers interviewed Wren in 1994 before they hired
Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   The early word on pitcher Randy Johnson is he's looking for a
three-year deal worth between $10 million and $13 million per
season. Johnson would prefer to play for the Arizona Diamondbacks
because he lives in the Phoenix area. But if that doesn't happen,
he would prefer to return to the American League.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Rangers have done little with pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre's agent, Tony Attanasio, except exchange phone
messages. But re-signing him as a free agent could turn out to be
an expensive proposition. Major-league officials said Mets pitcher
Al Leiter has turned down a four-year, $28 million offer from his
team. Meanwhile, Kevin Brown, 33, is rumored to be seeking a
seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are expected to decide shortly between Davey Johnson
and Kevin Kennedy as their next manager. Nobody really knows which
way new general manager Kevin Malone is leaning, but betting money
appears to favor Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Molitor has been seen at the World Series sitting with
commissioner Bud Selig and Major League Baseball president Paul
Beeston. Baseball's top honchos would like Molitor to become a
deputy commissioner and liaison to the players' association in the
hopes of smoother labor relations. Molitor hasn't decided whether
he'll play another season.
</P>
<P>
   Two words on the supposed low television ratings for the World
Series: sports bars. Hasn't anybody figured out that many members
of baseball's target audience are sitting in their favorite saloons
watching the game with others rather than at home?
</P>
<P>
   Officials said few teams are talking trade right now, preferring
instead to wait on the free-agent market. But three players likely
to be traded during the off-season are Angels outfielder Jim
Edmonds, Mets catcher Todd Hundley and Braves pitcher Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs have exclusive negotiating rights with their free agents
for 15 days after the Series. The Red Sox are expected to use this
time to make one more run at first baseman Mo Vaughn. If they can't
get it done within that period, he's gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   Last word on the Mets is they were ready to give Mike Piazza a
$98 million, seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Padres general manager Kevin Towers said it's important for the
club to re-sign at least a couple of their free agents before the
Nov. 3 vote on their new stadium. Said Towers: ``We want to be able
to say, `See this guy is coming back, that guy is coming back,
we're still going to be good, we're still going to be here spending
money.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch can demand a trade
because he was traded in the middle of a multiyear contract. But
the Yankees are trying to keep that from happening by giving him a
two-year, $18 million extension.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's old team, the Minnesota Twins, might have a $17
million payroll next year.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees general manager Brian Cashman said re-signing center
fielder Bernie Williams is a top priority, but they might have to
give him $14 million a year to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Selig is trying to revive the winter meetings. The last true
winter meetings were held in 1992 but were stopped because owners
felt the meetings had become a free-agent bazaar that allowed
agents to play one club against another. But the absence of the
meetings has not stopped salaries from skyrocketing, and Selig
likes the positive publicity and news generated at last year's
expansion draft in Phoenix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
