<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN BACK, SHOWS NO RUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman returned to
practice yesterday for the first time since suffering a fractured
collarbone six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey said Aikman threw the ball sharply and showed
no signs of rust from the lengthy layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good out there,'' said Aikman, who acknowledged
that he felt a little pain when throwing. ``It's the first day.
I'll get more practice time tomorrow and next week. I need all the
practice I can get. I feel confident about going out and playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who was replaced by Jason Garrett the past five games,
took most of the snaps at practice. He will continue to do so
leading up to the Cowboys' Nov. 2 game at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   However, Aikman's collarbone, which is still broken, won't be
completely healed until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern is getting hit,'' Aikman said. ``I haven't
been hit yet. There is a concern about whether the shoulder will
hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will fit Aikman with extra padding to support the
collarbone. However, Aikman said the padding is really useless in
protecting against a direct hit. But more than taking a direct hit,
Aikman is concerned about how the collarbone will hold up if he has
to stick out his left arm when he is falling.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gailey and the rest of the Cowboys were just
happy to have him back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look like he missed hardly anything,'' Gailey said.
``He looked very good. Other than the obvious tangible things, it's
good to have him back for the intangibles, as well. He's been a
great leader for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bye this week, Aikman will use the extra time to get back
into practice and allow his collarbone to heal more.
Briefly
Receiver Billy Davis (left foot), defensive end Kavika Pittman
(soreness), defensive tackle Chad Hennings (left ankle) and
defensive tackle Leon Lett (left knee) missed practice yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he will use the bye week to get cornerback Deion
Sanders more involved as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys will also use the bye week to begin work
on a game plan for the Thanksgiving Day matchup against the
Minnesota Vikings because that game comes during a short week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
