<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SUCCESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM BRINGS RESULTS AT ONE LOS ANGELES CHARTER SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Health education teacher Larry Marshall has
worked at Palisades Charter High School for 33 years, yet he barely
recognizes the place.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in decades, the Pacific Palisades school has
reached its capacity of 2,500 students -- doubling the enrollment
in just a few years. There's a waiting list of 600 students and
even private school pupils are taking a second look, with more than
200 returning to the campus during the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall and others credit Palisades' metamorphosis to a host of
reforms, including achieving charter status in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed a whole lot,'' Marshall said. ``Before, it wasn't
really going up. Now it's going up and up.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the school in a coastal community approximately 18 miles
west of downtown Los Angeles became a charter, average Scholastic
Assessment Test results have shot up eight points for a combined
verbal and math score of 1,007 and the number of students enrolling
and completing Advanced Placement courses has doubled. The school
also has made computer literacy a graduation requirement for the
class of 2002 and established a math, science and technology magnet
as well as a new media entertainment academy.
</P>
<P>
   Palisades is part of a complex of eight fiscally dependent
charter schools that includes five elementary schools, one middle
school and a continuation high school. As a dependent charter, the
complex relies on the Los Angeles Unified School District for
funding but is able to obtain state and district waivers to perform
certain functions, such as draw students from outside its
attendance boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Each campus in the complex also belongs to LEARN, the district's
largest reform effort, which gives teachers, parents,
administrators and school staffers more authority over their
budgets and curriculum. The complex joined the charter movement to
increase enrollment, implement complexwide programs and increase
schools' power and autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them more independence and gives them the ability to
work together and plan together,'' said Stuart Bernstein, leader of
the Hamilton/Palisades/University cluster, which includes the
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The effort has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized reading and math scores have improved 5 to 6
percentile points, the dropout rate is down 4 percent, the
attendance rate is up 6 percent, the number of disadvantaged
students entering four-year colleges has increased and most of the
schools now boast waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   And with the help of a $677,644 Annenberg Challenge Grant, the
complex has implemented mentoring, tutoring, parent education and
college awareness programs to help underachieving students. As part
of the grant, Palisades Charter High School created a satellite
tutoring center in South Central Los Angeles for its traveling
students. Now it hopes to create another one for students who live
in East Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're victims of our own success. They're literally banging
down our doors from all parts of the district,'' said Merle Price,
principal of Palisades Charter High. Local youngsters now account
for 40 percent of total enrollment compared to less than 30 percent
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Price said the charter and the Los Angeles Educational Alliance
for Restructuring Now (LEARN) reform movements have had positive
impacts on the complex. Charter status allowed the high school to
set higher graduation standards than the district, requiring all
students to perform 10 hours of community service each year from
ninth through 12th grades and demonstrate computer literacy by
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charter freed everybody up to develop new ideas, the way
kids could be engaged, the type of courses, the type of
instruction,'' Price said. ``LEARN helped us learn and implement
new curriculum. They were very compatible.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
