<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SIART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES COMPANY FORMED TO AID CHARTER SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Bill Siart lost his bid last year to become
superintendent of the Los Angeles Unified School District, but that
hasn't halted his campaign to reform the nation's second-largest
school system.
</P>
<P>
   From a fourth-floor office in Santa Monica, Calif., the former
chairman of First Interstate Bancorp has launched a for-profit
company, Exed LLC, that will handle business matters for charter
schools -- everything from accounting to purchasing to janitorial
services.
</P>
<P>
   Siart hopes his effort will build and strengthen the charter
school movement, which he sees as an alternative to the LAUSD's
poor-performing campuses for parents who can't afford private
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I've looked into it, the basic problem with urban
education is they don't have competition, they haven't been forced
to change,'' Siart said. ``Charter schools provide another choice
for parents, and that competition should force everyone to improve
their product.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are allowed to operate free of most state and
district regulations, with the expectation that student achievement
will improve. While all charters become instructionally
independent, some of the schools opt to have their districts
continue to handle their finances.
</P>
<P>
   Siart said it is the business of running a school that often
intimidates educators, and keeps them from full charter autonomy --
or from becoming a charter school altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like facing the start-up of a small business,'' Siart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Price, principal of Palisades Charter High School, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am contacted several times a year from groups who are
considering charters. Their reasons range from dissatisfaction with
their local school system to wanting to focus on a particular
philosophy. The common denominator is their reluctance to handle
the fiscal side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   An outside consultant is evaluating the finances of the
Palisades charter cluster -- a group of eight schools in Pacific
Palisades, which includes Price's high school. When their fiscal
report is presented -- likely in early 1999 -- the schools will
have to decide whether it's time to become financially independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my focus to be on my students' educational progress, I
don't want to get caught up negotiating contracts when I should be
visiting classrooms,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Exed will do some of the financial work, or negotiate contracts
from service providers. Sometimes, that might mean that the charter
campus contracts with its own school district for certain work. But
however it's done, Siart believes he can save the charter schools
money.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-98 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
