<DOCNO> NYT19981021.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0103 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2ndTa     10-21 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: professional development lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Hillary's village, finally,'' said Principal Yvonne Chan,
referring to the adage oft-quoted by the first lady, that it takes
a village to raise a child.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela Pelayo, whose three children attend Vaughn, said she
was drawn to the school because of its parent involvement. Parents
must sign a contract that calls for, among other responsibilities,
volunteering 30 hours each year, reviewing their children's
homework and visiting the school's family center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to talk to teachers and work together. This is a
team of parents and teachers working for children,'' said Pelayo,
who works as an enrollment clerk at Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Vaughn has ended each fiscal year with a nearly $1
million surplus, including $1.2 million in the first year of
operation, which the school used to buy property for the 14 new
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Vaughn generates stays at Vaughn,'' Chan said. ``We're
free to deploy human and fiscal resources. You can give big
bonuses, fire people. . . . You don't have to go through the
district.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenton -- once considered one of the worst schools in the Valley
-- also has made gains since becoming a charter school in 1994.
Named a California Distinguished School, the nation's largest
elementary charter school has made technology education its focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very little control as to what policies would be
governing us,'' said Lucente, who helps oversee the year-round
school with 1,300 students in pre-kindergarten through fifth grade.
``This school community now has total control.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, the school was able to wire an integrated sound,
image and data network for the entire campus. It also has been able
to install 350 computers -- with Internet access -- and provide
each fifth-grader with a classroom computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the bottom. Now we're on the top,'' Lucente said.
</P>
<P>
   At Fenton, overall standardized test scores rose nearly 48
percent this year, with fifth-graders showing the most improvement.
Their scores in reading, math and language increased by nearly 72
percent from last year. Reading scores rose from the 11th
percentile in 1996-97 to the 20th percentile this year; math scores
increased from the 19th percentile to the 29th percentile and
language marks grew from the 15th percentile to the 27th
percentile.
</P>
<P>
   Even Montague Charter Academy in Pacoima, the youngest charter
school in the Valley, has improved.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1996, the school increased its redesignation rate
of limited-English-proficient students into English-only classrooms
by 46 percent -- the highest rate in the district in 1996-97. The
school also boosted student attendance from 91 percent in 1992 to
98 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized test scores remain below the 50th percentile,
though more students are reading at grade level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Test scores haven't moved much but students are moving from
one level to the next,'' said Principal Diane Pritchard, citing a
class that had begun with scores below the 25th percentile and has
now reached grade level.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
