<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTER SCHOOLS GET RESULTS WITH FREEDOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In the northeast San Fernando Valley, which is
home to some of the worst-performing schools in Los Angeles,
Cristina Moran says her two daughters are farther ahead than many
students their age.
</P>
<P>
   And the reason is simple, she asserts: They attend Fenton Avenue
Charter School in Lake View Terrace, one of three charter schools
in the Valley and 30 in the Los Angeles Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   Moran's 8-year-old daughter has her own classroom computer to
surf the Web, write essays and even draw. Her 7-year-old daughter
also has access to a computer in the classroom. Best of all, Moran
said, is that both girls recently scored at or above the national
average on the Stanford 9 Achievement Test -- a remarkable feat,
considering that the average student in the LAUSD scored in the
bottom third nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them being average and above average is super,'' said Moran,
who works as a teaching assistant at Fenton. ``I feel teachers are
going above and beyond to get them the manipulatives they need,
whether it's from the BookMobile or the Internet or another
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Created in response to calls for academic reform seven years
ago, charter schools are granted financial autonomy and freedom
from state and LAUSD rules in exchange for improving student
performance. That means parents and teachers decide what books are
used, where to spend the school's money and how children will be
taught.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that charter schools don't have to comply with
state laws such as Proposition 227, which virtually bans bilingual
education and requires that public schools enroll
limited-English-proficient children in one-year English-immersion
classes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, if student performance doesn't
improve, the schools can be shut down. So far, only one has closed
in the district: Edutrain Charter School in downtown Los Angeles in
1994, for inappropriate spending.
</P>
<P>
   Since the charter movement started in 1991, nearly 800 such
schools have opened nationwide including 154 in California. The
LAUSD oversees nine charters that cover 30 schools.
</P>
<P>
   Test scores show that most charter schools have made good on
their promises to raise student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   A Daily News analysis of the Stanford 9 Achievement Test found
that the district's charter schools scored well into the 50th and
60th percentiles, with seventh-graders achieving the 69th
percentile in language and ninth-graders reaching the 69th
percentile in math.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of charter schools said they are having success
because they can experiment with different administrative and
educational approaches for which they are held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're taken out of the system, you can't point fingers.
We've taken on the responsibility totally now,'' said Joe Lucente,
co-director of Fenton. ``If something's not working, we have the
ability to fix it and fix it fast.''
</P>
<P>
   An independent evaluation of 13 charter schools in the district
indicates they show great promise: charter students performed just
as well or even better than students at similar, noncharter
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, charter schools have had fairly high levels of
student performance,'' said Priscilla Wohlstetter, professor and
director of the Center on Educational Governance at the University
of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Guilbert Hentschke, dean of the School of Education at USC, said
that nationwide, about 4 percent of all such schools have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not all good. They're all different,'' Hentschke said.
``That's a vastly smaller rate than most start-up businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even champions of charter schools said it is too early
to determine how well the schools are doing. Schools that performed
well on standardized tests did so before adopting charters.
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley schools that have made the biggest gains are
Fenton Avenue and Vaughn Next Century Learning Center in suburban
Pacoima, approximately 20 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming a charter school in 1993, Vaughn received
California Distinguished School and National Blue Ribbon awards.
Visitors have included first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and state
schools Superintendent Delaine Eastin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Vaughn razed a crack house to build 14 classrooms. Now
using a combination of school funds and in-kind labor, the school
is nearing completion on a $3 million campus complex that will
feature a community library, mini-museums, a business co-op, child
care center for staff and -- in collaboration with California State
University, Northridge -- a professional development lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
