<HEADLINE>
KENNELLY REGRETS CRITICIZING PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANBURY, Conn. _ Democratic Rep. Barbara B. Kennelly, who told
newspaper editors Tuesday that she was disappointed with the
support she had received from her party during her campaign for
governor, backed away from those comments Wednesday, saying that
she regretted her criticism but had no regrets about entering the
race.
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic Party chairman said that Kennelly's
original remarks were driven by frustration with her own
fund-raising efforts. As Kennelly's position in the polls has
tumbled, her campaign has had trouble raising money. And those poll
numbers fell further Wednesday as Quinnipiac College released a
poll showing Kennelly trailing Gov. John G. Rowland by 48 points.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday with the editorial boards of The
Advocate of Stamford and The Greenwich Time, Kennelly said she had
been ``naive'' and should have been more realistic about her
chances to defeat Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   She also criticized the Democratic State Central Committee and
its chairman, Edward L. Marcus, saying they had failed to raise
money for herself and other Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here, Kennelly said she regretted
``criticizing anyone'' during her meeting with the editorial
boards. But in an interview earlier in the day her campaign
manager, Jonathan W. Pelto, said the party needed to do more to
help its nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the outcome on Nov. 3, it's clear the Democratic
Party needs to do more to rebuild its infrastructure and support
its candidates,'' Pelto said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent financial disclosure statements,
filed three weeks before the election, Rowland has $2.17 million on
hand and Kennelly has $348,000. Marcus said he had personally
raised and donated $40,000 to Kennelly's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the party's central committee, which organizes
get-out-the-vote drives, could barely pay its bills, much less give
money to candidates. Marcus said the party had not given money to
an individual candidate since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle we have been able to stay out of debt,'' Marcus
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennelly's father, John M. Bailey, ran the state Democratic
Party from 1946 to 1975, when the parties had a bigger role in
getting their candidates elected.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll, conducted from Oct. 13 to Oct. 19, showed Rowland
leading Kennelly 72 percent to 24 percent among likely voters. The
survey had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3.8 percent
for likely voters, according to the poll's director, Douglas
Schwartz.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rowland, in an interview with the Connecticut Radio Network,
said his strong showing in the polls reflected the strength of the
economy, support for his administration's policies, and problems
with Kennelly's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are generally happy with the direction of the
state, happy with their leadership and that is reflected in the
polls,'' he said. The Quinnipiac College poll found that 83 percent
of registered voters were satisfied with general conditions in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Kennelly was in Danbury to criticize Rowland's proposal last
year to cut rail service along the Danbury, Waterbury and Shoreline
East lines. The candidate, who has said in the past that polls are
important, said she was ignoring the new poll and concentrating on
the election.
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not regret entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran for the right reasons,'' she said, ``to make sure
Connecticut was first again in educating all its children, in
having a good environment, and first in having a good
transportation system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
