<HEADLINE>
POWELL, LARRY TO START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's been a couple of changes in the USC
starting lineup: Marvin Powell has become the new starter at
fullback and defensive end Lawrence Larry has reclaimed his
starting position.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who has been a reserve all season, was named a starter
Wednesday by USC coach Paul Hackett in place of Ted Iacenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really stepped up,'' Hackett said of the Birmingham High
School graduate. ``We still have the other guys, but Marvin has
really done a nice job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hoping somebody would step up and Marvin did a
great job. I'm really excited about where he is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who played tight end last year, started four games at
fullback in 1996. He is the third Trojan, along with Iacenda and
Brennan Ochs, to start at fullback this season.
</P>
<P>
   As for defensive end, Larry has overtaken Shamsud-Din
Abdul-Shaheed, who started most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership is valuable to us, especially with Marc Matock
out with an injury,'' defensive line coach Ed Orgeron said of
Larry, a Littlerock graduate. ``I feel this is Lawrence's senior
year, and he's come on strong.''
</P>
<P>
   It also hasn't hurt Larry's cause that the coaching staff feels
Abdul-Shaheed has some maturity issues to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's making strides in that area, but he needs to keep
on making strides,'' Orgeron said. ``I think that's part of my job.
Some need a little more help in some areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett also announced that Eric Denmon would start at center
but continue to share time with Matt McShane.
</P>
<P>
   __ Good news for Soward: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward is
continuing to do well academically since experiencing problems last
spring. Soward received a B on his history midterm two weeks ago.
He also had his last 6 a.m. running session Wednesday, which occurs
when a player misses a class.
</P>
<P>
   __ Van Raaphorst passes tests: Quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst
passed a second round of tests at USC University Hospital, which
found no reason to explain why Van Raaphorst suffered nausea during
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can put this behind me and go out and play,'' Van Raaphorst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst said he was not concerned that the tests could not
explain his illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want an answer,'' he said. ``But what if the answer is
really bad?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Cusano still out: Doctors did not clear linebacker Mark
Cusano (sore thigh muscle) to play and he sat out another day of
practice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned about him,'' Hackett said. ``We're hoping
to have him for the game. We've got our fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   He will try to practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Kori Dickerson has been bothered by back spasms
but is expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   __ Long time, no see: USC has not played in Eugene since 1993.
The Trojans did not play the Ducks in 1995 and '96 and played
Oregon at the Coliseum last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans defeated the Ducks 24-13 in '93.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's forecast is for showers with the temperature in the
low 50s.
</P>
</TEXT>
